001|access-date=2016-08-19}}\n{{certification Table Entry|region=Japan|type=album|title=Share My World |artist=MAry J. Blige|award=Gold|relyear=2001|certyear=2001-08|format=3col}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Netherlands|type=Album|award=Gold|salesamount=40,000|title=No More Drama|artist=Mary J. Blige|relyear=2001|certyear=2002|access-date=September 20, 2018}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|type=album |region=Sweden|artist=Mary J. Blige|title=No More Drama|award=Gold|certyear=2001 |relyear=2001|access-date=2016-08-19}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|type=album |region=Switzerland|artist=Mary J. Blige|title=No More Drama|award=Platinum|certyear=2001 |relyear=2001|access-date=2017-06-18}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|type=album |region=United Kingdom |artist=Mary J. Blige|title=No More Drama|award=Platinum|certyear=2002 |relyear=2002|access-date=2016-08-19}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|type=album |region=United States |artist=Mary J. Blige|title=No More Drama|award=Platinum |number=2|certyear=2002 |relyear=2001|access-date=2016-08-19}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom|format=3col|nosales=yes}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{metacritic album|no-more-drama/mary-j-blige}}\n\n{{Mary J. Blige}}\n{{Mary J. Blige singles}}\n\n\u2033\n\n[[Category:2001 albums]]\n[[Category:2002 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Dr. Dre]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Irv Gotti]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Jimmy Jam and Terry Lewis]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Missy Elliott]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by The Neptunes]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Rockwilder]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Rich Harrison]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Swizz Beatz]]\n[[Category:Mary J. Blige albums]]\n[[Category:MCA Records albums]]\n[[Category:Interscope Geffen A&M Records albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Dame Grease]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = No More Drama\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Mary J. Blige]]\n| cover      = Nomoredrama.jpg\n| alt        =\n| caption    = The original release CD artwork for the album.\n| released   = {{Start date|2001|8|28|mf=y}}\n| recorded   = 2001\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n| length     = 71:50\n| label      = [[MCA Records|MCA]]\n| producer   = {{flatlist|\n*Mary J. Blige <small>(also [[executive producer#Music|exec.]])</small>\n*[[Ron \"Amen-Ra\" Lawrence|Ron Lawrence]]\n*Charlemagne\n*[[Dr. Dre]]\n*[[Missy Elliott]]\n*Kenny Flaw\n*[[Irv Gotti]]\n*[[Dame Grease]]\n*Kiyamma Griffin\n*[[Rich Harrison]]\n*[[G\u00e9rald Isaac]]\n*[[Jimmy Jam & Terry Lewis]]\n*[[Kwame|K-1 Million]]\n*Kenny Lav\n*[[The Neptunes]]\n*[[Rockwilder]]\n*[[Swizz Beatz]]\n*[[Chucky Thompson]]\n*[[Mario Winans]]\n}}\n| prev_title = [[Mary (Mary J. Blige album)|Mary]]\n| prev_year  = 1999\n| next_title = [[Love & Life (Mary J. Blige album)|Love & Life]]\n| next_year  = 2003\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = No More Drama\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Family Affair (Mary J. Blige song)|Family Affair]]\n | single1date = June 12, 2001\n | single2     = [[Dance for Me (Mary J. Blige song)|Dance for Me]]\n | single2date = August 7, 2001\n | single3     = [[No More Drama (song)|No More Drama]]\n | single3date = September 11, 2001\n | single4     = [[Rainy Dayz]]\n | single4date = January 29, 2002\n}}\n}}\n'''''No More Drama''''' is the fifth studio album by American R&B recording artist [[Mary J. Blige]]. The album was released by [[MCA Records|MCA]] on August 28, 2001.\n\nFollowing the critical and commercial success of her fourth studio album ''[[Mary (Mary J. Blige album)|Mary]]'' (1999), ''No More Drama'' was similarly well-received.  It debuted at number two on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and at number one on the [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums|R&B Albums]] chart, selling 324,000 copies in its first week.<ref>[http://www.hitsdailydouble.com/sales/archcht.cgi?cht760 HITS Daily Double: Previous Album Sales Chart<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120604211103/http://www.hitsdailydouble.com/sales/archcht.cgi?cht760 |date=2012-06-04 }}</ref> It has spawned four singles that have attained ''[[Billboard charts|Billboard]]'' chart success, including its lead single \"[[Family Affair (2001 song)|Family Affair]]\", which became Blige's first career number-one single on the [[Billboard Hot 100|US ''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart and a worldwide number-one hit.\n\nThe album received two [[Grammy Award]] nominations for [[Grammy Award for Best R&B Album|Best R&B Album]] and [[Grammy Award for Best Female R&B Vocal Performance|Best Female R&B Vocal Performance]] (for \"[[Family Affair (2001 song)|Family Affair]]\") at the [[44th Grammy Awards]]. Blige would win her first in the latter category for the track \"He Think I Don't Know\" the following year. As of December 2016, the album has been certified triple platinum for shipping over three million copies in the US by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA).\n\n==Conception==\nThe inspiration for ''No More Drama'' came largely from Blige's own confused and hectic life. In a later interview she confessed to living a life of alcohol and drug abuse at the time, and as a result getting involved in a series of abusive relationships. The album was an attempt to break free from this vicious circle, which was a result of a deprived childhood.<ref name=\"Brown\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/3670996/Mary-J-Blige-Proud-to-shout-it-out-without-selling-out-on-Growing-Pains.html|title=Mary J Blige: Proud to shout it out without selling out on 'Growing Pains'|last=Brown|first=Helen|date=2008-07-02|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=2009-07-21}}</ref>\n\nStylistically, the album diverged from Blige's typically blues-soaked R&B into the hip-hop beats and influences that had made her debut, 1992's ''[[What's the 411?]]'', a hit. This is especially evident in the first single, \"[[Family Affair (2001 song)|Family Affair]]\". Rapper [[Eve (rapper)|Eve]] appears on the track \"Where I've Been\" as well, and urban influences can be heard throughout the album.{{Citation needed|date=August 2009}}\n\nEarly in its development, the album carried the full title '''''Mary Jane - No More Drama''''' and was to be a sequel to 1999's ''[[Mary (Mary J. Blige album)|Mary]]''. Blige's then-manager hinted that the album would be the second in a trilogy and be followed by an album titled '''''Mary Jane Blige'''''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1442450/20010403/blige_mary_j.jhtml|title=Mary J. Blige Wants 'No More Drama' On Fifth LP|last=Reid|first=Shaheem|date=2001-04-03|accessdate=2009-02-24|publisher=MTV.com}}</ref> During this time, the first single was supposed to be a song called \"Rock Steady\" featuring a rap from [[Jay-Z]] and [[Lenny Kravitz]] on guitar. The song was leaked to mixtapes around June 2001, two months before the album was scheduled to be released and subsequently did not make the final cut on the album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1444771/20010625/jay_z.jhtml|title=Blige May Cut Leaked Jay-Z/Kravitz Track From Album|publisher=MTV News}}</ref>\n\nThe original advance copy of ''No More Drama'' was slightly different from the later, official release. A vocal loop repeated throughout the whole of the version included with the intention of [[Copy protection#Anti-piracy|anti-piracy]] sings \"Mary J. Blige, No More Drama!\". The first publish of an AMG review printed in All Music Guide to Soul, a guide to R&B and soul, of ''No More Drama'' mistakenly pointed this out as if it were part of the actual album, calling it \"as subtle and congruent as a consistent drum hit.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=o552g5xRRiwC&pg=PA59&dq=%22no+more+drama+aug+28+2001%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=xwimU77bJYeOyATjloKIDQ#v=onepage&q=%22no%20more%20drama%20aug%2028%202001%22&f=false|title=All Music Guide to Soul: The Definitive Guide to R&B and Soul|publisher=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n|MC = 77/100<ref name=\"Metacritic\"/>\n|rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n|rev1score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Liana\"/>\n|rev2 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n|rev2score = A<ref name=\"EW\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,255016,00.html|title=No More Drama|last=Browne|first=David|authorlink=David Browne (journalist)|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=September 7, 2001|accessdate=August 22, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902204348/https://ew.com/article/2001/09/07/no-more-drama-mary-j-blige/|archivedate=September 2, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|rev3 = ''[[The Guardian]]''\n|rev3score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2001/aug/24/shopping.artsfeatures1|title=Mary J Blige: No More Drama (Universal)|last=Lynskey|first=Dorian|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=August 24, 2001|accessdate=January 5, 2019}}</ref>\n|rev4 = ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''\n|rev4score = {{Rating|3|4}}<ref name=\"latimes\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/nov/22/news/wk-ggpop22|title=Choices From the Charts|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=November 22, 2001|accessdate=August 22, 2016}}</ref>\n|rev5 = ''[[NME]]''\n|rev5score = 7/10<ref name=\"nme\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.nme.com/reviews/mary-j-blige/5613|title=Blige, Mary J: No More Drama|last=Ward|first=Christian|magazine=[[NME]]|date=September 6, 2001|accessdate=August 22, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130205011707/http://www.nme.com/reviews/mary-j-blige/5613|archivedate=February 5, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|rev6 = ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]''\n|rev6Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Mary J. Blige: No More Drama|magazine=[[Q (magazine)|Q]]|issue=182|date=October 2001|page=117}}</ref>\n|rev7 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n|rev7score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"Marriott\"/>\n|rev8 = ''[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]''\n|rev8Score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Mary J. Blige: No More Drama|magazine=[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]|issue=54|date=November 2001|page=102}}</ref>\n|rev9 = ''[[USA Today]]''\n|rev9score = {{Rating|3.5|4}}<ref name=\"usatoday\">{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/USAToday/access/78958483.html?dids=78958483:78958483&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Aug+28%2C+2001&author=Steve+Jones+and+Elysa+Gardner+and+Brian+Mansfield&pub=USA+TODAY&desc=Pick+and+choose+from+Blige%2C+Scruggs+and+friends&pqatl=google|title=Mary J. Blige, No More Drama|last=Jones|first=Steve|newspaper=[[USA Today]]|date=August 28, 2001|accessdate=August 22, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025195623/http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/USAToday/access/78958483.html?dids=78958483:78958483&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Aug+28,+2001&author=Steve+Jones+and+Elysa+Gardner+and+Brian+Mansfield&pub=USA+TODAY&desc=Pick+and+choose+from+Blige,+Scruggs+and+friends&pqatl=google|archivedate=October 25, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|rev10 = ''[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]''\n|rev10score = 4/5<ref name=\"vibe\">{{cite magazine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2SUEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA150|title=Mary J. Blige: No More Drama|first=Craig|last=Seymour|magazine=[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]|volume=9|issue=10|date=October 2001|accessdate=August 22, 2016|page=150}}</ref> \n}}\n''No More Drama'' received generally positive reviews from critics. At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a normalized rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream publications, the album received an average score of 77, based on 12 reviews.<ref name=\"Metacritic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/no-more-drama/mary-j-blige|title=Reviews for No More Drama by Mary J. Blige|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=August 20, 2012}}</ref> [[AllMusic]] editor Liana Jonas complimented Blige's ability to write relatable lyrics, writing that she \"has a killer instinct for creating gritty, thick, and soul-infused R&B fare. Her music is more than heard. It is felt, and audiences would be hard-pressed to not surrender to her groove.\"<ref name=\"Liana\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/no-more-drama-mw0000658167|title=No More Drama \u2013 Mary J. Blige|last=Jonas|first=Liana|website=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=July 21, 2009}}</ref> Writing for ''[[The A.V. Club]]'', [[Nathan Rabin]] believed \"Blige sounds happier and more relaxed than ever. Boasting nearly as many producers as songs, ''No More Drama'' [is] a testament to Blige's force of personality and the authenticity of her vision that the disc feels as personal and intimate as the most heartfelt four-track demo.\"<ref name=\"avclub\">{{cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/mary-j-blige-no-more-drama,18417/|title=Mary J. Blige: No More Drama|last=Rabin|first=Nathan|authorlink=Nathan Rabin|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|date=August 28, 2001|accessdate=August 5, 2016}}</ref> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''{{'}}s [[David Browne (journalist)|David Browne]] felt that \"from the Dre-produced theatricality of the single \u201dFamily Affair\u201d to refined funk and crisp quiet-storm R&B, the multi-producer arrangements are expansive yet warm, and Blige's pushy rasp has never sounded better.\"<ref name=\"EW\"/> Robert Marriott from ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' said the record \"presents Blige more in touch with her roots, more grounded and ready for her next set of challenges, musical and otherwise, an analog soul thriving in a digital age.\"<ref name=\"Marriott\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/no-more-drama-20010820|title=No More Drama|last=Marriott|first=Robert|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=August 20, 2001|accessdate=July 21, 2009}}</ref> Barry Walters from ''[[The Village Voice]]'' called it \"Blige's most rhythm album ever, and even the ballads that can drag r&b down here bristle with bumping beats.\"<ref name=\"village\">{{cite news|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/music/marked-woman-6414827|title=Marked Woman|last=Walters|first=Barry|newspaper=[[The Village Voice]]|date=September 4, 2001|accessdate=August 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe newspaper's [[Robert Christgau]] was somewhat less enthusiastic, finding the record \"front-loaded\",<ref name=\"Christgau\">{{cite news|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2003-09-23/music/the-commoner-queen/|title=The Commoner Queen|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|newspaper=The Village Voice|date=September 23, 2003|accessdate=August 20, 2012}}</ref> highlighting the songs \"PMS\" and \"Steal Away\" while writing \"positive attitude's a bitch, not to mention a drag\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Christgau|first=Robert|date=September 18, 2001|url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/cg/cgv901-01.php|title=Consumer Guide|newspaper=The Village Voice|accessdate=October 1, 2016}}</ref> [[Ethan Brown]] was unimpressed by Blige's more optimistic songs, writing in ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' magazine that, \"miserable, Blige can be penetrating and profound; happy, she comes off generic and bland.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Brown|first=Ethan|authorlink=Ethan Brown|date=August 27, 2001|url=http://nymag.com/nymetro/arts/music/pop/reviews/5102/|title=Ladies Sing the Blues|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|accessdate=October 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\n[[File:Mary j-02-mika.jpg|thumb|right|220px|In the United States, ''No More Drama'' opened to Blige's biggest first week sales up to then.<ref name=\"mtvnews2\"/>]] \n''No More Drama'' debuted and peaked at number two on the ''[[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]]'', the official albums chart in the United States, on September 6, 2001 \u2013 second only to [[Aaliyah]]'s [[Aaliyah (album)|self-titled third album]].<ref name=\"nyd\">{{cite web|first=Jim|last=Farber|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/nydn-features/aaliyah-surges-no-1-album-article-1.937942|title=Aaliyah Surges To No. 1 Album|work=[[New York Daily News]]|publisher=[[Mortimer Zuckerman]]|date=2001-09-06|accessdate=2015-07-21}}</ref> The album sold 294,351 units in its first week of release.<ref name=\"nyd\"/> ''No More Drama'' was Blige's highest debut week album sales, until it was surpassed by ''[[The Breakthrough]]'' (2005), which sold 729,000 copies in its first week.<ref name=\"mtvnews\">{{cite web |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2003/sep/04/news/wk-albums4 |title=Mary J. Blige, Hilary Duff Take Over Top Slots On Albums Chart|first=Joe|last=D'Angelo |work=[[MTV News]] |publisher=[[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]] |date=2003-09-03|accessdate=2016-08-22}}</ref> By the end of 2001, the album was [[platinum certification|certified platinum]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA), and became the seventy-third best-selling album of that year in the United States. The album's commercial performance was reinforced by the subsequent release of a reissue. The release of the special edition helped ''No More Drama'' to re-enter the top ten in February 2002, gaining more than 200 percent in sales at a total of 61,000 copies.<ref name=\"mtvnews2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1452183/mary-js-reissue-the-only-drama-in-stagnant-billboard-top-10/ |title=Mary J.'s Reissue The Only 'Drama' In Stagnant Billboard Top 10|first=Joe|last=D'Angelo |work=[[MTV News]] |publisher=[[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]] |date=2002-02-06|accessdate=2016-08-22}}</ref> The same month, ''No More Drama'' was certified [[double platinum]] by the RIAA. As of August 2003, the album has sold 1.9 million copies in the US, while the special edition moved an additional 1.1 million units.<ref name=\"billboard01\">{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_axEEAAAAMBAJ|page=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_axEEAAAAMBAJ/page/n12 13]|quote=blige LOVE & LIFE.|title=Mary J. Blige: Love & Life|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=2003-08-09|accessdate=2016-08-22}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Germany]], the album was her most successful one in her career in this country, reaching #13 and staying in the [[German Albums Chart]] for 35 weeks <ref name=autogenerated1>{{Cite web |url=http://www.musicline.de/de/chartverfolgung_summary/artist/Blige%2CMary+J./?type=longplay |title=Die ganze Musik im Internet: Charts, Neuerscheinungen, Tickets, Genres, Genresuche, Genrelexikon, K\u00fcnstler-Suche, Musik-Suche, Track-Suche, Ticket-Suche - musicline.de<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=2010-07-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303215828/http://www.musicline.de/de/chartverfolgung_summary/artist/Blige,Mary+J./?type=longplay |archive-date=2016-03-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\nEstimated worldwide sales for the album are at 6,500,000.<ref name=\"FoM\">{{cite web|url=http://fanofmusic.free.fr/BestSellers.php?Act=MaryJBlige |title=Mary J. Blige |publisher=Fan of Music |accessdate=2009-07-21 }}{{dead link|date=September 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{track listing\n| headline        = ''No More Drama'' \u2013 Standard edition\n| collapsed       = no\n| extra_column    = Producer(s)\n| title1          = Love\n| writer1         = {{hlist|Blige|Bruce Miller|[[Ron \"Amen-Ra\" Lawrence|Ron Lawrence]]|[[Kwam\u00e9|Kwame Holland]]}}\n| extra1          = {{hlist|Amen-Ra|[[Kwam\u00e9|K-1 Million]]}}\n| length1         = 2:46\n\n| title2          = [[Family Affair (Mary J. Blige song)|Family Affair]]\n| writer2         = {{hlist|Blige|Bruce|Camara Kambon|[[Dr. Dre|Andre Young]]|[[Mike Elizondo]]}}\n| extra2          = {{hlist|[[Dr. Dre]]}}\n| length2         = 4:28\n\n| title3          = Steal Away \n| writer3         = {{hlist|Pharrell Williams|Chad Hugo|Gene Thornton}}\n| note3           = featuring [[Pharrell Williams|Pharrell]] and [[No Malice]]\n| extra3          = {{hlist|[[The Neptunes]]}}\n| length3         = 4:27\n\n| title4          = Crazy Games\n| writer4         = {{hlist|Blige|Kenny Dickerson}}\n| extra4          =