essdate=2018-08-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627144741/http://maxdefense.blogspot.com/2018/06/elbit-systems-wins-contract-to-upgrade.html |archive-date=2018-06-27 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==== Light Tank Project ====\nThe Philippine Army, along with the [[Department of National Defense (Philippines)|DND]], plans to acquire 15 light to medium tanks as training units for future Main Battle Tank acquisitions, as well for urban warfare, as part of a lesson during the [[Battle of Marawi]], wherein the current firepower of the AFP, from fire-support to IFVs guns were proven insufficient and unable to hit through concrete structures used as defensive positions during the battle, as well as proper armor protection under heavy fire. The project is under the Horizon 2 phase projects of the Modernization Program.<ref name=\"Philippine Army's Planned Acquisition of Tanks and Armoured Assets for Horizon 2 Phase\">{{cite web |title=Philippine Army's Planned Acquisition of Tanks and Armoured Assets for Horizon 2 Phase |url=http://maxdefense.blogspot.com/2018/03/philippine-armys-planned-acquisition-of.html |website=Philippine Army's Planned Acquisition of Tanks and Armoured Assets for Horizon 2 Phase ~ MaxDefense Philippines |accessdate=12 December 2019 |date=24 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe main contenders for the project are: The [[K21|K21-105 Medium Tank]] of South Korea, The [[ASCOD|GDELS ASCOD 2 MMBT]] of Austria and Spain, and The [[Modern Medium Weight Tank|PT Pindad Harimau]] of Indonesia and Turkey.\n\n=== Heavy weapons ===\n\n==== Land-Based Surface Missile System acquisition ====\n\nThe DND plans to acquire a shore-based missile system with a budget of \u20b16.5 billion that will be placed under the control and supervision of the Army.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.zambotimes.com/archives/news/81840-PHL-to-acquire-shore-based-missile-system.html |title=PHL to acquire shore-based missile system |publisher=ZamboTimes |date=2013-12-04 |accessdate=2013-12-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131211063133/http://www.zambotimes.com/archives/news/81840-PHL-to-acquire-shore-based-missile-system.html |archive-date=2013-12-11 |url-status=live }}</ref> It will consist of 12 launchers with its attendant trailers and tracking systems plus the missiles themselves. These shore-to-ship missiles could be fired to hit naval or other sea-based targets.<ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite web |url=http://www.mb.com.ph/govt-eyes-enhanced-hawk-surface-to-air-missiles/ |title=Gov\u2019t eyes enhanced HAWK surface-to-air missiles |work=Manila Bulletin |date=2014-03-31 |accessdate=2014-03-31 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140331095844/http://www.mb.com.ph/govt-eyes-enhanced-hawk-surface-to-air-missiles/ |archivedate=2014-03-31 }}</ref>\n\nThe Shore Based Missile systems were shelved in favor for body kits and other internal security operations.\n\nIn 2018, the plan was back on track as part of the PHP 300 billion/USD $5.6 billion Horizon 2 phase projects, with the budget for the Land-Based Missile System approved by President Duterte in June 2018. The [[BrahMos]] Missile Systems being the main contender for the project. The talks are expected to end in a deal at 2020, with at least 2 batteries set to be acquired.<ref name=\"The BrahMos Supersonic Missile System and the Philippine Army's Land Based Missile System Project\">{{cite web |title=The BrahMos Supersonic Missile System and the Philippine Army's Land Based Missile System Project |url=http://maxdefense.blogspot.com/2019/10/the-brahmos-supersonic-missile-system.html |website=The BrahMos Supersonic Missile System and the Philippine Army's Land Based Missile System Project ~ MaxDefense Philippines |accessdate=12 December 2019 |date=31 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Philippines likely to finalise BrahMos deal by next year\">{{cite web |title=Philippines likely to finalise BrahMos deal by next year |url=https://m.hindustantimes.com/india-news/philippines-likely-to-finalise-brahmos-deal-by-next-year/story-pzQe35AYmpvKKByglm4osL_amp.html |website=hindustantimes.com |accessdate=12 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"Philippines in talks with India to procure BrahMos supersonic cruise missile {{!}} Jane's 360\">{{cite web |title=Philippines in talks with India to procure BrahMos supersonic cruise missile {{!}} Jane's 360 |url=https://www.janes.com/article/93074/philippines-in-talks-with-india-to-procure-brahmos-supersonic-cruise-missile |website=www.janes.com |accessdate=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Rocket Systems ====\n\nThe Philippine Army is negotiating with the [[South Korea]]n Government on the possible transfer of 3 batteries consisting 6 launchers of second-hand [[K136|K136 Kooryong]] rocket systems for the newly created 2nd Multiple Launch Rocket System Battery unit under the Army's Artillery Regiment.<ref name=\"DEFENSE STUDIES: Army Displays Mock up Unit of K136 Kooryong MLRS\">{{cite web |title=DEFENSE STUDIES: Army Displays Mock up Unit of K136 Kooryong MLRS |url=http://defense-studies.blogspot.com/2019/12/army-displays-mock-up-unit-of-k136.html |website=DEFENSE STUDIES |accessdate=12 December 2019 |date=}}</ref>\n\nThe Army is also planning to acquire at least 6 [[HIMARS]] launchers, however, the two sides have been unable to reach a deal due to budgeting reasons, as well as the Israeli [[LYNX (MRL)|LYNX]] System.\n\n==== Self Propelled Artillery System ====\nThe Philippine Army is preparing to acquire at least 2 batteries of the [[ATMOS 2000]] [[Self-propelled gun]] system in 39 and 52 caliber variants from [[Elbit Systems]], based in [[Israel]]. Plans were announced since 2013, as part of phase one of the Horizon 1 projects, and was moved to the Horizon 2 phase after funding problems. The Army is set to acquire the 52 caliber variant of the system within 2020 <ref name=\"155mm Howitzer, Self Propelled System Acquisition Project of the Philippine Army\">{{cite web |title=155mm Howitzer, Self Propelled System Acquisition Project of the Philippine Army |url=http://maxdefense.blogspot.com/p/155mm-self-propelled-howitzer.html |website=155mm Howitzer, Self Propelled System Acquisition Project of the Philippine Army ~ MaxDefense Philippines |accessdate=3 February 2020}}</ref>, with the expected completion of delivery is set by February 2022.<ref name=\"Philippine Army Finally Orders the ATMOS 155mm/52cal Self-Propelled Howitzer System from Elbit Systems\">{{cite web |title=Philippine Army Finally Orders the ATMOS 155mm/52cal Self-Propelled Howitzer System from Elbit Systems |url=http://maxdefense.blogspot.com/2020/02/philippine-army-finally-orders-atmos.html |website=Philippine Army Finally Orders the ATMOS 155mm/52cal Self-Propelled Howitzer System from Elbit Systems ~ MaxDefense Philippines |accessdate=19 February 2020 |date=9 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Short Ranged Air-Defense (SHORAD) Systems===\nWith the activation of 2nd Air Defense Artillery Battery, The Philippine Army is preparing to acquire air defense systems, as part of the Horizon 2 projects. The Army is eyeing the [[Mistral (missile)|MBDA Mistral]] system from [[France]], and the [[Chiron (missile)|LIG Nex1 Chiron]] system from [[South Korea]], aside from the current [[M39 cannon]]s and other AA guns, as well as some limited short ranged anti-aircraft missile systems in its inventory. Decisions on the acquisition will be announced within 2020, and deliveries are expected on or before 2024.<ref name=\"Philippines shortlists MBDA Mistral, LIG Nex1 Chiron for SHORAD requirements\">{{cite web |title=Philippines shortlists MBDA Mistral, LIG Nex1 Chiron for SHORAD requirements |url=https://www.asiapacificdefensejournal.com/2020/01/philippines-shortlists-mbda-mistral-lig.html |website=Asia Pacific Defense Journal |accessdate=3 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Armored Vehicle-Launched Bridge===\nThe Philippine Army has recently awarded the [[Elbit Systems]] for the acquisition of the [[M1074 Joint Assault Bridge]]. <ref name=\"Joint Assault Bridge {{!}} Leonardo DRS\">{{cite web |title=Joint Assault Bridge {{!}} Leonardo DRS |url=https://www.leonardodrs.com/products-and-services/joint-assault-bridge-jab/ |website=www.leonardodrs.com |accessdate=8 February 2020}}</ref> The contract signing is expected at the 1st quarter of 2020. <ref name=\"Philippine Army Awards Armored Vehicle-Launched Bridge to Elbit-IMI JV, to Possibly Supply Joint Assault Bridge\">{{cite web |title=Philippine Army Awards Armored Vehicle-Launched Bridge to Elbit-IMI JV, to Possibly Supply Joint Assault Bridge |url=https://maxdefense.blogspot.com/2020/01/philippine-army-awards-armored-vehicle.html |website=Philippine Army Awards Armored Vehicle-Launched Bridge to Elbit-IMI JV, to Possibly Supply Joint Assault Bridge ~ MaxDefense Philippines |accessdate=8 February 2020 |date=25 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Armed Forces of the Philippines]]\n*[[Philippine Air Force]]\n*[[Philippine Navy]]\n*[[Philippine Marine Corps]]\n*[[Philippine Coast Guard]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.army.mil.ph/ Official website]\n\n{{Military of the Philippines}}\n{{Association of SouthEast Asian Nations Armed Forces}}\n{{Department of National Defense of the Philippines}}\n\n[[Category:Philippine Army| ]]\n", "name_user": "Jsnueva1022", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philippine_Army"}
{"title_page": "Tornado outbreak of April 13\u201316, 2012", "text_new": "{{Infobox storm\n| name = Tornado outbreak of April 13\u201316, 2012\n| image = April 14, 2012 Marquette, Kansas EF4 tornado.JPG\n| alt = \n| caption = A violent EF4 tornado near [[Marquette, Kansas]].\n| type = Tornado outbreak\n| active = April 13\u201316, 2012 \n| lowest pressure = \n| lowest temperature =\n| tornadoes = 113 confirmed\n| fujitascale = EF4\n| tornado duration = 2 days, 16 hours, 37 minutes\n| highest winds = \n| hail =  <!-- unused? -->\n| gusts =\n| maximum snow = \n| power outages =\n| total fatalities =  6 fatalities<ref name=\"Tornadoes Kill 6\">{{cite news|publisher=Fox News Latino|date=April 16, 2012|accessdate=April 16, 2012|title=Tornadoes Kill 6 Across Great Plains|url=http://latino.foxnews.com/latino/news/2012/04/16/tornadoes-kill-6-across-great-plains/}}</ref>\n| damages = At least $283&nbsp;million (in Wichita, unknown elsewhere)<ref name=\"WichitaDamage\">{{cite news|newspaper=Kansas City Star|date=April 15, 2012|accessdate=April 15, 2012|title=Tornadoes rake Wichita area, causing significant damage|url=http://www.kansascity.com/2012/04/14/3555382/tornado-heavily-damages-south.html}}</ref>\n| affected = \n| current advisories =\n| enhanced = yes\n| notes = \n}} \nFrom April 13 to 16, 2012, a major [[tornado outbreak]] occurred across a large portion of the [[Great Plains]]. The storms resulted in 6 tornado-related fatalities, all of which occurred as a result of a nighttime EF3 tornado that caused major damage in and around [[Woodward, Oklahoma]]. Numerous other tornadoes occurred, including a violent EF4 tornado that passed near [[Marquette, Kansas]], and an EF3 that caused major damage in [[Wichita, Kansas|Wichita]].\n\n==Meteorological synopsis==\nAn impressive low pressure area and associated trough began tracking into the Great Plains on April 13, and a slight risk of severe weather was issued. The outlook mentioned the possibility of tornadoes, including the risk for isolated strong tornadoes. No strong tornadoes occurred, though an EF1 tornado caused considerable damage in [[Norman, Oklahoma]].\n[[File:Evolution of SPC Forecasts Leading to April 14, 2012.png|thumb|left|A montage of the Storm Prediction Center's severe weather outlooks leading up to the outbreak. The final image is a verification of the day one high-risk outlook with reported events.]]\n\nFor only the second time in history ([[April 6\u20138, 2006 tornado outbreak|previously for April 7, 2006]]), a day two [[List of SPC high-risk days|high risk]]  <ref>[http://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/outlook/archive/2012/day2otlk_20120413_0600.html Storm Prediction Center April 13, 2012 0600 UTC Day 2 Convective Outlook]</ref> of severe weather was issued by the [[Storm Prediction Center]]. In the discussion, the SPC stated that a major tornado outbreak was likely across central Kansas and north-central Oklahoma during the afternoon and overnight hours of April 14, with long-tracked violent tornadoes likely. It was later expanded to include a second high risk area across much of Nebraska, where a rare 45% tornado probability was given during the late morning update on April&nbsp;13.  During the morning hours on the 14th, the high risk area was expanded again to combine the two separate areas into a single large one. Later in the day, the 45% tornado probability was shifted from Nebraska south to Kansas and northern Oklahoma. A large outbreak of tornadoes impacted the Great Plains states on April 14, and several [[Particularly dangerous situation|PDS]] [[Tornado Warning]]s were issued during the outbreak. Initially, most of the tornadoes were small or remained over open country, though more significant tornado activity began to develop throughout the day. A high-end EF2 tornado struck [[Creston, Iowa]], flipping vehicles and causing major structural damage to homes and other buildings in town. Another EF2 wedge tornado struck [[Thurman, Iowa]], damaging 75% of the town. In Nebraska, a strong EF2 tornado destroyed outbuildings and badly damaged a home near [[Cook, Nebraska|Cook]], while a large and violent EF4 tornado leveled a home and debarked trees near [[Marquette, Kansas]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cnn.com/2012/04/14/us/midwest-storms/index.html?hpt=hp_t1 | work=CNN | title=Storm hits Iowa hospital; tornado warning issued for Wichita | date=April 15, 2012}}</ref> Later that evening, a cyclic supercell thunderstorm developed in northern Oklahoma before moving into southern Kansas, producing multiple tornadoes along the way. This included a large EF3 wedge tornado that destroyed homes near [[Conway Springs, Kansas|Conway Springs]]. As this supercell moved into [[Wichita, Kansas|Wichita]] around 10:15 pm CDT (0315 UTC), another large EF3 wedge tornado touched down and caused major damage in the southeastern part of the city. Staff at the Wichita [[National Weather Service]] Weather Forecast Office at [[Wichita Mid-Continent Airport]] were forced to hand over responsibility for their County Warning Area to the National Weather Service office in Topeka and take shelter at about 10:00 pm CDT (0300 UTC), returning to duty half an hour later. Another supercell thunderstorm also produced two EF3 wedge tornadoes that passed near [[Fellsburg, Kansas|Fellsburg]] and [[Hudson, Kansas|Hudson]], causing significant damage.<ref name=\"WFO ICT shelter\">{{cite web|url=https://www.weather.gov/ict/april14_ked|title=Why NWS Wichita Took Shelter and Requested Service Back-up the Evening of April 14, 2012|author=Kevin Darmofal, NWS Wichita Lead Meteorologist|date=April 20, 2012|publisher=[[National Weather Service]]|accessdate=November 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAround 10:00&nbsp;p.m. CDT (0300 UTC), a broken [[squall line]] began to form across the eastern portions of the Texas and Oklahoma panhandles; a thunderstorm developed ahead of the northern line segment in northwestern [[Wheeler County, Texas]] at approximately 10:30&nbsp;p.m. CDT (0330 UTC), and began developing supercell characteristics as it tracked northeastward into the Oklahoma counties of [[Ellis County, Oklahoma|Ellis]] and [[Roger Mills County, Oklahoma|Roger Mills]]. A tornado warning was issued for Ellis, [[Harper County, Oklahoma|Harper]] and [[Woodward County, Oklahoma|Woodward counties]] at 12:00 am CDT (0500 UTC) on April 15 after weather spotters reported a tornado spawned by this supercell located {{convert|7|mi|km}} southeast of [[Gage, Oklahoma|Gage]] in Ellis County.<ref>[http://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=TOROUN&e=201204150500 National Weather Service Raw Text Product]</ref> This high-end EF3 tornado later struck [[Woodward, Oklahoma]] at 12:20 am CDT (0520 UTC), killing six people. Multiple homes and businesses were destroyed in Woodward, and all fatalities occurred as a result of destroyed mobile homes.<ref name=\"Woodward 1\">{{cite news| url=https://www.usatoday.com/weather/storms/tornadoes/story/2012-04-15/tornadoes-midwest-storms/54290010/1?csp=34news | work=USA Today | title=Most Popular E-mail Newsletter | date=April 15, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Woodward 2\">http://newsok.com/injuries-reported-after-tornado-hits-woodward/article/3666724</ref> Additional weak tornadoes occurred on April 15 and 16 before the outbreak came to an end.<ref>https://apps.dat.noaa.gov/StormDamage/DamageViewer/</ref>\n\n==Tornadoes==\n{{main article|List of tornadoes in the tornado outbreak of April 13\u201316, 2012}}\n{{Tornado Chart\n|Total = 113\n|F0 = 68\n|F1 = 36\n|F2 = 3\n|F3 = 5\n|F4 = 1\n|F5 = 0\n|Enhanced=yes\n}}\n\n===April 13 event===\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible\" width=\"100%\"\n!colspan=\"7\"|List of reported tornadoes - Friday, April 13, 2012\n|-\n|<center>'''[[Enhanced Fujita scale|EF#]]'''</center> || <center>'''Location'''</center> || <center>'''County'''</center> || <center>'''Coord.'''</center> || <center>'''Time (UTC)'''</center> || <center>'''Path length'''</center> || <center>'''Comments/Damage'''</cen