oma|Mooreland]]'''\n|[[Woodward County, Oklahoma|Woodward]]\n|{{Coord|36.51|-98.99|name=Mooreland (Apr. 14, EF0)}}\n|2351\n|{{convert|0.2|mi|m|}}\n|A brief multiple-vortex tornado remained over open country, causing no damage.\n|-\n|bgcolor=#{{storm colour|storm}} | <big>'''EF0'''</big>\n|'''SSW of [[Waynoka, Oklahoma|Waynoka]]'''\n|[[Major County, Oklahoma|Major]]\n|{{Coord|36.46|-98.94|name=Waynoka (Apr. 14, EF0)}}\n|0001\n|{{convert|0.1|mi|m|}}\n|Brief tornado remained over open country, causing no damage.\n|-\n|bgcolor=#{{storm colour|cat1}} | <big>'''EF1'''</big>\n|'''S of [[Waynoka, Oklahoma|Waynoka]]'''\n|[[Major County, Oklahoma|Major]], [[Woods County, Oklahoma|Woods]]\n|{{Coord|36.49|-98.88|name=Waynoka (Apr. 14, EF1)}}\n|0006\n|{{convert|7.2|mi|km|}}\n|Equipment at an oil field was damaged by this tornado, causing a fire.\n|-\n|bgcolor=#{{storm colour|storm}} | <big>'''EF0'''</big>\n|'''SE of [[Waynoka, Oklahoma|Waynoka]]'''\n|[[Woods County, Oklahoma|Woods]]\n|{{Coord|36.55|-98.83|name=Waynoka (Apr. 14, EF0)}}\n|0019\n|{{convert|1|mi|km|}}\n|This tornado remained over open country, causing no damage.\n|-\n|bgcolor=#{{storm colour|storm}} | <big>'''EF0'''</big>\n|'''E of [[Waynoka, Oklahoma|Waynoka]] to NE of [[Hopeton, Oklahoma|Hopeton]]'''\n|[[Woods County, Oklahoma|Woods]]\n|{{Coord|36.59|-98.70|name=Hopeton (Apr. 14, EF0)}}\n|0030\n|{{convert|9|mi|km|}}\n|This tornado remained over open country, causing no damage.\n|-\n|bgcolor=#{{storm colour|cat1}} | <big>'''EF1'''</big>\n|'''W of [[Cherokee, Oklahoma|Cherokee]]'''\n|[[Alfalfa County, Oklahoma|Alfalfa]]\n|{{Coord|36.69|-98.52|name=Dacoma (Apr. 14, EF1)}}\n|0047\n|{{convert|10|mi|km|}}\n|This likely significant tornado was photographed and caught on video by many storm chasers, though it avoided well-built structures. Farm equipment, two metal barns, and some outbuildings were damaged or destroyed.\n|-\n|bgcolor=#{{storm colour|storm}} | <big>'''EF0'''</big>\n|'''NW of [[Cherokee, Oklahoma|Cherokee]] to NW of [[Amorita, Oklahoma|Amorita]]'''\n|[[Alfalfa County, Oklahoma|Alfalfa]]\n|{{Coord|36.78|-98.39|name=Amorita (Apr. 14, EF0)}}\n|0057\n|{{convert|12|mi|km|}}\n|This tornado occurred simultaneously with the previous tornado. Several trees and outbuildings were damaged.\n|-\n|bgcolor=#{{storm colour|cat1}} | <big>'''EF1'''</big>\n|'''E of [[Byron, Oklahoma|Byron]] to NE of [[Danville, Kansas|Danville, KS]]'''\n|[[Alfalfa County, Oklahoma|Alfalfa]], [[Grant County, Oklahoma|Grant]], [[Harper County, Kansas|Harper (KS)]]\n|{{Coord|36.90|-98.22|name=Byron (Apr. 14, EF1)}}\n|0119\n|{{convert|36.6|mi|km|}}\n|This large, long-tracked, and likely significant stovepipe tornado began in Oklahoma before crossing into Kansas, passing near the towns of [[Amorita, Oklahoma|Amorita]], [[Manchester, Oklahoma|Manchester]], [[Bluff City, Kansas|Bluff City]] and [[Anthony, Kansas|Anthony]]. Damage was limited to trees in Oklahoma, though farmsteads sustained considerable damage in Kansas. A small semi-truck at a farm was tossed 140 yards over a fence, and a nearby home had windows blown out and lost most of its roof shingles. A pickup truck and a tractor were moved as well. At a second farmstead, a house had one of its exterior garage walls blown out, broken windows, and sustained damage from a tree falling onto it. A second nearby home sustained partial roof removal, while a small airplane hangar, metal sheds, and a barn were also destroyed. At an abandoned farmstead, a home sustained major structural damage. Many trees were snapped or uprooted as well.\n|-\n|bgcolor=#{{storm colour|cat3}} | <big>'''EF3'''</big>\n|'''N of [[Arnett, Oklahoma|Arnett]] to NE of [[Woodward, Oklahoma|Woodward]]'''\n|[[Ellis County, Oklahoma|Ellis]], [[Woodward County, Oklahoma|Woodward]]\n|{{Coord|36.43|-99.39|name=Woodward (Apr. 14, EF3)}}\n|0442\n|{{convert|31|mi|km|}}\n|'''6 deaths'''&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[April 13\u201316, 2012 tornado outbreak#Woodward, Oklahoma tornado|See section on this tornado]]