multinational [[Investment banking|investment bank]]<!-- Its investment banking arm is a separate institution to its financial services. They are separate components that add up to the diversified services of the company. Leave as \"investment bank and financial services company\".--> and [[financial services]] company headquartered in [[New York City]]. It offers services in [[investment management]], securities, [[asset management]], [[prime brokerage]], and [[securities underwriting]].\n\nThe bank is one of the [[List of investment banks|largest investment banking enterprises]] in the world,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statista.com/statistics/371143/leading-global-investment-banks-by-revenue/|title=Top investment banks 2017|website=Statista|language=en|access-date=March 29, 2018}}</ref> and is a [[primary dealer]] in the [[United States Treasury security]] market and more generally, a prominent [[market maker]]. The group also owns Goldman Sachs Bank USA, a [[direct bank]]. Goldman Sachs was founded in 1869 and is headquartered at [[200 West Street]] in [[Lower Manhattan]] with additional offices in other international financial centers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goldmansachs.com/our-firm/locations.html|title=Goldman Sachs - Our Firm|website=Goldman Sachs|access-date=May 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAs a result of its involvement in securitization during the [[subprime mortgage crisis]], Goldman Sachs suffered during the [[financial crisis of 2007\u20132008]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/freeexchange/2009/07/like_everyone_else_goldman_was | title=Like everyone else, Goldman was in trouble | website=The Economist | date=July 28, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/politics-government/article24561376.html | title=How Goldman secretly bet on the U.S. housing crash | publisher=McClatchy |date=November 1, 2009}}</ref> and received a $10 billion investment from the [[United States Department of the Treasury]] as part of the [[Troubled Asset Relief Program]], a financial [[bailout]] created by the [[Emergency Economic Stabilization Act of 2008]]. The investment was made in November 2008 and was repaid in June 2009.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/money/economy/2009-04-14-tarp-repay-bank-bailout_N.htm | title=Goldman Sachs to return $10B of bailout money | newspaper=[[USA Today]] | date=April 15, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2009June17\">{{cite news|title=JPMorgan and 9 Other Banks Repay TARP Money|url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2009/06/17/jpmorgan-repays-treasury-as-tarp-exits-continue/|accessdate=March 19, 2017|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=DealBook|work=New York Times|date=June 17, 2009|location=United States|language=English|url-access=limited}}</ref>\n\n[[list of former employees of Goldman Sachs|Former employees of Goldman Sachs]] have moved on to government positions. Notable examples includes former U.S. Secretaries of the Treasury [[Robert Rubin]] and [[Henry Paulson]]; current United States Secretary of the Treasury [[Steven Mnuchin]]; former Under Secretary of State [[John C. Whitehead]]; former chief economic advisor [[Gary Cohn (investment banker)|Gary Cohn]]; [[United States Senate|United States Senator]] and former [[Governor of New Jersey]] [[Jon Corzine]]; former Prime Minister of Italy [[Mario Monti]]; European Central Bank President [[Mario Draghi]]; former Bank of Canada Governor and current Governor of the Bank of England [[Mark Carney]]; and the former Prime Minister of Australia [[Malcolm Turnbull]]. In addition, former Goldman employees have headed the [[New York Stock Exchange]], the [[World Bank]], and competing banks such as [[Citigroup]] and [[Merrill Lynch]].\n\nThe company is ranked 62nd on the [[Fortune 500]] list of the largest United States corporations by total revenue.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://fortune.com/fortune500/goldman-sachs-group/ | title=Fortune 500 Companies: Goldman Sachs | publisher=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Founding and establishment ===\n{{See also|Goldman\u2013Sachs family}}\nGoldman Sachs was founded in [[New York City|New York]] in 1869 by [[Marcus Goldman]].<ref>{{cite news | first=Leah Nathans | last=Spiro | first2=Stanley | last2=Reed | title=Inside the Money Machine-In a big-is-all business, Goldman vows to go it alone | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/1997-12-21/inside-the-money-machine | publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]] | date=December 22, 1997}}</ref> In 1882, Goldman's son-in-law [[Samuel Sachs]] joined the firm.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,770464,00.html | title=Business & Finance: Cash & Comeback | work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] | date=November 9, 1936 |url-access=subscription }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/2010/05/21/goldman-sachs-fraud-case-personal-finance-gs.html#1b2ef41476b3|title=The Evolution Of Goldman Sachs|last=Beattie|first=Andrew|date=|website=Forbes|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref> In 1885, Goldman took his son Henry and his son-in-law Ludwig Dreyfuss into the business and the firm adopted its present name, Goldman Sachs & Co.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Endlich|first=Lisa|authorlink=Lisa Endlich|title=Goldman Sachs: The Culture Of Success|publisher=[[A.A. Knopf]]|location=New York|year=1999|isbn=978-0-679-45080-1|page=[https://archive.org/details/goldmansachscult00endl/page/34 34]|url=https://archive.org/details/goldmansachscult00endl/page/34}}</ref> The company pioneered the use of [[commercial paper]] for entrepreneurs and joined the [[New York Stock Exchange]] (NYSE) in 1896.<ref name=\"Cohan2012\">{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=91XpjbCqbbcC | author=William D. Cohan | title=Money and Power: How Goldman Sachs Came to Rule the World | year=2012 | publisher=[[Penguin Random House]]| isbn=978-0-241-95406-5}}</ref> By 1898, the firm's capital stood at $1.6 million.<ref name=\"Cohan2012\"/>\n\nGoldman entered the [[initial public offering]] market in 1906 when it took [[Sears, Roebuck and Company]] public.<ref name=\"Cohan2012\"/> The deal was facilitated by Henry Goldman's personal friendship with  [[Julius Rosenwald]], an owner of Sears.<ref name=\"Cohan2012\" /> Other IPOs followed, including [[F. W. Woolworth Company|F. W. Woolworth]] and [[Continental Can]].<ref name=\"Cohan2012\"/> In 1912, Henry S. Bowers became the first non-member of the founding family to become a partner of the company and share in its profits.<ref name=\"Cohan2012\" />\n\nIn 1917, under growing pressure from the other partners in the firm due to his pro-German stance, Henry Goldman resigned.<ref name=\"Cohan2012\" /> The Sachs family gained full control of the firm until [[Waddill Catchings]] joined the company in 1918.<ref name=\"Cohan2012\" /> By 1928, Catchings was the Goldman partner with the single largest stake in the firm.<ref name=\"Cohan2012\" />\n\nOn December 4, 1928, the firm launched the Goldman Sachs Trading Corp, a [[closed-end fund]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/photo-essays/2011-07-20/goldman-sachs-the-good-the-bad-and-the-ugly|title=Goldman Sachs, the Good, the Bad, and the Ugly|date=July 20, 2011|work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=August 1, 2017}}</ref> The fund failed during the [[Stock Market Crash of 1929]], amid accusations that Goldman had engaged in share price manipulation and [[insider trading]].<ref name=\"Cohan2012\"/>\n\n===Mid-20th century===\nIn 1930, the firm ousted Catchings, and [[Sidney Weinberg]] assumed the role of senior partner and shifted Goldman's focus away from trading and toward [[investment banking]].<ref name=\"Cohan2012\"/> Weinberg's actions helped to restore some of Goldman's tarnished reputation. Under Weinberg's leadership, Goldman was lead advisor on the [[Ford Motor Company]]'s IPO in 1956, a major coup on Wall Street at the time. Under Weinberg's reign, the firm started an investment research division and a [[municipal bond]] department, and it became an early innovator in [[risk arbitrage]].<ref name=\"Cohan2012\" />\n\nIn the 1950's, [[Gus Levy]] joined the firm as a securities trader, where two powers fought for supremacy, one from investment banking and one from securities trading. Levy was a pioneer in [[block trade|block trading]] and the firm established this trend under his guidance. Due to Weinberg's heavy influence, the firm formed an investment banking division in 1956 in an attempt to shift focus off Weinberg.<ref name=\"Cohan2012\" />\n\nIn 1969, Levy took over Weinberg's role as Senior Partner and built Goldman's trading franchise once again.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Endlich|first=Lisa|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BDionNrrBqwC&pg=PA62&lpg=PA62&dq=In+1969,+Levy+took+over+as+Weinberg%E2%80%99s+role+as+Senior+Partner&source=bl&ots=W6jSFlxB2k&sig=ACfU3U3RX0WHpa4kVnPTaB-yIis6FN5Udg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiA_Zr6i7bnAhVDGM0KHaTvAL4Q6AEwC3oECDUQAQ#v=snippet&q=1969%20levy&f=false|title=Goldman Sachs: The Culture Of Success|date=2000-03-09|publisher=Simon and Schuster|year=|isbn=978-0-684-86968-1|location=|pages=62|language=en}}</ref> Levy is credited with Goldman's famous philosophy of being \"long-term greedy,\" which implied that as long as money is made over the long term, short-term losses are bearable. At the same time, partners reinvested nearly all of their earnings in the firm.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Endlich|first=Lisa|authorlink=Lisa Endlich|title=Goldman Sachs: The Culture Of Success|publisher=[[A.A. Knopf]]|location=New York|year=1999|isbn=978-0-679-45080-1|page=[https://archive.org/details/goldmansachscult00endl/page/18 18]|url=https://archive.org/details/goldmansachscult00endl/page/18}}</ref> That same year, Weinberg retired from the firm.{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\nAnother financial crisis for the firm occurred in 1970, when the [[Penn Central Transportation Company]] went bankrupt with over $80 million in [[commercial paper]] outstanding, most of it issued through Goldman Sachs. The bankruptcy was large, and the resulting lawsuits, notably by the [[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission|SEC]], threatened the partnership capital, life, and reputation of the firm.<ref name=\"cohan_wpost2012\">{{cite news\n| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/goldman-sachss-long-history-of-duping-its-clients/2012/03/15/gIQAVlu3GS_story.html | title=Goldman Sachs's long history of duping its clients | last=Cohan |first=William D. | work=[[Washington Post]] | date=March 16, 2012}}</ref> It was this bankruptcy that resulted in [[credit rating]]s for every issuer of commercial paper today by several credit rating services.<ref>{{cite web | last=Hahn | first=Thomas K. | editor=Timothy Q. Cook |editor2=Robert K. Laroche | title=Instruments of the Money Market | url=https://www.richmondfed.org/~/media/richmondfedorg/publications/research/special_reports/instruments_of_the_money_market/pdf/full_publication.pdf | edition=Seventh | publisher=Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond | location=[[Richmond, Virginia]] | year=1993}}</ref>\n\nUnder the direction of Senior Partner Stanley R. Miller, the firm opened its first international office in London in 1970 and created a [[Private Wealth Management|private wealth]] division along with a [[fixed income]] division in 1972.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Colchester|first=Max|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/who-loses-the-most-from-brexit-try-goldman-sachs-1460403274|title=Who Loses the Most From \u2018Brexit\u2019? Try Goldman Sachs|date=2016-04-11|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2020-02-12|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref>{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}} It pioneered the \"[[white knight (business)|white knight]]\" strategy in 1974 during its attempts to defend Electric Storage Battery against a [[hostile takeover]] bid from International Nickel and Goldman's rival, [[Morgan Stanley]].<ref>{{cite book | first=Gary | last=Giroux |title=Accounting Fraud: Maneuvering and Manipulation, Past and Present | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gxNMAgAAQBAJ | publisher=Business Expert Press |date=December 9, 2013| isbn=9781606496299 }}</ref>{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}} This action improved the firm's reputation as an [[investment advisor]] because it pledged to no longer participate in hostile takeovers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thisismoney.co.uk/money/news/article-1681590/Goldman-Sachs-Life-and-times-of-Golden-Sacks.html|title=Goldman Sachs: Life and times of 'Golden Sacks'|last=Daily|website=This is Money|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref> [[John Weinberg|John L. Weinberg]] (the son of Sidney Weinberg), and [[John C. Whitehead]] assumed roles of co-senior partners in 1976, once again emphasizing the co-leadership at the firm. One of their initiatives was the establishment of 14 business principles that the firm still claims to apply.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Jr|first=Landon Thomas|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/08/09/business/09weinberg.html|title=John L. Weinberg, 81, Former Leader of Goldman, Dies|date=2006-08-09|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-12|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n===Late 20th century===\nOn November 16, 1981, the firm acquired J. Aron & Company, a [[commodities trading]] firm which merged with the Fixed Income division to become known as Fixed Income, Currencies, and Commodities. J. Aron was a player in the coffee and gold markets, and the former CEO of Goldman, [[Lloyd Blankfein]], joined the firm as a result of this merger. In 1985 it underwrote the public offering of the [[real estate investment trust]] that owned [[Rockefeller Center]], then the largest [[Real estate investment trust|REIT]] offering in history. In accordance with the beginning of the [[dissolution of the Soviet Union]], the firm also became involved in facilitating the global privatization movement by advising companies that were spinning off from their parent governments.\n\nIn 1986, the firm formed Goldman Sachs Asset Management, which manages the majority of its mutual funds and [[hedge fund]]s today. In the same year, the firm also underwrote the IPO of [[Microsoft]], advised [[GE|General Electric]] on its acquisition of [[RCA]] and joined the [[London Stock Exchange|London]] and [[Tokyo stock exchange]]s. 1986 also was the year when Goldman became the first United States bank to rank in the top 10 of [[mergers and acquisitions]] in the United Kingdom. During the 1980s the firm became the first bank to distribute its investment research electronically and created the first public offering of original issue deep-discount [[bond (finance)|bond]].\n\n[[Robert Rubin]] and [[Stephen Friedman (PFIAB)|Stephen Friedman]] assumed the Co-Senior Partnership in 1990 and pledged to focus on globalization of the firm and strengthening the Merger & Acquisition and Trading business lines. During their reign, the firm introduced paperless trading to the New York Stock Exchange and lead-managed the first-ever global [[Corporate bond|debt offering]] by a U.S. corporation. It also launched the [[Goldman Sachs Commodity Index]] (GSCI) and opened a Beijing office in 1994. Also in 1994, [[Jon Corzine]] assumed leadership of the firm as CEO, following the departure of Rubin and Friedman.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes1994September14RamirezAnthony\">{{cite news|last1=Ramirez|first1=Anthony|title=Chairman of Goldman Will Retire|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/09/14/business/chairman-of-goldman-will-retire.html|accessdate=May 9, 2017|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=Business|page=D1|work=New York Times|date=September 14, 1994|location=United States|language=English|url-access=limited}}</ref> Rubin drew criticism in Congress for using a Treasury Department account under his personal control to distribute $20 billion to bail out Mexican bonds, of which Goldman was a key distributor.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes1995March2BradsherKeith\">{{cite news|last1=Bradsher|first1=Keith|title=House Votes to Request Clinton Data on Mexico|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/03/02/business/house-votes-to-request-clinton-data-on-mexico.html|accessdate=June 7, 2010|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=Business|page=D2|work=New York Times|date=March 2, 1995|location=United States|language=English|url-access=limited}}</ref> On November 22, 1994, the Mexican Bolsa stock market had admitted Goldman Sachs and one other firm to operate on that market.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes1994November22\">{{cite news|title=Bolsa Admits 2 Foreign Firms|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/11/22/business/bolsa-admits-2-foreign-firms.html|accessdate=June 7, 2010|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=Associated Press/Business|page=D9|work=New York Times|date=November 22, 1994|location=United States|language=English|url-access=limited}}</ref> The [[1994 economic crisis in Mexico]] threatened to wipe out the value of Mexico's bonds held by Goldman Sachs.\n\nIn 1994, Goldman financed [[Rockefeller Center]] in a deal that allowed it to take an ownership interest<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes1994November18HansellSaul\">{{cite news|last1=Hansell|first1=Saul|title=Loan Arranged at Rockefeller Center|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/11/18/business/loan-arranged-at-rockefeller-center.html|accessdate=May 9, 2017|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=Business|page=D7|work=New York Times|date=November 18, 1994|location=United States|language=English|url-access=limited}}</ref> in 1996, and sold Rockefeller Center to [[Tishman Speyer]] in 2000.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://money.cnn.com/2000/12/22/deals/rockefellercenter/ | title=Rockefeller Center sold | work=[[CNN Money]] | date=December 22, 2000}}</ref> In April 1996, Goldman was lead underwriter of the [[Yahoo!]] IPO.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes1996April6\">{{cite news|title=Yahoo! Offering Is Set for Today|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/04/12/business/yahoo-offering-is-set-for-today.html|accessdate=December 6, 2019|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=Business|page=D7|work=New York Times|date=April 6, 1996|location=United States|language=English|url-access=limited}}</ref> In 1998 it was the co-lead manager of the 2 trillion yen [[NTT DoCoMo]] IPO.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/business/1998/10/20/japans-34000-per-share-question/f3b0cb5c-59bd-4180-9744-473190e01fd5/ | title=JAPAN'S $34,000-PER-SHARE QUESTION | first=Sandra | last=Sugawara | work=[[Washington Post]] | date=December 22, 2000}}</ref> In 1999, Goldman acquired [[Hull Trading Company]], one of the world's premier market-making firms, for $531 million.<ref>{{Cite news | url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1999-07-13/business/9907130269_1_hull-group-madoff-securities-stock-trading-system | title=Goldman Sachs Buys Hull Group | first=Greg | last=Burns | work=[[Chicago Tribune]] | date=July 13, 1999}}</ref><ref name=\"NewYorkTimes1999July13KahnJoseph\">{{cite news|last1=Kahn|first1=Joseph|title=Goldman Sachs to Acquire Electronic Trading Concern|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/07/13/business/goldman-sachs-to-acquire-electronic-trading-concern.html|accessdate=April 7, 2017|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=Business|page=C6|work=New York Times|date=July 13, 1999|location=United States|language=English|url-access=limited}}</ref> After decades of debate among the partners, the company became a [[public company]] via an [[initial public offering]] in May 1999.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/1999/05/04/goldman-sachs-ipo-debuts-today-at-3-66b/|title=GOLDMAN SACHS IPO DEBUTS TODAY AT $3.66B|last=Piskora|first=Beth|date=1999-05-04|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref> Goldman sold 12.6% of the company to the public, and, after the IPO, 48.3% of the company was held by the 221 former partners, 21.2% of the company was held by non-partner employees, and the remaining 17.9% was held by retired Goldman partners and two long-time investors, [[Sumitomo Bank Ltd.]] and Assn, the investing arm of [[Kamehameha Schools]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/1999-05-16/goldman-sachs-how-public-is-this-ipo | title=Goldman Sachs: How Public Is This IPO? | first=Leah Nathans | last=Spiro | publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]] | date=May 17, 1999}}</ref> The shares were priced at $53 each and, after the IPO, Henry Paulson became Chairman and Chief Executive Officer, succeeding Jon Corzine.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://money.cnn.com/1999/05/03/markets/goldman/ | title=End of an era for Goldman | publisher=[[CNN Money]] | date=May 3, 1999}}</ref>\n\n===21st century===\nGoldman Sachs purchased Spear, Leeds, & Kellogg, one of the largest specialist firms on the New York Stock Exchange, for $6.3 billion in September 2000.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2000September12McGeehanPatrick\">{{cite news|last1=McGeehan|first1=Patrick|title=Goldman Sachs to Acquire Top Firm on Trading Floors|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/09/12/business/goldman-sachs-to-acquire-top-firm-on-trading-floors.html|accessdate=May 18, 2017|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=Business|page=C2|work=New York Times|date=September 12, 2000|location=United States|language=English|url-access=limited}}</ref> In January 2000, Goldman, along with [[Lehman Brothers]], was the lead manager for the first internet bond offering for the [[World Bank]].<ref>{{cite press release | url=http://treasury.worldbank.org/cmd/htm/InauguralInternetBond.html | title=The World Bank's First Internet Bond-From concept to reality | publisher=[[The World Bank]] | date=January 25, 2000}}</ref> In March 2003, the firm took a 45% stake in a joint venture with JBWere, the Australian investment bank.<ref>{{cite press release | title=GOLDMAN SACHS AND JBWERE AGREE ON AUSTRALIAN / NZ MERGER | url=http://www.goldmansachs.com/media-relations/press-releases/archived/2003/2003-03-26.html | publisher=Goldman Sachs | date=March 27, 2003}}</ref> In April 2003, Goldman acquired The Ayco Company L.P., a fee-based financial counseling service.<ref>{{Cite press release|url=https://www.goldmansachs.com/media-relations/press-releases/archived/2003/2003-04-15.html|title=Goldman Sachs to Acquire Ayco|website=Goldman Sachs|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-13}}</ref> In December 2005, four years after its report on the emerging \"[[BRIC]]\" economies (Brazil, Russia, India, and China), Goldman Sachs named its \"[[Jim O'Neill, Baron O'Neill of Gatley#Next Eleven|Next Eleven]]\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.goldmansachs.com/hkchina/insight/research/pdf/BRICs_3_12-1-05.pdf |title=Goldman Sachs Paper No.134 Relevant Emerging Markets |publisher=.goldmansachs.com |accessdate=November 2, 2011}}</ref> list of countries, using macroeconomic stability, political maturity, openness of trade and investment policies and quality of education as criteria: [[Bangladesh]], [[Egypt]], [[Indonesia]], [[Iran]], [[Mexico]], [[Nigeria]], [[Pakistan]], the [[Philippines]], [[Turkey]], [[South Korea]] and [[Vietnam]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Jasim Uddin|last=Khan|title=Bangladesh on Goldman Sachs 'Next Eleven' list|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/2005/12/15/d5121501107.htm|work=The Daily Star|date=December 15, 2005|accessdate=January 17, 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2006, Paulson left the firm to serve as [[United States Secretary of the Treasury]], and [[Lloyd C. Blankfein]] was promoted to Chairman and Chief Executive Officer. In January 2007, Goldman, along with [[CanWest Global Communications]], acquired [[Alliance Atlantis]], the company with the broadcast rights to the [[CSI (franchise)|CSI franchise]].\n\nOn September 10, 2018, Goldman Sachs acquired Boyd Corporation for a Leveraged Buyout of [[United States dollar|$]]3 billion.\n\nOn May 16, 2019, Goldman Sachs acquired [[United Capital]] Financial Advisers, LLC for $750 million cash.{{cn|date=November 2019}}\n\nGoldman Sachs will, among others, rely on CoreCard, a card management software owned by the Fintech company Intelligent Systems Corporation.<ref>{{cite news | title=Goldman Sachs will rely on CoreCard, a card management software owned by the Fintech company Intelligent Systems Corporation.| url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-03-11/goldman-s-apple-card-said-to-land-big-win-for-tiny-georgia-firm | first=Anders| last=Melin  | agency=[[Bloomberg News|Bloomberg]] | publisher=[[Technology]] | date=Mar 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Subprime mortgage crisis: 2007\u20132008 ===\nDuring the 2007 [[subprime mortgage crisis]], Goldman profited from the collapse in subprime mortgage bonds in summer 2007 by [[short (finance)|short-selling]] subprime [[Mortgage-backed security|mortgage-backed securities]]. Two Goldman traders, Michael Swenson and [[Josh Birnbaum]], are credited with being responsible for the firm's large profits during the crisis.<ref name=\"FinancialTimes2010December10AllowayTracy\">{{cite news|last1=Alloway|first1=Tracy|title=Goldman's uneasy subprime short|url=https://ftalphaville.ft.com/2010/12/10/433571/goldmans-uneasy-subprime-short/|accessdate=June 3, 2012|agency=Nikkei|issue=Alphaville|publisher=Financial Times|date=December 10, 2010|language=English|url-access=subscription }}</ref><ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/banksandfinance/2788346/Subprime-star-Josh-Birnbaum-leaves-Goldman.html Subprime star Josh Birnbaum leaves Goldman. ''The Telegraph''.]</ref> The pair, members of Goldman's [[structured product]]s group in [[New York City]], made a profit of $4 billion by \"betting\" on a collapse in the subprime market and shorting mortgage-related securities. By summer 2007, they persuaded colleagues to see their point of view and convinced skeptical risk management executives.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2007/dec/21/goldmansachs.useconomy |title=Success shines unwelcome spotlight on to Goldman Sachs|work=The Guardian |date=December 21, 2007 |location=London |first=Andrew |last=Clark |access-date=September 12, 2013}}</ref> The firm initially avoided large subprime write-downs and achieved a net profit due to significant losses on non-prime [[securitization|securitized]] loans being offset by gains on short mortgage positions. The firm's viability was later called into question as the crisis intensified in September 2008.\n\nOn October 15, 2007, as the crisis had begun to unravel, [[Allan Sloan]], a senior editor for ''[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]'' magazine, wrote:<ref>{{cite news | url=http://fortune.com/2016/04/12/goldman-sachs-house-of-junk-mortgage-bonds/ | title=Goldman Sachs' House of Junk | first=Allan | last=Sloan | authorlink=Allan Sloan | publisher=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]] | date=October 16, 2007 }}</ref>\n<blockquote>So let's reduce this macro story to human scale. Meet GSAMP Trust 2006-S3, a $494 million drop in the junk-mortgage bucket, part of the more than half-a-trillion dollars of mortgage-backed securities issued last year. We found this issue by asking mortgage mavens to pick the worst deal they knew of that had been floated by a top-tier firm - and this one's pretty bad.\nIt was sold by Goldman Sachs - GSAMP originally stood for Goldman Sachs Alternative Mortgage Products but now has become a name itself, like [[AT&T Inc.|AT&T]] and [[3M]].\nThis issue, which is backed by ultra-risky second-mortgage loans, contains all the elements that facilitated the housing bubble and bust. It's got speculators searching for quick gains in hot housing markets; it's got loans that seem to have been made with little or no serious analysis by lenders; and finally, it's got Wall Street, which churned out mortgage \"product\" because buyers wanted it. As they say on the Street, \"When the ducks quack, feed them.\"</blockquote>\n\nOn September 21, 2008, Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley, the last two major investment banks in the United States, both confirmed that they would become traditional [[bank holding company|bank holding companies]].<ref name=\"Reuters2008September21HallJessica\">{{cite news|last1=Hall|first1=Jessica|last2=Heavens|first2=Louise|title=Goldman Sachs to be regulated by Fed|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-goldmansachs-idUSNWEN838420080922|accessdate=September 22, 2008|agency=Thompson Reuters|issue=Fund News|publisher=Reuters|date=September 21, 2008|location=Philadelphia, PA, United States|language=English}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2008/sep/22/wallstreet.morganstanley | title=Wall Street in crisis: Mitsubishi to buy stake in Morgan Stanley | first1=Julia | last1=Kollewe | first2=David | last2=Teather | publisher=[[The Guardian]] | date=September 22, 2008}}</ref> The Federal Reserve's approval of their bid to become banks ended the business model of an independent securities firm, 75 years after Congress separated them from deposit-taking lenders, and capped weeks of chaos that sent [[Lehman Brothers]] into bankruptcy and led to the rushed sale of [[Merrill Lynch]] to [[Bank of America Corp.]]<ref name=\"WSJ2008September22HilsenrathJon\">{{cite news|last1=Hilsenrath|first1=Jon|last2=Paletta|first2=Damian|title=Goldman, Morgan Scrap Wall Street Model, Become Banks in Bid to Ride Out Crisis|journal=The Wall Street Journal. Eastern Edition|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB122202739111460721|accessdate=May 18, 2017|agency=Dow Jones & Company Inc|issue=Business|publisher=Wall Street Journal|date=September 22, 2008|location=United States|language=English|url-access=subscription|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> On September 23, 2008, [[Berkshire Hathaway]] agreed to purchase $5 billion in Goldman's preferred stock, and also received [[Warrant (finance)|warrants]] to buy another $5 billion in Goldman's [[common stock]] within five years.<ref name=\"5billion\">{{cite web | url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/886982/000095012308011720/y71480exv3w1.htm | title=Berkshire Hathaway to Invest $5 billion in Goldman Sachs | publisher=[[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]] | date=September 23, 2008}}</ref> The company also raised $5 billion via a public offering of shares at $123 per share.<ref name=\"5billion\" /> Goldman also received a $10 billion [[preferred stock]] investment from the [[U.S. Treasury]] in October 2008, as part of the [[Troubled Asset Relief Program]] (TARP).<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/10/15/AR2007101501435.html | work=The Washington Post | title=An Unsavory Slice of Subprime | first=Allan | last=Sloan | date=October 16, 2007 | access-date=May 3, 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[Andrew Cuomo]], then [[New York Attorney General]], questioned Goldman's decision to pay 953 employees bonuses of at least $1 million each after it received TARP funds in 2008.<ref name=\"WSJ2009July30GrocerStephen\">{{cite news|last1=Grocer|first1=Stephen|title=Wall Street Compensation\u2013'No Clear Rhyme or Reason'|journal=The Wall Street Journal. Eastern Edition|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/deals/2009/07/30/wall-street-compensation-no-clear-rhyme-or-reason/|accessdate=May 31, 2017|agency=Dow Jones & Company Inc|issue=Blogs|publisher=Wall Street Journal|date=July 30, 2009|location=United States|language=English|url-access=subscription|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> In that same period, however, CEO Lloyd Blankfein and six other senior executives opted to forgo bonuses, stating they believed it was the right thing to do, in light of \"the fact that we are part of an industry that's directly associated with the ongoing economic distress\".<ref name=\"Reuters2008November16GiannoneJoseph\">{{cite news|last1=Giannone|first1=Joseph|last2=Bansal|first2=Paritosh|title=Goldman CEO, 6 others forgo 2008 bonuses|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-goldmansachs-bonus-idUSTRE4AF2KV20081117|accessdate=May 18, 2017|agency=Thompson Reuters|issue=Business News|publisher=Reuters|date=November 16, 2008|location=New York, N.Y., United States|language=English}}</ref> Cuomo called the move \"appropriate and prudent\", and urged the executives of other banks to follow the firm's lead and refuse bonus payments.<ref name=\"Reuters2008November16GiannoneJoseph\" /> In June 2009, Goldman Sachs repaid the U.S. Treasury's TARP investment, with 23% interest (in the form of $318 million in [[preferred stock|preferred dividend]] payments and $1.418 billion in warrant redemptions).<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20090722005842/en/Goldman-Sachs-Pays-1.1-Billion-Redeem-TARP|title=Goldman Sachs Pays $1.1 Billion to Redeem TARP Warrants: US Taxpayers Make 23 Percent Return|publisher=[[Business Wire]]|date=July 22, 2009}}<br />{{cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/id/32085262|title=Goldman Sachs Pays $1.1 Billion to Redeem Warrants|publisher=[[CNBC]]|date=July 22, 2009}}</ref> On March 18, 2011, Goldman Sachs acquired [[Federal Reserve]] approval to buy back Berkshire's preferred stock in Goldman.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/id/42153208 |title=Warren Buffett Gets an Unwanted Call from Goldman Sachs|work=CNBC|date=March 18, 2011|access-date=February 15, 2013|first1=Alex|last1=Crippe}}</ref> In December 2009, Goldman announced that its top 30 executives would be paid year-end bonuses in restricted stock that they cannot sell for five years, with [[clawback]] provisions.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://usatoday30.usatoday.com/MONEY/usaedition/2009-12-10-goldman-execs_NU.htm | title=Goldman Sachs gives top execs bonuses in stock | agency=[[Bloomberg News]] | publisher=[[USA Today]] | date=December 10, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"WSJ2010January10CraigSusanne\">{{cite news|last1=Craig|first1=Susanne|last2=Enrich|first2=David|title=Banks Brace for Bonus Fury|journal=The Wall Street Journal. Eastern Edition|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB126317064618124057|accessdate=January 13, 2010|agency=Dow Jones & Company Inc|issue=Management|publisher=Wall Street Journal|date=January 10, 2010|location=United States|language=English|url-access=subscription|issn=0099-9660}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 2008 financial crisis, the [[Federal Reserve]] introduced a number of short-term credit and liquidity facilities to help stabilize markets. Some of the transactions under these facilities provided liquidity to institutions whose disorderly failure could have severely stressed an already fragile financial system.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.federalreserve.gov/newsevents/press/monetary/20101201a.htm |title=\"FRB: Press Release - Federal Reserve releases detailed information about transactions conducted to stabilize markets during the recent financial crisis\". Federal Reserve. December 1, 2010 |publisher=Federalreserve.gov |access-date=November 2, 2011}}</ref> Goldman Sachs was one of the heaviest users of these loan facilities, taking out many loans between March 18, 2008, and April 22, 2009. The [[Primary Dealer Credit Facility]] (PDCF), the first Fed facility ever to provide overnight loans to investment banks, loaned Goldman Sachs a total of $589 billion against collateral such as corporate market instruments and [[Mortgage-backed security|mortgage-backed securities]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.federalreserve.gov/newsevents/reform_pdcf.htm |title=\"Primary Dealer Credit Facility (PDCF)\". Federal Reserve. Retrieved December 3, 2010 |publisher=Federalreserve.gov |access-date=November 2, 2011}}</ref> The [[Term Securities Lending Facility]] (TSLF), which allows primary dealers to borrow liquid Treasury securities for one month in exchange for less liquid collateral, loaned Goldman Sachs a total of $193 billion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.federalreserve.gov/newsevents/reform_tslf.htm |title=Term Securities Lending Facility (TSLF) and TSLF Options Program (TOP)|publisher=FederalReserve.gov |access-date=November 2, 2011}}</ref> Goldman Sachs's borrowings totaled $782 billion in hundreds of revolving transactions over these months.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.federalreserve.gov/newsevents/reform_transaction.htm |title=FRB: Regulatory Reform: Transaction Data|publisher=FederalReserve.gov |date=October 11, 2011 |access-date=November 2, 2011}}</ref> The loans were fully repaid in accordance with the terms of the facilities.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.marketwatch.com/story/jp-morgan-goldman-sachs-other-banks-repay-tarp | title=J.P. Morgan, Goldman Sachs, other banks repay TARP | first=ALISTAIR | last=BARR | work=[[MarketWatch]] | date=June 17, 2009}}</ref>\n\n=== Reemergence: 2008\u2013present ===\nAccording to a 2009 BrandAsset Valuator survey taken of 17,000 people nationwide, the firm's reputation suffered in 2008 and 2009, and rival Morgan Stanley was respected more than Goldman Sachs, a reversal of the sentiment in 2006. Goldman refused to comment on the findings.<ref name=\"FinancialTimes2009August2FarrellGreg\">{{cite news|last1=Farrell|first1=Greg|title=Goldman Sachs' reputation tarnished|url=https://www.ft.com/content/ae3d459a-7f8e-11de-85dc-00144feabdc0|accessdate=August 24, 2009|agency=Nikkei|issue=Banks|publisher=Financial Times|date=August 2, 2009|location=New York, N.Y., United States|language=English|url-access=subscription}}</ref> In 2011, Goldman took full control of JBWere in a $1 billion buyout.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/business/goldman-sachs-takes-full-control-in-1bn-buyout/news-story/f790b0a14a6ed33018b1110a7418eb68 | title=Goldman Sachs takes full control in $1bn buyout | first1=JAMES | last1=CHESSELL | first2=NABILA | last2=AHMED | work=[[The Australian]] | date=April 8, 2011}}</ref> In 2011, Goldman Sachs shut down the Global Alpha fund, once the firm's largest hedge funds. The announcement followed a reported decline in fund balances to less than $1.7 billion in June 2011 from $11 billion in 2007. The decline was caused by investors withdrawing from the fund following earlier substantial market losses.<ref name=\"Reuters2011September16LaCapraLaurenTara\">{{cite news|last1=LaCapra|first1=LaurenTara|last2=Herbst-Bayliss|first2=Svea|title=Goldman to close Global Alpha fund after losses|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-goldmansachs-hedgefund-idUSTRE78F28Y20110916|accessdate=May 18, 2017|agency=Thompson Reuters|publisher=Reuters|date=September 16, 2011|location=New York, N.Y., United States|language=English}}</ref><ref name=\"WSJ2011September16RappaportLiz\">{{cite news|last1=Rappaport|first1=Liz|title=Goldman to Close Global Alpha Hedge Fund|journal=The Wall Street Journal. Eastern Edition|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424053111904060604576573053089881550|accessdate=May 18, 2017|agency=Dow Jones & Company Inc|issue=Markets|publisher=Wall Street Journal|date=September 16, 2011|location=United States|language=English|url-access=subscription|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> Global Alpha was at one point one of the largest hedge funds in the world, with over $12 billion under management.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.cnbc.com/id/44549144 | title=How Goldman Sachs Lost One Of Its Crown Jewels, Global Alpha | first=John | last=Carney | work=[[CNBC]] | date=September 16, 2011}}</ref> It was started in 1995 with $10 million.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2011September15\">{{cite news|title=Goldman Sachs to Shut Its Global Alpha Hedge Fund|url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2011/09/15/goldman-to-shut-global-alpha-hedge-fund/|accessdate=May 18, 2017|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=DealBook|work=New York Times|date=September 15, 2011|location=United States|language=English|url-access=limited}}</ref> In September 2013, Goldman Sachs Asset Management announced it had entered into an agreement with Deutsche Asset & Wealth Management to acquire its stable value business, with total assets under supervision of $21.6 billion {{as of|2013|June|30|lc=y|df=US}}.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.marketwatch.com/story/goldman-sachs-asset-management-to-acquire-stable-value-business-from-deutsche-asset-wealth-management-2013-09-25 | title=Goldman Sachs Asset Management to Acquire Stable Value Business from Deutsche Asset & Wealth Management | work=[[MarketWatch]] | date=September 25, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2013, together with [[Deutsche Bank]], Goldman led a $17 billion bond offering by [[Apple Inc.]], the largest corporate-bond deal in history<ref name=\"WSJ2013April30BurneKaty\">{{cite news|last1=Burne|first1=Katy|last2=Cherney|first2=Mike|title=Apple's Record Plunge Into Debt Pool|journal=The Wall Street Journal. Eastern Edition|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887324482504578454691936382274|accessdate=April 7, 2014|agency=Dow Jones & Company Inc|issue=Markets|publisher=Wall Street Journal|date=April 30, 2013|location=United States|language=English|url-access=subscription|issn=0099-9660}}</ref><ref name=\"appleraises\">{{cite news | title=Apple Raises $17 Billion in Record Corporate Bond Sale | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2013-04-30/apple-plans-six-part-bond-sale-in-first-offering-since-1996-1- | last1=Mead | first1=Charles | first2=Sarika | last2=Gangar | work=[[Bloomberg News]] | date=April 30, 2013}}</ref> and Apple's first since 1996. Goldman Sachs managed both of Apple's previous bond offerings in the 1990s.<ref name=\"appleraises\" /> Goldman Sachs was the lead underwriter for [[Twitter]]'s initial public offering in 2013. At the time, Goldman's position as lead underwriter for Twitter was considered \"one of the biggest tech prizes around\".<ref name=\"FinancialTimes2013September13AllowayTracy\">{{cite news|last1=Alloway|first1=Tracy|last2=Massoudi|first2=Arash|title=Goldman Sachs wins prime role in Twitter IPO|url=https://www.ft.com/content/095fd274-1c59-11e3-8894-00144feab7de|accessdate=April 1, 2014|agency=Nikkei|publisher=Financial Times|date=September 13, 2013|location=New York, N.Y., United States|language=English|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Goldman earned approximately $22.8 million in fees from the Twitter IPO; however, the chief economist and strategist at ZT Wealth said, \"Goldman being the first name on the S-1 has little to do with fees. This is about Goldman rebalancing itself as a serious leader and competing with Morgan Stanley's dominant position in technology.\"<ref>{{cite news | title=Goldman-Led Twitter Underwriters Share $59.2 Million in IPO Fees | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2013-11-07/goldman-led-twitter-underwriters-to-make-59-2-million-from-ipo | work=[[Bloomberg News]] | first1=Lee | last1=Spears| first2=Leslie | last2=Picker | date=November 7, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Goldman underwrote the $2.913 billion Grand Parkway System Toll Revenue Bond offering for the Houston, Texas area, one of the fastest growing areas in the United States. The bond will be repaid from toll revenue.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.transportation.gov/tifia/financed-projects/grand-parkway-segments-d%E2%80%93g | title=Grand Parkway Segments D-G | publisher=[[United States Department of Transportation]]| date=January 21, 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.fhwa.dot.gov/ipd/project_profiles/tx_grandparkway.aspx | title=Project Profiles: Grand Parkway | publisher=US Dept of Transportation:Federal Highway Administration | year=2014 | quote=Goldman Sachs, Underwriter for the Revenue Bonds | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170403195104/https://www.fhwa.dot.gov/ipd/project_profiles/tx_grandparkway.aspx | archivedate=April 3, 2017 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> In June 2013, Goldman Sachs purchased loan portfolio from Brisbane-based [[Suncorp Group]], one of Australia's largest banks and insurance companies. The [[Australian dollar|A$]]1.6 billion face amount loan portfolio was purchased for A$960 million.<ref name=\"WSJ2013June12KellyRoss\">{{cite news|last1=Kelly|first1=Ross|title=Suncorp Sells 'Bad Bank' Loans to Goldman Sachs|journal=The Wall Street Journal. Eastern Edition|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887323734304578542262346050342|accessdate=May 17, 2017|agency=Dow Jones & Company Inc|issue=Business|publisher=Wall Street Journal|date=June 12, 2013|location=Sydney, Australia|language=English|url-access=subscription|issn=0099-9660}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/business/financial-services/suncorp-sells-16bn-loan-portfolio-to-goldman-sachs/news-story/f16b35946f1ecde6b284e75186d16fdb | title=Suncorp sells $1.6bn loan book to Goldman Sachs for $960m | first=MICHAEL | last=BENNET | work=[[The Australian]] | date=June 13, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2015, Goldman Sachs agreed to acquire [[General Electric Co.]]'s GE Capital Bank on-line deposit platform. Terms of the transaction were not disclosed, but the purchase includes US$8-billion of on-line deposits and another US$8-billion of brokered certificates of deposit. The purchase allows Goldman Sachs to access a stable and inexpensive pool of source of funding.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-08-13/goldman-sachs-to-buy-ge-bank-unit-with-16-billion-of-deposits | title=Goldman Sachs to Acquire GE Capital Bank's on-line deposit platform | work=[[Bloomberg News]] | date=August 13, 2015 | first=Michael J. | last=Moore}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Marcus by Goldman Sachs Logo.svg|thumb|200px|Logo of Marcus by Goldman Sachs]]\nIn April 2016, Goldman Sachs launched a [[direct bank]], GS Bank.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.businessinsider.com/goldman-sachs-launches-online-saving-account-gsbank-2016-4 | title=Goldman Sachs is launching a bank account for ordinary people - not just the super rich | work=[[Business Insider]] | date=April 25, 2016 | first=Oscar | last=Williams-Grut}}</ref> In October 2016, Goldman Sachs Bank USA started offering no-fee [[Unsecured debt|personal loans]] under the brand Marcus by Goldman Sachs.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.usnews.com/news/business/articles/2016-10-13/goldman-sachs-launches-personal-loan-service | title=Goldman Sachs launches personal loan service | first=Ken | last=Sweet | work=[[Associated Press]] | publisher=[[U.S. News & World Report]] | date=October 13, 2016}}</ref> In March 2016, Goldman Sachs agreed to acquire [[financial technology]] startup [[Whurley#Honest Dollar (2014-present)|Honest Dollar]], a digital retirement savings tool founded by American entrepreneur [[whurley]], focused on helping small-business employees and self-employed workers obtain affordable retirement plans. Terms of the deal were not disclosed.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2016March14MoyerLiz\">{{cite news|last1=Moyer|first1=Liz|title=Goldman Sachs to Buy Honest Dollar, a Small Plan Start-Up|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/03/15/business/dealbook/goldman-sachs-to-buy-honest-dollar-a-small-plan-start-up.html|accessdate=December 5, 2016|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=DealBook|page=B2|work=New York Times|date=March 14, 2016|location=New York, N.Y., United States|language=English|url-access=limited}}</ref> In May 2017, Goldman Sachs purchased $2.8 billion of [[PDVSA]] 2022 bonds from the [[Central Bank of Venezuela]] during the [[2017 Venezuelan protests]].<ref name=\"WSJ2017May28VyasKejal\">{{cite news|last1=Vyas|first1=Kejal|last2=Kurmanaev|first2=Anatoly|title=Goldman Sachs Bought Venezuela's State Oil Company's Bonds Last Week|journal=The Wall Street Journal. Eastern Edition|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/goldman-sachs-bought-venezuelan-oil-co-bonds-last-week-1496020176|accessdate=May 31, 2017|agency=Dow Jones & Company Inc|issue=Markets|publisher=Wall Street Journal|date=May 28, 2017|location=Caracas, Venezuela|language=English|url-access=subscription|issn=0099-9660}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, Goldman Sachs bought Clarity Money, a personal finance startup, to be added to its Marcus by Goldman Sachs roster. This acquisition is expected to add over 1 million customers to the Marcus business.<ref>{{cite news | title=Goldman Sachs bought a money-management app | url=http://www.businessinsider.com/r-goldman-sachs-buys-personal-finance-start-up-clarity-money-2018-4 | first=Jessica | last=Resnick-Ault | agency=[[Reuters]] | publisher=[[Business Insider]] | date=April 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, Goldman Sachs joined [[Wells Fargo]], [[Nvidia|NVIDIA]] and Nexus Venture Partners to invest in H2O.ai. Under the terms of the deal, Jade Mandel from Goldman Sachs will be joining the H2O.ai Board. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://social.techcrunch.com/2019/08/20/h20-ai-announces-72-5m-series-d-led-by-goldman-sachs/|title=H2O.ai announces $72.5M Series D led by Goldman Sachs|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-20}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, Goldman Sachs, along with Aquiline and World Innovation Lab, raised $51 million to invest in Unqork, a New York-based software company, to accelerate a global expansion and move into new industries beyond insurance and financial services.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/tosv2.html?vid=&uuid=ed374e30-5a11-11ea-957c-89c286da433b&url=L25ld3MvYXJ0aWNsZXMvMjAyMC0wMi0yNi9nb2xkbWFuLXBsb3dzLW1vcmUtZnVuZGluZy1pbnRvLW5vLWNvZGUtc29mdHdhcmUtc3RhcnR1cA==|title=Bloomberg - Are you a robot?|website=www.bloomberg.com|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref>\n\n==Current operations==\nThe company includes 4 business units, as follows:<ref name=\"reutersoverview\">{{cite web | url=https://www.goldmansachs.com/investor-relations/investor-day-2020/presentations/consolidated-presentations.pdf  | title=Company Overview (GS) | accessdate=January 20, 2020| publisher=[[Goldman Sachs]]}}</ref>\n\n===Investment banking===\nIn 2015, [[investment banking]] accounted for 21% of total company revenues.\n\n[[Investment banking]] includes financial advisory (mergers and acquisitions, investitures, corporate defense activities, [[restructuring]], and spin-offs) and underwriting (capital raises, public offerings, and [[private placements]] of equity and debt instruments).\n\nGoldman Sachs is one of the leading M&A advisory firms, often topping the [[Thomson Financial league tables]] in sizes of transactions. The firm gained a reputation as a white knight in the mergers and acquisitions sector by advising clients on how to avoid unfriendly [[hostile takeover]]s. During the 1980s, Goldman Sachs was the only major investment bank with a strict policy against helping to initiate a hostile takeover, which increased the firm's reputation immensely among sitting management teams at the time.\n\n===Global Markets===\nIn 2017, Global Markets accounted for 37% of revenues.\n\nThe segment is divided into four divisions and includes Fixed Income (the trading of interest rate and [[credit (finance)|credit]] products, [[Mortgage-backed security|mortgage-backed securities]], [[Insurance-Linked Securities (ILS)|insurance-linked securities]] and structured and derivative products), Currency and Commodities (the trading of currencies and commodities), Equities (the trading of equities, [[equity derivative]]s, [[structured product]]s, [[option (finance)|options]], and [[futures contract]]s), and Principal Investments (merchant banking investments and funds). This segment consists of the revenues and profit gained from the Bank's trading activities, both on behalf of its clients (known as [[flow trading]]) and for its own account (known as [[proprietary trading]]).\n\n===Asset Management===\nIn 2015, asset management accounted for 18% of total company revenues.<ref name=\"reutersoverview\" />\n\nThe Asset Management division provides investment advisory and financial planning services and offers investment products (primarily through [[separately managed account]]s and commingled vehicles) across all major asset classes to a diverse group of institutions and individuals worldwide. The division provides [[clearing (finance)|clearing]], financing, [[custodian bank|custody]], securities lending, and reporting services to institutional clients, including hedge funds, mutual funds, and pension funds. The division generates revenues primarily in the form of spreads, or management and transaction fees.<ref name=\"reutersoverview\" />\n\n====Goldman Sachs Capital Partners====\n{{Main|Goldman Sachs Capital Partners}}\nGoldman Sachs Capital Partners is the private equity arm of Goldman Sachs that invests on behalf of institutional clients. It has invested over $17 billion in the 20 years from 1986 to 2006. One of the most prominent funds is the GS Capital Partners V fund, which raised over $8.5 billion for investment.<ref>{{cite press release | url=https://www.goldmansachs.com/media-relations/press-releases/archived/2005/2005-04-13.html | title=Goldman Sachs Closes GS Capital Partners V at $8.5 Billion | publisher=Goldman Sachs | date=April 13, 2005}}</ref> On April 23, 2007, Goldman closed new investment in GS Capital Partners VI with $20 billion in committed capital, including $11 billion from qualified institutional and high-net-worth clients and $9 billion from Goldman Sachs and its employees.<ref>{{cite press release | url=http://www.businesswire.com/portal/site/google/index.jsp?ndmViewId=news_view&newsId=20070423005856&newsLang=en | title=Goldman Sachs Closes GS Capital Partners VI | publisher=[[Business Wire]] | date=April 23, 2007}}</ref> In 2016, the company announced it will raise up to $8 billion for a new fund focused on corporate buyouts, its first new fund since the [[financial crisis of 2007-2008]].<ref name=\"WSJ2016July21HoffmanLiz\">{{cite news|last1=Hoffman|first1=Liz|title=Goldman Sachs Raising Private-Equity Fund of $5 Billion to $8 Billion|journal=The Wall Street Journal. Eastern Edition|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/goldman-sachs-raising-private-equity-fund-of-5-billion-to-8-billion-sources-1469141281|accessdate=May 7, 2017|agency=Dow Jones & Company Inc|issue=Markets|publisher=Wall Street Journal|date=July 21, 2016|location=United States|language=English|url-access=subscription|issn=0099-9660}}</ref>\n\n===Consumer & Wealth Management===\n\nConsumer & Wealth Management includes management and other fees, incentive fees and results from deposit-taking activities related to the firm\u2019s wealth management business. It also includes the results from providing loans through the firm\u2019s private bank, providing unsecured loans and accepting deposits through the firm\u2019s digital platform, Marcus by Goldman Sachs, and providing credit cards. Consumer & Wealth Management oversees Goldman Sachs Private Wealth, Ayco, and [[Goldman Sachs Personal Financial Management]].\n\n==Philanthropy==\n{{see also|Goldman Sachs Foundation}}\n\nAccording to its website, Goldman Sachs has committed in excess of $1.6 billion to philanthropic initiatives since 2008.<ref name=\"engagement\">{{cite web|url=https://www.goldmansachs.com/citizenship/corporate-engagement/|title=Goldman Sachs - Corporate Engagement - Corporate Engagement|website=Goldman Sachs|access-date=May 14, 2019}}</ref> Goldman Sachs reports its environmental and social performance in an annual report on [[Corporate social responsibility]] that follows the [[Global Reporting Initiative]] protocol.<ref name=esg>{{cite web | url=http://www.goldmansachs.com/s/esg-report/ | title=Goldman Sachs: ENVIRONMENTAL, SOCIAL AND GOVERNANCE REPORT | publisher=Goldman Sachs}}</ref>{{primary inline|date=February 2019}}\n\nThe company offers a [[donor advised fund]] (DAF) called Goldman Sachs Gives that donates to charitable organizations with an employee donation match of up to $20,000.<ref name=esg/><ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2016March3PickerLeslie\">{{cite news|last1=Picker|first1=Leslie|title=Goldman Sachs Expands Philanthropic Fund to Younger Workers|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/03/04/business/dealbook/goldman-sachs-expands-philanthropic-fund-to-younger-workers.html|accessdate=May 14, 2017|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=DealBook|work=New York Times|date=March 3, 2016|location=United States|language=English|url-access=limited}}</ref> A 2019 investigation by ''Sludge'' of DAFs and [[hate group]]s found that Goldman Sach's donor advised fund had not been used to fund any SPLC hate groups, but that the fund did not have any explicit policy preventing such donations.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kotch |first1=Alex |title=America's Biggest Charities Are Funneling Millions to Hate Groups From Anonymous Donors |url=https://readsludge.com/2019/02/19/americas-biggest-charities-are-funneling-millions-to-hate-groups-from-anonymous-donors/ |accessdate=February 22, 2019 |work=Sludge |date=February 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies and legal issues==\n{{Very long|section|date=April 2018}}\n{{Main|Goldman Sachs controversies}}\nGoldman has been accused of an assortment of misdeeds, including a general decline in ethical standards,<ref name=topexec/><ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2012March14SmithGreg\" /> working with dictatorial regimes,<ref name=\"GS Russia\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2013-02-06/goldman-sachs-shouldn-t-work-for-russia-human-rights-group-says|title=Goldman Sachs Shouldn't Work for Russia, Human Rights Group Says|last=Harper|first=Christine|publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]]|date=February 6, 2013}}</ref> cozy relationships with the US federal government via a \"[[Revolving door (politics)|revolving door]]\" of former employees,<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2008October17CreswellJulie\">{{cite news|last1=Creswell|first1=Julie|last2=White|first2=Ben|title=The Guys From 'Government Sachs'|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/10/19/business/19gold.html|accessdate=January 31, 2014|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=Business|work=New York Times|date=October 17, 2008|location=United States|language=English|url-access=limited}}</ref> [[insider trading]] by some of its traders,<ref name=\"james-npr\"/> and driving up prices of [[Commodity market|commodities]] through [[Futures exchange|futures]] speculation.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2013July20KocieniewskiDavid\" /> Goldman has denied wrongdoing in these cases.\n\n=== CEO-to-worker pay ratio ===\nFor the first time in 2018, a new Securities and Exchange Commission rule mandated under the 2010 Dodd-Frank financial reform requires publicly traded companies to disclose how their CEOs are compensated in comparison with their employees. In public filings, companies have to disclose their \u201cPay Ratios,\u201d or the CEO's compensation divided by the median employee's.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2018/4/8/17212796/ceo-pay-ratio-corporate-governance-wealth-inequality|title=How does a company's CEO pay compare to its workers'? Now you can find out.|last=|first=|date=April 8, 2018|website=|access-date=}}</ref> According to SEC filings, The Goldman Sachs Group Inc. paid its CEO $21,995,266 in 2017. The average worker employed by The Goldman Sachs Group Inc. was paid $135,165 in 2017; thus marking a CEO-to-worker Pay Ratio of 163 to 1.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/graphics/ceo-pay-ratio/|title=How Your Pay Stacks Up With The CEO's|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref>{{as of|2018|April}}, steelmaker Nucor represented the median CEO-to-worker Pay Ratio from SEC filings with values of 133 to 1.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://inequality.org/great-divide/how-to-track-ceo-worker-pay-ratios/|title=How to Track CEO-Worker Pay Ratios|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> ''Bloomberg BusinessWeek'' on May 2, 2013, found the ratio of CEO pay to the typical worker rose from about 20-to-1 in the 1950s to 120-to-1 in 2000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://corpgov.law.harvard.edu/2015/02/23/the-ceo-employee-pay-ratio/|title=The CEO-Employee Pay Ratio|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===Role in the financial crisis of 2007-2008===\nGoldman has been criticized in the aftermath of the [[financial crisis of 2007\u20132008]], where some alleged that it misled its investors and profited from the collapse of the mortgage market. That time in Goldman's history brought investigations from the [[United States Congress]], the [[United States Department of Justice]], and a lawsuit from the [[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]]<ref name=\"FCIR-p192\"/> that resulted in Goldman paying a $550 million settlement.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2010July15\" /> Goldman Sachs was \"excoriated by the press and the public\"<ref>{{cite book | first1=Bethany | last1=McLean | first2=Joe | last2=Nocera | authorlink1=Bethany McLean | authorlink2=Joe Nocera | title=All the Devils Are Here: The Hidden History of the Financial Crisis | page=153 | quote=In the aftermath of the crisis, Goldman Sachs would be excoriated by the press and the public and investigated by Congress, the SEC, and the Justice Department| title-link=All the Devils Are Here: The Hidden History of the Financial Crisis }}</ref> despite the non-retail nature of its business that would normally have kept it out of the public eye.<ref name=\"Devils-TARP\"/><ref name=\"Reuters2010June11SalmonFelix\">{{cite news|last1=Salmon|first1=Felix|title=BP: Still not as evil as Goldman Sachs|url=http://blogs.reuters.com/felix-salmon/2010/06/11/bp-still-not-as-evil-as-goldman-sachs/|accessdate=February 27, 2014|agency=Thompson Reuters|issue=Blogs|publisher=Reuters|date=June 11, 2010|language=English}}</ref> Visibility and antagonism came from the $12.9 billion Goldman received, more than any other firm, from AIG counterparty payments provided by the bailout of AIG, the $10 billion in [[Troubled Asset Relief Program|TARP]] money it received from the government (though the firm paid this back to the government), and a record $11.4 billion set aside for employee bonuses in the first half of 2009.<ref name=\"Devils-TARP\">{{cite book | author=McLean and Nocera |title=All the Devils Are Here | page=361 | quote=By the middle of the summer, Goldman Sachs was producing blowout profits, had repaid its $10 billion in TARP funds, and had already set aside $11.4 billion -- a record sum -- with which to pay bonuses to employees.}}</ref><ref name=Harper>{{cite news | url=http://archive.fortune.com/2009/07/14/news/companies/goldman.pay.fortune/index.htm | title=The return of the $773,000 paycheck | first=Colin | last=Barr | publisher=[[Fortune Magazine]] | date=July 14, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2009July14BowleyGraham\">{{cite news|last1=Bowley|first1=Graham|title=With Big Profit, Goldman Sees Big Payday Ahead|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/07/15/business/15goldman.html|accessdate=May 16, 2017|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=Business|work=New York Times|date=July 14, 2009|location=United States|language=English|url-access=limited}}</ref> While all the investment banks were scolded by congressional investigations, Goldman Sachs was subject to \"a solo hearing in front of the [[Permanent Subcommittee on Investigations#Wall Street and the Financial Crisis|Senate Permanent Subcommitee on Investigations]]\" and a quite critical report.<ref name=Devils-TARP/><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/halahtouryalai/2011/04/14/criminal-charges-loom-for-goldman-sachs-after-scathing-senate-report/ | title=Criminal Charges Loom For Goldman Sachs After Scathing Senate Report | first=Halah | last=Touryalai | publisher=[[Forbes Magazine]] | date=April 14, 2011}}</ref> In a widely publicized story in ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', [[Matt Taibbi]] characterized Goldman Sachs as a \"great vampire squid\" sucking money instead of blood, allegedly engineering \"every major market manipulation since the [[Great Depression]] ... from tech stocks to high gas prices\".<ref name=carney>{{cite web|title=Matt Taibbi's \"Vampire Squid\" Takedown Of Goldman Sachs Is Finally Online|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/matt-taibbis-vampire-squid-take-down-of-goldman-sachs-is-finally-online-2009-7|last=Carney|first=John| publisher=[[Business Insider]]|date=July 16, 2009|quote=What's fascinating to us is how the spirit of Taibbi's piece, if not its details, has really caught on. Yesterday, the Wall Street Journal attacked Goldman Sachs as a heavily subsidized, implicitly guaranteed firm akin to Fannie Mae. They called it \"Goldie Mac\". ''The New York Times'' news report on the reaction to Goldman's earnings also didn't shy away from these sentiments. It said that Goldman's traders are known as the Bandits of Broad Street (which is clever, although we haven't heard that one before) and quoted an unnamed Wall Street who compared Goldman staff to \"orcs\" in the Lord of the Rings (which is even better).}}</ref><ref name=Taibbi>{{cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/news/the-great-american-bubble-machine-20100405|title=The Great American Bubble Machine|last=Taibbi|first=Matt|publisher=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=July 9, 2009|quote=From tech stocks to high gas prices, Goldman Sachs has engineered every major market manipulation since the Great Depression -- and they're about to do it again}}</ref><ref name=Zamansky>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jakezamansky/2013/08/08/the-great-vampire-squid-keeps-on-sucking/|title=The Great Vampire Squid Keeps On Sucking|last=Zamansky|first=Jake|publisher=[[Forbes Magazine]]|date=August 8, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2011December13RooseKevin\">{{cite news|last1=Roose|first1=Kevin|title=The Long Life of the Vampire Squid|url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2011/12/13/the-long-life-of-the-vampire-squid-metaphor/|accessdate=February 27, 2014|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=DealBook|work=New York Times|date=December 13, 2011|location=United States|language=English|url-access=limited}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2009, after the firm repaid the TARP investment from the U.S. Treasury, Goldman made some of the largest bonus payments in its history due to its strong financial performance.<ref name=\"WSJ2010January10CraigSusanne\" /><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2009/jun/21/goldman-sachs-bonus-payments | title=Goldman to make record bonus payout | first=Phillip | last=Inman | publisher=The Guardian | date=June 20, 2009}}</ref> [[Andrew Cuomo]], then [[New York Attorney General]], questioned Goldman's decision to pay 953 employees bonuses of at least $1 million each after it received TARP funds in 2008.<ref name=\"WSJ2009July30GrocerStephen\" /> That same period, however, CEO Lloyd Blankfein and 6 other senior executives opted to forgo bonuses, stating they believed it was the right thing to do, in light of \"the fact that we are part of an industry that's directly associated with the ongoing economic distress\".<ref name=\"Reuters2008November16GiannoneJoseph\" />\n\nGoldman Sachs maintained that its net exposure to AIG was 'not material', and that the firm was protected by [[hedge (finance)|hedges]] (in the form of CDSs with other counterparties) and $7.5 billion of [[collateral (finance)|collateral]].<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2009March20\">{{cite news|title=Goldman Maintains It Had No A.I.G. Exposure|url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2009/03/20/goldman-maintains-it-had-no-aig-exposure/|accessdate=November 24, 2009|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=DealBook|work=New York Times|date=March 20, 2009|location=United States|language=English|url-access=limited}}</ref> The firm stated the cost of these hedges to be over $100 million.<ref name=\"WSJ2009April14vanPraagLucas\">{{cite news|last1=van Praag|first1=Lucas|title=Goldman Protected Its Clients From AIG's Weakness|journal=The Wall Street Journal. Eastern Edition|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123967007321015621|accessdate=May 18, 2009|agency=Dow Jones & Company Inc|issue=Opinion|publisher=Wall Street Journal|date=April 14, 2009|location=United States|language=English|url-access=subscription|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> According to Goldman, both the collateral and CDSs would have protected the bank from incurring an economic loss in the event of an AIG bankruptcy (however, because AIG was bailed out and not allowed to fail, these hedges did not pay out).<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theatlantic.com/business/archive/2009/11/the-media-is-wrong-about-goldman-sachs-aig/30565/ | title=The Media is Wrong about Goldman Sachs, AIG | first=Jordan | last=Terry | work=[[The Atlantic]] | date=November 20, 2009}}</ref> CFO [[David Viniar]] stated that profits related to AIG in the first quarter of 2009 \"rounded to zero\", and profits in December were not significant. He went on to say that he was \"mystified\" by the interest the government and investors have shown in the bank's trading relationship with AIG.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/goldman-cfo-doesnt-get-why-everyone-is-so-obsessed-with-aig-2009-4|title=Goldman CFO Doesn't Get Why Everyone Is So Obsessed With AIG|first=Joe|last=Weisenthal| publisher=[[Business Insider]]|date=April 14, 2009}}</ref>\n\nSome have said, incorrectly according to others,<ref>[http://economicsofcontempt.blogspot.com/2009/03/another-dishonest-nyt-editorial-on-aig.html \"Another Dishonest NYT Editorial on AIG\"], Economics of Contempt (blog). Retrieved April 29, 2009.</ref> that Goldman Sachs received preferential treatment from the government by being the only Wall Street firm to have participated in the crucial September meetings at the New York Fed, which decided AIG's fate. Much of this has stemmed from an inaccurate but often quoted ''New York Times'' article.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2008September27MorgensonGretchen\">{{cite news|last1=Morgenson|first1=Gretchen|title=Behind Insurer's Crisis, Blind Eye to a Web of Risk|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/09/28/business/28melt.html|accessdate=June 25, 2011|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=Business|work=New York Times|date=September 27, 2008|location=United States|language=English|url-access=limited}}</ref> The article was later corrected to state that Blankfein, CEO of Goldman Sachs, was \"''one of'' the Wall Street chief executives at the meeting\". [[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]] has also reported that representatives from other firms were indeed present at the September AIG meetings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sanders.senate.gov/newsroom/must-read/goldman-merrill-collect-billions-after-feds-aig-bailout-loans-bloomberg|title=Goldman, Merrill Collect Billions After Fed's AIG Bailout Loans|first=Mark|last=Pittman|work=[[Bloomberg L.P.]]|publisher=[[Bernie Sanders]]|date=September 29, 2008}}</ref> Furthermore, Goldman Sachs CFO [[David Viniar]] stated that CEO Blankfein had never \"met\" with his predecessor and then-US Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson to discuss AIG;<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marketwatch.com/story/goldman-rejected-offers-settle-aig-trades-discount-goldman |title=Goldman rejected settling of AIG trades at discount | first1=Greg|last1=Morcroft|first2=Alistair|last2=Barr|publisher=[[Marketwatch]]|date=March 20, 2009}}</ref> however, there were frequent phone calls between the two of them.<ref>{{cite book|author=Matt Taibbi|title=Griftopia|publisher=[[Spiegel & Grau]], 2010|page=[https://archive.org/details/griftopiabubblem0000taib/page/248 248]|isbn=978-0-385-52995-2|author-link=Matt Taibbi|title-link=Griftopia|year=2010}}</ref> Paulson was not present at the September meetings at the New York Fed. [[Morgan Stanley]] was hired by the Federal Reserve to advise on the AIG bailout.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2008September16AndrewsEdmund\">{{cite news|last1=Andrews|first1=Edmund|last2=Walsh|first2=MaryWilliams|title=Fed's $85 Billion Loan Rescues Insurer|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/09/17/business/17insure.html|accessdate=May 21, 2017|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=Business|work=New York Times|date=September 16, 2008|location=New York, N.Y., United States|language=English|url-access=limited}}</ref>\n\n===Sale of Dragon Systems to Lernout & Hauspie despite accounting issues===\nIn 2000, Goldman Sachs advised [[Dragon NaturallySpeaking|Dragon Systems]] on its sale to [[Lernout & Hauspie]] of Belgium for $580 million in L&H stock. L&H later collapsed due to accounting fraud and its stock price declined significantly. Jim and Janet Baker, founders and together 50% owners of Dragon, filed a lawsuit against Goldman Sachs, alleging negligence, intentional and negligent misrepresentation, and breach of fiduciary duty since Goldman did not warn Dragon or the Bakers of the accounting problems of the acquirer, L&H. On January 23, 2013, a federal jury rejected the Bakers' claims and found Goldman Sachs not liable to the Bakers.<ref name=\"Reuters2013January23McLaughlinTim\">{{cite news|last1=McLaughlin|first1=Tim|last2=Pressman|first2=Aaron|title=Goldman cleared of all charges in doomed Dragon sale|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-goldman-dragon-trial-idUSBRE90M1GX20130123|accessdate=February 23, 2013|agency=Thompson Reuters|issue=Wealth|publisher=Reuters|date=January 23, 2013|location=Boston, MA, United States|language=English}}</ref>\n\n===Stock price manipulation===\nGoldman Sachs was charged for repeatedly issuing research reports with extremely inflated financial projections for [[Exodus Communications]] and Goldman Sachs was accused of giving Exodus its highest stock rating even though Goldman knew Exodus did not deserve such a rating.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://casetext.com/case/60223-trust-v-goldman-2|title=60223 Trust v. Goldman, Sachs Co. (S.D.N.Y. 007), 540 F. Supp. 2d 449 - Casetext|website=Casetext.com|access-date=May 14, 2019}}</ref> On July 15, 2003, Goldman Sachs, [[Lehman Brothers]] and [[Morgan Stanley]] were sued for artificially inflating the stock price of RSL Communications by issuing untrue or materially misleading statements in research analyst reports, and paid $3,380,000 for settlement.<ref>{{cite court|litigants=FOGARAZZO V. LEHMAN BROS., INC.|court=[[United States District Court for the Southern District of New York]]|date=2004|url=https://casetext.com/case/fogarazzo-v-lehman-bros-inc-sdny-2004}}</ref>\n\nGoldman Sachs is accused of asking for [[kickback (bribery)|kickback bribes]] from institutional clients who made large profits [[flipping]] stocks which Goldman had intentionally undervalued in [[initial public offering]]s it was underwriting. Documents [[under seal]] in a decade-long lawsuit concerning [[eToys.com]]'s [[initial public offering]] (IPO) in 1999 but released accidentally to the ''New York Times'' show that IPOs managed by Goldman were underpriced and that Goldman asked clients able to profit from the prices to increase business with it. The clients willingly complied with these demands because they understood it was necessary in order to participate in further such undervalued IPOs.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2013March10NoceraJoe\">{{cite news|last1=Nocera|first1=Joe|title=Rigging the I.P.O. Game|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/03/10/opinion/sunday/nocera-rigging-the-ipo-game.html|accessdate=March 16, 2013|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=Opinions|page=SR1|work=New York Times|date=March 10, 2013|location=New York, N.Y., United States|language=English|url-access=limited}}</ref> Companies going public and their initial consumer stockholders are both defrauded by this practice.<ref name=\"Reuters2013March11SalmonFelix\">{{cite news|last1=Salmon|first1=Felix|title=Where banks really make money on IPOs|url=http://blogs.reuters.com/felix-salmon/2013/03/11/where-banks-really-make-money-on-ipos/|accessdate=March 14, 2013|agency=Thompson Reuters|issue=Blogs|publisher=Reuters|date=March 11, 2013|language=English}}</ref>\n\n===Use of offshore tax havens===\nA 2016 report by [[Citizens for Tax Justice]] stated that \"Goldman Sachs reports having 987 subsidiaries in offshore tax havens, 537 of which are in the [[Cayman Islands]], despite not operating a single legitimate office in that country, according to its own website. The group officially holds $28.6 billion offshore.\" The report also noted several other major U.S. banks and companies use the same tax-avoidance tactics.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://ctj.org/ctjreports/2016/10/offshore_shell_games_2016.php |title=Offshore Shell Games 2016 |access-date=March 26, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202035438/http://ctj.org/ctjreports/2016/10/offshore_shell_games_2016.php |archive-date=February 2, 2017 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Goldman Sachs had an effective tax rate of only 1%, down from 34% the year before, and its tax liability decreased to $14 million in 2008, compared to $6 billion in 2007.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2008December16WhiteBen\">{{cite news|last1=White|first1=Ben|title=Goldman Sachs Reports $2.1 Billion Quarterly Loss|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/17/business/17goldman.html|accessdate=March 26, 2017|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=Business|work=New York Times|date=December 16, 2008|location=United States|language=English|url-access=limited}}</ref> Critics have argued that the reduction in Goldman Sachs's tax rate was achieved by shifting its earnings to subsidiaries in low or no-tax nations, such as the Cayman Islands.<ref>{{cite journal | url=http://www.thenation.com/slideshow/158255/slide-show-8-corporations-owe-you-money | title=The Nation: \"8 Corporations That Owe You Money\" | journal=The Nation | date=February 3, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Involvement in the European sovereign debt crisis===\n[[File:Lucas Papademos 2011-11-11.jpg|thumb|upright|Former Prime Minister of Greece Lucas Papademos]]\nGoldman is being criticized for its involvement in the 2010 [[European sovereign debt crisis]]. Goldman Sachs is reported to have systematically helped the Greek government mask the true facts concerning its national debt between the years 1998 and 2009.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/europe/0,1518,676634,00.html | title=How Goldman Sachs Helped Greece to Mask its True Debt | first=Beat | last=Balzli | work=Der Spiegel | date=February 8, 2010 | accessdate=July 1, 2011}}</ref> In September 2009, Goldman Sachs, among others, created a special [[credit default swap]] (CDS) index to cover the high risk of Greece's national debt.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://usatoday30.usatoday.com/money/economy/2010-02-25-bernanke-fed-greece_N.htm |title=Fed chief: We're looking into firms betting on Greek default | first=Jeannine | last=Aversa | publisher=USA Today |date=February 25, 2010}}</ref> The interest-rates of Greek national bonds soared, leading the Greek economy very close to bankruptcy in 2010 and 2011.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2011June19CastleStephen\">{{cite news|last1=Castle|first1=Stephen|last2=Kitsantonis|first2=Niki|title=Deal on Lifeline to Avert Greek Bankruptcy Is Postponed|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/06/20/business/20euro.html|accessdate=July 1, 2011|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=Business|page=B1|work=New York Times|date=June 19, 2011|location=Luxembourg|language=English|url-access=limited}}</ref>\n\nTies between Goldman Sachs and European leadership positions were another source of controversy.<ref name=\"Foley\" /> [[Lucas Papademos]], Greece's former prime minister, ran the Central Bank of Greece at the time of the controversial derivatives deals with Goldman Sachs that enabled Greece to hide the size of its debt.<ref name=\"Foley\">{{cite news | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/analysis-and-features/what-price-the-new-democracy-goldman-sachs-conquers-europe-6264091.html | title=What price the new democracy? Goldman Sachs conquers Europe | first=Stephen | last=Foley| publisher=[[The Independent]] | date=November 18, 2011}}</ref> [[Petros Christodoulou]], General Manager of the Greek [[Public Debt Management Agency (Greece)|Public Debt Management Agency]] is a former employee of Goldman Sachs.<ref name=\"Foley\" /> [[Mario Monti]], Italy's former prime minister and finance minister, who headed the new government that took over after Berlusconi's resignation, is an international adviser to Goldman Sachs.<ref name=\"Foley\" /> [[Otmar Issing]], former board member of the Bundesbank and the Executive Board of the European Bank also advised Goldman Sachs.<ref name=\"Foley\" /> [[Mario Draghi]], head of the [[European Central Bank]], is the former managing director of Goldman Sachs International.<ref name=\"Foley\" /> [[Ant\u00f3nio Borges (economist)|Ant\u00f3nio Borges]], Head of the European Department of the [[International Monetary Fund]] in 2010-2011 and responsible for most of enterprise [[privatization]]s in [[Portugal]] since 2011, is the former Vice Chairman of Goldman Sachs International.<ref name=\"Foley\" /> [[Carlos Moedas]], a former Goldman Sachs employee, was the Secretary of State to the [[Prime Minister of Portugal]] and Director of ESAME, the agency created to monitor and control the implementation of the structural reforms agreed by the government of [[Portugal]] and the [[troika (triumvirate)|troika]] composed of the [[European Commission]], the European Central Bank and the International Monetary Fund. [[Peter Sutherland]], former Attorney General of Ireland was a non-executive director of Goldman Sachs International.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/goldman-sachs-chairman-peter-sutherland-retires-1.2220241 | title=Goldman Sachs chairman Peter Sutherland retires | first=Stephen | last=Collins | publisher=[[Irish Times]] | date=May 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Employee's views===\nIn March 2012, Greg Smith, then-head of Goldman Sachs US equity derivatives sales business in [[Europe, the Middle East and Africa]] (EMEA), resigned his position via a critical letter printed as an [[op-ed]] in ''[[The New York Times]]''. In the letter, he attacked Goldman Sachs CEO and Chairman Lloyd Blankfein for losing touch with the company's culture, which he described as \"the secret sauce that made this place great and allowed us to earn our clients' trust for 143 years\". Smith said that advising clients \"to do what I believe is right for them\" was becoming increasingly unpopular. Instead there was a \"toxic and destructive\" environment in which \"the interests of the client continue to be sidelined\", senior management described clients as \"[[Wikt:muppet|muppets]]\" and colleagues callously talked about \"ripping their clients off\".<ref name=topexec>{{cite news | title=Top Goldman executive quits over culture of 'toxic' greed | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/top-goldman-sachs-executive-quits-over-culture-of-toxic-greed-7566430.html | first=John | last=Hall | work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] | date=March 14, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2012March14SmithGreg\">{{cite news|last1=Smith|first1=Greg|title=Why I Am Leaving Goldman Sachs|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/14/opinion/why-i-am-leaving-goldman-sachs.html|accessdate=March 14, 2012|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=Opinions|page=A27|work=New York Times|date=March 14, 2012|location=New York, N.Y., United States|language=English|url-access=limited}}</ref> In reply, Goldman Sachs said that \"we will only be successful if our clients are successful\", claiming \"this fundamental truth lies at the heart of how we conduct ourselves\", and that \"we don't think [Smith's comments] reflect the way we run our business\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/schumpeter/2012/03/goldman-sachs | title=A noisy exit | first=Joseph | last=Schumpeter | work=[[The Economist]] | date=March 14, 2012}}</ref> Later that year, Smith published a book titled ''Why I left Goldman Sachs''.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.economist.com/news/finance-and-economics/21565219-insider%E2%80%99s-take-goldman-sachs-strikes-nerve-mammon-and-muppets | title=Of Mammon and muppets | work=[[The Economist]] | date=October 27, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2012October19StewartJames\">{{cite news|last1=Stewart|first1=James|title=A Tell-All on Goldman Has Little Worth Telling|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/10/20/business/why-i-left-book-about-goldman-falls-short.html|accessdate=May 16, 2017|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=Business|page=B1|work=New York Times|date=October 19, 2012|location=New York, N.Y., United States|language=English|url-access=limited}}</ref>\n\nAccording to research by ''[[The New York Times]]'' after the op-ed was printed, almost all the claims made in Smith's incendiary Op-Ed about Goldman Sachs turned out to be \"curiously short\" on evidence. ''The New York Times'' never issued a retraction or admitted to any error in judgment in initially publishing Smith's op-ed.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2012October19StewartJames\" /><ref>{{cite news | url=http://observer.com/2012/10/the-making-and-unmaking-of-goldman-sachs-whistleblower-greg-smith/ | title=The Making (and Unmaking) of Goldman Sachs Whistleblower Greg Smith | first=Ryan | last=Holiday | work=[[The Observer]]| date=October 26, 2012}}<br/>{{cite news | url=http://theweek.com/articles/471202/why-left-goldman-sachs-banks-most-famous-quitter-con-man | title=Why I Left Goldman Sachs: Is the bank's most famous quitter a con man? | work=[[The Week]] | date=October 19, 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Steven Mandis photo.jpg|thumb|upright|Steven Mandis]]\nIn 2014 a book by former Goldman portfolio manager [[Steven George Mandis]] was published entitled ''What Happened to Goldman Sachs: An Insider's Story of Organizational Drift and Its Unintended Consequences''.<ref name=HBR>{{cite web | url=https://hbr.org/product/what-happened-to-goldman-sachs-an-insider-s-story-of-organizational-drift-and-its-unintended-consequences/an/11798E-KND-ENG | title=What Happened to Goldman Sachs: An Insider's Story of Organizational Drift and Its Unintended Consequences | first=Steven G. | last=Mandis | work=[[Harvard Business Review]] | date=October 1, 2013}}</ref> Mandis also has a PhD dissertation about Goldman at [[Columbia University]]. Mandis left in 2004 after working for the firm for 12 years.<ref name=Mandis>{{cite web | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2013-09-25/goldman-sachs-insider-tale-doubles-as-phd-thesis | title=Goldman Sachs Insider Tale Doubles as PhD Thesis | last=Brady | first=Diane | work=[[Bloomberg News]] | date=September 25, 2013}}</ref> In an interview, Mandis said, \"You read about Goldman Sachs, and it's either the bank is the best or the bank is the worst, this is not one of those books - things are never black or white.\"<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2013September30LattmanPeter\">{{cite news|last1=Lattman|first1=Peter|title=An Ex-Trader, Now a Sociologist, Looks at the Changes in Goldman|url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2013/09/30/goldman-as-case-study-not-hero-or-villain/|accessdate=May 16, 2017|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=DealBook|work=New York Times|date=September 30, 2013|location=New York, N.Y., United States|language=English|url-access=limited}}</ref> According to Mandis, there was an \"organizational drift\" in the company's evolution.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2013September30LattmanPeter\" />\n\n=== Gender bias lawsuit ===\nIn 2010, two former female employees filed a lawsuit against Goldman Sachs for gender discrimination. Cristina Chen-Oster and Shanna Orlich claimed that the firm fostered an \"uncorrected culture of sexual harassment and assault\" causing women to either be \"sexualized or ignored\". The suit cited both cultural and pay discrimination including frequent client trips to strip clubs, client golf outings that excluded female employees, and the fact that female vice presidents made 21% less than their male counterparts.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://money.cnn.com/2014/07/02/investing/goldman-sachs-lawsuit/index.html | title=Suit alleges \"boy club\" culture at Goldman | first=Jesse | last=Solomon | work=[[CNN]] | date=July 2, 2014}}<br />{{cite news | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2014-07-02/a-lawsuit-peeks-inside-the-goldman-sachs-boys-club | title=A Lawsuit Peeks Inside the Goldman Sachs 'Boys' Club' | first=Sheelah | last=Kolhatkar | work=[[Bloomberg News]]| date=July 2, 2014}}<br />{{cite news | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/goldman-sachs-lawsuit-wall-street-giant-is-a-boys-club-where-drinking-strip-clubs-and-sexism-9582743.html|title=Goldman Sachs lawsuit: Wall Street giant is a 'boys club where drinking, strip clubs and sexism tolerated' | first=Mark | last=McSherry | work=[[The Independent]] | date=July 3, 2014}}</ref> In March 2018, the judge ruled that the female employees may pursue their claims as a group in a class-action lawsuit against Goldman on gender bias, but the class action excludes their claim on sexual harassment.<ref name=\"Reuters2018March30StempelJonathan\">{{cite news|last1=Stempel|first1=Jonathan|last2=Thomas|first2=Susan|title=U.S. judge certifies Goldman Sachs gender bias class action|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-goldman-sachs-bias-lawsuit-idUSKBN1H61SN|accessdate=February 21, 2019|agency=Thompson Reuters|issue=Business News|publisher=Reuters|date=March 30, 2018|location=New York, N.Y., United States|language=English}}</ref>\n\n===Advice to short California bonds underwritten by the firm===\nOn November 11, 2008, the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' reported that Goldman Sachs had both earned $25 million from underwriting California bonds, and advised other clients to [[Short (finance)|short]] those bonds.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://articles.latimes.com/2008/nov/11/business/fi-goldman11 | title=Firm urged hedge against state bonds it helped sell | first1=Sharona | last1=Coutts | first2=Marc | last2=Lifsher | first3=Michael A. | last3=Hiltzik | work=[[Los Angeles Times]] | date=November 11, 2008}}</ref> While some journalists criticized the contradictory actions,<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.adn.com/uncategorized/article/why-did-blue-chip-goldman-take-walk-subprimes-wild-side/2009/10/27/ | title=Why did blue-chip Goldman take a walk on subprime's wild side? | first=Greg | last=Gordon | work=[[Alaska Dispatch News]] | date=October 27, 2009}}</ref> others pointed out that the opposite investment decisions undertaken by the underwriting side and the trading side of the bank were normal and in line with regulations regarding [[Chinese wall#Finance|Chinese walls]], and in fact critics had demanded increased independence between underwriting and trading.<ref name=\"theatlantic\">{{cite web | url=https://www.theatlantic.com/business/archive/2009/07/matt-taibbi-gets-his-sarah-palin-on/21084/ | title=Matt Taibbi Gets His Sarah Palin On | first=Megan | last=McArdle | work=[[The Atlantic]] | date=July 10, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Personnel \"revolving-door\" with U.S. government===\nDuring 2008 Goldman Sachs received criticism for an apparent [[Revolving door (politics)|revolving door]] relationship, in which its employees and consultants have moved in and out of high level U.S. Government positions, creating the potential for conflicts of interest. The large number of former Goldman Sachs employees in the US government has been jokingly referred to \"Government Sachs\".<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2008October17CreswellJulie\" /> Former Treasury Secretary Paulson is a former CEO of Goldman Sachs. Additional controversy attended the selection of former Goldman Sachs [[lobbyist]] [[Mark A. Patterson]] as chief of staff to Treasury Secretary [[Timothy Geithner]], despite President [[Barack Obama]]'s campaign promise that he would limit the influence of lobbyists in his administration.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://abcnews.go.com/Blotter/story?id=6735898 | title=Another Lobbyist Headed Into Obama Administration | first1=JUSTIN | last1=ROOD | first2=EMMA | last2=SCHWARTZ | work=[[ABC News]] | date=January 27, 2009}}</ref> In February 2011, the ''[[Washington Examiner]]'' reported that Goldman Sachs was \"the company from which Obama raised the most money in 2008\", and that its \"CEO [[Lloyd Blankfein]] has visited the White House 10 times\".<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/obamas-top-funder-also-leads-the-nation-in-white-house-visits/article/141278 | title=Obama's top funder also leads the nation in White House visits | first=Timothy P. | last=Carney | work=[[Washington Examiner]] | date=February 23, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Insider trading cases===\nIn 1986, Goldman Sachs investment banker David Brown pleaded guilty to charges of passing inside information on a takeover deal that eventually was provided to [[Ivan Boesky]].<ref name=spreading>{{cite news |first=Ford S. |last=Worthy |author2=Brett Duval Fromson |author3=Lorraine Carson |title=Wall Street's Spreading Scandal |url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1986/12/22/68462/index.htm |work=[[Fortune Magazine]] |publisher=Cable News Network LP, LLLP. A Time Warner Company |date=December 22, 1986 |accessdate=January 17, 2007}}</ref> In 1989, [[Robert M. Freeman]], who was a senior Partner, who was the Head of Risk Arbitrage, and who was a prot\u00e9g\u00e9 of [[Robert Rubin]], pleaded guilty to [[insider trading]], for his own account and for the firm's account.<ref>{{cite news |first=Landon Jr. |last=Thomas |title=Cold Call | url=http://nymag.com/nymetro/news/bizfinance/columns/businessclass/5693/ | work=[[New York Magazine]]|date=February 18, 2002 |accessdate=January 17, 2007}}</ref>\n\n====Rajat Gupta insider trading case====\n{{Main|Raj Rajaratnam/Galleon Group, Anil Kumar, and Rajat Gupta insider trading cases}}\n[[File:Rajat Kumar Gupta - World Economic Forum Annual Meeting Davos 2010 crop.jpg|thumb|Rajat Gupta]]\nIn April 2010, Goldman director [[Rajat Gupta]] was named in an insider-trading case. It was said Gupta had \"tipped off a hedge-fund billionaire\", [[Raj Rajaratnam]] of [[Galleon Group]], about the $5 billion Berkshire Hathaway investment in Goldman during the [[Financial crisis of 2007\u20132008#Impacts on financial institutions|financial crisis of 2007-2008]]. According to the report, Gupta had told Goldman the month before his involvement became public that he wouldn't seek re-election as a director.<ref name=\"james-npr\">James, Frank, [https://www.npr.org/blogs/thetwo-way/2010/04/goldman_sachs_director_linked.html \"Goldman Sachs Director Tied To Insider-Trading Scandal\"], [[NPR]], April 23, 2010. Retrieved March 1, 2011.</ref> In early 2011, with the delayed Rajaratnam criminal trial about to begin,<ref name=\"Reuters2011February10McCoolGrant\">{{cite news|last1=McCool|first1=Grant|last2=McCormick|first2=Gerald|title=Judge postpones Rajaratnam trial to March 8|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-galleon-rajaratnam-idUSTRE7193V120110210|accessdate=March 1, 2011|agency=Thompson Reuters|issue=Business News|publisher=Reuters|date=February 10, 2011|location=New York, N.Y., United States|language=English}}</ref> the [[United States Securities and Exchange Commission]] (SEC) announced civil charges against Gupta covering the Berkshire investment as well as confidential quarterly earnings information from Goldman and [[Procter & Gamble]] (P&G). Gupta was board member at P&G until voluntarily resigning the day of the SEC announcement, after the charges were announced. \"Gupta was an investor in some of the Galleon hedge funds when he passed the information along, and he had other business interests with Rajaratnam that were potentially lucrative.... Rajaratnam used the information from Gupta to illegally profit in hedge fund trades.... The information on Goldman made Rajaratnam's funds $17 million richer.... The Procter & Gamble data created illegal profits of more than $570,000 for Galleon funds managed by others, the SEC said.\" Gupta was said to have \"vigorously denied the SEC accusations\". He was also a board member of [[AMR Corporation]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2011-10-26/ex-goldman-sachs-director-gupta-said-to-face-insider-trading-probe-charges | title=Ex-Goldman Director Gupta Indicted in Probe of Rajaratnam Trades | first1=Patricia | last1=Hurtado | first2=David | last2=Glovin | first3=Chris | last3=Dolmetsch | work=[[Bloomberg News]] | date=November 11, 2014 |url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nGupta was convicted in June 2012 on [[insider trading]] charges stemming from [[Raj Rajaratnam/Galleon Group, Anil Kumar, and Rajat Gupta insider trading cases|Galleon Group case]] on [[#Insider trading conviction|four criminal felony counts]] of [[conspiracy (crime)|conspiracy]] and [[securities fraud]]. He was sentenced in October 2012 to two years in prison, an additional year on supervised release and ordered to pay $5 million in fines.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://articles.latimes.com/2012/oct/24/business/la-fi-mo-gupta-sentenced-20121024 | title=Rajat Gupta, former Goldman Sachs director, is sentenced | first=Andrew | last=Tangel | work=[[Los Angeles Times]] | date=October 24, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Abacus mortgage-backed CDOs and $550 million settlement (2010)===\n{{anchor|Abacus CDO}}\n{{See also|Merrill Lynch#CDO controversies|Magnetar Capital}}\n\nUnlike many investors and investment bankers, Goldman Sachs anticipated the [[subprime mortgage crisis]] that developed in 2007-8.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2009December24MorgensonGretchen\">{{cite news|last1=Morgenson|first1=Gretchen|last2=Story|first2=Louise|title=Banks Bundled Bad Debt, Bet Against It and Won|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/24/business/24trading.html|accessdate=April 14, 2010|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=Business|page=A1|work=New York Times|date=December 24, 2009|location=New York, N.Y., United States|language=English|url-access=limited}} ''This article describes the intricate links between Goldman Sachs trader, Jonathan M. Egol, synthetic collateralized debt obligations, or C.D.O., ABACUS, and asset-backed securities index (ABX)''</ref> Some of its traders became \"bearish\" on the housing boom beginning in 2004 and developed mortgage-related securities, originally intended to protect Goldman from investment losses in the housing market. In late 2006, Goldman management changed the firm's overall stance on the mortgage market from positive to negative. As the market began its downturn, Goldman \"created even more of these securities\", no longer just hedging or satisfying investor orders but, according to business journalist Gretchen Morgenson, \"enabling it to pocket huge profits\" from the mortgage defaults and that Goldman \"used the C.D.O.'s to place unusually large negative bets that were not mainly for hedging purposes\".<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2009December24MorgensonGretchen\" /> Authors Bethany McLean and Joe Nocera stated that \"the firm's later insistence that it was merely a 'market maker' in these transactions - implying that it had no stake in the economic performance of the securities it was selling to clients - became less true over time\"-<ref>{{cite book | author=McLean and Nocera | title=All the Devils Are Here | page=271}}</ref>\n\nThe investments were called [[synthetic CDO]]s because unlike regular [[collateralized debt obligation]]s, the principal and interest they paid out came not from mortgages or other loans, but from premiums to pay for insurance against mortgage defaults - the insurance known as \"[[credit default swap]]s\". Goldman and some other hedge funds held a \"short\" position in the securities, paying the premiums, while the investors (insurance companies, pension funds, etc.) receiving the premiums were the \"long\" position. The longs were responsible for paying the insurance \"claim\" to Goldman and any other shorts if the mortgages or other loans defaulted. Through April 2007, Goldman issued over 20 CDOs in its \"Abacus\" series worth a total of $10.9 billion.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2010April16StoryLouise\">{{cite news|last1=Story|first1=Louise|last2=Morgenson|first2=Gretchen|title=S.E.C. Accuses Goldman of Fraud in Housing Deal|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/04/17/business/17goldman.html|accessdate=January 26, 2014|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=Business|page=A1|work=New York Times|date=April 16, 2010|location=New York, N.Y., United States|language=English|url-access=limited}}</ref> All together Goldman packaged, sold, and shorted a total of 47 synthetic CDOs, with an aggregate face value of $66 billion between July 1, 2004, and May 31, 2007.<ref>''FCIR'' p.145</ref>\n\nBut while Goldman was praised for its foresight, some argued its bets against the securities it created gave it a vested interest in their failure. These securities performed very poorly for the long investors and by April 2010, at least US$5 billion worth of the securities either carried \"junk\" ratings, or had defaulted.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.smh.com.au/business/world-business/abacus-let-goldman-shuffle-mortgage-risk-like-beads-20100418-smx3.html | title=Abacus Let Goldman Shuffle Mortgage Risk Like Beads | first1=Jody | last1=Shenn | first2=Bob | last2=Ivry | agency=[[Bloomberg News]] | publisher=[[Sydney Morning Herald]] | date=April 16, 2010}}</ref> One CDO examined by critics which Goldman bet against, but also sold to investors, was the $800 million Hudson Mezzanine CDO issued in 2006. In the Senate Permanent Subcommittee hearings, Goldman executives stated that the company was trying to remove subprime securities from its books. Unable to sell them directly, it included them in the underlying securities of the CDO and took the short side, but critics McLean and Nocera complained the CDO prospectus did not explain this but described its contents as \"'assets sourced from the Street', making it sound as though Goldman randomly selected the securities, instead of specifically creating a hedge for its own book\".<ref name=\"devils-p274-1\">{{cite book | author1=Bethany McLean | author2=Joe Nocera | title=All the Devils Are Here: The Hidden History of the Financial Crisis |page=274 |quote=The CDO had been constructed, Goldman executives later told the Senate Permanent Subcommittee, while the company was trying to remove triple-B assets from its books. Among those assets was a long position in the ABX index that Goldman had gotten 'stuck' with while putting together deals for hedge fund clients that wanted to go short. Unable to find counterparties to take the long position off its hands, Goldman used Hudson as a means by which it hedged its long position. ... None of which was clear from the Hudson prospectus. Instead, the disclosure merely said that the CDO's contents were 'assets sourced from the Street', making it sound as though Goldman randomly selected the securities, instead of specifically creating a hedge for its won book.}}</ref> The CDO did not perform well, and by March 2008 - just 18 months after its issue - so many borrowers had defaulted that holders of the security paid out \"about US$310 million to Goldman and others who had bet against it\".<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2009December24MorgensonGretchen\" /> Goldman's head of European fixed-income sales lamented in an e-mail made public by the Senate Permanent Subcommittee on Investigations, the \"real bad feeling across European sales about some of the trades we did with clients\" who had invested in the CDO. \"The damage this has done to our franchise is very significant.\"<ref name=\"devils-p274-2\">{{cite book | author1=Bethany McLean | author2=Joe Nocera | title=All the Devils Are Here: The Hidden History of the Financial Crisis | page=274}}</ref>\n\n====2010 SEC civil fraud lawsuit====\nIn April 2010, the [[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]] (SEC) charged Goldman Sachs and one of its vice-presidents, Fabrice Tourre, with securities fraud. The SEC alleged that Goldman had told buyers of a [[synthetic CDO]], a type of investment, that the underlying assets in the investment had been picked by an independent CDO manager, ACA Management. In fact, [[Paulson & Co.]] a [[hedge fund]] that wanted to bet against the investment had played a \"significant role\" in the selection,<ref name=\"FCIR-p192\">''[http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/GPO-FCIC/pdf/GPO-FCIC.pdf Financial Crisis Inquiry Report]'', by the Financial Crisis Inquiry Commission, 2011, p.192</ref> and the package of securities turned out to become \"one of the worst-performing mortgage deals of the housing crisis\" because \"less than a year after the deal was completed, 100% of the bonds selected for Abacus had been downgraded\".<ref name=\"WSJ2010April20LucchettiAaron\">{{cite news|last1=Lucchetti|first1=Aaron|last2=Ng|first2=Serena|title=Abacus Deal: As Bad as They Come|journal=The Wall Street Journal. Eastern Edition|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748703757504575194521257607284|accessdate=February 26, 2014|agency=Dow Jones & Company Inc|issue=Business|publisher=Wall Street Journal|date=April 20, 2010|location=United States|language=English|url-access=subscription|issn=0099-9660}}</ref>\n\nThe particular synthetic CDO that the SEC's 2010 fraud suit charged Goldman with misleading investors with was called Abacus 2007-AC1. Unlike many of the Abacus securities, 2007-AC1 did not have Goldman Sachs as a short seller, in fact, Goldman Sachs lost money on the deal.<ref name=7pillars>{{cite web | title=Goldman Sachs and The ABACUS Deal | url=http://sevenpillarsinstitute.org/case-studies/goldman-sachs-and-the-abacus-deal | first1=Philip | last1=Whalen | first2=Kara | last2=Tan Bhala | publisher=[[Seven Pillars Institute]] }}</ref> That position was taken by the customer ([[John Paulson]]) who hired Goldman to issue the security (according to the SEC's complaint). Paulson and his employees selected 90 BBB-rated mortgage bonds<ref name=\"WSJ2010April20LucchettiAaron\" /><ref name=\"Reuters2010April16WilchinsDan\">{{cite news|last1=Wilchins|first1=Dan|last2=Brettell|first2=Karen|title=Factbox: How Goldman's ABACUS deal worked|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-goldmansachs-abacus-factbox/factbox-how-goldmans-abacus-deal-worked-idUSTRE63F5CZ20100416|accessdate=February 9, 2014|agency=Thompson Reuters|issue=Business News|publisher=Reuters|date=April 16, 2010|location=New York, N.Y., United States|language=English|quote=''Hedge fund manager John Paulson tells Goldman Sachs in late 2006 he wants to bet against risky subprime mortgages using derivatives. The risky mortgage bonds that Paulson wanted to short were essentially subprime home loans that had been repackaged into bonds. The bonds were rated \"BBB\", meaning that as the home loans defaulted, these bonds would be among the first to feel the pain.''}}</ref> that they believed were most likely to lose value and so the best bet to buy insurance for.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2010July15\" /> Paulson and the manager of the CDO, ACA Management, worked on the portfolio of 90 bonds to be insured (ACA allegedly unaware of Paulson's short position), coming to an agreement in late February 2007.<ref name=\"Reuters2010April16WilchinsDan\" /> Paulson paid Goldman approximately US$15 million for its work in the deal.<ref>The $15 million has been described as \"rent\" for the Abacus name. <br />{{cite book|author1=Bethany McLean |author2=Joe Nocera |title=All the Devils Are Here: The Hidden History of the Financial Crisis |page=279|quote=Paulson knocked on Goldman's door at a fortuitous moment. The firm had begun thinking about 'ABACUS-renal strategies' ... By that, he meant that Goldman would 'rent' - for a hefty fee - the Abacus brand to a hedge fund that wanted to make a massive short bet. ... Paulson paid Goldman $15 million to rent the Abacus name.}}</ref> Paulson ultimately made a US$1 billion profit from the short investments, the profits coming from the losses of the investors and their insurers. These were primarily [[IKB Deutsche Industriebank]] (US$150 million loss), and the investors and insurers of another US$900 million - ACA Financial Guaranty Corp,<ref name=\"Reuters2010April19SalmonFelix\">{{cite news|last1=Salmon|first1=Felix|title=Goldman's misleading statement on ACA|url=http://blogs.reuters.com/felix-salmon/2010/04/19/goldmans-misleading-statement-on-aca/|accessdate=August 14, 2010|agency=Thompson Reuters|issue=Blogs|publisher=Reuters|date=April 19, 2010|language=English|quote=when Goldman wrapped the super-senior tranche of the Abacus deal, it did so with ABN Amro, a too-big-to-fail bank, and not with ACA. ABN Amro then laid off that risk onto ACA, but was on the hook for all of it if ACA went bust. As, of course, it did.}}</ref> [[ABN AMRO]], and the [[Royal Bank of Scotland]].<ref name=\"sec21489\" /><ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2010April22ThomasLandon\">{{cite news|last1=Thomas|first1=Landon|title=A Routine Deal Became an $840 Million Mistake|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/04/23/business/23cdo.html|accessdate=February 27, 2014|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=Business|page=A1|work=New York Times|date=April 22, 2010|location=New York, N.Y., United States|language=English|url-access=limited|quote=R.B.S. [Royal Bank of Scotland] became involved in Abacus almost by accident. Bankers working in London for ABN Amro, a Dutch bank that was later acquired by R.B.S., agreed to stand behind a portfolio of American mortgage investments that were used in the deal. ABN Amro shouldered almost all of the risks for what, in retrospect, might seem like a small reward: that $7 million. When the housing market fell and Abacus collapsed, R.B.S. ended up on the hook for most of the losses.}}</ref>\n\nThe SEC alleged that Goldman \"materially misstated and omitted facts in disclosure documents\" about the financial security,<ref name=\"FCIR-p192\" /> including the fact that it had \"permitted a client that was betting against the mortgage market [the hedge fund manager Paulson & Co.] to heavily influence which mortgage securities to include in an investment portfolio, while telling other investors that the securities were selected by an independent, objective third party\", ACA Management.<ref name=\"sec21489\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sec.gov/litigation/complaints/2010/comp21489.pdf|date=April 16, 2010|publisher=[[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]]|title=Securities and Exchange Commission vs Goldman Sachs & Co & Fabrice Tourre, Complaint (Securities Fraud)|accessdate=April 17, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release | url=https://www.sec.gov/news/press/2010/2010-59.htm | title=SEC Charges Goldman Sachs With Fraud in Structuring and Marketing of CDO Tied to Subprime Mortgages | publisher=[[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]] | date=April 16, 2010}}</ref> The SEC further alleged that \"Tourre also misled ACA into believing ... that Paulson's interests in the collateral section [sic] process were aligned with ACA's, when, in reality, Paulson's interests were sharply conflicting\".<ref name=\"sec21489\" />\n\nIn reply, Goldman issued a statement saying the SEC's charges were \"unfounded in law and fact\", and in later statements maintained that it had not structured the portfolio to lose money,<ref name=\"Goldman-Media Release\" /> that it had provided extensive disclosure to the long investors in the CDO, that it had lost $90 million, that ACA selected the portfolio without Goldman suggesting Paulson was to be a long investor, that it did not disclose the identities of a buyer to a seller, and vice versa, as it was not normal business practice for a market maker,<ref name=\"Goldman-Media Release\" /> and that ACA was itself the largest purchaser of the Abacus pool, investing US$951 million. Goldman also stated that any investor losses resulted from the overall negative performance of the entire sector, rather than from a particular security in the CDO.<ref name=\"Goldman-Media Release\">{{cite press release | url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20100416006143/en/Goldman-Sachs-Comments-SEC-Complaint | title=Goldman Sachs Makes Further Comments on SEC Complaint | publisher=[[Business Wire]] | date=April 16, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"WSJ2010April19CorkeryMichael\">{{cite news|last1=Corkery|first1=Michael|title=Goldman Responds Again to SEC Complaint|journal=The Wall Street Journal. Eastern Edition|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/deals/2010/04/19/goldman-responds-again-to-sec-complaint/|accessdate=May 18, 2017|agency=Dow Jones & Company Inc|issue=Blogs|publisher=Wall Street Journal|date=April 19, 2010|location=United States|language=English|url-access=subscription|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> While some journalists and analysts have called these statements misleading,<ref name=\"Reuters2010April19SalmonFelix\" /> others believed Goldman's defense was strong and the SEC's case was weak.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://justoneminute.typepad.com/main/2010/04/cnbc-on-the-goldman-complaint-this-is-surreal.html |title=CNBC On The Goldman Complaint - This Is Surreal | publisher=Justoneminute.typepad.com | first=Tom | last=Maguire | date=April 21, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2010/04/20/betting-the-farm-on-goldman | title=The SEC's Dangerous Gamble | first=Harvey | last=Pitt | authorlink=Harvey Pitt | newspaper=[[The Daily Beast]] | date=April 20, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.theatlantic.com/business/archive/2010/04/goldman-in-the-eye-of-the-beholder/39255/ |title=Goldman in the Eye of the Beholder | publisher=[[The Atlantic]] | date=October 29, 2011}}</ref>\n\nSome experts on securities law such as [[Duke University School of Law|Duke University]] law professor James Cox, believed the suit had merit because Goldman was aware of the relevance of Paulson's involvement and took steps to downplay it. Others, including [[Wayne State University Law School]] law professor Peter Henning, noted that the major purchasers were sophisticated investors capable of accurately assessing the risks involved, even without knowledge of the part played by Paulson.<ref name=\"WSJ2010April19JonesAshby\">{{cite news|last1=Jones|first1=Ashby|title=Goldman v. SEC: It's All About Materiality|journal=The Wall Street Journal. Eastern Edition|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/law/2010/04/19/goldman-v-sec-its-all-about-materiality/|accessdate=April 20, 2010|agency=Dow Jones & Company Inc|issue=Blogs|publisher=Wall Street Journal|date=April 19, 2010|location=United States|language=English|url-access=subscription|issn=0099-9660}}</ref>\n\nCritics of Goldman Sachs point out that Paulson went to Goldman Sachs after being turned down for ethical reasons by another investment bank, [[Bear Stearns]] who he had asked to build a CDO. Ira Wagner, the head of Bear Stearns's CDO Group in 2007, told the [[Financial Crisis Inquiry Commission]] that having the short investors select the referenced collateral as a serious conflict of interest and the structure of the deal Paulson was proposing encouraged Paulson to pick the worst assets.<ref>''Federal Crisis Inquiry Report'', p.193</ref><ref name=Fiderer>{{cite news | title=The Moral Compass Missing From The Greatest Trade Ever | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/david-fiderer/the-moral-compass-missing_b_358856.html | last=Fiderer | first=David | work=[[The Huffington Post]] | date= May 25, 2011}}</ref> Describing Bear Stearns's reasoning, one author compared the deal to \"a bettor asking a football owner to bench a star quarterback to improve the odds of his wager against the team\".<ref name=Zuckerman>{{cite news | last=Zuckerman|first=Gregory|title=Inside Paulson's Deal with Goldman |url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2010/04/19/inside-paulsons-deal-with-goldman.html|date=April 19, 2010|newspaper=Daily Beast|quote=Scott Eichel, a senior Bear Stearns trader, was among those at the investment bank who sat through a meeting with Paulson but later turned down the idea. He worried that Paulson would want especially ugly mortgages for the CDOs, like a bettor asking a football owner to bench a star quarterback to improve the odds of his wager against the team. Either way, he felt it would look improper. ... it didn't pass the ethics standards; it was a reputation issue, and it didn't pass our moral compass. |accessdate=February 6, 2014}}</ref> Goldman claimed it lost $90 million, critics maintain it was simply unable (not due to a lack of trying) to shed its position before the underlying securities defaulted.<ref name=7pillars />\n\nCritics also question whether the deal was ethical, even if it was legal.<ref name=\"devils-ethics-2\">{{cite book |author1=Bethany McLean |author2=Joe Nocera |title=All the Devils Are Here: The Hidden History of the Financial Crisis |page=278 |quote=... in truth, the legal issues were far from the most disturbing thing about Abacus 2007-ACI}}</ref><ref name=chron /> Goldman had considerable advantages over its long customers. According to McLean and Nocera, there were dozens of securities being insured in the CDO - for example, another ABACUS<ref>called ABACUS 2005-3</ref> - had 130 credits from several different mortgage originators, commercial mortgage-backed securities, debt from Sallie Mae, credit cards, etc. Goldman bought mortgages to create securities, which made it \"far more likely than its clients to have early knowledge\" that the housing bubble was deflating and the mortgage originators like [[New Century]] had begun to falsify documentation and sell mortgages to customers unable to pay the mortgage-holders back<ref name=\"McLean-272\" /> - which is why the fine print on at least one ABACUS prospectus warned long investors that the 'Protection Buyer' (Goldman) 'may have information, including material, non-public information' which it was not providing to the long investors.<ref name=\"McLean-272\">McLean and Nocera, ''All the Devils Are Here'', 2010, p.272</ref>\n\nAccording to an article in the ''[[Houston Chronicle]]'', critics also worried that Abacus might undermine the position of the US \"as a safe harbor for the world's investors\" and that \"The involvement of European interests as losers in this allegedly fixed game has attracted the attention of that region's political leaders, most notably British Prime Minister Gordon Brown, who has accused Goldman of \"moral bankruptcy\". This is, in short, a big global story ... Is what Goldman Sachs did with its Abacus investment vehicle illegal? That will be for the courts to decide, ... But it doesn't take a judge and jury to conclude that, legalities aside, this was just wrong.\"<ref name=chron>{{cite web | url=http://www.chron.com/opinion/editorials/article/The-Goldman-case-Legal-or-illegal-the-Abacus-1704276.php | title=The Goldman case: Legal or illegal, the Abacus deal was morally wrong. Wall Street needs a new compass | work=[[Houston Chronicle]] | date=April 22, 2010}}</ref> On July 15, 2010, Goldman settled out of court, agreeing to pay the SEC and investors US$550 million, including $300 million to the U.S. government and $250 million to investors, one of the largest penalties ever paid by a Wall Street firm.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2010July15\" /> In August 2013, Tourre was found liable on 6 of 7 counts by a federal jury.<ref name=\"Reuters2013August1RaymondNate\">{{cite news|last1=Raymond|first1=Nate|title=SEC wins as ex-Goldman executive Tourre found liable for fraud|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-sec-goldman-tourre-idUSBRE96G19720130801|accessdate=February 27, 2014|agency=Thompson Reuters|issue=Business News|publisher=Reuters|date=August 1, 2013|location=New York, N.Y., United States|language=English}}</ref><ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2013August1CraigSusanne\">{{cite news|last1=Craig|first1=Susanne|last2=Protess|first2=Ben|title=Former Trader Is Found Liable in Fraud Case|url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2013/08/01/former-goldman-trader-is-found-liable-in-mortgage-deal/|accessdate=August 1, 2013|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=DealBook|work=New York Times|date=August 1, 2013|location=New York, N.Y., United States|language=English|url-access=limited}}</ref> The company did not admit or deny wrongdoing, but did admit that its marketing materials for the investment \"contained incomplete information\", and agreed to change some of its business practices regarding mortgage investments.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2010July15\" />\n\n====Tourre defense of ABACUS lawsuit====\nThe 2010 Goldman settlement did not cover charges against Goldman vice president and salesman for ABACUS, Fabrice Tourre.<ref name=7pillars/><ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2010July15\">{{cite news|title=Goldman Settles With S.E.C. for $550 Million|url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2010/07/15/goldman-to-settle-with-s-e-c-for-550-million/|accessdate=May 18, 2017|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=DealBook|work=New York Times|date=July 15, 2010|location=United States|language=English|url-access=limited}}</ref> Tourre unsuccessfully sought a dismissal of the suit,<ref name=\"Reuters2010September30StempelJonathan\">{{cite news|last1=Stempel|first1=Jonathan|last2=Wallace|first2=John|title=Goldman's Tourre says SEC suit should be dismissed|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-goldman-tourre-idUSTRE68T3L120100930|accessdate=September 30, 2010|agency=Thompson Reuters|issue=Business News|publisher=Reuters|date=September 30, 2010|location=New York, N.Y., United States|language=English}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/jurors-hear-closing-arguments-in-sec-fraud-case-against-fabrice-tourre/2013/07/30/a50da674-f954-11e2-b018-5b8251f0c56e_story.html | title=Jurors hear closing arguments in SEC fraud case against Fabrice Tourre | last=ElBoghdady | first=Dina| work=[[The Washington Post]] | date=July 30, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"WSJ2010September28KoppelNathan\">{{cite news|last1=Koppel|first1=Nathan|last2=Jones|first2=Ashby|title=Securities Ruling Limits Claims of Fraud|journal=The Wall Street Journal. Eastern Edition|url=http://online.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748703694204575518301351548676|accessdate=May 18, 2017|agency=Dow Jones & Company Inc|issue=Business|publisher=Wall Street Journal|date=September 28, 2010|location=United States|language=English|url-access=subscription|issn=0099-9660}}</ref><ref name=\"WSJ2010September29BrayChad\">{{cite news|last1=Bray|first1=Chad|title=Goldman Trader Seeks Suit Dismissal|journal=The Wall Street Journal. Eastern Edition|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704116004575522600695880486|accessdate=May 18, 2017|agency=Dow Jones & Company Inc|issue=Business|publisher=Wall Street Journal|date=September 29, 2010|location=New York, N.Y., United States|language=English|url-access=subscription|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> which then went to trial in 2013. On August 1, a federal jury found Tourre liable on six of seven counts, including that he misled investors about the mortgage deal. He was found not liable on the charge that he had deliberately made an untrue or misleading statement.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2013August1CraigSusanne\" />\n\n===Alleged commodity price manipulation===\n{{Hatnote|See also: [[2000s commodities boom]]}}\n\nA provision of the 1999 financial deregulation law, the [[Gramm-Leach-Bliley Act]], allows commercial banks to enter into any business activity that is \"complementary to a financial activity and does not pose a substantial risk to the safety or soundness of depository institutions or the financial system generally\".<ref name=devious>{{cite journal | last=Taibbi | first=Matt | title=The Vampire Squid Strikes Again: The Mega Banks' Most Devious Scam Yet | journal=Rolling Stone | date=February 12, 2014 | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/news/the-vampire-squid-strikes-again-the-mega-banks-most-devious-scam-yet-20140212|accessdate=February 14, 2014}}</ref> In the years since the laws passing, Goldman Sachs and other investment banks (Morgan Stanley, JPMorgan Chase) have branched out into ownership of a wide variety of enterprises including raw materials, such as food products, zinc, copper, tin, nickel and, aluminum.\n\nSome critics, such as Matt Taibbi, believe that allowing a company to both \"control the supply of crucial physical commodities, and also trade in the financial products that might be related to those markets\", is \"akin to letting casino owners who take book on NFL games during the week also coach all the teams on Sundays\".<ref name=devious/>\n\n===Unauthorized trades by Goldman Sachs trader Matthew Marshall Taylor===\nFormer Goldman Sachs trader Matthew Marshall Taylor was convicted of hiding $8.3 billion worth of unauthorized trades involving derivatives on the [[S&P 500]] index by making \"multiple false entries\" into a Goldman trading system. When Goldman Sachs management uncovered the trades, Taylor was immediately fired. The trades cost the company $118 million, which Taylor was ordered to repay. In 2013, Taylor plead guilty to charges and was sentenced to 9 months in prison in addition to the monetary damages.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2013December6AbramsRachel\">{{cite news|last1=Abrams|first1=Rachel|title=Ex-Goldman Trader Sentenced to 9 Months in Prison|url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2013/12/06/ex-goldman-trader-sentenced-to-9-months-in-prison/|accessdate=April 21, 2016|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=DealBook|work=New York Times|date=December 6, 2013|location=New York, N.Y., United States|language=English|url-access=limited}}</ref>\n\n====Goldman Sachs Commodity Index and the 2005-2008 Food Bubble====\nFrederick Kaufman, a contributing editor of ''[[Harper's Magazine]]'', argued in a 2010 article that Goldman's creation of the Goldman Sachs Commodity Index (now the [[S&P GSCI]]) helped passive investors such as pension funds, mutual funds and others engage in food price [[speculation]] by betting on financial products based on the commodity index. These financial products disturbed the normal relationship between [[supply and demand]], making prices more volatile and defeating the price stabilization mechanism of the futures exchange.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://frederickkaufman.typepad.com/files/the-food-bubble-pdf.pdf | title=The Food Bubble: How Wall Street Starved Millions and got away with it | first=Frederick | last=Kaufman | publisher=[[Harper's Magazine]] | date=July 1, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.democracynow.org/2010/7/16/the_food_bubble_how_wall_street | title=The Food Bubble: How Wall Street Starved Millions and Got Away With It | first1=Amy | last1=Goodman | first2=Juan | last2=Gonzales | first3=Frederick | last3=Kaufman | publisher=[[Democracy Now!]] | date=July 16, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.pacificfreepress.com/news/1/6154-a-global-food-bubble.pdf | title=Global Food Bubble? (interview with Jayati Ghosh) | publisher=[[Atlantic Free Press]] | last=Jay | first=Paul | date=May 6, 2010}}</ref>\n\nA June 2010 article in ''[[The Economist]]'' defended commodity investors and oil index-tracking funds, citing a report by the [[Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development]] that found that commodities without futures markets and ignored by index-tracking funds also saw price rises during the period.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.economist.com/node/16432870 | title=Clearing the usual suspects | last=Buttonwood | work=[[The Economist]] | date=June 24, 2010 |url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\n====Aluminum price and supply====\nIn a July 2013 article, [[David Kocieniewski]], a journalist with ''[[The New York Times]]'' accused Goldman Sachs and other Wall Street firms of \"capitalizing on loosened federal regulations\" to manipulate \"a variety of commodities markets\", particularly aluminum, citing \"financial records, regulatory documents, and interviews with people involved in the activities\".<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2013July20KocieniewskiDavid\">{{cite news|last1=Kocieniewski|first1=David|title=A Shuffle of Aluminum, but to Banks, Pure Gold|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/21/business/a-shuffle-of-aluminum-but-to-banks-pure-gold.html|accessdate=February 27, 2014|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=Business|page=A1|work=New York Times|date=July 20, 2013|location=United States|language=English|url-access=limited}}</ref> After Goldman Sachs purchased aluminum warehousing company Metro International in 2010, the wait of warehouse customers for delivery of aluminum supplies to their factories - to make beer cans, home siding, and other products - went from an average of 6 weeks to more than 16 months, \"according to industry records\".<ref name=Zamansky /><ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2013July20KocieniewskiDavid\" /> \"Aluminum industry analysts say that the lengthy delays at Metro International after Goldman took over are a major reason the premium on all aluminum sold in the spot market has doubled since 2010.\"<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2013July20KocieniewskiDavid\" /> The price increase has cost \"American consumers more than $5 billion\" from 2010 to 2013 according to former industry executives, analysts and consultants.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2013July20KocieniewskiDavid\" /> The cause of this was alleged to be Goldman's ownership of a quarter of the national supply of aluminum - a million and a half tons - in network of 27 Metro International warehouses Goldman owns in Detroit, Michigan.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2013July20KocieniewskiDavid\" /><ref name=Stanley>{{cite web | url=https://www.usnews.com/opinion/blogs/economic-intelligence/2013/07/24/how-goldman-sachs-and-wall-street-manipulate-alumnimum-and-other-commodities | title=The Goldman Sachs Guide To Manipulating Commodities | last=Stanley | first=Marcus | work=[[U.S. News & World Report]] | date=July 24, 2013}}</ref> To avoid hoarding and price manipulation, the London Metal Exchange requires that \"at least 3,000 tons of that metal must be moved out each day\". Goldman has dealt with this requirement by moving the aluminum - not to factories, but \"from one warehouse to another\" - according to the Times.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2013July20KocieniewskiDavid\" />\n\nIn August 2013, Goldman Sachs was subpoenaed by the federal [[Commodity Futures Trading Commission]] as part of an investigation into complaints that Goldman-owned metals warehouses had \"intentionally created delays and inflated the price of aluminum\".<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2013August12KocieniewskiDavid\">{{cite news|last1=Kocieniewski|first1=David|title=U.S. Subpoenas Goldman in Inquiry of Aluminum Warehouses|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/08/13/business/us-subpoenas-goldman-in-inquiry-of-aluminum-warehouses.html|accessdate=February 27, 2014|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=Business|page=B3|work=New York Times|date=August 12, 2013|location=New York, N.Y., United States|language=English|url-access=limited}}</ref> In December 2013, it was announced that 26 cases accusing Goldman Sachs and JPMorgan Chase, the two investment banks' warehousing businesses, and the London Metal Exchange in various combinations - of violating U.S. anti-trust laws, would be assigned to [[United States District Court for the Southern District of New York]] Judge [[Katherine B. Forrest]] in [[Manhattan]].<ref name=Harris>{{cite news | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2013-12-16/goldman-sachs-aluminum-antitrust-suits-shipped-to-nyc | title=Goldman Sachs Aluminum Antitrust Suits Shipped to NYC | first=Andrew |last=Harris | publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]] | date=December 16, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Lydia DePillis of Wonkblog, when Goldman bought the warehouses it \"started paying traders extra to bring their metal\" to Goldman's warehouses \"rather than anywhere else. The longer it stays, the more rent Goldman can charge, which is then passed on to the buyer in the form of a premium.\"<ref name=DePillis>{{cite news | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonk/wp/2013/07/22/heres-how-goldman-sachs-is-making-your-beer-more-expensive/ | title=Here's how Goldman Sachs is making your beer more expensive | first=Lydia | last=DePillis | work=[[The Washington Post]] | date=July 22, 2013}}</ref> The effect is \"amplified\" by another company, [[Glencore]], which is \"doing the same thing in its warehouse in [[Vlissingen]]\".<ref name=DePillis />\n\nMichael DuVally, a spokesman for Goldman Sachs, said the cases are without merit.<ref name=Harris /> Columnist Matt Levine, writing for ''[[Bloomberg News]]'', described the conspiracy theory as \"pretty silly\", but said that it was a rational outcome of an irrational and inefficient system which Goldman Sachs may not have properly understood.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/view/articles/2014-11-20/the-goldman-sachs-aluminum-conspiracy-was-pretty-silly | title=The Goldman Sachs Aluminum Conspiracy Was Pretty Silly | first=Matt | last=Levine | work=[[Bloomberg News]] | date=November 20, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2014, Goldman Sachs sold its aluminum warehousing business to Ruben Brothers.<ref name=\"WSJ2014December22BerthelsenChristian\">{{cite news|last1=Berthelsen|first1=Christian|last2=Iosebashvili|first2=Ira|title=Goldman Sachs Sells Aluminum Business to Swiss Firm|journal=The Wall Street Journal. Eastern Edition|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/goldman-sachs-sells-aluminum-business-to-swiss-firm-1419279027|accessdate=May 21, 2017|agency=Dow Jones & Company Inc|issue=Markets|publisher=Wall Street Journal|date=December 22, 2014|location=United States|language=English|url-access=subscription|issn=0099-9660}}</ref><ref name=\"Reuters2014December22LeffJonathan\">{{cite news|last1=Leff|first1=Jonathan|last2=Mason|first2=Josephine|title=UPDATE 2-Goldman sells Metro metals warehouse unit to Reuben Bros|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/goldman-metro-idUSL1N0U61FW20141222|accessdate=May 21, 2017|agency=Thompson Reuters|issue=Fund News|publisher=Reuters|date=December 22, 2014|location=New York, N.Y., United States|language=English}}</ref><ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2014December22PopperNathaniel\">{{cite news|last1=Popper|first1=Nathaniel|title=Goldman Sells Aluminum Subsidiary|url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/12/22/goldman-sells-aluminum-subsidiary/|accessdate=May 21, 2017|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=DealBook|page=B5|work=New York Times|date=December 22, 2014|location=New York, N.Y., United States|language=English|url-access=limited}}</ref>\n\n====Oil futures speculation====\nInvestment banks, including Goldman, have also been accused of driving up the price of [[gasoline]] by speculating on the oil [[futures exchange]]. In August 2011, \"confidential documents\" were leaked \"detailing the positions\"<ref name=Sheppard/> in the oil futures market of several investment banks, including Goldman Sachs, [[Morgan Stanley]], [[JPMorgan Chase]], [[Deutsche Bank]], and [[Barclays]], just before the peak in gasoline prices in the summer of 2008. The presence of positions by investment banks on the market was significant for the fact that the banks have deep pockets, and so the means to significantly sway prices, and unlike traditional market participants, neither produced oil nor ever took physical possession of actual barrels of oil they bought and sold. Journalist Kate Sheppard of [[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]] called it \"a development that many say is artificially raising the price of crude\".<ref name=Sheppard>{{cite news | url=https://www.motherjones.com/environment/2011/09/oil-speculators-goldman-sachs | title=$4 Gas: Brought to You by Wall Street | last=Sheppard | first=Kate | publisher=[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]] | date=September 8, 2011}}</ref> However, another source stated that, \"Just before crude oil hit its record high in mid-2008, 15 of the world's largest banks were betting that prices would fall, according to private trading data...\"<ref name=sanders>{{cite news | url=http://fuelfix.com/blog/2011/08/29/big-banks-bet-crude-oil-prices-would-fall-in-2008-run-up-leaked-data-show/ | title=Big Banks Bet Crude Oil Prices Would Fall in 2008 Run-Up, Leaked Data Show | work=[[Bloomberg L.P.]] | quote=Just before crude oil hit its record high in mid-2008, 15 of the world's largest banks were betting that prices would fall, according to private trading data released by U.S. Senator Bernie Sanders. The net positions of the banks undermine arguments made by Sanders that speculative trades on Wall Street drove oil prices in 2008, said Craig Pirrong, director of the Global Energy Management Institute at the University of Houston. Retail gasoline reached a record $4.08 a gallon on July 7, 2008, and oil peaked at $147.27 a barrel on July 11 that year.}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2011, a couple of observers - Brad Johnson of the blog Climate Progress,<ref name=blame/> founded by [[Joseph J. Romm]], and Alain Sherter of [[CBS MoneyWatch]]<ref name=Sherter/> - noted that Goldman Sachs was warning investors of a dangerous spike in the price of oil. Climate Progress quoted Goldman as warning \"that the price of oil has grown out of control due to excessive speculation\" in petroleum futures, and that \"net speculative positions are four times as high as in June 2008\", when the price of oil peaked.<ref name=sanders/>\n\nIt stated that, \"Goldman Sachs told its clients that it believed speculators like itself had artificially driven the price of oil at least $20 higher than supply and demand dictate.\"<ref name=blame>{{cite web | title=Goldman Sachs Admits Record Speculation To Blame For Skyrocketing Gas Prices | url=https://thinkprogress.org/goldman-sachs-admits-record-speculation-to-blame-for-skyrocketing-gas-prices-2d3eb98320d2/ | first=Brad | last=Johnson | publisher=[[ThinkProgress]] | date=April 13, 2011}}</ref> Sherter noted that Goldman's concern over speculation did not prevent it (along with other speculators) from lobbying against regulations by the Commodity Futures Trading Commission to establish \"position limits\", which would cap the number of futures contracts a trader can hold, and thus prevent speculation.<ref name=Sherter>{{cite news | url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/when-goldman-sachs-warns-that-speculation-drives-oil-prices-listen-up/ | title=When Goldman Sachs Warns That Speculation Drives Oil Prices, Listen Up | first=Alain | last=Sherter | work=[[CBS News]] | date=April 13, 2011}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Joseph P. Kennedy II, by 2012, prices on the oil commodity market had become influenced by \"hedge funds and bankers\" pumping \"billions of purely speculative dollars into commodity exchanges, chasing a limited number of barrels and driving up the price\".<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2012April10KennedyJoseph\" /> The problem started, according to Kennedy, in 1991, when <blockquote>just a few years after oil futures began trading on the [[New York Mercantile Exchange]], Goldman Sachs made an argument to the Commodity Futures Trading Commission that Wall Street dealers who put down big bets on oil should be considered legitimate hedgers and granted an exemption from regulatory limits on their trades.\n\nThe commission granted an exemption that ultimately allowed Goldman Sachs to process billions of dollars in speculative oil trades. Other exemptions followed,<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2012April10KennedyJoseph\" /></blockquote> and \"by 2008, eight investment banks accounted for 32% of the total oil futures market\".<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2012April10KennedyJoseph\">{{cite news|last1=Kennedy|first1=Joseph|title=The High Cost of Gambling on Oil|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/04/11/opinion/ban-pure-speculators-of-oil-futures.html|accessdate=February 27, 2014|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=Opinions|page=A23|work=New York Times|date=April 10, 2012|location=Boston, MA, United States|language=English|url-access=limited}}</ref>\n\n===Danish utility sale (2014)===\nGoldman Sachs's purchase of an 18% stake in state-owned [[DONG Energy]] (now [[\u00d8rsted (company)|\u00d8rsted A/S]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/10/02/dong-energy-changes-name-to-orsted-goes-big-on-renewables.html|title=Dong Energy changes name to Orsted goes big on renewables|last=Frangoul|first=Anmar|date=2017-10-02|website=www.cnbc.com|access-date=2019-04-12}}</ref>) - [[Denmark]]'s largest electric utility - set off a \"political crisis\" in [[Denmark]]. The sale - approved in January 30, 2014 - sparked protest in the form of the resignation of six cabinet ministers and the withdrawal of a party ([[Socialist People's Party (Denmark)|Socialist People's Party]]) from Prime Minister [[Helle Thorning-Schmidt]]'s leftist governing coalition.<ref name=Levring>{{cite web | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2014-02-06/in-denmark-goldman-sachs-deal-ignites-political-crisis | title=In Denmark, Goldman Sachs Deal Ignites Political Crisis | last1=Levring | first1=Peter | first2=Christian | last2=Wienberg | publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]] | date=February 6, 2014}}</ref> According to ''[[Bloomberg Businessweek]]'', \"the role of Goldman in the deal struck a nerve with the Danish public, which is still suffering from the after-effects of the global financial crisis\". Protesters in [[Copenhagen]] gathered around a banner \"with a drawing of a vampire squid - the description of Goldman used by Matt Taibbi in Rolling Stone in 2009\".<ref name=Levring /> Opponents expressed concern that Goldman would have some say in DONG's management, and that Goldman planned to manage its investment through \"subsidiaries in Luxembourg, the Cayman Islands, and Delaware, which made Danes suspicious that the bank would shift earnings to tax havens\".<ref name=Levring /> Goldman purchased the 18% stake in 2014 for 8 billion kroner and sold just over a 6% stake in 2017 for 6.5 billion kroner.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-02-05/goldman-sale-reignites-conspiracy-theories-in-danish-parliament | title=Goldman Sale Reignites Conspiracy Theories in Danish Parliament | last=Levring | first=Peter | publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]] | date=February 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Libya investment losses (2013)===\nIn January 2014, the [[Libyan Investment Authority]] (LIA) filed a lawsuit against Goldman for $1 billion after the firm lost 98% of the $1.3 billion the LIA invested with Goldman in 2007.<ref name=Hodges/><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/afontevecchia/2011/05/31/goldman-sachs-lost-98-of-libyas-1-3b-sovereign-wealth-fund-investment/ | title=Goldman Sachs Lost 98% of Libya's $1.3B Sovereign Wealth Fund Investment | first=Agustino | last=Fontevecchia | work=[[Forbes (magazine)|Forbes]] | date=May 31, 2011}}</ref>\n\nGoldman made more than $1 billion in derivatives trades with the LIA funds, which lost almost all their value but earned Goldman $350 million in profit.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2014January30AndersonJenny\">{{cite news|last1=Anderson|first1=Jenny|title=Libyan Investment Fund Sues Goldman Over Loss|url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/01/30/libyan-investment-fund-files-suit-against-goldman/|accessdate=August 19, 2014|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=DealBook|page=B7|work=New York Times|date=January 30, 2014|location=New York, N.Y., United States|language=English|url-access=limited}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2014/nov/24/goldman-sachs-libya-high-court | title=High court judge orders Goldman Sachs to disclose Libya profits | first=Jennifer | last=Rankin | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=November 24, 2014}}</ref> In court documents the firm has admitted to having used small gifts, occasional travel and an internship in order to gain access to Libya's sovereign wealth fund.<ref name=\"FinancialTimes2014September19BinhamCaroline\">{{cite news|last1=Binham|first1=Caroline|last2=Croft|first2=Jane|title=Goldman admits cultivating ties with Gaddafi-era Libya fund|url=https://www.ft.com/content/b2d79034-4021-11e4-936b-00144feabdc0|accessdate=March 7, 2016|agency=Nikkei|publisher=Financial Times|date=September 19, 2014|location=London|language=English|url-access=subscription}}</ref> In August 2014, Goldman dropped a bid to end the suit in a London court.<ref name=\"Hodges\">{{cite news | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-08-19/goldman-sachs-drops-bid-to-throw-out-libyan-wealth-fund-suit.html | title=Goldman Sachs Drops Bid to End Libyan Wealth Fund Suit | last1=Hodges | first1=Jeremy | work=[[Bloomberg News]] | date=August 19, 2014}}</ref> In October 2016, after trial, the court entered a judgment in Goldman Sachs's favor.\n\n===Improper securities lending practices===\nIn January 2016, Goldman Sachs agreed to pay $15 million after it was found that a team of Goldman employees, between 2008 and 2013, \"granted locates\" by arranging to borrow securities to settle short sales without adequate review. However, U.S. regulation for short selling requires brokerages to enter an agreement to borrow securities on behalf of customers or to have \"reasonable grounds\" for believing that it can borrow the security before entering contracts to complete the sale. Additionally, Goldman Sachs gave \"incomplete and unclear\" responses to information requests from SEC compliance examiners in 2013 about the firm's securities lending practices.<ref name=\"Reuters2016January14BarlynSuzanne\">{{cite news|last1=Barlyn|first1=Suzanne|last2=Hay|first2=Andrew|title=Goldman Sachs to pay $15 million to settle SEC stock lending case|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-goldman-sachs-sec-lending-idUSKCN0US2NN20160114|accessdate=February 1, 2016|agency=Thompson Reuters|issue=Wealth|publisher=Reuters|date=January 14, 2016|language=English}}</ref>\n\n===1MDB Malaysian sovereign wealth fund scandal (2015-present)===\n{{Main|1Malaysia Development Berhad scandal}}\nAccording to the [[Thomson Reuters league tables]], Goldman Sachs was the most successful foreign investment bank in Malaysia from 2011 to 2013. In 2013, the bank had a 21% [[market share]] in Malaysia's investment banking segment, double that of its nearest rival, mostly due to business with the Malaysian sovereign wealth fund, [[1Malaysia Development Berhad]] (1MDB).<ref name=\"Reuters2014January6KoswanageNiluksi\">{{cite news|last1=Koswanage|first1=Niluksi|last2=Azhar|first2=Saeed|title=Deutsche Bank hires Goldman Sachs's Malaysia head: sources|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-deutsche-malaysia-idUSBREA050CE20140106|accessdate=January 7, 2014|agency=Thompson Reuters|issue=Business News|publisher=Reuters|date=January 6, 2014|location=Singapore|language=English}}</ref><ref>Goldman reportedly scrutinized by police for relation to money laundering probe [https://www.cnbc.com/2017/11/02/1mdb-money-laundering-singapore-reportedly-probing-goldman-sachs-link.html]</ref>\n\nIn 2015, U.S. prosecutors began examining the role of Goldman in helping 1MDB raise more than $6 billion. The 1MDB bond deals were said to generate \"above-average\" commissions and fees for Goldman amounting close to $600 million or more than 9% of the proceeds.<ref>{{cite news | title=Goldman's Leissner Said to Get Money From Ex-1MDB Employee | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-05-18/goldman-s-leissner-said-to-get-money-from-ex-1mdb-employee | last1=Farrell | first1=Greg | last2=Geiger | first2=Keri | publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]] | date=May 18, 2016}}</ref>\n\nBeginning in 2016, Goldman was investigated for a $3 billion bond created by the bank for 1MDB. Prosecutors investigated whether the bank failed to comply with the U.S. [[Bank Secrecy]] Act, which requires financial institutions to report suspicious transactions to regulators.<ref name=\"WSJ2016June7BaerJustin\">{{cite news|last1=Baer|first1=Justin|last2=Wright|first2=Tom|title=Goldman Probed Over Malaysia Fund 1MDB|journal=The Wall Street Journal. Eastern Edition|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/goldman-probed-over-malaysia-fund-1465257383|accessdate=June 6, 2016|agency=Dow Jones & Company Inc|issue=Markets|publisher=Wall Street Journal|date=June 7, 2016|location=United States|language=English|url-access=subscription|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> In November 2018, Goldman's former chairman of Southeast Asia, Tim Leissner, admitted that more than US$200 million in proceeds from 1MDB bonds went into the accounts controlled by him and a relative.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-11-12/goldman-shares-tumble-to-2016-levels-as-1mdb-pressure-mounts|title=Goldman Sachs Tumbles on 1MDB Scandal and 'Fear of the Unknown'|website=www.bloomberg.com|access-date=2018-11-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/11/02/1mdb-how-did-leissner-and-other-execs-bypass-goldmans-compliance-rules/|title=1MDB: How did Leissner and other execs bypass Goldman's compliance rules? - Nation {{!}} The Star Online|website=www.thestar.com.my|access-date=November 14, 2018}}</ref> Leissner and another former Goldman banker, Roger Ng, together with Malaysian financier [[Jho Low]] were charged with money laundering.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-46062576 Ex-Goldman bankers face 1MDB charges] ''[[BBC]]''</ref> Goldman chief executive David Solomon felt \"horrible\" about the ex-staff breaking the law by going around the policies<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-goldmansachs-1mdb-probe/goldman-sachs-ceo-i-feel-horrible-ex-bankers-broke-law-in-1mdb-case-idUSKCN1NC0SN|title=Goldman Sachs CEO: I feel horrible ex-bankers broke law in 1MDB case|last=Geddie|first=John|work=U.S.|access-date=2018-11-08|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/11/07/goldman-sachs-ceo-i-feel-horrible-ex-bankers-broke-law/|title=Goldman Sachs CEO: I feel horrible ex-bankers broke law in 1MDB case - Nation {{!}} The Star Online|website=www.thestar.com.my|access-date=November 8, 2018}}</ref> and apologized to Malaysians for Leissner\u2019s role in the 1MDB scandal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theedgemarkets.com/article/goldman-ceo-apologises-leissners-role-1mdb-scandal|title=Goldman CEO apologises for Leissner's role in 1MDB scandal|date=2019-01-18|website=The Edge Markets|access-date=2019-01-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190118154500/http://www.theedgemarkets.com/article/goldman-ceo-apologises-leissners-role-1mdb-scandal|archive-date=January 18, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2019/01/18/goldman-sachs-ceo-apologises-for-exbankers-role-in-1mdb-scandal/|title=Goldman Sachs CEO apologises for ex-banker's role in 1MDB scandal - Nation {{!}} The Star Online|website=www.thestar.com.my|access-date=2019-01-18}}</ref>\n\nOn December 17, 2018, Malaysia filed criminal charges against subsidiaries of Goldman and their former employees Leissner and Ng, alleging their commission of misleading statements in order to dishonestly misappropriate US$2.7 billion from the proceeds of 1MDB bonds arranged and underwritten by Goldman in 2012 and 2013.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thesundaily.my/local/malaysia-files-charges-against-goldman-over-1mdb-scandal-JI280092|title=Malaysia files charges against Goldman over 1MDB scandal|website=www.thesundaily.my|language=en|access-date=December 17, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/12/17/agc-files-criminal-charges-against-subsidiaries-of-goldman-sachs-and-employees/|title=AGC files criminal charges against subsidiaries of Goldman Sachs and employees - Nation {{!}} The Star Online|date=December 17, 2018|website=www.thestar.com.my|access-date=December 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Purchase Petr\u00f3leos de Venezuela bonds (2017) ===\nIn May 2017, Goldman Sachs purchased $2.8 billion of PDVSA 2022 bonds from the [[Central Bank of Venezuela]] during the [[2017 Venezuelan protests]],<ref name=\"WSJ2017May28VyasKejal\" /> when the country was suffering from malnutrition and hyperinflation.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-venezuela-goldman-idUSKBN1HH36H|title=Amid Venezuela default, Goldman receives 'hunger bond' payment: sources|date=2018-04-10|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-04-13|language=en}}</ref> In its original statement, Goldman stated that \u201cWe recognize that the situation is complex and evolving and that Venezuela is in crisis. We agree that life there has to get better, and we made the investment in part because we believe it will.\u201d.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-venezuela-goldman-sachs-idUSKBN18Q1D6|title=Venezuelan opposition condemns Goldman for $2.8 billion bond deal|date=2017-05-31|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-04-13|language=en}}</ref> Venezuelan politicians and protesters in New York opposed to Maduro accused the bank of being of complicit of human rights abuses under the government and declared that the operation would fuel hunger in Venezuela by depriving the government of foreign exchange to import food, leading the securities to be dubbed \u201chunger bonds.\u201d<ref name=\":0\" /> The opposition-led [[National Assembly (Venezuela)|National Assembly]] voted to ask the [[United States Congress|U.S. Congress]] to investigate the deal, which they called \"immoral, opaque, and hypocritical given the socialist government\u2019s anti-Wall Street rhetoric\".<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nIn a public letter to the bank\u2019s chief executive, [[Lloyd Blankfein]], the National Assembly president [[Julio Borges]] said that \u201cGoldman Sachs\u2019s financial lifeline to the regime will serve to strengthen the brutal repression unleashed against the hundreds of thousands of Venezuelans peacefully protesting for political change in the country.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Rushe|first=Dominic|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/may/30/goldman-sachs-venezuela-bonds|title=Goldman Sachs condemned for buoying Venezuela with $2.8bn bond purchase|date=2017-05-30|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-13|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Sheila Patel, CEO of Goldman Sachs Asset Management\u2019s international division, said in an interview that the incident \"turned into a teachable moment within the firm\" and \"helped sharpen its focus on investing with an eye toward environmental, social and governance policies\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloombergquint.com/onweb/goldman-says-it-s-learned-from-venezuela-hunger-bonds-backlash|title=Goldman Says It's Learned From Venezuela `Hunger Bonds' Backlash|website=BloombergQuint|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n===Misreporting transactions===\nIn March 2019, Goldman Sachs was fined \u00a334.4 million by the City (London) regulator for misreporting millions of transactions over a decade.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/business/2019/mar/28/city-watchdog-fines-goldman-sachs-misreporting-transactions City watchdog fines Goldman Sachs \u00a334.4m for misreporting], ''Guardian'', March 28, 2019.</ref>\n\n==Political contributions==\nGoldman Sachs employees have donated to both major American political parties, as well as candidates and [[super PAC]]s belonging to both parties. According to the [[Center for Responsive Politics]], Goldman Sachs and its employees collectively gave $4.7 million in the [[2014 United States elections|2014 elections]] to various candidates, [[leadership PAC]]s, political parties, [[527 group]]s, and outside spending entities.<ref>[https://www.opensecrets.org/orgs/summary.php?id=d000000085 Goldman Sachs: Profile for 2014 Election Cycle], [[Center for Responsive Politics]].</ref> In the 2016 election cycle, Goldman employees were reported ({{as of|2016|September|lc=y}}) to have donated $371,245 to the [[Republican National Committee]] and $301,119 to the [[Hillary Clinton 2016 presidential campaign|Hillary Clinton presidential campaign]]. Goldman Sachs forbade its top level employees from donating to the [[Donald Trump 2016 presidential campaign|Donald Trump presidential campaign]].<ref name=\"CNNDonationsPolicy\"/>\n\nIn 2010, the [[Securities and Exchange Commission]] issued regulations that limit asset managers' donations to state and local officials, and prohibit certain top-level employees from donating to such officials.<ref name=\"CNNDonationsPolicy\">{{cite news|last1=Gillespie|first1=Patrick|title=Goldman Sachs' top 1% employees can't donate to Trump|url=http://money.cnn.com/2016/09/06/investing/goldman-sachs-political-donations/|access-date=September 7, 2016|publisher=CNN Money|date=September 6, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"MarketWatch\">Sara Sjolin, [http://www.marketwatch.com/story/goldman-sachs-bans-top-staff-from-donating-to-trump-reports-2016-09-07-91031857 Why Goldman Sachs staff can donate to Hillary Clinton but not Donald Trump], ''MarketWatch'' (September 7, 2016).</ref> This SEC regulation is an anti-\"pay-to-play\" measure, intended to avoid the creation of a [[conflict of interest]], or the appearance of a conflict of interest, as Goldman Sachs has business in managing state [[pension fund]]s and municipal debt.<ref name=\"CNNDonationsPolicy\"/><ref name=\"MarketWatch\"/> In 2016, Goldman Sachs's compliance department barred the firm's 450 partners (its most senior employees) from making donations to state or local officials, as well as \"any federal candidate who is a sitting state or local official\".<ref name=\"CNNDonationsPolicy\"/> One effect of this rule was to bar Goldman partners from directly donating to [[Donald Trump]]'s [[Donald Trump 2016 presidential campaign|presidential campaign]], since Trump's running mate, [[Mike Pence]], was the sitting [[governor of Indiana]]. Donations to [[Hillary Clinton]]'s [[Hillary Clinton 2016 presidential campaign|presidential campaign]] were not barred by the policy, since neither Clinton nor her running mate [[Tim Kaine]] was a sitting state or local official.<ref name=\"CNNDonationsPolicy\"/><ref name=\"MarketWatch\"/>\n\n==Corporate affairs==\n[[File:30hudson.jpg|thumb|Goldman Sachs Tower at [[30 Hudson Street]] in Jersey City.]]\n\n===Employee satisfaction===\nThe company has been on [[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune Magazine]]'s [[100 Best Companies to Work For]] list since the list was launched in 1998, with emphasis placed on its support for employee philanthropic efforts and high employee compensation levels.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://beta.fortune.com/best-companies/goldman-sachs | title=100 Best Companies to Work | publisher=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://reviews.greatplacetowork.com/goldman-sachs | title=Goldman Sachs Group - Best Companies to Work}}</ref>\n\n===Compensation===\nIn the first three months of 2016, the average total compensation per employee was $72,931 for the three months, 44% below the same period in 2015.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://fortune.com/2016/04/19/goldman-sachs-employees-pay-cut/ | title=Goldman Sachs Employees Have Gotten a Huge Pay Cut | first=Lucinda | last=Shen | publisher=[[Fortune Magazine]] | date=April 19, 2016}}</ref> The average total compensation per employee for the full year of 2006 was $622,000.<ref>{{cite news |first=Robert |last=Gavin |title=Good deal: Average Goldman Sachs employee makes $622,000 | url=http://archive.boston.com/business/articles/2006/12/12/good_deal_average_goldman_sachs_employee_makes_622000/ | work=[[Boston Globe]] | date=December 12, 2006 | access-date=January 17, 2007}}</ref> The average compensation in the first three months of 2013 was $135,594.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.businessweek.com/articles/2013-04-16/at-goldman-the-average-pay-for-3-months-is-135-594 | title=At Goldman, the Average Pay for Three Months Is $135,594 | author=Peter Coy| work=[[Bloomberg Businessweek]] | date=April 16, 2013}}</ref> However, these numbers represent the [[arithmetic mean]] of total compensation and are highly skewed upwards as several hundred of the top recipients command the majority of the bonus pools, leaving the median that most employees receive well below this number.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://nymag.com/nymetro/news/bizfinance/biz/features/15197/ | title=Please, Sir, I want Some More | access-date=August 24, 2007 | publisher=New York Magazine | date=December 5, 2005}}</ref> In ''Business Week'''s September 2008 release of the ''Best Places to Launch a Career'', Goldman Sachs was ranked No. 4 out of 119 total companies on the list.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2008-09-03/the-best-places-to-launch-a-career | title=Best Places to Launch a Career 2008 | first=Lindsey | last=Gerdes | publisher=[[Bloomberg Businessweek]] | date=September 4, 2008}}</ref> It was ranked No. 62 on the list of best places to work by ''[[Fortune Magazine]]'' in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://beta.fortune.com/best-companies/goldman-sachs-62/|title=Fortune: Best Companies #62 Goldman Sachs|website=Fortune.com|access-date=May 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\nCEO Blankfein received a $67.9 million bonus in 2007, his first year. He chose to receive \"some\" cash unlike his predecessor, Paulson, who chose to take his bonus entirely in company stock.<ref>{{cite news | title=Goldman Awards Blankfein a Record $67.9 million Bonus | last=Harper | first=Christine | publisher=Bloomberg | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087&sid=ac1OzKh7snD4 | date=December 21, 2007 | accessdate=December 21, 2007}}</ref> In 2011, the bank had nearly 11,000 more staffers than it did in 2005, but performances of workers drastically declined. In 2011, Goldman's 33,300 employees generated $28.8 billion in revenue and $2.5 billion in profit, but it represented a 25% decline in revenue per worker and a 71% decline in profit per worker compared with 2005. In 2011, the company reduced its workforce by 2,400 positions.<ref name=\"Reuters2012March19LaCapraLaurenTara\">{{cite news|last1=LaCapra|first1=LaurenTara|last2=Scott|first2=Alwyn|title=Goldman Sachs cuts staff in annual review process|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-goldman-jobcuts-idUSBRE82I11A20120319|accessdate=March 29, 2012|agency=Thompson Reuters|issue=Business News|publisher=Reuters|date=March 19, 2012|language=English}}</ref>\n\n===Officers and directors===\nNotable members currently on the [[board of directors]] of the company are\n[[M. Michele Burns]], [[Bill George (professor and author)|William W. George]], [[James A. Johnson (businessman)|James A. Johnson]], [[Ellen J. Kullman]], [[Lakshmi Mittal]], [[Adebayo Ogunlesi]], [[Peter Oppenheimer]], [[Debora Spar]], [[Mark Tucker (business)|Mark Tucker]], and [[David Viniar]]. Directors receive annual compensation of $600,000.<ref name=proxy/>\n\nThe company's officers are listed on its website as follows:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goldmansachs.com/our-firm/leadership/board-of-directors/|title=Goldman Sachs - Board of Directors|website=Goldman Sachs|access-date=May 14, 2019}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name\n! Nationality\n! Current position\n! Since\n! Total compensation (2016)<ref name=proxy>{{cite web|url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/886982/000119312517086538/d535038ddef14a1.pdf|title=2017 Annual Meeting of Shareholders Proxy Statement|website=sec.gov|access-date=May 14, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[David M. Solomon|David Solomon]]\n|align=center|{{Flag icon|USA}}\n|Chairman and CEO<ref>[https://www.goldmansachs.com/our-firm/leadership/executive-officers/david-m-solomon.html \"David M. Solomon\"], ''The Goldman Sachs Group, Inc.''.</ref>\n|2018<ref name=proxy/>\n|$N/A<ref name=proxy/>\n|-\n|John E. Waldron<ref>[https://www.goldmansachs.com/our-firm/leadership/executive-officers/john-waldron.html \"John E. Waldron\"], ''The Goldman Sachs Group, Inc.''.</ref>\n|align=center|{{Flag icon|USA}}\n|President and COO\n|2018\n|-\n|Stephen M. Scherr<ref>[https://www.goldmansachs.com/our-firm/leadership/executive-officers/stephen-m-scherr.html \"Stephen M. Scherr\"], ''The Goldman Sachs Group, Inc.''.</ref>\n|align=center|{{Flag icon|USA}}\n|Executive Vice President and CFO\n|\n|}\n\n===Headquarters and other major offices===\nIn 1957, the company's headquarters was relocated to 20 [[Broad Street (Manhattan)|Broad Street]], New York City.<ref name=\"Cohan2012\"/>\n\nGoldman Sachs's global headquarters is now at [[200 West Street]], New York City, and the company has major offices and regional headquarters in [[London]], [[Bangalore]], [[Hong Kong]], [[Tokyo]] and [[Salt Lake City]].<ref name=\"reutersoverview\" />\n\nThe Bangalore office, inaugurated among much fanfare in 2019, was the third largest global office for Goldman Sachs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/companies/goldman-sachs-opens-250-million-bengaluru-office-no-3-globally/article27348065.ece|language=en|title=Press release covering the unveiling of the Bangalore office as the third largest office globally|access-date=2 Sep 2019}}</ref>\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Goldman Sachs River Court Building Fleet Street 1977c.jpg|Goldman Sachs River Court Building, [[Fleet Street]], [[London]]\nFile:Slc 222 south main.jpg|[[Salt Lake City]] office at [[222 South Main]]\n</gallery>\n\n==Goldman Sachs research papers==\nThe following are notable Goldman Sachs research papers:\n* Global Economics Paper No: 93 (South Africa Growth and Unemployment: A Ten-Year Outlook): Makes economic projections for [[South Africa]] for the next 10 years. Published on May 13, 2003.\n* Global Economics Paper No: 99 (Dreaming With BRICs: The Path to 2050): Introduced the [[BRIC]] concept, which became highly popularized in the media and in economic research from this point on. Also made economic projections for 2050 for the [[G7]] and South Africa as well. These were the first long-term economic projections covering the GDP of numerous countries. Published on October 1, 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:0wclCY_isxgJ:www.goldmansachs.com/korea/ideas/brics/99-dreaming.pdf+list+of+goldman+sachs+economic+papers+93&gl=us&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESiopq3dDZ-DN-IFPVZKvhl5tEc69t11Wi-AW3v50E3D5DdifjmCuRqcUgfUKG1eKwtUX1qsfw8aASfJXGtDc5sXqqZHpsG-xUYh1jBHWp0XB-kSmYa_J5x79Dp3JHN2mjaPKGAq |title=Google Drive Viewer |accessdate=June 23, 2013}}</ref>\n* Global Economics Paper No: 134 (How Solid are the BRICs): Introduced the [[Jim O'Neill, Baron O'Neill of Gatley#Next Eleven|Next Eleven]] concept. Published on December 1, 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:v0KuAixZqv8J:www.goldmansachs.com/our-thinking/topics/brics/brics-reports-pdfs/how-solid.pdf+list+of+goldman+sachs+economic+papers+134&gl=us&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESgPaw7FhzXQaRAFNxv4KWhjHpsq_osttcZ8jqxngiB1zt-wfYUko3L9C60DTBdrFGBAJk7khUNgGr2H7UXLmjHCM9Snnj0mlQ089WwsGtaBI7DPm0t0uLG1rTG40EiDmKc85UsS |title=Google Drive Viewer |accessdate=June 23, 2013}}</ref>\n* Global Economics Paper No: 173 (New EU Member States - A Fifth BRIC?): Makes 2050 economic projections for the new [[European Union|EU]] member states as a whole. Published on September 26, 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:8TBcTgte254J:s3.amazonaws.com/zanran_storage/www2.goldmansachs.com/ContentPages/18582260.pdf+goldman+sachs+economic+paper+173&gl=us&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEEShE3V_SwvaxoAYlm_FbjWdmPV5R5TxYtkGxVKFs4ythXsTIfXbjP37p21b7yt9HQgnnfMmABxYEH7XRvhnchgS22K0nDVu6WasaJLue29J4NgKgDfuxDdHg8gXrYtvDDIAmE35j |title=Google Drive Viewer |accessdate=June 23, 2013}}</ref>\n* Global Economics Paper No: 188 (A United Korea; Reassessing North Korea Risks (Part I)): Makes 2050 economic projections for North Korea in the hypothetical event that North Korea makes large free-market reforms right now. Published on September 21, 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:8mj24w6JGqMJ:www.nkeconwatch.com/nk-uploads/global_economics_paper_no_188_final.pdf+list+of+goldman+sachs+economic+papers+188&gl=us&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESjK-MGNf_sZyUZgIQPPEXhluqCvyZ56b0FwsUThY8LKsUwR39VtuZ48vF8Z4n4lvsprbbNiqA4YvTyftYDeVOTRTfUZSb6eZfxueiPZmwhDUXgDnMrC5RyQ_906EtmJUNTpBY16 |title=Google Drive Viewer |accessdate=June 23, 2013}}</ref>\n* The Olympics and Economics 2012: Makes projections for the number of gold medals and told Olympic medals that each country wins at the [[2012 Olympics]] using economic data and previous Olympic data. Published in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:jXNNn3k37rAJ:www.goldmansachs.com/our-thinking/topics/global-economic-outlook/olympics-and-economics-.pdf+goldman+sachs+economic+papers+olympics&gl=us&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESjFo3sCgF6my72ziFGPCaFV-2EEv81UmHjGiLK0qZ_MDpwWaU1iK4mAWxJi0QCsM_GWsNKKL4-M89g2knlCNRilKlwHEAHlZAtaysVIFqFuPY4UXEeddOjgQHNLPLDg6JbkGQUD |title=Google Drive Viewer |accessdate=June 23, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portalbar|New York City|Banks}}\n* [[List of former employees of Goldman Sachs]]\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{Cite book |author=Clinton, Hillary |title=''The Goldman Sachs Speeches.'' With an introduction by Julian Assange and annotations by Doug Henwood |publisher=OR Books |location=New York |year=2016 |isbn=978-1-682190-85-2|author-link=Hillary Clinton }}\n* [[William D. Cohan|Cohan, William D.]] (2011). ''[[Money and Power|Money and Power: How Goldman Sachs Came to Rule the World]]''\n* {{Cite book |author=McGee, Suzanne |title=Chasing Goldman Sachs: How the Masters of the Universe Melted Wall Street Down ... And Why They'll Take Us to the Brink Again |publisher=[[Crown Business]] |location=New York |year=2010 |isbn=978-0-307-46011-0}}\n* {{Cite book |authorlink=Robert Brenner |author=Brenner, Robert |title=What is Good for Goldman Sachs is Good for America - The Origins of the Present Crisis |url=http://repositories.cdlib.org/cstch/2009-1 |publisher=Center for Social Theory and Comparative History. UCLA |year= 2009}}\n* {{Cite book |author=Ellis, Charles D. |title=The Partnership: The Making of Goldman Sachs |publisher=[[The Penguin Press HC]] |location=New York |year=2008 |isbn=978-1-59420-189-9 |url=https://archive.org/details/partnershipmak00elli }}\n* {{Cite book |author=Vault |title=Vault employer profile. Goldman Sachs |publisher=Vault, Inc. |location=New York |year=2006 |isbn=1-58131-469-8}}\n* {{Cite book |author=WetFeet |title=The Goldman Sachs Group |publisher=WetFeet |location=San Francisco, CA |year=2004 |isbn=1-58207-450-X}}\n* {{cite book |author=Endlich, Lisa |authorlink=Lisa Endlich |title=Goldman Sachs: The Culture Of Success |publisher=[[A.A. Knopf]] |location=New York |year=1999 |isbn=0-679-45080-7 |url=https://archive.org/details/goldmansachscult00endl }}\n* {{Cite book |author=Lindskoog, Nils |title=Long-Term Greedy: The Triumph of Goldman Sachs |publisher=McCrossen Pub. |location=Appleton, WI |year=1998 |isbn=0-9652153-3-4}}\n; Videos:\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PXgUea6JVcI|title=Why Goldman Sachs Went From Investing For The Rich To Targeting Everyone|publisher=[[CNBC]]|date=2019-05-02}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Goldman Sachs}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.goldmansachs.com/}}\n{{Finance links\n| name = Goldman Sachs Group Inc\n| symbol = GS\n| sec_cik = 886982\n| bloomberg = GS:US\n| google = GS\n| yahoo = GS\n}}\n\n{{Dow Jones Industrial Average companies}}\n{{Major investment banks}}\n{{Goldman Sachs}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Companies listed on the New York Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:1869 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Banks established in 1869]]\n[[Category:Financial services companies established in 1869]]\n[[Category:Banks based in New York City]]\n[[Category:Systemically important financial institutions]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Companies in the Dow Jones Industrial Average]]\n[[Category:Financial services companies based in New York City]]\n[[Category:Goldman Sachs| ]]\n[[Category:Investment banks in the United States]]\n[[Category:Multinational companies based in New York City]]\n[[Category:Primary dealers]]\n[[Category:Publicly traded companies based in New York City]]\n[[Category:Subprime mortgage crisis]]\n[[Category:Subprime mortgage lenders]]\n[[Category:1999 initial public offerings]]\n", "name_user": "Joseagush", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOfficers and directors", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goldman_Sachs"}
{"title_page": "Controversies about the word niggardly", "text_new": "{{pp-move-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:Controversies about the word ''niggardly''}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{wiktionarypar|niggardly|niggard}}\nIn the [[United States]], there have been several '''controversies involving the word ''niggardly''''', an adjective meaning 'stingy' or 'miserly', because of its [[phonetics|phonetic]] similarity to the [[racial slur]] ''[[nigger]]''. [[Etymology|Etymologically]], the two words are unrelated. The term ''niggardly,'' arising in the [[Middle Ages]], long predates the term ''[[nigger]]'', which arose in the 16th century.<ref name=\"Pilgrim\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ferris.edu/news/jimcrow/caricature/|title=Nigger and Caricatures|last=Pilgrim|first=David|date=September 2001|accessdate=June 19, 2007}}</ref>\n\n== Etymology ==\n''Niggardly'' (noun: ''niggard'') is an adjective meaning \"stingy\" or \"miserly\". It is derived from the [[Middle English]] word ''{{lang|enm|nigard}}'', which is probably derived from [[Old Norse]] ''{{lang|non|hn\u01ebggr}}'' (\"stingy\").<ref>Erik Bj\u00f6rkman, ''[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=IZRMl0NXHZ8C&pg=PA34&lpg=PA34&dq=middle+english+word+nig&#v=onepage&q=middle%20english%20word%20nig&f=false Scandinavian Loan-words in Middle English]'', page 34.</ref>\n\n''Nigger'', a racial epithet in English, derives from the [[Spanish language|Spanish]]/[[Portuguese language|Portuguese]] word ''{{lang|es|negro}}'', meaning \"[[black]]\", and the [[French language|French]] word ''{{lang|fr|n\u00e8gre}}''. Both ''{{lang|es|negro}}'' and ''{{lang|fr|noir}}'' (and therefore also ''{{lang|fr|n\u00e8gre}}'' and ''nigger'') ultimately come from ''{{lang|la|nigrum}}'', the [[accusative case]] singular masculine and neuter <!-- Nouns in Western Romance languages typically come from the accusative case, rather than the nominative case that we quote in English. --> form of the [[Latin]] masculine adjective ''{{lang|la|niger}}'', meaning \"black\" or \"[[dark]]\".<ref>{{cite dictionary |url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/nigger |title=''Nigger'' Usage Note |dictionary=[[Dictionary.com]] |accessdate=May 17, 2015 }}</ref> Its first recorded use dates to 1574, and its first recorded derogatory use to 1775.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Peterson|first1=Christopher|title=Bestial Traces: Race, Sexuality, Animality|date=2013|publisher=Fordham Univ Press|isbn=978-0-8232-4520-8|page=91|url=https://www.google.com/books?id=_Z54563cYpoC&pg=PA91#v=onepage|accessdate=August 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Patricia T. O'Conner, Stewart Kellerman|title=Origins of the Specious: Myths and Misconceptions of the English Language|date=2010|publisher=Random House Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-8129-7810-0|page=134|url=https://www.google.com/books?id=hsu47CBwJPUC&pg=PA134#v=onepage|accessdate=August 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== David Howard incident ==\nOn January 15, 1999, David Howard, an aide to [[Anthony A. Williams]], the [[mayor]] of [[Washington, D.C.]], used \"niggardly\" in reference to a [[budget]].<ref name=\"Dowd\">{{cite news|last=Dowd|first=Maureen|title=Liberties; Niggardly City|work=The New York Times|page=17|date=January 31, 1999|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/01/31/opinion/liberties-niggardly-city.html}}</ref> This apparently upset one of his black colleagues, who misinterpreted it as a racial slur and lodged a complaint. As a result, on January 25, Howard tendered his resignation, and Williams accepted it.<ref name=\"washpost\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/local/longterm/williams/williams020499.htm|title=D.C. Mayor Acted 'Hastily,' Will Rehire Aide|newspaper=[[Washington Post]]|accessdate=October 25, 2009|date=February 4, 1999}}</ref> However, after public pressure, an internal review into the matter was brought about, and the mayor offered Howard the chance to return to his position as Office of the Public Advocate on February 4. Howard refused but accepted another position with the mayor instead, insisting that he did not feel victimized by the incident. On the contrary, Howard felt that he had learned from the situation. \"I used to think it would be great if we could all be colorblind; that's na\u00efve, especially for a white person, because a white person can't {{sic}}<!-- in context, ''can'' makes more sense \u2013 since emphatic ''can'' is sometimes pronounced identically to ''can't'' in American English \u2013 IPA [k\u02b0e\u0259n] \u2013 or at least ''can't'' can sound pretty close \u2013 IPA [k\u02b0e\u0259nt\u031a] \u2013, see also https://www.reddit.com/r/linguistics/comments/7b5o89/phonology_of_can_and_cant_in_standard_american/, there's a good chance that an emphatic ''can'' was misheard and transcribed as ''can't'' here --> afford to be colorblind. They don't have to think about race every day. An African American does.\"<ref name=\"washpost\" />\n\nIt had been speculated that this incident inspired [[Philip Roth]]'s novel ''[[The Human Stain]]'',<ref>{{citation |url= http://www.bfi.org.uk/sightandsound/review/969/ |title=Sight & Sound \u2013 The Human Stain (2003) |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090401003346/http://www.bfi.org.uk/sightandsound/review/969 |archivedate=April 1, 2009 |first=Xan |last=Brooks |publisher=British Film Institute |date=March 2004 |accessdate=February 3, 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref> though Roth has stated that his source was an incident in the career of [[Sociology|sociologist]] and professor [[Melvin Tumin]].<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.newyorker.com/books/page-turner/an-open-letter-to-wikipedia |title=An Open Letter to Wikipedia |first=Philip |last=Roth |authorlink=Philip Roth |date=March 22, 2016 |magazine=The New Yorker}}</ref>\n\n=== Public response ===\nThe Howard incident led to a national debate in the U.S., in the context of racial sensitivity and [[political correctness]], on whether use of ''niggardly'' should be avoided. As [[James Poniewozik]] wrote in ''[[Salon.com|Salon]]'', the controversy was \"an issue that opinion-makers right, left and center could universally agree on.\" He wrote that \"the defenders of the [[dictionary]]\" were \"[[wiktionary:legion|legion]], and still queued up six [[wiktionary:abreast|abreast]]\".<ref name=jp>{{cite news|url=http://www.salon.com/1999/02/02/poni_8/|title=The little N-word|work=[[Salon.com]]|accessdate=March 20, 2014|last=Poniewozik|first=James|date=February 2, 1999}}</ref> [[Julian Bond]], then chairman of the [[NAACP|National Association for the Advancement of Colored People]], deplored the offense that had been taken at Howard's use of the word. \"You hate to think you have to censor your language to meet other people's lack of understanding\", he said. \"David Howard should not have quit. Mayor Williams should bring him back\u2014and order dictionaries issued to all staff who need them.\"<ref>Demarco, Donald, \"Acting Niggardly\", article reprinted at the ''Catholic Education Resource Center'' Web site, which states the article originally appeared in ''Social Justice Review'' 91, no. 3\u20134 (March\u2013April 2000): 45\u201348; the article cites ''The Washington Post'', January 29, 1999, page A24, Web page accessed March 15, 2007</ref> Bond also said, \"Seems to me the mayor has been niggardly in his judgment on the issue\" and that as a nation the US has a \"hair-trigger sensibility\" on race that can be tripped by both real and false grievances.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=GXcfAAAAIBAJ&sjid=Ky8EAAAAIBAJ&pg=6910,3749147&dq=hair-trigger-sensibility|title=NAACP official calls word flap overreaction|work=Milwaukee Journal Sentinel|publisher=Associated Press|date=January 29, 1999|accessdate=July 15, 2011}}</ref>\n\n== University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison incident ==\nShortly after the Washington incident, another controversy erupted over the use of the word at the [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison]]. At a February 1999 meeting of the Faculty Senate, Amelia Rideau, a junior English major and vice chairwoman of the Black Student Union told the group how a professor teaching [[Chaucer]] had used the word ''niggardly''. She later said she was unaware of the related Washington, D.C., controversy that had come to light the week before. She said the professor continued to use the word even after she told him that she was offended. \"I was in tears, shaking,\" she told the faculty. \"It's not up to the rest of the class to decide whether my feelings are valid.\"<ref name=kors>{{cite magazine|url=http://reason.com/archives/1999/07/01/cracking-the-speech-code|title=Cracking the speech code|magazine=[[Reason (magazine)|Reason]]|accessdate=October 25, 2009|author=[[Alan Charles Kors]]|date=July 1999}}</ref>\n\nThe student's plea, offered as evidence in support of the school's [[speech code]], instead struck an unintended chord helping to destroy it. \"Many 'abolitionists', as they now were called, believe that [the student's] speech, widely reported, was the turning point,\" according to an article in ''[[Reason (magazine)|Reason]]'' magazine. An editorial in the ''[[Wisconsin State Journal]]'' addressed the student who complained, saying: \"Thank you [...] for clarifying precisely why the UW\u2013Madison does not need an academic speech code. [...] Speech codes have a chilling effect on academic freedom and they reinforce defensiveness among students who ought to be more open to learning.\"<ref name=kors />\n\n== Wilmington, North Carolina incident ==\nIn late January or early February 2002, a white fourth-grade teacher in [[Wilmington, North Carolina]], was formally reprimanded for teaching the word and told to attend sensitivity training.<ref name=adv>{{cite web|url=http://www.starnewsonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?Site=WM&Date=20020904&Category=NEWS&ArtNo=209040302&Ref=AR&Profile=1004&template=printart|title=Teacher reprimanded for word choice|publisher=[[Wilmington Star-News]]|accessdate=October 25, 2009|date=September 4, 2002}}</ref> The teacher, Stephanie Bell, said she used \"niggardly\" during a discussion about literary characters. Parent Akwana Walker, who is black, protested the use of the word, saying it offended her.<ref name=adv />\n\nBell's teacher's association, the [[North Carolina Association of Educators]], told her not to speak about the situation, so her son spoke to the newspaper, saying that his mother received a letter from the school principal stating that the teacher used poor judgment and instructing her to send an apology to the parents of her students, which was done. The principal's letter also criticized the teacher for lacking sensitivity.<ref name=adv /> The daughter of the complaining parent was moved to another classroom.\n\nNorm Shearin, the deputy superintendent of schools for the district, said the teacher made a bad decision by teaching the word because it was inappropriate for that grade level.<ref name=adv />\n\n== Mendocino County, California incident ==\nIn early 2009,<ref name=\"Ukiah Daily Journal\">{{cite news |last1=Stark |first1=Monica|title=Judge finds for school district in niggardly\" lawsuit |url=https://www.ukiahdailyjournal.com/2010/07/07/judge-finds-for-school-district-in-niggardly-lawsuit/ |newspaper=The Ukiah Daily Journal |date=7 July 2010}}</ref> Dennis Boaz, a history teacher, sued the administrators of the [[Mendocino County]] Office of Education for [[defamation]]. Boaz, who was bargaining for [[Ukiah, California|Ukiah]] schoolteachers, wrote a letter saying that the \"tenor of the negotiation tactics of the district office has become increasingly negative and niggardly.\" The response was a memo from one defendant of the lawsuit that implied that Boaz was racist, and a letter cosigned by the other defendant and nine other individuals in the Mendocino County school system stating that Boaz's comments were \"racially charged and show a complete lack of respect and integrity toward Dr. Nash, Ukiah Unified District Superintendent,\" who is a black woman.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Stark |first1=Monica|url=https://www.ukiahdailyjournal.com/2009/10/14/uproar-over-word-choice-results-in-lawsuit-by-ukiah-teacher/|title=Uproar over word choice results in lawsuit by Ukiah teacher|newspaper=Ukiah Daily Journal|accessdate=October 25, 2009|date=14 October 2009}}</ref>\n\n== Other complaints ==\n=== Letter to ''The Economist'' magazine, 1995 ===\nIn 1995, London-based magazine ''[[The Economist]]'' used the word \"niggardly\" in an article about the impact of computers and productivity: \"During the 1980s, when service industries consumed about 85% of the $1 trillion invested in I.T. in the United States, productivity growth averaged a niggardly 0.8% a year.\" ''The Economist'' later pointed out with amusement that it received a letter from a reader in Boston who thought the word \"niggardly\" was inappropriate. \"Why do we get such letters only from America?\" the British magazine commented.<ref name=jd>{{cite magazine|url=http://old.nationalreview.com/derbyshire/derbyshire091702.asp|title=Niggling doubts|magazine=[[National Review Online]]|accessdate=October 25, 2009|last=Derbyshire|first=John|date=September 17, 2002|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110502072428/http://old.nationalreview.com/derbyshire/derbyshire091702.asp|archivedate=May 2, 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Dallas Morning News'' ===\nAt some point before the Washington, D.C., incident (of early 1999), ''[[The Dallas Morning News]]'' had banned the use of the word after its use in a restaurant review had raised complaints.<ref name=jp /><ref>\"Even before the Washington incident, the ''Dallas Morning News'' had ixnayed the word after its use in a restaurant review raised ire.\"</ref>\n\n=== Acampo, California ===\nOn March 31, 2010, a [[billboard]] appeared along the frontage of [[California State Route 99]] in [[Acampo, California]], that referred to [[Barack Obama]], the first black [[President of the United States]], as \"niggardly\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fox40.com/news/headlines/ktxl-news-obamasign0331,0,1047633.story|title='Niggardly Obama' Billboard Generates Outrage In Acampo|first=Matthew|last=Keys|work=fox40.com|date=March 31, 2010|accessdate=July 15, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120318151315/http://www.fox40.com/news/headlines/ktxl-news-obamasign0331%2C0%2C1047633.story|archivedate=March 18, 2012}}</ref> The sign was placed among several billboards advertising a local coffee shop that was going out of business that week. The restaurant's owner stated that they were unaware of the Obama sign until contacted by a local news station. The sign was removed shortly after news reports about it appeared on local television stations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news10.net/news/local/story.aspx?storyid=78454|title=Acampo anti-Obama sign taken down|first=James|last=Scullary|work=news10.net|date=March 31, 2010|accessdate=July 15, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607083702/http://www.news10.net/news/local/story.aspx?storyid=78454|archive-date=June 7, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== Broward County, Florida ===\nIn November 2011, a [[Broward County, Florida|Broward County]] drug counsellor was fired and another suspended for an incident in which the word \"niggardly\" was used. A substance-abuse client filed a complaint saying a counsellor called him \"niggardly dumb\" in a June meeting with two workers at a county rehab center. In an investigative report, the county's professional standards office found the workers, who are both white, engaged in \"unprofessional, unethical and discriminatory\" behavior.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/columnists/fl-niggardly-mayocol-b110811-20111107,0,488452.column|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130203210120/http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/columnists/fl-niggardly-mayocol-b110811-20111107,0,488452.column|url-status=dead|archive-date=February 3, 2013|title=Is using this N-word (niggardly) a firing offense?|first=Michael|last=Mayo|work=sun-sentinel.com|date=November 11, 2011|accessdate=November 11, 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Publicity and racial use ==\nThe public controversies caused some commentators to speculate that \"niggardly\" would be used more often, both in its correct sense and as fodder for humor, as a racist [[Code word (figure of speech)|code word]], or both.\n\n\"The word's new lease of life is probably among manufacturers and retailers of sophomoric humor,\" wrote [[John Derbyshire]], a conservative commentator, in 2002. \"I bet that even as I write, some adolescent boys, in the stairwell of some high school somewhere in America, are accusing each other of being niggardly, and sniggering at their own outrageous wit. I bet ... Wait a minute. 'Sniggering'? Oh, my God. ...\"<ref name=jd /> Derbyshire wrote that although he loved to use words that are sometimes considered obscure, he would not use the word among black people, especially among less-educated black people, out of politeness and to avoid causing someone to feel uncomfortable, regardless of any non-racial meanings he would intend.<ref name=jd />\n\nShortly after the Washington, D.C., incident, [[James Poniewozik]] wrote in his column at ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' online magazine that some were already using \"niggardly\" in a way that made their motives ambiguous. He quoted a posting by a user from a reader forum at the ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' website \"who just happened to use 'niggardly'\u2014linguistically correctly\" in commenting on two witnesses to a Congressional investigation:<ref name=jp />\n\n{{quote|[[Betty Currie|B. Curry]] [sic] got a pc pass because her testimony like that of all Clintonistas was niggardly with the truth. It is predictable that [[Vernon Jordan|V. Jordan]] will have his opportunity to be equally niggardly in this regard. Witnesses? A woman (child), a negro, and a jew\u2014very PC indeed!}}\n\n\"You can't say [the commenter]\u2014white, black or [[Klingon]] for all I know\u2014had racist motives. And you can't exactly not say it,\" Poniewozik wrote. He expected a number of \"[[Pinhead|pinheads]]\" to be asking \"black waitresses not to be 'niggardly' with the coffee\".<ref name=jp /> But there would be a different reaction in polite company, especially in racially diverse company, so the word would probably be thought of only when people think of racial epithets. \"In theory, you, I and the columnist next door will defend to the death our right to say 'niggardly.' But in practice, will we use it?\"<ref name=jp />\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Tar-Baby]], a term with a benign usage that has also been perceived as a racial slur\n*[[Water buffalo incident]], a similar controversy involving remarks regarded as racist\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Politics and race in the United States|Niggardly]]\n[[Category:English words and phrases|Niggardly]]\n[[Category:African-American-related controversies|Niggardly]]\n[[Category:Connotation|Niggardly]]\n[[Category:English words|Niggardly]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-move-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:Controversies about the word ''niggardly''}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{wiktionarypar|niggardly|niggard}}\nIn the United States, there have been several '''controversies involving the word ''niggardly''''', an adjective meaning 'stingy' or 'miserly', because of its [[phonetics|phonetic]] similarity to the [[racial slur]] ''[[nigger]]''. [[Etymology|Etymologically]], the two words are unrelated. The term ''niggardly,'' arising in the [[Middle Ages]], long predates the term ''nigger'', which arose in the 16th century.<ref name=\"Pilgrim\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ferris.edu/news/jimcrow/caricature/|title=Nigger and Caricatures|last=Pilgrim|first=David|date=September 2001|accessdate=June 19, 2007}}</ref>\n\n== Etymology ==\n''Niggardly'' (noun: ''niggard'') is an adjective meaning \"stingy\" or \"miserly\". It is derived from the [[Middle English]] word ''{{lang|enm|nigard}}'', which is probably derived from [[Old Norse]] ''{{lang|non|hn\u01ebggr}}'' (\"stingy\").<ref>Erik Bj\u00f6rkman, ''[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=IZRMl0NXHZ8C&pg=PA34&lpg=PA34&dq=middle+english+word+nig&#v=onepage&q=middle%20english%20word%20nig&f=false Scandinavian Loan-words in Middle English]'', page 34.</ref>\n\n''[[Nigger]]'', a racial epithet in English, derives from the [[Spanish language|Spanish]]/[[Portuguese language|Portuguese]] word ''{{lang|es|negro}}'', meaning \"[[black]]\", and the [[French language|French]] word ''{{lang|fr|n\u00e8gre}}''. Both ''{{lang|es|negro}}'' and ''{{lang|fr|noir}}'' (and therefore also ''{{lang|fr|n\u00e8gre}}'' and ''nigger'') ultimately come from ''{{lang|la|nigrum}}'', the [[accusative case]] singular masculine and neuter <!-- Nouns in Western Romance languages typically come from the accusative case, rather than the nominative case that we quote in English. --> form of the [[Latin]] masculine adjective ''{{lang|la|niger}}'', meaning \"black\" or \"[[dark]]\".<ref>{{cite dictionary |url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/nigger |title=''Nigger'' Usage Note |dictionary=[[Dictionary.com]] |accessdate=May 17, 2015 }}</ref> Its first recorded use dates to 1574, and its first recorded derogatory use to 1775.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Peterson|first1=Christopher|title=Bestial Traces: Race, Sexuality, Animality|date=2013|publisher=Fordham Univ Press|isbn=978-0-8232-4520-8|page=91|url=https://www.google.com/books?id=_Z54563cYpoC&pg=PA91#v=onepage|accessdate=August 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Patricia T. O'Conner, Stewart Kellerman|title=Origins of the Specious: Myths and Misconceptions of the English Language|date=2010|publisher=Random House Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-8129-7810-0|page=134|url=https://www.google.com/books?id=hsu47CBwJPUC&pg=PA134#v=onepage|accessdate=August 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== David Howard incident ==\nOn January 15, 1999, David Howard, an aide to [[Anthony A. Williams]], the mayor of [[Washington, D.C.]], used \"niggardly\" in reference to a budget.<ref name=\"Dowd\">{{cite news|last=Dowd|first=Maureen|title=Liberties; Niggardly City|work=The New York Times|page=17|date=January 31, 1999|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/01/31/opinion/liberties-niggardly-city.html}}</ref> This apparently upset one of his black colleagues, who misinterpreted it as a racial slur and lodged a complaint. As a result, on January 25, Howard tendered his resignation, and Williams accepted it.<ref name=\"washpost\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/local/longterm/williams/williams020499.htm|title=D.C. Mayor Acted 'Hastily,' Will Rehire Aide|newspaper=[[Washington Post]]|accessdate=October 25, 2009|date=February 4, 1999}}</ref> However, after public pressure, an internal review into the matter was brought about, and the mayor offered Howard the chance to return to his position as Office of the Public Advocate on February 4. Howard refused but accepted another position with the mayor instead, insisting that he did not feel victimized by the incident. On the contrary, Howard felt that he had learned from the situation. \"I used to think it would be great if we could all be colorblind; that's na\u00efve, especially for a white person, because a white person can't {{sic}}<!-- in context, ''can'' makes more sense \u2013 since emphatic ''can'' is sometimes pronounced identically to ''can't'' in American English \u2013 IPA [k\u02b0e\u0259n] \u2013 or at least ''can't'' can sound pretty close \u2013 IPA [k\u02b0e\u0259nt\u031a] \u2013, see also https://www.reddit.com/r/linguistics/comments/7b5o89/phonology_of_can_and_cant_in_standard_american/, there's a good chance that an emphatic ''can'' was misheard and transcribed as ''can't'' here --> afford to be colorblind. They don't have to think about race every day. An African American does.\"<ref name=\"washpost\" />\n\nIt had been speculated that this incident inspired [[Philip Roth]]'s novel ''[[The Human Stain]]'',<ref>{{citation |url= http://www.bfi.org.uk/sightandsound/review/969/ |title=Sight & Sound \u2013 The Human Stain (2003) |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090401003346/http://www.bfi.org.uk/sightandsound/review/969 |archivedate=April 1, 2009 |first=Xan |last=Brooks |publisher=British Film Institute |date=March 2004 |accessdate=February 3, 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref> though Roth has stated that his source was an incident in the career of sociologist and professor [[Melvin Tumin]].<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.newyorker.com/books/page-turner/an-open-letter-to-wikipedia |title=An Open Letter to Wikipedia |first=Philip |last=Roth |authorlink=Philip Roth |date=March 22, 2016 |magazine=The New Yorker}}</ref>\n\n=== Public response ===\nThe Howard incident led to a national debate in the U.S., in the context of racial sensitivity and [[political correctness]], on whether use of ''niggardly'' should be avoided. As [[James Poniewozik]] wrote in ''[[Salon.com|Salon]]'', the controversy was \"an issue that opinion-makers right, left and center could universally agree on.\" He wrote that \"the defenders of the dictionary\" were \"legion, and still queued up six abreast\".<ref name=jp>{{cite news|url=http://www.salon.com/1999/02/02/poni_8/|title=The little N-word|work=[[Salon.com]]|accessdate=March 20, 2014|last=Poniewozik|first=James|date=February 2, 1999}}</ref> [[Julian Bond]], then chairman of the [[NAACP|National Association for the Advancement of Colored People]], deplored the offense that had been taken at Howard's use of the word. \"You hate to think you have to censor your language to meet other people's lack of understanding\", he said. \"David Howard should not have quit. Mayor Williams should bring him back\u2014and order dictionaries issued to all staff who need them.\"<ref>Demarco, Donald, \"Acting Niggardly\", article reprinted at the ''Catholic Education Resource Center'' Web site, which states the article originally appeared in ''Social Justice Review'' 91, no. 3\u20134 (March\u2013April 2000): 45\u201348; the article cites ''The Washington Post'', January 29, 1999, page A24, Web page accessed March 15, 2007</ref> Bond also said, \"Seems to me the mayor has been niggardly in his judgment on the issue\" and that as a nation the US has a \"hair-trigger sensibility\" on race that can be tripped by both real and false grievances.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=GXcfAAAAIBAJ&sjid=Ky8EAAAAIBAJ&pg=6910,3749147&dq=hair-trigger-sensibility|title=NAACP official calls word flap overreaction|work=Milwaukee Journal Sentinel|publisher=Associated Press|date=January 29, 1999|accessdate=July 15, 2011}}</ref>\n\n== University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison incident ==\nShortly after the Washington incident, another controversy erupted over the use of the word at the [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison]]. At a February 1999 meeting of the Faculty Senate, Amelia Rideau, a junior English major and vice chairwoman of the Black Student Union told the group how a professor teaching [[Chaucer]] had used the word ''niggardly''. She later said she was unaware of the related Washington, D.C., controversy that had come to light the week before. She said the professor continued to use the word even after she told him that she was offended. \"I was in tears, shaking,\" she told the faculty. \"It's not up to the rest of the class to decide whether my feelings are valid.\"<ref name=kors>{{cite magazine|url=http://reason.com/archives/1999/07/01/cracking-the-speech-code|title=Cracking the speech code|magazine=[[Reason (magazine)|Reason]]|accessdate=October 25, 2009|author=[[Alan Charles Kors]]|date=July 1999}}</ref>\n\nThe student's plea, offered as evidence in support of the school's [[speech code]], instead struck an unintended chord helping to destroy it. \"Many 'abolitionists', as they now were called, believe that [the student's] speech, widely reported, was the turning point,\" according to an article in ''[[Reason (magazine)|Reason]]'' magazine. An editorial in the ''[[Wisconsin State Journal]]'' addressed the student who complained, saying: \"Thank you [...] for clarifying precisely why the UW\u2013Madison does not need an academic speech code. [...] Speech codes have a chilling effect on academic freedom and they reinforce defensiveness among students who ought to be more open to learning.\"<ref name=kors />\n\n== Wilmington, North Carolina incident ==\nIn late January or early February 2002, a white fourth-grade teacher in [[Wilmington, North Carolina]], was formally reprimanded for teaching the word and told to attend sensitivity training.<ref name=adv>{{cite web|url=http://www.starnewsonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?Site=WM&Date=20020904&Category=NEWS&ArtNo=209040302&Ref=AR&Profile=1004&template=printart|title=Teacher reprimanded for word choice|publisher=[[Wilmington Star-News]]|accessdate=October 25, 2009|date=September 4, 2002}}</ref> The teacher, Stephanie Bell, said she used \"niggardly\" during a discussion about literary characters. Parent Akwana Walker, who is black, protested the use of the word, saying it offended her.<ref name=adv />\n\nBell's teacher's association, the [[North Carolina Association of Educators]], told her not to speak about the situation, so her son spoke to the newspaper, saying that his mother received a letter from the school principal stating that the teacher used poor judgment and instructing her to send an apology to the parents of her students, which was done. The principal's letter also criticized the teacher for lacking sensitivity.<ref name=adv /> The daughter of the complaining parent was moved to another classroom.\n\nNorm Shearin, the deputy superintendent of schools for the district, said the teacher made a bad decision by teaching the word because it was inappropriate for that grade level.<ref name=adv />\n\n== Mendocino County, California incident ==\nIn early 2009,<ref name=\"Ukiah Daily Journal\">{{cite news |last1=Stark |first1=Monica|title=Judge finds for school district in niggardly\" lawsuit |url=https://www.ukiahdailyjournal.com/2010/07/07/judge-finds-for-school-district-in-niggardly-lawsuit/ |newspaper=The Ukiah Daily Journal |date=7 July 2010}}</ref> Dennis Boaz, a history teacher, sued the administrators of the [[Mendocino County]] Office of Education for [[defamation]]. Boaz, who was bargaining for [[Ukiah, California|Ukiah]] schoolteachers, wrote a letter saying that the \"tenor of the negotiation tactics of the district office has become increasingly negative and niggardly.\" The response was a memo from one defendant of the lawsuit that implied that Boaz was racist, and a letter cosigned by the other defendant and nine other individuals in the Mendocino County school system stating that Boaz's comments were \"racially charged and show a complete lack of respect and integrity toward Dr. Nash, Ukiah Unified District Superintendent,\" who is a black woman.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Stark |first1=Monica|url=https://www.ukiahdailyjournal.com/2009/10/14/uproar-over-word-choice-results-in-lawsuit-by-ukiah-teacher/|title=Uproar over word choice results in lawsuit by Ukiah teacher|newspaper=Ukiah Daily Journal|accessdate=October 25, 2009|date=14 October 2009}}</ref>\n\n== Other complaints ==\n=== Letter to ''The Economist'' magazine, 1995 ===\nIn 1995, London-based magazine ''[[The Economist]]'' used the word \"niggardly\" in an article about the impact of computers and productivity: \"During the 1980s, when service industries consumed about 85% of the $1 trillion invested in I.T. in the United States, productivity growth averaged a niggardly 0.8% a year.\" ''The Economist'' later pointed out with amusement that it received a letter from a reader in Boston who thought the word \"niggardly\" was inappropriate. \"Why do we get such letters only from America?\" the British magazine commented.<ref name=jd>{{cite magazine|url=http://old.nationalreview.com/derbyshire/derbyshire091702.asp|title=Niggling doubts|magazine=[[National Review Online]]|accessdate=October 25, 2009|last=Derbyshire|first=John|date=September 17, 2002|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110502072428/http://old.nationalreview.com/derbyshire/derbyshire091702.asp|archivedate=May 2, 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Dallas Morning News'' ===\nAt some point before the Washington, D.C., incident (of early 1999), ''[[The Dallas Morning News]]'' had banned the use of the word after its use in a restaurant review had raised complaints.<ref name=jp /><ref>\"Even before the Washington incident, the ''Dallas Morning News'' had ixnayed the word after its use in a restaurant review raised ire.\"</ref>\n\n=== Acampo, California ===\nOn March 31, 2010, a billboard appeared along the frontage of [[California State Route 99]] in [[Acampo, California]], that referred to [[Barack Obama]], the first black [[President of the United States]], as \"niggardly\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fox40.com/news/headlines/ktxl-news-obamasign0331,0,1047633.story|title='Niggardly Obama' Billboard Generates Outrage In Acampo|first=Matthew|last=Keys|work=fox40.com|date=March 31, 2010|accessdate=July 15, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120318151315/http://www.fox40.com/news/headlines/ktxl-news-obamasign0331%2C0%2C1047633.story|archivedate=March 18, 2012}}</ref> The sign was placed among several billboards advertising a local coffee shop that was going out of business that week. The restaurant's owner stated that they were unaware of the Obama sign until contacted by a local news station. The sign was removed shortly after news reports about it appeared on local television stations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news10.net/news/local/story.aspx?storyid=78454|title=Acampo anti-Obama sign taken down|first=James|last=Scullary|work=news10.net|date=March 31, 2010|accessdate=July 15, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607083702/http://www.news10.net/news/local/story.aspx?storyid=78454|archive-date=June 7, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== Broward County, Florida ===\nIn November 2011, a [[Broward County, Florida|Broward County]] drug counsellor was fired and another suspended for an incident in which the word \"niggardly\" was used. A substance-abuse client filed a complaint saying a counsellor called him \"niggardly dumb\" in a June meeting with two workers at a county rehab center. In an investigative report, the county's professional standards office found the workers, who are both white, engaged in \"unprofessional, unethical and discriminatory\" behavior.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/columnists/fl-niggardly-mayocol-b110811-20111107,0,488452.column|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130203210120/http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/columnists/fl-niggardly-mayocol-b110811-20111107,0,488452.column|url-status=dead|archive-date=February 3, 2013|title=Is using this N-word (niggardly) a firing offense?|first=Michael|last=Mayo|work=sun-sentinel.com|date=November 11, 2011|accessdate=November 11, 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Publicity and racial use ==\nThe public controversies caused some commentators to speculate that \"niggardly\" would be used more often, both in its correct sense and as fodder for humor, as a racist [[Code word (figure of speech)|code word]], or both.\n\n\"The word's new lease of life is probably among manufacturers and retailers of sophomoric humor,\" wrote [[John Derbyshire]], a conservative commentator, in 2002. \"I bet that even as I write, some adolescent boys, in the stairwell of some high school somewhere in America, are accusing each other of being niggardly, and sniggering at their own outrageous wit. I bet ... Wait a minute. 'Sniggering'? Oh, my God. ...\"<ref name=jd /> Derbyshire wrote that although he loved to use words that are sometimes considered obscure, he would not use the word among black people, especially among less-educated black people, out of politeness and to avoid causing someone to feel uncomfortable, regardless of any non-racial meanings he would intend.<ref name=jd />\n\nShortly after the Washington, D.C., incident, [[James Poniewozik]] wrote in his column at ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' online magazine that some were already using \"niggardly\" in a way that made their motives ambiguous. He quoted a posting by a user from a reader forum at the ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' website \"who just happened to use 'niggardly'\u2014linguistically correctly\" in commenting on two witnesses to a Congressional investigation:<ref name=jp />\n\n{{quote|[[Betty Currie|B. Curry]] [sic] got a pc pass because her testimony like that of all Clintonistas was niggardly with the truth. It is predictable that [[Vernon Jordan|V. Jordan]] will have his opportunity to be equally niggardly in this regard. Witnesses? A woman (child), a negro, and a jew\u2014very PC indeed!}}\n\n\"You can't say [the commenter]\u2014white, black or [[Klingon]] for all I know\u2014had racist motives. And you can't exactly not say it,\" Poniewozik wrote. He expected a number of \"pinheads\" to be asking \"black waitresses not to be 'niggardly' with the coffee\".<ref name=jp /> But there would be a different reaction in polite company, especially in racially diverse company, so the word would probably be thought of only when people think of racial epithets. \"In theory, you, I and the columnist next door will defend to the death our right to say 'niggardly.' But in practice, will we use it?\"<ref name=jp />\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Tar-Baby]], a term with a benign usage that has also been perceived as a racial slur\n*[[Water buffalo incident]], a similar controversy involving remarks regarded as racist\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Politics and race in the United States|Niggardly]]\n[[Category:English words and phrases|Niggardly]]\n[[Category:African-American-related controversies|Niggardly]]\n[[Category:Connotation|Niggardly]]\n[[Category:English words|Niggardly]]\n", "name_user": "Likebeingawesome", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added links so that readers can understand topics mentioned in the article if they do not know the topic", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Controversies_about_the_word_niggardly"}
{"title_page": "Times New Roman", "text_new": "{{short description|Canonical serif font}}\n{{Infobox font  \n| name = Times New Roman\n| image = Times New Roman-sample.svg\n| style = [[Serif]]\n| classifications = Mixed<br>[[Transitional serif|Transitional]]<br>[[Serif#Old-style|Old-style]]\n| releasedate = 1932<ref name=\"Clarke 1946\">{{cite news|last1=Clarke|first1=C.F.O.|title=The Times: A Revolution in Newspaper Printing|url=http://magazines.iaddb.org/issue/GR/1946-05-01/edition/15/page/86|work=Graphis|date=1946|pages=362\u2013375}}</ref>\n| creator = [[Stanley Morison]]<br>[[Victor Lardent]]\n| foundry = [[Monotype Corporation|Monotype]]\n| commissioned_by = ''[[The Times]]''\n| based_on = [[Plantin (typeface)|Plantin]]\n| license = [[Proprietary software|Proprietary]]\n|}}\n'''Times New Roman''' is a [[serif typeface|serif]] [[typeface]]. It was commissioned by the British newspaper ''[[The Times]]'' in 1931 and conceived by [[Stanley Morison]], the artistic adviser to the British branch of the printing equipment company [[Monotype Imaging|Monotype]], in collaboration with [[Victor Lardent]], a lettering artist in ''The Times's'' advertising department. It has become one of the most popular typefaces of all time and is installed on most [[desktop computer]]s.\n\nAsked to advise on a redesign, Morison recommended that ''The Times'' change their text typeface from a spindly nineteenth-century face to a more robust, solid design, returning to traditions of printing from the eighteenth century and before. This matched a common trend in printing tastes of the period. Morison proposed an older Monotype typeface named [[Plantin (typeface)|Plantin]] as a basis for the design, and Times New Roman mostly matches Plantin's dimensions. The main change was that the contrast between strokes was enhanced to give a crisper image. The new design made its debut in ''The Times'' on 3 October 1932. After one year, the design was released for commercial sale. In Times New Roman's name, Roman is a reference to the regular or [[Roman type|roman]] style (sometimes also called [[Antiqua\u2013Fraktur dispute|Antiqua]]), the first part of the Times New Roman family to be designed. Roman type has roots in Italian printing of the late 15th and early 16th centuries, but Times New Roman's design has no connection to [[Rome]] or to the [[Ancient Rome|Romans]].\n\n''The Times'' stayed with Times New Roman for 40 years, but new production techniques and the format change from [[broadsheet]] to [[Tabloid (newspaper format)|tabloid]] in 2004 have caused it to switch typeface five times from 1972 to 2007. However, all the new fonts have been variants of the original New Roman typeface.\n\n==Design==\n[[File:Times New Roman and predecessor.jpg|thumb|right|Twenty-two lines in Times New Roman compared to its predecessor \"modern\" serif font.{{efn|\"Modern\" in typography is a generic term referring to designs in the [[Didone (typography)|modern or Didone]] style of the nineteenth century.}} Times appears larger on the page, with tighter linespacing and more solid in appearance.<ref name=\"Printing the Times 1932\">{{cite book |title=Printing the Times: A record of the changes introduced in the issue for October 3, 1932 |date=1932 |location=London}}</ref>]]\nTimes New Roman has a robust [[Type color|colour]] on the page and influences of European [[Early modern period|early modern]] and [[Baroque period|Baroque]] printing.<ref name=\"Monotype Recorder: The Changing Newspaper\">{{cite journal|first=Stanley|last=Morison|title=Monotype Recorder: The Changing Newspaper|journal=Monotype Recorder|volume=35|issue=1|date=1936|url=http://www.metaltype.co.uk/downloads/mr/mr_35_1.pdf}}</ref>{{efn|\"The Changing Newspaper\" articles in the ''Monotype Recorder'' are unsigned, but Monotype's newspaper consultant Allen Hutt, who co-authored the issue, attributes them to Morison.{{sfn|Hutt|1970|p=263}}}} As a typeface designed for newspaper printing, Times New Roman has a high [[x-height]], short [[descender]]s to allow tight linespacing and a relatively condensed appearance.{{sfn|Williamson|1956|p=117}}{{efn|While Times is often described as being quite \"condensed\" this is relative to its high x-height: typefaces with lower x-height, such as many versions of [[Garamond]], [[Caslon]] and [[Bembo]], are narrower at equalised cap height. Although Hutt,{{sfn|Hutt|1970|p=261}} and most other authors, describe Times New Roman as having a higher x-height than Plantin, Tracy reports based on published Monotype dimensions that in the original small metal-type sizes the difference was not great.{{sfn|Tracy|2003|p=197}}}}\n\n[[File:Times ancestors.png|thumb|A digitisation of Times New Roman below the three typefaces originally considered as a basis for the ''Times'' project: [[Perpetua (typeface)|Perpetua]], [[Baskerville]] and [[Plantin (typeface)|Plantin]]. Times is most based on Plantin, but with the letters made taller and its appearance \"modernised\" by adding eighteenth- and nineteenth-century influences, in particular enhancing the stroke contrast. Compared to Baskerville and Perpetua, the [[x-height]] is a larger proportion of the type height.]]\nThe roman style of Plantin was loosely based on a metal type created in the late sixteenth century by the French artisan [[Robert Granjon]] and preserved in the collection of the [[Plantin-Moretus Museum]] of [[Antwerp]].<ref name=\"Where Did Times New Roman Come From?\">{{cite web|last1=Mann|first1=Meredith|title=Where Did Times New Roman Come From?|url=http://www.nypl.org/blog/2014/12/09/times-new-roman|publisher=[[New York Public Library]]|accessdate=2 February 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Vervliet2008\">{{cite book|author=Hendrik D. L. Vervliet|title=The Palaeotypography of the French Renaissance: Selected Papers on Sixteenth-century Typefaces|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6sidSDlif48C&pg=PA226|year=2008|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-16982-1|pages=226\u20137}}</ref><ref name=\"Tally of Types\">{{cite book|last1=Morison|first1=Stanley|title=A Tally of Types|url=https://archive.org/details/tallyoftypes0000mori|url-access=registration|date=7 June 1973|publisher=CUP Archive|isbn=978-0-521-09786-4|pages=[https://archive.org/details/tallyoftypes0000mori/page/22 22]\u201324, 106, 124 etc.}}</ref><ref name=\"Mosley Gros Cicero\">{{cite web|last1=Mosley|first1=James|title=Comments on Typophile thread|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111013140635/http://www.typophile.com/node/53050|website=Typophile (archived)|accessdate=16 December 2016|quote=The consensus appears to be that not only the wrong-fount a in the cases at Antwerp but also the italic that Monotype adapted for their Plantin (which can be seen on that first page of the 1905 specimen) may be the work of Johann Michael Schmidt (died 1750), also known as J. M. Smit or Smid.}}</ref> This style is sometimes categorised as part of the \"[[Serif#Old-style|old-style]]\" of serif fonts (from before the eighteenth century).<ref name=\"Typographic milestones\">{{cite book|last1=Haley|first1=Allan|title=Typographic Milestones|date=1992|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|location=Hoboken, NJ|isbn=9780471288947|pages=99\u2013107|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dKeVor1olhkC&pg=PA106|accessdate=26 January 2016|chapter=Stanley Morison}}</ref><ref name=\"ABC's of type\">{{cite book |last1=Haley |first1=Allen |title=ABC's of type |date=1990 |publisher=Watson-Guptill Publications |isbn=9780823000531 |page=[https://archive.org/details/abcsoftype0000hale/page/86 86] |quote=Times looks like Plantin on a diet. |url=https://archive.org/details/abcsoftype0000hale/page/86 }}</ref><ref name=\"Leipzig as a Centre of Type-Founding\">{{cite book|last=Morison|first=Stanley|editor-last=McKitterick |editor-first=David |title=Selected essays on the history of letterforms in manuscript and print|chapter=Chapter 8: Leipzig as a Centre of Type-Founding|date=2009|pages=149\u2013170|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge|isbn=978-0-521-18316-1|edition=Paperback reissue, digitally printed version|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-G2tQVnPiCAC&pg=PA132&lpg=PA132}}</ref>{{efn|Times New Roman was called \"Times Old Style\" in an early stage of its development.{{sfn|Dreyfus|1973|p=166}}}} (The 'a' of Plantin was not based on Granjon's work: the Plantin-Moretus Museum's type had a substitute 'a' cut later.<ref name=\"Matthew Carter\">{{cite book|last1=Mosley|first1=James|chapter=Reviving the Classics: Matthew Carter and the Interpretation of Historical Models|editor1-last=Mosley|editor1-first=James|editor2-last=Re|editor2-first=Margaret|editor3-last=Drucker|editor3-first=Johanna|editor4-last=Carter|editor4-first=Matthew|title=Typographically Speaking: The Art of Matthew Carter|date=2003|publisher=Princeton Architectural Press|isbn=9781568984278|pages=31\u201334|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WqXd_w4S4SsC&pg=PA32|quote=Plantin was a recreation of one of the old types held at the Plantin-Moretus Museum in Antwerp, of which a specimen, printed in 1905, had been acquired by Pierpont on a visit. The type from which the specimen was printed was not only centuries old and worn almost beyond use, but it was contaminated with wrong-font letters (notably the letter 'a') and the italic did not even belong to the roman. The revival, derived by Monotype from an indirect and confused original, is [nonetheless] as sound a piece of type-making as was ever created in the 20th century\u2026behind the foggy image of the roman type lies the...'Gros Cicero' Roman of [[Robert Granjon]], acquired by the Plantin printing office after the death of its founder.}}</ref>) Indeed, the working title of Times New Roman was \"Times Old Style\".{{sfn|Dreyfus|1973|p=166}}\n\nHowever, Times New Roman modifies the Granjon influence further than Plantin due to features such as its 'a' and 'e', with very large [[Counter (typography)|counters and apertures]], its [[ball terminal]] detailing and an increased level of contrast between thick and thin strokes, so it has often been compared to fonts from the late eighteenth century, the so-called '[[Serif#Transitional|transitional]]' genre, in particular the [[Baskerville]] typeface of the 1750s.<ref name=Busic-Snyder>{{cite book|last1=Busic-Snyder|first1=Kate Clair, Cynthia|title=A typographic workbook a primer to history, techniques, and artistry|date=2005|publisher=Wiley|location=Hoboken, N.J.|isbn=9781118399880|page=171|edition=2nd|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Lf0iDYCr6w0C&pg=PA171|accessdate=16 January 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Fonts & Encodings\">{{cite book|last1=Horne|first1=Yannis Haralambous ; translated by P. Scott|title=Fonts & Encodings|date=2007|publisher=O'Reilly Media|location=Sebastopol, Calif.|isbn=9780596102425|page=417|edition=1st|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qrElYgVLDwYC&pg=PA417|accessdate=26 January 2016}}</ref> Historian and sometime Monotype executive Allan Haley commented that compared to Plantin \"serifs had been sharpened...contrast was increased and character curves were refined,\" while Lawson described Times's higher-contrast crispness as having \"a sparkle [Plantin] never achieved\".<ref name=\"Haley1992\">{{cite book|author=Allan Haley|title=Typographic Milestones|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dKeVor1olhkC&pg=PA106|date=15 September 1992|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-0-471-28894-7|page=106}}</ref><ref name=\"Anatomy of a Typeface\" /> Other changes from Plantin include a straight-sided 'M' and 'W' with three upper terminals not Plantin's four, both choices that move away from the old-style model.{{sfn|Tracy|2003|p=56}}\n===Italic and bold===\n[[File:Times ancestors italic.png|thumb|right|Times compared with its influences in italic. The italic was made simpler than Plantin's, losing flourishes on the 'w' and 'v', but less radically than that of Perpetua.]]\nMorison described the companion [[Italic type|italic]] as also being influenced by the typefaces created by the [[Didot family]] in the late 18th and early 19th centuries: a \"rationalistic italic that owed nothing to the tradition of the sixteenth or seventeenth centuries. It has, indeed, more in common with the eighteenth century.\"<ref name=\"Changing the Times\">{{cite web|last1=Morison|first1=Stanley|title=Changing the Times|url=http://www.eyemagazine.com/feature/article/stanley-morison-changing-the-times|website=Eye|accessdate=28 July 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Stanley Morison: A Portrait\">{{cite book|last1=Barr|first1=John|title=Stanley Morison: A Portrait|date=1971|publisher=British Museum|page=33|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8ojgAAAAMAAJ}}</ref><ref name=\"Mosley times italic\">{{cite web|last1=Mosley|first1=James|title=Comments on Typophile thread|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130313143211/http://typophile.com/node/70542|website=Typophile (archived)|accessdate=27 March 2017|quote=One of the distinctive things about French calligraphy of [the 1680s] is that the lead-in stroke of letters like i, m, n and so on have flat, rather 'roman', serifs, making them look a bit like a [[Oblique type|'sloped roman']]\u2026Fournier used it fifty years later in his 'new style' italics, and later so did Firmin Didot. And that French flat serif also turns up in\u2026the italic to Times New Roman.}}</ref> Morison had several years earlier attracted attention for promoting the radical idea that [[italic type|italics]] in book printing were too disruptive to the flow of text, and should be phased out.<ref name=\"wardle5\">{{cite book\n |last        = Wardle\n |first       = Tiffany\n |title       = The story of Perpetua\n |publisher   = [[University of Reading]]\n |year        = 2000\n |page        = 5\n |url         = http://www.typeculture.com/academic_resource/articles_essays/pdfs/tc_article_38.pdf\n |accessdate  = 2009-03-26\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20061110180517/http://www.typeculture.com/academic_resource/articles_essays/pdfs/tc_article_38.pdf\n |archivedate = 10 November 2006\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref><ref name=\"Fine Print\">{{cite journal|last1=Mosley|first1=James|author-link=James Mosley|title=Eric Gill's Perpetua Type|journal=Fine Print}}</ref> He rapidly came to concede that the idea was impractical, and later wryly commented to historian [[Harry Carter (typographer)|Harry Carter]] that Times' italic \"owes more to [[Didot (typeface)|Didot]] than dogma.\"<ref name=\"Tally of Types\" /> Morison wrote in a personal letter of Times New Roman's mixed heritage that it \"has the merit of not looking as if it had been designed by somebody in particular.\"<ref name=\"Loxley2006_MorisononGoudy\">{{cite book|author=Simon Loxley|title=Type: The Secret History of Letters|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9AfP2prmEDUC&pg=PA134|date=12 June 2006|publisher=I.B.Tauris|isbn=978-1-84511-028-4|pages=134\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"The history of the Times New Roman typeface\">{{cite web|last1=Alas|first1=Joel|title=The history of the Times New Roman typeface|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/a2fa033e-7ca1-11de-a7bf-00144feabdc0.html|website=Financial Times|accessdate=16 January 2016}}</ref>{{efn|Morison continued: \"\u2013 [[Frederic Goudy|Mr. Goudy]] for instance.\"<ref name=\"Updike Morison Letters\">{{cite book |last1=Updike |first1=Daniel Berkeley |last2=Morison |first2=Stanley |authorlink1=Daniel Berkeley Updike |authorlink2=Stanley Morison |editor1-last=McKitterick |editor1-first=David |editor1-link=David McKitterick |title=Stanley Morison & D.B. Updike: selected correspondence |publisher=Moretus Press |isbn=9780896790018 |pages=184-6}}</ref> This refers to [[Frederic Goudy]], one of the leading American type designers of the period. Morison considered his very organic tastes in letter design somewhat florid and self-indulgent.}}\n[[File:Times and bold.png|thumb|right|Times New Roman compared to its bold. The bold weight has a different style, more \"nineteenth-century\" in appearance, with flat serifs on the tops of letters and a more vertical axis visible on the 'o'.{{efn|In the roman style that the high serifs of the 'v' do not sit well with the lower shape of the 'i'. In his commentary on Times, Walter Tracy wrote that the designers should have tested words like 'divide' and 'jump' to spot this.{{sfn|Tracy|2003|p=204}}}}]]\nRather than creating a companion [[boldface]] with letterforms similar to the roman style, Times New Roman's bold has a different character, with a more condensed and more upright effect caused by making the horizontal parts of curves consistently the thinnest lines of each letter, and making the top serifs of letters like 'd' purely horizontal.<ref name=\"By printers, for printers\">{{cite web|last1=Hare|first1=Steve|title=By printers, for printers|url=http://www.eyemagazine.com/feature/article/by-printers-for-printers|website=Eye Magazine|accessdate=2 February 2016|quote=[Shown are] overlays from the article 'The Evolution of Times New Roman\u2019 by [[John Dreyfus]]. He writes: 'These drawings demonstrate how severely the bowl of \"p\" has been reduced in the bold version, because mainstrokes have been thickened without drawing the bold version any wider.'}}</ref> This effect is not found in sixteenth-century typefaces (which, in any case, did not have bold versions); it is most associated with [[Didone (typography)|Didone]] type of the early nineteenth century (and with the more recent 'Ionic' styles of type influenced by it that were offered by Linotype, discussed below).<ref name=\"Anatomy of a Typeface\">{{cite book|last1=Lawson|first1=Alexander|title=Anatomy of a Typeface|date=1990|publisher=David R. Godine|location=New York|isbn=9780879233334|pages=270\u2013294|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FiJ87ixLs0sC&pg=PA270|accessdate=6 March 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Dutch type 94\">{{cite book|last1=Middendorp|first1=Jan|title=Dutch type|date=2004|publisher=010 Publishers|location=Rotterdam|isbn=9789064504600|page=94|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sR9g5xPPJVQC&pg=PA94|accessdate=26 January 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Three chapters in the development of Clarendon/Ionic typefaces\">{{cite journal|last1=Miklav\u010di\u010d |first1=Mitja |title=Three chapters in the development of Clarendon/Ionic typefaces |journal=MA Thesis (University of Reading) |date=2006 |url=http://www.typefacedesign.org/resources/essay/MitjaMiclavcic_essay_scr.pdf |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111125001608/http://www.typefacedesign.org/resources/essay/MitjaMiclavcic_essay_scr.pdf |archivedate=25 November 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Coles|first1=Stephen|title=Times Bold Modified|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/stewf/8548006644|website=Flickr|accessdate=26 January 2016|}}</ref> Some commentators have found Times' bold unsatisfactory and too condensed, such as [[Walter Tracy]].{{sfn|Tracy|2003|p=204}}\n\n===Historical background===\nDuring the nineteenth century, the standard roman types for general-purpose printing were [[Didone (typography)|\"Modern\" or Didone]] designs,{{efn|Excluding some countries, such as Germany, where [[blackletter]] types were still very popular for extended text into the nineteenth century. For some higher-class literary printing eighteenth-century [[Caslon]] types, or more often [[Modernised Old Style (typeface)|Old Style]] faces in imitation of it, were common in Britain.<ref name=\"Ovink I\">{{cite journal|last1=Ovink|first1=G.W.|title=Nineteenth-century reactions against the didone type model - I|journal=Quaerendo|date=1971|volume=1|issue=2|pages=18\u201331|url=http://booksandjournals.brillonline.com/content/journals/10.1163/157006971x00301|accessdate=20 February 2016|doi=10.1163/157006971x00301}}</ref>}} and these were standard in all newspaper printing.{{sfn|Tracy|2003|p=181}}<ref name=\"Unger 1981\">{{cite journal|last1=Unger|first1=Gerard|authorlink1=Gerard Unger|title=Experimental No. 223, a newspaper typeface, designed by W.A. Dwiggins|journal=Quaerendo|date=1 January 1981|volume=11|issue=4|pages=302\u2013324|doi=10.1163/157006981X00274}}</ref> Designs in the nineteenth-century style remain a common part of the aesthetic of newspaper printing.{{efn|For example, in 2017 digital typeface designer [[Tobias Frere-Jones]] wrote that he kept his Exchange family, designed for the ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'', based on the nineteenth-century model as it \"had to feel like the news.\"<ref name=\"Frere-Jones Exchange\">{{cite web|last1=Frere-Jones|first1=Tobias|title=Decompiled & Remixed History: The Making of Exchange|url=https://frerejones.com/blog/decompiled-and-remixed-history-the-making-of-exchange|publisher=Frere-Jones Type|accessdate=1 August 2017}}</ref>}} According to Mosley and Williamson the modern-face used by ''The Times'' was Monotype's Series 7 or \"Modern Extended\", based on typefaces by [[Miller and Richard]].{{sfn|Williamson|1956|p=97}}<ref name=Mosley>{{cite web|last1=Mosley |first1=James|author-link=James Mosley |title=Comments on Typophile thread |url=http://typophile.com/node/49754 |website=Typophile |accessdate=27 July 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120612021330/http://typophile.com/node/49754 |archivedate=12 June 2012 }}</ref>{{efn|Because the cover of an issue of Monotype's trade magazine the ''Monotype Recorder'' compared the new \"Times New Roman\" with a sample of the previous type labelled as \"Times Old Roman\", some writers have assumed that the Times' previous typeface was actually called this, which it never was.<ref name=\"It was never called Times Old Roman\">{{cite web|last1=Rhatigan|first1=Dan|title=It was never called Times Old Roman|url=http://ultrasparky.org/archives/2011/08/it_was_never_ca.html|website=Ultrasparky|accessdate=27 July 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Mosley\" />}}\n\n[[File:Times prior newspaper faces.png|thumb|left|Times compared to a modern-face and the wide, monoline Excelsior, part of Linotype's [[Legibility Group]].]]\nBy the 1920s, some in the publishing industry felt that the modern-face model was too spindly and high-contrast for optimal legibility at the small sizes and punishing printing techniques of newspaper printing.{{sfn|Hutt|1960|p=54}}{{efn|Although it praised many-though not all-aspects of Times' design, so cannot be considered entirely unbiased, a 1937 article by the historian of printing [[Harry Carter (typographer)|Harry Carter]], who had been a draughtsman at the Monotype factory, commented in 1937 that modern faces at 9-point size made for \"a very fine engineer's job, but a poor design for reproduction on so small a scale.\"<ref name=\"Carter optical\">{{cite journal |last1=Carter |first1=Harry |authorlink1=Harry Carter (typographer) |title=Optical scale in type founding |journal=Typography |date=1937 |volume=4 |url=https://issuu.com/letterror/docs/harry_carter_optical_scale_in_typefounding |accessdate=15 September 2019}}</ref>}} In 1925, the Mergenthaler Linotype Company, Monotype's main competitor, launched a new newspaper typeface called Ionic, which became the first in a series known as the [[Legibility Group]].{{sfn|Hutt|1960|p=55}}<ref name=\"Three chapters in the development of Clarendon/Ionic typefaces\" /> These kept to the nineteenth-century model but greatly reduced the contrast of the letterform.<ref name=\"Gaultney Balancing\" /> The thinnest strokes of the letter were made thicker and strokes were kept as far apart as possible to maximise legibility. It proved extremely successful: Allen Hutt, Monotype's newspaper printing consultant in the late 1930s,<ref name=\"Allen Hutt Pimlott\">{{cite journal |last1=Pimlott |first1=Herbert |title=The Radical Type? G. Allen Hutt, the Communist Party and the politics of journalistic practice |journal=Journalism Practice |date=February 2013 |volume=7 |issue=1 |pages=81\u201395 |doi=10.1080/17512786.2012.685556}}</ref> later noted that it \"revolutionized newspaper text setting...within eighteen months it was adopted by 3,000 papers.\"{{sfn|Hutt|1960|p=55}} Although Times New Roman does not in any way resemble it, [[Walter Tracy]] commented that its arrival must at least have influenced the decision to consider a redesign.{{sfn|Tracy|2003|p=194}}\n\nThe development of Times New Roman was relatively involved due to the lack of a specific pre-existing model \u2013 or perhaps a surfeit of possible choices.<ref name=\"Lang 1946\">{{cite journal |last1=Lang |first1=Peggy |title=Times Roman: A Revaluation |journal=Alphabet & Image |date=1946 |pages=5\u201317}}</ref> Morison wrote in a memo that he hoped for a design that would have relatively sharp serifs, matching the general design of the Times' previous font, but on a darker and more traditional basic structure. Bulked-up versions of Monotype's pre-existing but rather dainty [[Baskerville]] and [[Perpetua (typeface)|Perpetua]] typefaces were considered for a basis, and the [[Legibility Group]] designs were also examined. (Perpetua, which Monotype had recently commissioned from sculptor [[Eric Gill]] at Morison's urging, is considered a 'transitional' design in aesthetic, although it does not revive any specific model.) Walter Tracy, who knew Lardent, suggested in the 1980s that \"Morison did not begin with a clear vision of the ultimate type, but felt his way along.\"{{sfn|Tracy|2003|p=202}}\n\n[[File:Ludlow Times New Roman Type Specimen (14204771208).jpg|thumb|left|A Ludlow Typograph specimen of Times New Roman Type Specimen from the metal type period. The design was altered in smaller sizes to increase readability, particularly obvious in the widened spacing of the six and eight point samples at centre right of the diagram.<ref name=\"Gaultney Balancing\">{{cite web|last1=Gaultney|first1=Victor|title=Balancing typeface legibility and economy Practical techniques for the type designer|url=http://scripts.sil.org/cms/scripts/page.php?site_id=nrsi&id=BalanLegEcon|publisher=University of Reading (MA thesis)|accessdate=13 October 2017}}</ref> The hollows at the top of upstrokes are also not seen in the standard digitisations.]]\nMorison's biographer [[Nicolas Barker]] has written that Morison's memos of the time wavered over a variety of options before it was ultimately concluded that Plantin formed the best basis for a condensed font that could nonetheless be made to fill out the full size of the letter space as far as possible. (Morison ultimately conceded that Perpetua, which had been his pet project, was 'too basically circular' to be practical to condense in an attractive way.{{efn|Dreyfus shows proofs of the experimental recut of Perpetua with shortened descenders to allow tighter linespacing.{{sfn|Dreyfus|1973|p=166}} Morison later commented that \"it stared at the reader\".}})\n\n[[Walter Tracy]] and James Moran, who discussed the design's creation with Lardent in the 1960s, found that Lardent himself had little memory of exactly what material Morison gave him as a specimen to use to design the typeface, but he told Moran that he remembered working on the design from archive photographs of vintage type; he thought this was a book printed by [[Christophe Plantin]].{{sfn|Tracy|2003|p=196}} Moran and Tracy suggested that this actually might have been the same specimen of type from the Plantin-Moretus Museum that Plantin had been based on.{{sfn|Tracy|2003|p=199}} (Although based on a type in the collection of the [[Plantin-Moretus Museum]], which preserves much of the collection of sixteenth-century printer [[Christophe Plantin]], Plantin is actually based specifically on a Granjon font for which matrices (moulds) only arrived in the collection after Plantin's death.<ref name=\"Vervliet2008\" />) The sharpened serifs somewhat recall Perpetua, although Morison's stated reason for them was to provide continuity with the previous Didone design and the crispness associated with the ''Times''' printing; he also cited as a reason that sharper serifs looked better after [[Stereotype (printing)|stereotyping]] or printed on a [[Rotary printing press|rotary press]].<ref name=\"From a Cambridge Diary\" /> Although Morison may not have literally drawn the design, his influence on its concept was sufficient that he felt in a letter to [[Daniel Berkeley Updike]] that he could call it \"my one effort at designing a font\".{{efn|Spelling modernised. Morison wrote \"fount\", the usual spelling in British English at the time.<ref name=\"Updike Morison Letters\" />}} Morison's several accounts of his reasoning in designing the concept of Times New Roman were somewhat contradictory and historians of printing have suggested that in practice they were mostly composed to rationalise his pre-existing aesthetic preferences. After Morison's death Allen Hutt went so far as to describe his unsigned 1936 article on the topic as \"rather odd\u2026it can only be regarded as a piece of Morisonian mystification\".{{sfn|Hutt|1970|p=264}}\n\nLardent's original drawings are according to Rhatigan lost, but photographs exist of his drawings. Rhatigan comments that Lardent's originals show \"the spirit of the final type, but not the details.\"<ref name=\"Time and Times again\">{{cite web|last1=Rhatigan|first1=Dan|title=Time and Times again|url=http://ultrasparky.org/archives/2011/09/time_and_times_.html|website=ultrasparky.org|accessdate=28 July 2015}}</ref> The design was adapted from Lardent's large drawings by the Monotype drawing office team in [[Salfords]], [[Surrey]], which worked out spacing and simplified some fine details.{{sfn|Tracy|2003|p=202}}  Further changes were made after manufacturing began (the latter a difficult practice, since new punches and matrices had to be machined after each design change).{{sfn|Tracy|2003|p=202}}\n\nMorison continued to develop a close connection with the ''Times'' that would last throughout his life. Morison edited the History of the Times from 1935 to 1952, and in the post-war period, at a time when Monotype effectively stopped developing new typefaces due to [[Social history of the United Kingdom (1945\u2013present)#Age of Austerity|pressures of austerity]], took a post as editor of the ''[[Times Literary Supplement]]'' which he held from 1945 to 1948.<ref name=\"oxdnb\">{{cite book|last=Carter|first=H. G.|others=rev. David McKitterick|title=Morison, Stanley Arthur (1889\u20131967)|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|year=2004|volume=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography}}</ref> Times New Roman remained Morison's only type design; he designed a type to be issued by the [[Bauer Type Foundry]] of Frankfurt but the project was abandoned due to the war. Morison's friend Brooke Crutchley recorded in his diary being told by Morison that the test type sent to him just before the war was sent to the government to be \"analysed in order that we should know whether the Hun is hard up for lead or antimony or tin.\"<ref name=\"From a Cambridge Diary\">{{cite journal |last1=Crutchley |first1=Brooke |title=From a Cambridge Diary |journal=Matrix |date=1990 |volume=10 |publisher=[[Whittington Press]]}}</ref>\n\n==Metal type versions==\nA large number of variants of Times were cut during the metal type period, in particular families of titling capitals for headlines.{{sfn|Williamson|1956|p=39}} Walter Tracy in ''Letters of Credit'', Allen Hutt and others have discussed these extensively in their works on the family.{{sfn|Hutt|1970|p=270}}{{sfn|Tracy|2003|p=207}}{{sfn|Hutt|1960|p=107}}\n\n===Titling===\nMonotype also created some caps-only 'titling' designs to match Times New Roman itself, which was intended for body text.<ref name=\"The Times: New roman and related founts.\" /> These are not sold by Monotype in digital format, although Linotype's Times Eighteen in the same style (see below) is.<ref name=\"Linotype Times Eighteen\" />\n\n===Times Hever Titling===\n[[File:Times Hever Titling.jpg|thumb|right|Times Hever Titling from a Monotype specimen.]]\nAn elegant titling caps design, quite different from Times New Roman with a [[Caslon|Caslon-style]] A (with a serif at top left of the letter, suggesting a stroke written with a quill) and old-style C and W; Tracy suggests Monotype's previous [[Bembo|Poliphilus]] design as an influence.{{sfn|Tracy|2003|p=208}} Named after [[Hever Castle]], the home of the ''Times''' owner [[John Jacob Astor|Lord Astor]] and designed early on, it was used by the ''Times'' for headings in the lighter sections such as [[Society reporting|society pages]], arts and fashion.{{sfn|Tracy|2003|p=207}}<ref name=\"Comments on Typophile thread Savoie Hudson\">{{cite web|last1=Savoie|first1=Alice|last2=Hudson|first2=John|title=Comments on Typophile thread |url=http://typophile.com/node/101099 |website=Typophile |accessdate=16 September 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140717150729/http://typophile.com/node/101099 |archivedate=17 July 2014 }}</ref> It has not been digitised.\n\n===Times Wide (1938, series 427)===\nA variant intended for book printing, avoiding the slight condensation of the original Times New Roman.<ref name=\"Monotype Recorder first showing\">{{cite journal|title=Typographic Problems of the Illustrated Book|journal=Monotype Recorder|date=1938|volume=37|issue=2|page=31|url=http://www.metaltype.co.uk/downloads/mr/mr_37_2.pdf|quote=Some types look larger, size for size, than others, because they have unusually short descenders and ascenders. This allows more room for the [[X-height|'x' or the middle part of the lower-case]] [but] a 'large x' is bound to waste space ''horizontally''...the imperceptible condensation of Monotype Times New Roman puts it in a class by itself as a news face. In the wider book measure, however, condensation is no asset.}}</ref> Although it was popular in the metal type period for book printing, it was apparently never digitised. Monotype also created a version, series 627, with long descenders more appropriate to classic book typography.{{sfn|Williamson|1956|p=102}} Optional [[text figures]] were also available.<ref name=\"Effra composition matrices\">{{cite web |title=Composition matrices |url=https://shop.effrapress.co.uk/composition-matrices/ |publisher=Effra Press |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Series 727 and 827===\nMonotype also produced Series 727, in which the heavier strokes of upper-case letters were made slightly thinner.<ref name=\"Monotype Recorder issue 3 1956\" /> This was done to produce a lighter effect in which capital letters do not stand out so much, and was particularly intended for [[German nouns|German use]], since in the German language capitals are far more common since they appear at the start of each noun.<ref name=\"Monotype Recorder issue 3 1956\" /> Series 827 modified some letters (notably the ''R'') to correspond to their appearance in other typefaces popular in French printing. This production of what are now called [[stylistic alternates]] to suit national tastes was common at the time, and many alternates were also offered for [[Gill Sans#History|Gill Sans]] for use in Europe.<ref name=\"Monotype Recorder issue 3 1956\">{{cite journal|title=Modifications and extensions of a single series|journal=Monotype Recorder|date=1956|volume=40|issue=3|page=14|url=http://www.metaltype.co.uk/downloads/mr/mr_40_3.pdf|accessdate=27 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Claritas===\nA modified 4\u00be point size of Times Roman was produced by Monotype for use in printing matter requiring a very small size of type. Listed as Times Newspaper Smalls, available as either Series 333 or 335, it was also referred to by the name Claritas.<ref name=\"Changing the Times\" />\n\n===Times 4-line Mathematics Series 569===\nThis is a variant designed for printing mathematical formulae, using the 4\u2011line system for mathematics developed by Monotype in 1957.<ref name=\"The Monotype 4-Line System for Setting Mathematics\">{{cite web |last1=Rhatigan |first1=Daniel |title=The Monotype 4-Line System for Setting Mathematics |url=http://typeculture.com/academic-resource/articles-essays/the-monotype-4-line-system-for-setting-mathematics/ |website=Type Culture |accessdate=17 August 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Three typefaces for mathematics\">{{cite web|last1=Rhatigan|first1=Daniel|title=Three typefaces for mathematics|url=http://ultrasparky.org/school/pdf/DanielRhatigan_Dissertation.pdf|publisher=[[University of Reading]] (MA thesis)|accessdate=2 February 2016}}</ref> This modified version of Times Roman was designed for use as part of Monotype's 4-line Mathematics system. The major changes to the Times Roman typeface itself were a reduction in the slope of italic characters to 12 degrees from 16 degrees, so as to reduce the need for kerning, and a change in the form of italic v and w so that italic v could be more easily distinguished from a Greek nu.<ref name=\"The Monotype 4-Line System for Setting Mathematics\" />\n\nThe 4-line system involved casting characters for 10-point Times Roman on 6-point [[Body (typography)|bodies]]. The top of the character would overhang the slug, forming a [[kern (typography)|kern]] which was less fragile than the normal kerns of foundry type, as it was on a slab of cast metal. This technique had been in previous use on Monotype machines, usually involving double-height matrices, to allow the automatic setting of \"advertising figures\" (numbers that occupy two or more lines, usually to clearly indicate a price in an advertisement set in small type). This meant that the same matrix could be used for both superscript and subscript numbers. More importantly, it allowed a variable or other item to have both a superscript and a subscript at the same time, one above the other, without inordinate difficulty.<ref name=\"The Monotype 4-Line System for Setting Mathematics\" />\n\nPreviously, while the Monotype system, due to its flexibility, was widely used for setting mathematical formulas, the typeface Modern Series 7 was usually used for this purpose.<ref>T. W. Chaundy, P. R. Barett, Charles Batey, ''The Printing of Mathematics'', Oxford University Press (1954, 1957)</ref> Because of the popularity of Times Roman at the time, Monotype chose to design a variant of Times Roman suited to mathematical composition, and recut many additional characters needed for mathematics, including special symbols as well as Greek and Fraktur alphabets, to accompany the system instead of designing it around the typeface that was being used, for which characters were already available. Matrices for some 700 characters were available as part of Times Roman Series 569 when it was released in 1958, with new characters constantly being added for over a decade afterwards (thus, in 1971, 8,000 characters were included, and new ones were being added at a rate of about 5 per week).<ref name=\"The Monotype 4-Line System for Setting Mathematics\" />\n{{clear}}\n\n==Usage==\n[[File:Colliers Times New Roman letter perfect.jpg|thumb|right|A 1943 brochure used by Crowell-Collier, one of the first major American users of Times New Roman, to promote the changeover.<ref name=\"Happiness is Times New Roman\" />]]\nTimes New Roman's popularity rapidly expanded beyond its original niche, becoming popular in book printing and general publishing. Monotype took advantage of this popularity by commissioning a widened version, Series 427, for book publishing, although many books ultimately used the original version.{{sfn|Williamson|1956|p=103}}\n\nAn early use of Times New Roman outside its origin was by [[Daniel Berkeley Updike]], an influential historian of printing with whom Morison carried an extensive correspondence. Impressed by the design, he used it to set his book ''Some Aspects of Printing, Old and New''.<ref name=\"Blackwell2004\">{{cite book|first=Lewis|last=Blackwell|title=20th-century Type|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WNUJ0dKGxmsC&pg=PA76|year=2004|publisher=Laurence King Publishing|isbn=978-1-85669-351-6|pages=76\u20139}}</ref><ref name=\"D.B. Updike Set Standard of Great Craftsmanship\">{{cite web|last1=Lawson|first1=Alexander S.|title=D.B. Updike Set Standard of Great Craftsmanship|url=http://www.alexanderslawson.com/d-b-updike-set-standard-of-great-craftsmanship/|website=The Alexander S. Lawson Archive|accessdate=15 December 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Lawson Morison Obituary\">{{cite web|last1=Lawson|first1=Alexander S.|title=Stanley Morison: Significant Historian (obituary)|url=http://www.alexanderslawson.com/stanley-morison-significant-historian/|website=The Alexander S. Lawson Archive|accessdate=14 May 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160527130023/http://www.alexanderslawson.com/stanley-morison-significant-historian/|archivedate=27 May 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It then was chosen by the Crowell-Collier magazines ''[[Woman's Home Companion]]'' and then its sister publications such as ''[[Collier's]]''.{{sfn|Dreyfus|1973|p=172}}<ref name=\"Lawson1990\">{{cite book|author=Alexander S. Lawson|title=Anatomy of a Typeface|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FiJ87ixLs0sC&pg=PA270|date=January 1990|publisher=David R. Godine Publisher|isbn=978-0-87923-333-4|pages=270\u2013294}}</ref><ref name=\"Crowell-Collier adopts a Type Developed by London Times\">{{cite journal|title=Crowell-Collier adopts a Type Developed by London Times|journal=Inland Printer and American Lithographer|volume=111}}</ref> A brochure was published to mark the change along with a letter from Morison hoping that the redesign would be a success.<ref name=\"Happiness is Times New Roman\">{{cite web|last1=Heller|first1=Steven|title=Happiness is Times New Roman|url=http://www.printmag.com/daily-heller/happiness-is-times-new-roman/|website=Print magazine|accessdate=15 December 2016}}</ref> Ultimately it became Monotype's best-selling metal type of all time.<ref name=Badaracco>{{cite journal|last1=Badaracco|first1=Claire|title=Innovative Industrial Design and Modern Public Culture: The Monotype Corporation, 1922\u20131932|journal=Business & Economic History|date=1991|volume=20 (second series)|pages=226\u2013233|url=http://www.thebhc.org/sites/default/files/beh/BEHprint/v020/p0226-p0233.pdf|accessdate=19 December 2015|publisher=Business History Conference}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet |author=Whittington Press |author-link= |user=whittingtonpres|number=720745586069213185|date=14 April 2016|title= Sales chart of Monotype die cases.}}</ref>\n\n[[Walter Tracy]], who worked on a redesign, however noted that the design's compression and fine detail extending to the edge of the [[Matrix (printing)|matrices]] was not ideal in the aggressive conditions of most newspaper printing, in which the ''Times'' was unusual for its particularly high standard of printing suiting its luxury market. Users found that in the hot metal period it was common for the molten metal to rapidly eat through the matrices as type was being cast, and so it did not become popular among other newspapers: \"Times Roman achieved its popularity chiefly in general printing, not in newspaper work.\"{{sfn|Tracy|2003|p=204}} He described it as particularly used in \"book work, especially non-fiction\" such as the ''[[Encyclopaedia Britannica]]''.{{sfn|Tracy|2003|p=204}} Hutt also commented that Times New Roman's relative condensation was less useful than might be expected for newspaper printing, since in a normal newspaper column frequent paragraph breaks tend to provide area that can absorb the space of wider letters without increasing the number of lines used\u2013but ''The Times'', whose [[Style guide|house style]] in the 1930s was to minimise the number of paragraph breaks, was an exception to this.{{sfn|Hutt|1970|p=264}}\n\nTimes New Roman remains popular in publishing, helped by the extremely large range of characters available for international and mathematics printing.{{sfn|Williamson|1956|p=102}}<ref name=\"Es gilt das gesprochene Wort\">{{cite web |last1=Bergmann |first1=Christopher |title=Es gilt das gesprochene Wort: Schriftarten f\u00fcr IPA-Transkriptionen |url=https://www.isoglosse.de/2014/03/schriftarten-ipa-transkriptionen/ |website=Isoglosse |accessdate=14 November 2018}}</ref> For example, the [[American Psychological Association]] suggests using Times New Roman in papers written in its [[APA style]].<ref name=\"APA Style Blog\">{{cite web |last1=Lee |first1=Chelsea |title=Fonts of Knowledge |url=https://blog.apastyle.org/apastyle/2013/03/fonts-of-knowledge.html |website=APA Style Blog |publisher=[[American Psychological Association]] |accessdate=14 November 2018}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n==Linotype releases==\n[[File:Many accented a (8277806822).jpg|thumb|Working drawings for a Linotype release of \"Times Roman\". Various accents are drawn together on the same sheet.<ref name=\"Charli Luc\">{{cite web |title=Pencil To Pixel \u2013 Monotype |url=https://luccharli.wordpress.com/2012/11/23/pencil-to-pixel-monotype-3/ |website=Charli Luc |accessdate=2 April 2019}}</ref>]]\n[[File:Times Roman vs Times New Roman.png|thumb|Some differences between Linotype's Times Roman and Monotype's Times New Roman typefaces.<ref name=\"Strizver TypeTalk\" /><ref name=\"Fonts in Use Low\u2190tech TNR vs. TR\">{{cite web |last1=Sluiter |first1=Matthijs |last2=Hardwig |first2=Florian |title=Low\u2190tech Magazine website |url=https://fontsinuse.com/uses/24504/low-tech-magazine-website#comment-630450 |website=Fonts in Use |accessdate=2 April 2019}}</ref>]]\nDespite Monotype's key role in creating Times New Roman, its rival  [[Mergenthaler Linotype Company|Linotype]] rapidly began to offer the design; ''The Times'' used Linotype equipment for much of its production. Linotype referred to the design as ''Times'' or ''Times Roman''. Monotype and Linotype have since merged, but slight differences have split the lineage of Times into two subtly different designs.\n\nAlthough Times New Roman and Times are very similar, various differences developed between the versions marketed by Linotype and Monotype when the master fonts were transferred from metal to [[cold type|photo]] and digital media. For example, Linotype has slanted [[serif]]s on the capital S, while Monotype's are vertical, and Linotype has an extra serif on the number 5.<ref name=\"Strizver TypeTalk\">{{cite web|first=Ilene|last=Strizver|url=http://www.creativepro.com/blog/typetalk-times-roman-vs-times-new-roman|title=TypeTalk: Times Roman vs Times New Roman|work=CreativePro.com}}</ref> Most of these differences are invisible in body text at normal reading distances, or 10pts at 300 dpi. Subtle competition grew between the two foundries, as the proportions and details as well as the width metrics for their version of Times grew apart.<ref name=\"times-development\" /> Differences between the two versions do occur in the lowercase z in the italic weight, (Times Linotype has a curl also followed in the STIX revival, Times New Roman is straight){{sfn|Tracy|2003|p=204}} and in the percent sign in all weights. (Linotype and STIX have a stroke connecting up the left-hand zero with a slash, Times New Roman does not.) Monotype's 'J' is non-descending, but Linotype's in the bold weight descends below the baseline.\n\nLinotype licensed its version to [[Xerox]] and then [[Adobe Systems|Adobe]] and [[Apple Inc.|Apple]], guaranteeing its importance in digital printing by making it one of the core fonts of the [[PostScript]] page description language.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Shaw|first1=Paul|title=Some history about Arial|url=http://www.paulshawletterdesign.com/2011/09/blue-pencil-no-18%E2%80%94some-history-about-arial/|website=Paul Shaw Letter Design|accessdate=22 May 2015}}</ref> Microsoft's version of Times New Roman is licensed from Monotype, hence the original name. For compatibility, Monotype had to subtly redraw their design to match the widths from the Adobe/Linotype version.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Simonson|first1=Mark|author-link=Mark Simonson|title=Monotype's Other Arials|url=http://www.marksimonson.com/notebook/view/monotypes-other-arials|publisher=Mark Simonson Studio|accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref> Versions of Times New Roman from Monotype (discussed below) exist which vary from the PostScript metrics.\n\nLinotype applied for registration of the trademark name ''Times Roman'' and received registration status in 1945. In the 1980s, there was an attempt by a group of entrepreneurs to seek from [[Rupert Murdoch]], who owned ''The Times'', the right to use the Times Roman name; separately, a legal action was also initiated to clarify the right of Monotype to use the name in the US despite Linotype's registration. As a result of legal action, Linotype and its licensees continued to use the name Times Roman, while Monotype and its licensees used the name Times New Roman.<ref name=\"times-development\">{{cite web |url= http://www.truetype-typography.com/articles/times.htm |title=Times (New) Roman and its part in the Development of Scalable Font Technology |author=Charles Bigelow |year=1994 |accessdate=4 July 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Modern releases==\n\n===As Times New Roman===\nMonotype sells a wider range of styles and [[Font#Optical size|optical sizes]] for Times New Roman than are offered with Windows, in order to meet the needs of newspapers and books which print at a range of text sizes.<ref name=\"Changing the Times\" /> Its current release includes Regular, Medium, Semi Bold and Bold weights with matching italics, Extra Bold, Condensed (in regular, italic and bold), Seven (for smaller text, in regular, italic, bold and bold italic) and Small Text (for very small text, in regular, italic and bold).<ref>{{cite web|title=Monotype Library: Times New Roman|url=http://www.linotype.com/1540/TimesNewRoman-family.html|publisher=Monotype|accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref> The four-weight version included with Windows was also distributed as part of Microsoft's [[Core Fonts for the Web]] package.<ref name=\"apple-techspot\">{{cite web | url=http://www.techspot.com/news/26438-microsoft-and-apple-extend-font-licensing-agreement.html |title=Microsoft and Apple extend font licensing agreement |author=Jose Vilches |date=2007-08-03 |accessdate=2011-06-25}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2017, the version of Times New Roman included with [[Windows 10]], version 6.96, includes [[small capitals]], [[text figures]], and italic [[swash capitals]].<ref name=\"TNR 6.96\">{{cite AV media | people = | date =\n | title = Times New Roman, v. 6.96 | medium = Font digitisation }}</ref><ref name=\"FIU New Roman Times Swash capital comment\">{{cite web |last1=Thiago |last2=Hardwig |first2=Florian |title=New Roman Times \u2013 Camper Van Beethoven |url=https://fontsinuse.com/uses/25135/new-roman-times-camper-van-beethoven#comment-631475 |website=Fonts in Use |accessdate=2 April 2019}}</ref> The Microsoft/Monotype digitisation of Times New Roman omits automatic [[typographic ligature|ligature]] insertion (although as of v. 6.96 it is selectable),<ref name=\"TNR 6.96\" /> which the version of Times installed with macOS has. (This can result in unsightly character collisions if the characters 'fi' are needed.)\n\n===Times New Roman World===\nThis is a version based on fonts released with [[Windows Vista]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Times New Roman OS|url=http://www.linotype.com/616201/TimesNewOSFamilyPack-valuepack.html?site=details&fetchPart=details|website=Linotype|publisher=Monotype|accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref> It includes fonts in [[Windows Glyph List|WGL]] character sets, Hebrew and Arabic characters. Similar to [[Helvetica#Helvetica World|Helvetica World]], Arabic in italic fonts are in roman positions.\n\n===Linotype variants===\nLike Monotype, Linotype released additional versions of Times for different text sizes. These include:\n*Times Ten is a version specially designed for smaller text (12 point and below). It features wider characters and stronger hairlines.<ref name=\"Linotype Times Ten\">{{cite web|title=Linotype Times Ten|url=http://www.myfonts.com/fonts/linotype/times-ten/|website=MyFonts|accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Adobe Times Ten|url=http://www.myfonts.com/fonts/adobe/times-ten/|website=MyFonts|accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref> In 2004 prominent typeface designer [[Erik Spiekermann]] said that he believed that it was the best Times New Roman digitisation then available.<ref name=\"State Department bans Courier New 12, except for treaties\">{{cite web |last1=Shaw |first1=Paul |authorlink1=Paul Shaw (design historian) |title=State Department bans Courier New 12, except for treaties |url=https://www.aiga.org/state-department-bans-courier-new-12-except-for-treaties |publisher=AIGA |accessdate=27 December 2018}}</ref>\n*Times Eighteen, a headline version for point sizes of 18 and larger. The characters are subtly condensed and the hairlines are finer. The current version has no italics, but does have a lower case (whereas some Times titling fonts were capitals only).<ref name=\"Linotype Times Eighteen\">{{cite web|title=Linotype Times Eighteen|url=http://www.myfonts.com/fonts/linotype/times-eighteen/|website=MyFonts|accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref>\n*Times Europa Office, a 2006 adaptation of ''The Times's'' 1972 design Times Europa (see below). This is a complete family of designs intended for use on poor-quality paper. The updating, created by Akira Kobayashi, contains [[Typeface#Typesetting numbers|tabular]] numbers, mathematical signs, and [[currency symbol]]s. Each character has the same advance width in all the fonts in the family so that changing from regular to bold or italic does not affect word wrap.<ref name=\"Europa Office\">{{cite web|url=http://www.linotype.com/en/137439/timeseuropaoffice-family.html |title=Times Europa Office Font Family |publisher=Linotype.com |accessdate=21 September 2013}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n==Later typefaces used by ''The Times''==\n[[File:Balfour Declaration in the Times 9 November 1917.jpg|thumb|''The Times''' previous typeface from an article describing the [[Balfour Declaration]] in 1917.]]\n''The Times'' newspaper has commissioned various successors to Times New Roman:\n*Times Europa was designed by [[Walter Tracy]] in 1972 for ''The Times'', as a sturdier alternative to the Times font family, designed for the demands of faster printing presses and cheaper paper.<ref name=\"Hutt Tracy 1973\">{{cite journal |last1=Hutt |first1=Allan |title=Walter Tracy, type designer |journal=[[The Penrose Annual]] |date=1973 |pages=101-115}}</ref> It has been released commercially by Adobe, among others, recently in an updating by Linotype as Times Europa Office (discussed above).<ref name=\"Adobe Times Europa\">{{cite web|title=Adobe Times Europa|url=http://www.myfonts.com/fonts/adobe/times-europa/|website=MyFonts|accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Europa Office\" />\n*Times Roman replaced Times Europa on 30 August 1982.<ref name=\"timesonline.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/news/uk/article1943001.ece |title=After 221 years, the world's leading newspaper shows off a fresh face |publisher=Thetimes.co.uk |date=20 November 2006 |accessdate=21 September 2013}}</ref>\n*Times Millennium was made in 1991, drawn by Gunnlaugur Briem on the instructions of Aurobind Patel, composing manager of News International.<ref name=\"timesonline.co.uk\"/><ref name=Briem>{{cite web|last1=Briem|first1=Gunnlaugur|title=BriemTimes|url=http://66.147.242.192/~operinan/2/2.2a/2.2.7.6.btim.letter.htm|publisher=Gunnlaugur SE Briem|accessdate=27 July 2015}}</ref>\n*Times Classic first appeared in 2001.<ref name=\"Hall Typography of News\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fontshop.com/blog/fontmag/002/02_news/|first=Peter|last=Hall|title=The Typography of News: Bigger, faster, better |publisher=Fontshop.com |accessdate=21 September 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120415015824/http://www.fontshop.com/blog/fontmag/002/02_news/|archive-date=15 April 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"New Cuts at The Times\">{{cite web |last1=Baines |first1=Phil |title=Face lift: new cuts at The Times |url=http://www.eyemagazine.com/feature/article/face-lift-new-cuts-at-the-times |website=Eye |accessdate=10 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Berry Typographic Texture of the News\">{{cite web |last1=Berry |first1=John |title=dot-font: The Typographic Texture of the News |url=https://creativepro.com/dot-font-the-typographic-texture-of-the-news/ |website=Creative Pro |accessdate=10 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Berry News on Paper\">{{cite web |last1=Berry |first1=John |title=dot-font: News on Paper in the Digital Age |url=https://creativepro.com/dot-font-news-on-paper-in-the-digital-age/ |website=Creative Pro |accessdate=10 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Design Week Housestyle\">{{cite web |title=Housestyle is just the type for redesign of The Times newspaper |url=https://www.designweek.co.uk/issues/14-february-2002/housestyle-is-just-the-type-for-redesign-of-the-times-newspaper/ |website=Design Week |accessdate=10 May 2019}}</ref> Designed as an economical face by Dave Farey and Richard Dawson, it took advantage of the new PC-based publishing system at the newspaper; the new typeface included 120 letters per font.<ref name=\"Driver 2006\">{{cite news |last1=Driver |first1=David |title=After 221 years, the world's leading newspaper shows off a fresh face |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/after-221-years-the-worlds-leading-newspaper-shows-off-a-fresh-face-vxs5wkc0ch6 |accessdate=9 April 2020 |work=The Times |date=2006}}</ref><ref name=\"Farey part 1\">{{cite journal|last1=Farey|first1=Dave|title=A Life and Times, Part 1|journal=Ultrabold|date=2014|issue=16|pages=16\u201325}}</ref><ref name=\"Farey part 2\">{{cite journal|last1=Farey|first1=Dave|title=A Life and Times, Part 2|journal=Ultrabold|date=2014|issue=15|pages=3\u201313}}</ref>\n*Times Modern was unveiled on 20 November 2006, as the successor of Times Classic.<ref name=\"timesonline.co.uk\"/> Designed for improving legibility in smaller font sizes, it uses 45-degree angled bracket serifs. It was designed by Research Studios, led by designer [[Neville Brody]] with input from [[Ben Preston]],  deputy editor of ''The Times''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prnewswire.co.uk/cgi/news/release?id=184449 |title=Neville Brody's Research Studios Creates New Font and Design Changes for The Times as Compact Format Continues to Attract Loyal Readership |location=LONDON |publisher=Prnewswire.co.uk |date=2006-11-15 |accessdate=21 September 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Luke Prowse interview\">{{cite web |first=Alan|last=Formby-Jackson|title=A conversation with Times Modern designer Luke Prowse |url=http://www.visualeditors.com/jackson/2006/11/a-conversation-with-time-modern-designer-luke-prowse/ |website=Visual Editors |accessdate=2 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070208180600/http://www.visualeditors.com/jackson/2006/11/a-conversation-with-time-modern-designer-luke-prowse/|archive-date=8 February 2007}}</ref> (Other designs have been released called Times Modern; see below.) During the Times New Roman period ''The Times'' also sometimes used [[Perpetua (typeface)|Perpetua Titling]].<ref name=\"Tally of Types\" /><ref name=\"The Times: New roman and related founts.\">{{cite web |title=The Times: New roman and related founts. |url=http://www.elbrecht.de/TNR&RF.jpg |publisher=Times/Monotype |accessdate=16 September 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150916043631/http://www.elbrecht.de/TNR%26RF.jpg |archivedate=16 September 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==William Starling Burgess==\nIn 1994 the printing historian [[Mike Parker (typographer)|Mike Parker]] published claims that the design of Times New Roman's roman or regular style was based on a 1904 design of [[William Starling Burgess]].<ref name=\"Burgess\">\n{{cite journal\n  | last = Parker\n  | first = Mike\n  | title = W. Starling Burgess, Type Designer?\n  | journal = Printing History\n  | volume = 31/32\n  | pages = 52\u2013108\n  | year = 1994}}\n</ref> This theory remains controversial.<ref name=\"Burgess2\">\n{{cite news\n | url = http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/a2fa033e-7ca1-11de-a7bf-00144feabdc0.html\n | last = Alas\n | first = Joel\n | accessdate = 26 August 2009\n | date = 1 August 2009\n | title = The history of the Times New Roman typeface\n | newspaper = Financial Times\n}}</ref><ref name=eastland>Katherine Eastland. [http://www.thedaily.com/page/2011/08/15/081511-opinions-history-times-new-roman-eastland-1-3/ The History Page: Exactly your type], TheDaily.com, 15 August 2011</ref> Parker and his friend [[Gerald Giampa]], a Canadian printer who had bought up the defunct American branch of Lanston Monotype, claimed that, in 1904, Burgess created a type design for company documents at his shipyard in Marblehead, Massachusetts, and hired Lanston Monotype to issue it.<ref name=eastland/> However, Burgess abandoned the idea and Monotype shelved the sketches, ultimately reusing them as a basis for Times New Roman. Giampa claimed that he stumbled upon original material in 1987, after he had purchased Lanston Monotype, and that some of the papers that had been his evidence had been lost in a flood at his house, while Parker claimed that an additional source was material in a section of the Smithsonian now closed due to [[asbestos]] contamination.<ref name=eastland/><ref name=\"Stanley Morison and Times New Roman\" /> Giampa asked Parker to complete the type from the limited number of surviving letters, which was issued in June 2009 by [[Font Bureau]] under the name of 'Starling'.<ref name=eastland/><ref name=\"Stanley Morison and Times New Roman\" />\n \nReception to the claims was sceptical, with dismissal from Morison's biographer [[Nicolas Barker]] and [[Luc Devroye]] among others; Barker suggested that the material had been fabricated in order to aid Giampa in embarrassing Monotype's British branch, while Devroye and Thomas Phinney of [[FontLab]] suggested that the claim had begun as a prank.<ref name=\"Stanley Morison and Times New Roman\">{{cite web|last1=Loxley|first1=Simon|title=Stanley Morison and Times New Roman|url=http://www.simonloxley.com/ar_02_stan.html|publisher=Ultrabold|accessdate=8 March 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Starling Burgess: No Type Designer\">{{cite book|last1=Barker|first1=Nicolas|title=Form and Meaning in the History of the Book : selected essays|date=2003|publisher=British Library|location=London|isbn=0-7123-4777-1|pages=[https://archive.org/details/formmeaninginhis0000bark/page/371 371\u2013390]|chapter=Starling Burgess: No Type Designer|chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/formmeaninginhis0000bark/page/371}}</ref><ref name=\"Devroye on Burgess\">{{cite web|last1=Devroye|first1=Luc|title=William Starling Burgess|url=http://luc.devroye.org/fonts-24415.html|website=Type Design Information|accessdate=8 March 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Hudson Phinney TypeDrawers\" /> In 2010, writer Mark Owens described Parker's article in retrospect as \"the scantest of evidence\" and a \"fog of irrelevant details\".<ref name=\"A Note on the Type\">{{cite book |last1=Owens |first1=Mark |title=A Note on the Type |date=2010 |publisher=Carnegie Museum of Art |pages=268\u2013270}}</ref>{{efn|Among the few prominent figures in typography to express even qualified support for the idea was Tiro Typeworks owner John Hudson, Giampa's neighbour. He wrote in 2008 that he had examined Giampa's claimed patterns and that they looked as if they were made using an early Monotype production process obsolete by 1931: \"the material evidence of the two-part patterns and their numbering -- if they are genuine --, suggests very strongly a design that significantly pre-dates 1931...The patterns are either deliberate hoax or they are historical artefacts\" and that he was \"unconvinced that this is a hoax\"; but in 2019, after Giampa and Parker's deaths, he said \"I do think it entirely possible that the whole thing was a hoax.\"<ref name=\"Hudson on Typophile\">{{cite web |last1=Hudson |first1=John |title=Comments on Typophile thread |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110908011822/http://typophile.com/node/50470 |website=Typophile (archived) |accessdate=30 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Hudson Phinney TypeDrawers\">{{cite web |last1=Hudson |first1=John |last2=Phinney |first2=Thomas |title=Comments on TypeDrawers thread |url=https://typedrawers.com/discussion/3073/never-mind-starling |website=TypeDrawers |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> The claims did convince prominent type designer [[Walter Tracy]], who had written a major analysis of Times New Roman's genesis in his book ''Letters of Credit''; however he died in April 1995, before Parker's finalised publication, and did not live to see the extensive rebuttals.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Tracy |first1=Walter |title=Letters of Credit: A Correction |journal=Journal of the Printing Historical Society |date=1995 |pages=2\u20133}}</ref>}} Monotype executive Dan Rhatigan described the theory as implausible in 2011: \"I'll admit that I tend to side with the more fully documented (both in general, and in agreement with what little I can find within Monotype to support it) notion that Times New Roman was based on Plantin...I won't rule out the possibility that Starling Burgess drew up the concept first, but [[Occam's razor]] makes me doubt it.\"<ref name=\"It was never called Times Old Roman\" />\n\nThe Times Online web site credits the design to \"Stanley Morrison, Victor Lardent and perhaps Starling Burgess\".<ref>\n{{cite news\n | url = http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/letters/feedback/article1185820.ece\n | accessdate = 26 August 2009\n | date = 25 January 2007\n | title = FAQ: infrequently asked questions\n | newspaper = Times Online\n}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n==Designs inspired by Times New Roman==\n[[File:Times Modern (7128712341).jpg|thumb|Times Modern [[Swash (typography)|Swash]], an exaggerated and unauthorised display adaptation of Times from the phototypesetting period.]]\n[[File:Pelham Infant.jpg|thumb|Pelham Infant]]\nIn the [[phototypesetting]] and digital typesetting periods many font designs have been published inspired by Times New Roman. Although the digital data of Monotype and Linotype releases of Times New Roman are copyrighted, and the name ''Times'' is trademarked,<ref name=\"Justus Estoesa\">{{cite web |last1=Justus |first1=Dana |last2=Estoesa |first2=Ivy Clarice |title=\"Types\" of Protection for Font and Typeface Designs |url=https://www.natlawreview.com/article/types-protection-font-and-typeface-designs |website=[[The National Law Review]] |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> the ''design'' is in many countries [[Intellectual property protection of typefaces|not copyrightable]], notably in the United States,<ref name=\"Compendium313.6C2\">{{cite web |url=http://copyright.gov/comp3/chap900/ch900-visual-art-122214.pdf |title=Compendium of U.S. Copyright Office Practices, \u00a7 906.4 (\"Typeface, Typefont, Lettering, Calligraphy, and Typographic Ornamentation\") |page=13 |publisher=[[United States Copyright Office]] |date=December 22, 2014 |accessdate=December 22, 2014 |quote=The copyright law does not protect typeface or mere variations of typographic ornamentation or lettering. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141223014120/http://copyright.gov/comp3/chap900/ch900-visual-art-122214.pdf |archive-date=23 December 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> allowing alternative interpretations if they do not reuse digital data.\n*Times Modern was a condensed and bold display variant published by, among others, [[Elsner+Flake]]. It was withdrawn from sale due to trademark disputes with the ''Times'' newspaper, which owns its own unrelated design named 'Times Modern' (see above).<ref>{{cite web|last1=Coles|first1=Stephen|title=Times Modern|url=http://fontsinuse.com/uses/3368/the-other-times-modern|website=Fonts in Use|accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref>\n*CG Times is a variant of Times family made by [[Compugraphic Corporation|Compugraphic]].\n*Pelham is a version of Times Roman by DTP Types of Britain, which also designed an [[Schoolbook characters|infant version]] with single-storey 'a' and 'g'.<ref name=\"Pelham Infant\">{{cite web |title=Pelham Infant |url=http://www.type.co.uk/categories/sp/Infant/id/42386 |website=Type.co.uk |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n[[File:Sample of IBM Magnetic Card Composer Output.png|thumb|Press Roman, a version of Times New Roman typed on a premium IBM typewriter.]]\n* In the mid-1960s, a derivative of Times New Roman known as 'Press Roman' was used as a font for the [[IBM Composer]]. This was an ultra-premium electric 'golfball' [[typewriter]] system, intended to be used for producing high-quality office documents or copy to be photographically enlarged for small-scale printing projects.<ref name=\"Typefaces - the complete works\">{{cite book|last1=Osterer|first1=Heidurn|last2=Stamm|first2=Philipp|last3=Frutiger|first3=Adrian|author-link3=Adrian Frutiger|title=Adrian Frutiger - Typefaces: The Complete Works|date=2009|publisher=Birkh\u00e4user|location=Basel|isbn=978-3764385811|page=192|edition=English}}</ref> Unlike most typewriters, the Composer produced proportional type, rather than monospaced letters. Ultimately the system proved a niche product, as it competed with increasingly cheap [[phototypesetting]], and then in the 1980s was largely displaced by word processors and general-purpose computers.<ref name=\"McEldowney2013\">{{cite book|first=Dennis|last=McEldowney|title=A Press Achieved: the Emergence of Auckland University Press, 1927-1972|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VT1eAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT102|date=1 October 2013|publisher=Auckland University Press|isbn=978-1-86940-671-4|pages=102\u20135}}</ref>{{efn|The system returned to public attention in 2004, during the [[Killian documents controversy]], when some documents apparently from the 1970s and presenting the future U.S. president [[George W. Bush]]'s [[George W. Bush military service controversy|military service]] in an unfavourable light were presented by the American news network CBS. The documents were typeset in a form of Times New Roman. As the documents [[Killian documents authenticity issues|looked unlike most typewritten documents]], having proportional spacing rather than the monospacing of almost all typewritten documents, some defenders of the documents suggested that they might have been typed using this method. It is now accepted that they were forged on a modern computer, according to digital font expert Thomas Phinney in the Linotype version of Times New Roman.<ref name=Typekit>{{cite web|last1=Phinney|first1=Thomas|title=Bush Guard memos used Times Roman, not Times New Roman|url=http://blog.typekit.com/2006/08/03/bush_guard_memo/|website=The Typekit Blog|accessdate=20 April 2015|date=3 August 2006}}</ref><ref name=WaPo0914>{{cite news | title=Expert Cited by CBS Says He Didn't Authenticate Papers  | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A18982-2004Sep13.html | accessdate=20 February 2007 | newspaper=The Washington Post | first1=Michael | last1=Dobbs | first2=Howard | last2=Kurtz | date=14 September 2004}}</ref>}}\n* Among many digital-period designs loosely inspired by Times, [[Kris Sowersby]]'s popular Tiempos family is a loose Times New Roman revival; it was created for a Spanish newspaper ('tiempo' is Spanish for 'time').<ref name=\"Tiempos Design Information\">{{cite web |last1=Sowersby |first1=Kris |title=Tiempos Design Information |url=https://klim.co.nz/blog/tiempos-design-information/ |publisher=Klim Type Foundry |accessdate=21 January 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Eye Reputations: Kris Sowersby\">{{cite web |last1=Thomson |first1=Mark |last2=Sowersby |first2=Kris |title=Reputations: Kris Sowersby |url=http://www.eyemagazine.com/feature/article/reputations-kris-sowersby |website=Eye |accessdate=12 September 2019}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n==Free alternatives==\n[[File:Times New Roman Liberation Serif comparison.png|thumb|Comparison between Times New Roman and Liberation Serif, showing its much squarer design]]\nThere are some [[free software]] fonts used as alternatives, including [[metric-compatible]] designs used for [[font substitution]].<ref name=\"gnufreefont-why\">{{cite web |url=https://www.gnu.org/software/freefont/articles/Why_Free_Fonts.html |title=GNU FreeFont - Why do we need free outline UCS fonts? |date=4 October 2009 |accessdate=2 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=A simple introduction to Font Licensing |url=https://www.keystonelaw.co.uk/keynotes/a-simple-introduction-to-font-licensing |website=Keystone |accessdate=7 June 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Times New Roman\u00ae Font Family License |url=https://www.fonts.com/font/monotype/times-new-roman/licenses |website=Fonts.com |accessdate=7 June 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=EULA - Monotype |url=https://www.monotype.com/legal/eula/ |website=monotype.com |accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref>\n*[[URW++]] produced a version of Times New Roman called [[Nimbus Roman]] in 1982. Nimbus Roman No9 L, URW's [[PostScript]] variant, was released under the [[GNU General Public License]] in 1996,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tug.org/fonts/deutsch-urw.txt |title=Finally! Good-quality free (GPL) basic-35 PostScript Type 1 fonts. |format=TXT |accessdate=6 May 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://mirror.cs.wisc.edu/pub/mirrors/ghost/aladdin/fonts/ghostscript-fonts-std-4.0.tar.gz |title=ghostscript-fonts-std-4.0.tar.gz - GhostScript 4.0 standard fonts - AFPL license |format=TAR.GZ |date=28 June 1996 |accessdate=6 May 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110424032316/http://mirror.cs.wisc.edu/pub/mirrors/ghost/aladdin/fonts/ghostscript-fonts-std-4.0.tar.gz |archivedate=24 April 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and available in major [[free software|free]] and [[open source software|open source]] operating systems.{{efn|This was later adapted in versions including [[FreeSerif]],<ref name=\"gnufreefont-why\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gnu.org/software/freefont/design-notes.html |title=GNU FreeFont - Design notes |date=4 October 2009 |accessdate=2 July 2010}}</ref> TeX Gyre Termes<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gust.org.pl/projects/e-foundry/tex-gyre/termes/index_html |title=TeX Gyre Termes \u2014 GUST Web Presence |accessdate=20 May 2018}}</ref> and TeX Gyre Termes Math.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gust.org.pl/projects/e-foundry/tg-math/download/readme-tex-gyre-termes-math.txt/view |title=README-TeX-Gyre-Termes-Math.txt \u2014 GUST Web Presence |accessdate=6 October 2018}}</ref>}} Like Times New Roman, many additional styles of Nimbus Roman exist that are only sold commercially, including condensed and extra-bold styles. URW also developed Nimbus Roman No. 4, which is metrically compatible with the slightly different CG Times.<ref name=\"Epson PCL Fonts\">{{cite web |title=PCL Fonts (WF-C5290) |url=https://files.support.epson.com/docid/cpd5/cpd55236/source/printers/source/specifications/reference/wfc5210_5290/pcl_font_table_wfc5290.html |publisher=Epson |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n[[File:Times and STIX.png|thumb|A standard Times New Roman digitisation compared to the STIX Two project, an open-source typeface for mathematics based on Times's smaller metal point sizes. STIX Two has a higher x-height and a reduction in fine detail.]]\n* The [[STIX Fonts project]] is a four-style set of open-source fonts. They were created for scientific publishing by the Scientific and Technical Information Exchange consortium of publishers, but are also very suitable for general use, including Greek and Cyrillic support.<ref name=STIX>{{cite web|title=STIX Project|url=http://www.stixfonts.org|publisher=Scientific and Technical Information Exchange|accessdate=16 September 2015}}</ref> The original version is installed by default on [[OS X|Mac OS X]], and adapted as [[XITS]]. In 2016, a completely redesigned version was released by Ross Mills and John Hudson of Tiro Typeworks. Unlike the previous version, it is an original design loosely inspired by a [[Optical size|smaller 10 point size]] of Times New Roman, with a higher [[x-height]] than Monotype's Times digitisation.<ref name=\"10pt metal Times\">{{cite web|title=Tweet|url=https://twitter.com/TiroTypeworks/status/804395547259867136|website=Twitter|publisher=Tiro Typeworks|accessdate=10 December 2016|quote=The original STIX fonts were based on a Times New Roman clone. The new #STIX2 faces are redesigned, inspired by 10pt metal Times fonts.}}</ref><ref name=\"stixfonts.org\">{{cite web|last1=Twardoch|first1=Adam|title=New \"STIX Two\" opensource fonts by Tiro: stixfonts.org|url=https://www.facebook.com/media/set/?set=a.10154700398143764.1073741830.561698763&type=1&l=16394cf489|website=Facebook|accessdate=10 December 2016|quote=The new design is fantastic \u2014 it can be described as \"the better Times New Roman\". It's somewhat similar to Times, but with a touch of [[Joan Micha\u00ebl Fleischman|Fleischmann]]. Its lower contrast, enlarged x-height and less inclined italic all contribute to superb(!) readability, in both web and print. STIX Text is a neutral, non-invasive text face for continuous reading.}}</ref> \n*[[Liberation Serif]] by [[Steve Matteson]] is metrically equivalent to Times New Roman.<ref name=\"CC Matteson\">{{cite web |last1=Middendorp |first1=Jan |title=Creative Characters: Steve Matteson |url=https://www.myfonts.com/newsletters/cc/201205.html |website=MyFonts |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> It was developed by [[Ascender Corporation|Ascender Corp.]] and published by [[Red Hat]] in 2007 under the GPL license with some exceptions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fedorahosted.org/liberation-fonts/browser/master/License.txt |title=Overview - liberation-fonts - Pagure |website=Red Hat pagure |accessdate=12 February 2018 }}</ref> It is used in some GNU/Linux distributions as a default font replacement for Times New Roman.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://archive.openmandriva.org/wiki/en/index.php?title=Mandriva_Linux_2008_Release_Tour#Liberation_font_set |title=Mandriva Linux 2008 Release Tour |quote=integrated into Mandriva Linux 2008 |accessdate=12 February 2018}}</ref> Widths aside, it does not particularly resemble Times New Roman, being much squarer in shape with less fine detail and blunt ends rather than ball terminals.<ref name=\"Bean Tinos\">{{cite journal |last1=Bean |first1=Jonathan |title=The Times New Roman lie |journal=interactions |date=27 April 2015 |volume=22 |issue=3 |pages=24\u201325 |doi=10.1145/2742938}}</ref> Google's Tinos in the [[Croscore fonts]] package is a derivative of Liberation Serif.\n* [[Bitstream Cyberbit]] is a roman-only font released by [[Bitstream Inc.|Bitstream]] for non-commercial use, with European alphabets based on Times New Roman.<ref name=\"Titus Unicode\">{{cite web|title=Titus Unicode|url=http://titus.fkidg1.uni-frankfurt.de/unicode/tituut.asp|website=Department of Empirical Linguistics|publisher=University of Frankfurt|accessdate=22 February 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Cyberbit Netscape\">{{cite web|title=pub/communicator/extras/fonts/windows|url=http://ftp.netscape.com/pub/communicator/extras/fonts/windows/|publisher=Netscape|accessdate=22 February 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080907182545/http://ftp.netscape.com/pub/communicator/extras/fonts/windows/|archivedate=7 September 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It has an expanded character range intended to cover a large proportion of [[Unicode]] for scholarly use. Bitstream no longer offers the font, but it remains downloadable from the [[Goethe University Frankfurt|University of Frankfurt]].<ref name=\"Titus Unicode 2\">{{cite web|title=Titus Unicode|url=http://titus.uni-frankfurt.de/indexe.htm?/unicode/unitest2.htm|publisher=University of Frankfurt|accessdate=22 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist|30em}}\n{{clear}}\n==References==\n===Cited literature===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Barker|first1=Nicolas|author-link=Nicolas Barker|title=Stanley Morison|date=1972}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Dreyfus|first=John|author-link=John Dreyfus|title=The Evolution of Times New Roman|journal=[[The Penrose Annual]]|date=1973|volume=66|}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Hutt |first1=Allen |title=Newspaper Design |date=1960 |publisher=Oxford University Press}}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Hutt|first1=Allen|title=Times Roman: a re-assessment|journal=Journal of Typographic Research|date=1970|volume=4|issue=3|url=http://visiblelanguagejournal.com/issue/15|accessdate=5 March 2017}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Moran |first1=James |title=Stanley Morison: His Typographic Achievement |date=1971 |publisher=Lund Humphries |location=London |isbn=0853313008}}\n* {{cite book|last=Tracy|first=Walter|author-link=Walter Tracy|title=Letters of Credit: A View of Type Design|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=y8NssjbqNcsC&pg=PA194|date=2003|publisher=D.R. Godine|isbn=978-1-56792-240-0}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Williamson|first1=Hugh|author-link=Hugh Williamson (book designer)|title=Methods of Book Design|date=1956|url=https://archive.org/details/MethodsOfBookDesign}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* Times Modern, by Dan Rhatigan: [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=n7hgQ_MXL8k&sns=tw  Part 1] and [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=szpBcBG9Vdw Part 2]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150916043631/http://www.elbrecht.de/TNR%26RF.jpg Times New Roman family] (different sizes, in hot metal type)\n* [https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/typography/font-list/times-new-roman Times New Roman font family - Typography | Microsoft Docs]\n* Fonts In Use: [https://fontsinuse.com/typefaces/5117/times-new-roman Times New Roman], [https://fontsinuse.com/typefaces/52/times Times]\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2011}}\n{{The Times}}\n{{Microsoft Windows Typefaces}}\n{{Monotype typefaces}}\n{{OS X typefaces}}\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Articles with inconsistent citation formats]]\n[[Category:Monotype typefaces]]\n[[Category:Windows XP typefaces]]\n[[Category:Transitional serif typefaces]]\n[[Category:Corporate typefaces]]\n[[Category:Typefaces with optical sizes]]\n[[Category:Newspaper and magazine typefaces]]\n[[Category:Typefaces with infant variants]]\n[[Category:Typefaces and fonts introduced in 1932]]\n[[Category:The Times]]\n[[Category:Old style serif typefaces]]\n[[Category:Typefaces with text figures]]\n[[Category:Latin-script typefaces]]\n[[Category:IPA typefaces]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Canonical serif font}}\n{{Infobox font  \n| name = Times New Roman\n| image = Times New Roman-sample.svg\n| style = [[Serif]]\n| classifications = Mixed<br>[[Transitional serif|Transitional]]<br>[[Serif#Old-style|Old-style]]\n| releasedate = 1932<ref name=\"Clarke 1946\">{{cite news|last1=Clarke|first1=C.F.O.|title=The Times: A Revolution in Newspaper Printing|url=http://magazines.iaddb.org/issue/GR/1946-05-01/edition/15/page/86|work=Graphis|date=1946|pages=362\u2013375}}</ref>\n| creator = [[Stanley Morison]]<br>[[Victor Lardent]]\n| foundry = [[Monotype Corporation|Monotype]]\n| commissioned_by = ''[[The Times]]''\n| based_on = [[Plantin (typeface)|Plantin]]\n| license = [[Proprietary software|Proprietary]]\n|}}\n'''Times New Roman''' is a [[serif typeface|serif]] [[typeface]]. It was commissioned by the British newspaper ''[[The Times]]'' in 1931 and conceived by [[Stanley Morison]], the artistic adviser to the British branch of the printing equipment company [[Monotype Imaging|Monotype]], in collaboration with [[Victor Lardent]], a lettering artist in ''The Times's'' advertising department. It has become one of the most popular typefaces of all time and is installed on most [[desktop computer]]s.\n\nAsked to advise on a redesign, Morison recommended that ''The Times'' change their text typeface from a spindly nineteenth-century face to a more robust, solid design, returning to traditions of printing from the eighteenth century and before. This matched a common trend in printing tastes of the period. Morison proposed an older Monotype typeface named [[Plantin (typeface)|Plantin]] as a basis for the design, and Times New Roman mostly matches Plantin's dimensions. The main change was that the contrast between strokes was enhanced to give a crisper image. The new design made its debut in ''The Times'' on 3 October 1932. After one year, the design was released for commercial sale. In Times New Roman's name, Roman is a reference to the regular or [[Roman type|roman]] style (sometimes also called [[Antiqua\u2013Fraktur dispute|Antiqua]]), the first part of the Times New Roman family to be designed. Roman type has roots in Italian printing of the late 15th and early 16th centuries, but Times New Roman's design has no connection to [[Rome]] or to the [[Ancient Rome|Romans]].\n\n''The Times'' stayed with Times New Roman for 40 years, but new production techniques and the format change from [[broadsheet]] to [[Tabloid (newspaper format)|tabloid]] in 2004 have caused it to switch typeface five times from 1972 to 2007. However, all the new fonts have been variants of the original New Roman typeface.\n\n==Design==\n[[File:Times New Roman and predecessor.jpg|thumb|right|Twenty-two lines in Times New Roman compared to its predecessor \"modern\" serif font.{{efn|\"Modern\" in typography is a generic term referring to designs in the [[Didone (typography)|modern or Didone]] style of the nineteenth century.}} Times appears larger on the page, with tighter linespacing and more solid in appearance.<ref name=\"Printing the Times 1932\">{{cite book |title=Printing the Times: A record of the changes introduced in the issue for October 3, 1932 |date=1932 |location=London}}</ref>]]\nTimes New Roman has a robust [[Type color|colour]] on the page and influences of European [[Early modern period|early modern]] and [[Baroque period|Baroque]] printing.<ref name=\"Monotype Recorder: The Changing Newspaper\">{{cite journal|first=Stanley|last=Morison|title=Monotype Recorder: The Changing Newspaper|journal=Monotype Recorder|volume=35|issue=1|date=1936|url=http://www.metaltype.co.uk/downloads/mr/mr_35_1.pdf}}</ref>{{efn|\"The Changing Newspaper\" articles in the ''Monotype Recorder'' are unsigned, but Monotype's newspaper consultant Allen Hutt, who co-authored the issue, attributes them to Morison.{{sfn|Hutt|1970|p=263}}}} As a typeface designed for newspaper printing, Times New Roman has a high [[x-height]], short [[descender]]s to allow tight linespacing and a relatively condensed appearance.{{sfn|Williamson|1956|p=117}}{{efn|While Times is often described as being quite \"condensed\" this is relative to its high x-height: typefaces with lower x-height, such as many versions of [[Garamond]], [[Caslon]] and [[Bembo]], are narrower at equalised cap height. Although Hutt,{{sfn|Hutt|1970|p=261}} and most other authors, describe Times New Roman as having a higher x-height than Plantin, Tracy reports based on published Monotype dimensions that in the original small metal-type sizes the difference was not great.{{sfn|Tracy|2003|p=197}}}}\n\n[[File:Times ancestors.png|thumb|A digitisation of Times New Roman below the three typefaces originally considered as a basis for the ''Times'' project: [[Perpetua (typeface)|Perpetua]], [[Baskerville]] and [[Plantin (typeface)|Plantin]]. Times is most based on Plantin, but with the letters made taller and its appearance \"modernised\" by adding eighteenth- and nineteenth-century influences, in particular enhancing the stroke contrast. Compared to Baskerville and Perpetua, the [[x-height]] is a larger proportion of the type height.]]\nThe roman style of Plantin was loosely based on a metal type created in the late sixteenth century by the French artisan [[Robert Granjon]] and preserved in the collection of the [[Plantin-Moretus Museum]] of [[Antwerp]].<ref name=\"Where Did Times New Roman Come From?\">{{cite web|last1=Mann|first1=Meredith|title=Where Did Times New Roman Come From?|url=http://www.nypl.org/blog/2014/12/09/times-new-roman|publisher=[[New York Public Library]]|accessdate=2 February 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Vervliet2008\">{{cite book|author=Hendrik D. L. Vervliet|title=The Palaeotypography of the French Renaissance: Selected Papers on Sixteenth-century Typefaces|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6sidSDlif48C&pg=PA226|year=2008|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-16982-1|pages=226\u20137}}</ref><ref name=\"Tally of Types\">{{cite book|last1=Morison|first1=Stanley|title=A Tally of Types|url=https://archive.org/details/tallyoftypes0000mori|url-access=registration|date=7 June 1973|publisher=CUP Archive|isbn=978-0-521-09786-4|pages=[https://archive.org/details/tallyoftypes0000mori/page/22 22]\u201324, 106, 124 etc.}}</ref><ref name=\"Mosley Gros Cicero\">{{cite web|last1=Mosley|first1=James|title=Comments on Typophile thread|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111013140635/http://www.typophile.com/node/53050|website=Typophile (archived)|accessdate=16 December 2016|quote=The consensus appears to be that not only the wrong-fount a in the cases at Antwerp but also the italic that Monotype adapted for their Plantin (which can be seen on that first page of the 1905 specimen) may be the work of Johann Michael Schmidt (died 1750), also known as J. M. Smit or Smid.}}</ref> This style is sometimes categorised as part of the \"[[Serif#Old-style|old-style]]\" of serif fonts (from before the eighteenth century).<ref name=\"Typographic milestones\">{{cite book|last1=Haley|first1=Allan|title=Typographic Milestones|date=1992|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|location=Hoboken, NJ|isbn=9780471288947|pages=99\u2013107|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dKeVor1olhkC&pg=PA106|accessdate=26 January 2016|chapter=Stanley Morison}}</ref><ref name=\"ABC's of type\">{{cite book |last1=Haley |first1=Allen |title=ABC's of type |date=1990 |publisher=Watson-Guptill Publications |isbn=9780823000531 |page=[https://archive.org/details/abcsoftype0000hale/page/86 86] |quote=Times looks like Plantin on a diet. |url=https://archive.org/details/abcsoftype0000hale/page/86 }}</ref><ref name=\"Leipzig as a Centre of Type-Founding\">{{cite book|last=Morison|first=Stanley|editor-last=McKitterick |editor-first=David |title=Selected essays on the history of letterforms in manuscript and print|chapter=Chapter 8: Leipzig as a Centre of Type-Founding|date=2009|pages=149\u2013170|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge|isbn=978-0-521-18316-1|edition=Paperback reissue, digitally printed version|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-G2tQVnPiCAC&pg=PA132&lpg=PA132}}</ref>{{efn|Times New Roman was called \"Times Old Style\" in an early stage of its development.{{sfn|Dreyfus|1973|p=166}}}} (The 'a' of Plantin was not based on Granjon's work: the Plantin-Moretus Museum's type had a substitute 'a' cut later.<ref name=\"Matthew Carter\">{{cite book|last1=Mosley|first1=James|chapter=Reviving the Classics: Matthew Carter and the Interpretation of Historical Models|editor1-last=Mosley|editor1-first=James|editor2-last=Re|editor2-first=Margaret|editor3-last=Drucker|editor3-first=Johanna|editor4-last=Carter|editor4-first=Matthew|title=Typographically Speaking: The Art of Matthew Carter|date=2003|publisher=Princeton Architectural Press|isbn=9781568984278|pages=31\u201334|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WqXd_w4S4SsC&pg=PA32|quote=Plantin was a recreation of one of the old types held at the Plantin-Moretus Museum in Antwerp, of which a specimen, printed in 1905, had been acquired by Pierpont on a visit. The type from which the specimen was printed was not only centuries old and worn almost beyond use, but it was contaminated with wrong-font letters (notably the letter 'a') and the italic did not even belong to the roman. The revival, derived by Monotype from an indirect and confused original, is [nonetheless] as sound a piece of type-making as was ever created in the 20th century\u2026behind the foggy image of the roman type lies the...'Gros Cicero' Roman of [[Robert Granjon]], acquired by the Plantin printing office after the death of its founder.}}</ref>) Indeed, the working title of Times New Roman was \"Times Old Style\".{{sfn|Dreyfus|1973|p=166}}\n\nHowever, Times New Roman modifies the Granjon influence further than Plantin due to features such as its 'a' and 'e', with very large [[Counter (typography)|counters and apertures]], its [[ball terminal]] detailing and an increased level of contrast between thick and thin strokes, so it has often been compared to fonts from the late eighteenth century, the so-called '[[Serif#Transitional|transitional]]' genre, in particular the [[Baskerville]] typeface of the 1750s.<ref name=Busic-Snyder>{{cite book|last1=Busic-Snyder|first1=Kate Clair, Cynthia|title=A typographic workbook a primer to history, techniques, and artistry|date=2005|publisher=Wiley|location=Hoboken, N.J.|isbn=9781118399880|page=171|edition=2nd|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Lf0iDYCr6w0C&pg=PA171|accessdate=16 January 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Fonts & Encodings\">{{cite book|last1=Horne|first1=Yannis Haralambous ; translated by P. Scott|title=Fonts & Encodings|date=2007|publisher=O'Reilly Media|location=Sebastopol, Calif.|isbn=9780596102425|page=417|edition=1st|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qrElYgVLDwYC&pg=PA417|accessdate=26 January 2016}}</ref> Historian and sometime Monotype executive Allan Haley commented that compared to Plantin \"serifs had been sharpened...contrast was increased and character curves were refined,\" while Lawson described Times's higher-contrast crispness as having \"a sparkle [Plantin] never achieved\".<ref name=\"Haley1992\">{{cite book|author=Allan Haley|title=Typographic Milestones|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dKeVor1olhkC&pg=PA106|date=15 September 1992|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-0-471-28894-7|page=106}}</ref><ref name=\"Anatomy of a Typeface\" /> Other changes from Plantin include a straight-sided 'M' and 'W' with three upper terminals not Plantin's four, both choices that move away from the old-style model.{{sfn|Tracy|2003|p=56}}\n===Italic and bold===\n[[File:Times ancestors italic.png|thumb|right|Times compared with its influences in italic. The italic was made simpler than Plantin's, losing flourishes on the 'w' and 'v', but less radically than that of Perpetua.]]\nMorison described the companion [[Italic type|italic]] as also being influenced by the typefaces created by the [[Didot family]] in the late 18th and early 19th centuries: a \"rationalistic italic that owed nothing to the tradition of the sixteenth or seventeenth centuries. It has, indeed, more in common with the eighteenth century.\"<ref name=\"Changing the Times\">{{cite web|last1=Morison|first1=Stanley|title=Changing the Times|url=http://www.eyemagazine.com/feature/article/stanley-morison-changing-the-times|website=Eye|accessdate=28 July 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Stanley Morison: A Portrait\">{{cite book|last1=Barr|first1=John|title=Stanley Morison: A Portrait|date=1971|publisher=British Museum|page=33|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8ojgAAAAMAAJ}}</ref><ref name=\"Mosley times italic\">{{cite web|last1=Mosley|first1=James|title=Comments on Typophile thread|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130313143211/http://typophile.com/node/70542|website=Typophile (archived)|accessdate=27 March 2017|quote=One of the distinctive things about French calligraphy of [the 1680s] is that the lead-in stroke of letters like i, m, n and so on have flat, rather 'roman', serifs, making them look a bit like a [[Oblique type|'sloped roman']]\u2026Fournier used it fifty years later in his 'new style' italics, and later so did Firmin Didot. And that French flat serif also turns up in\u2026the italic to Times New Roman.}}</ref> Morison had several years earlier attracted attention for promoting the radical idea that [[italic type|italics]] in book printing were too disruptive to the flow of text, and should be phased out.<ref name=\"wardle5\">{{cite book\n |last        = Wardle\n |first       = Tiffany\n |title       = The story of Perpetua\n |publisher   = [[University of Reading]]\n |year        = 2000\n |page        = 5\n |url         = http://www.typeculture.com/academic_resource/articles_essays/pdfs/tc_article_38.pdf\n |accessdate  = 2009-03-26\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20061110180517/http://www.typeculture.com/academic_resource/articles_essays/pdfs/tc_article_38.pdf\n |archivedate = 10 November 2006\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref><ref name=\"Fine Print\">{{cite journal|last1=Mosley|first1=James|author-link=James Mosley|title=Eric Gill's Perpetua Type|journal=Fine Print}}</ref> He rapidly came to concede that the idea was impractical, and later wryly commented to historian [[Harry Carter (typographer)|Harry Carter]] that Times' italic \"owes more to [[Didot (typeface)|Didot]] than dogma.\"<ref name=\"Tally of Types\" /> Morison wrote in a personal letter of Times New Roman's mixed heritage that it \"has the merit of not looking as if it had been designed by somebody in particular.\"<ref name=\"Loxley2006_MorisononGoudy\">{{cite book|author=Simon Loxley|title=Type: The Secret History of Letters|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9AfP2prmEDUC&pg=PA134|date=12 June 2006|publisher=I.B.Tauris|isbn=978-1-84511-028-4|pages=134\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"The history of the Times New Roman typeface\">{{cite web|last1=Alas|first1=Joel|title=The history of the Times New Roman typeface|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/a2fa033e-7ca1-11de-a7bf-00144feabdc0.html|website=Financial Times|accessdate=16 January 2016}}</ref>{{efn|Morison continued: \"\u2013 [[Frederic Goudy|Mr. Goudy]] for instance.\"<ref name=\"Updike Morison Letters\">{{cite book |last1=Updike |first1=Daniel Berkeley |last2=Morison |first2=Stanley |authorlink1=Daniel Berkeley Updike |authorlink2=Stanley Morison |editor1-last=McKitterick |editor1-first=David |editor1-link=David McKitterick |title=Stanley Morison & D.B. Updike: selected correspondence |publisher=Moretus Press |isbn=9780896790018 |pages=184-6}}</ref> This refers to [[Frederic Goudy]], one of the leading American type designers of the period. Morison considered his very organic tastes in letter design somewhat florid and self-indulgent.}}\n[[File:Times and bold.png|thumb|right|Times New Roman compared to its bold. The bold weight has a different style, more \"nineteenth-century\" in appearance, with flat serifs on the tops of letters and a more vertical axis visible on the 'o'.{{efn|In the roman style that the high serifs of the 'v' do not sit well with the lower shape of the 'i'. In his commentary on Times, Walter Tracy wrote that the designers should have tested words like 'divide' and 'jump' to spot this.{{sfn|Tracy|2003|p=204}}}}]]\nRather than creating a companion [[boldface]] with letterforms similar to the roman style, Times New Roman's bold has a different character, with a more condensed and more upright effect caused by making the horizontal parts of curves consistently the thinnest lines of each letter, and making the top serifs of letters like 'd' purely horizontal.<ref name=\"By printers, for printers\">{{cite web|last1=Hare|first1=Steve|title=By printers, for printers|url=http://www.eyemagazine.com/feature/article/by-printers-for-printers|website=Eye Magazine|accessdate=2 February 2016|quote=[Shown are] overlays from the article 'The Evolution of Times New Roman\u2019 by [[John Dreyfus]]. He writes: 'These drawings demonstrate how severely the bowl of \"p\" has been reduced in the bold version, because mainstrokes have been thickened without drawing the bold version any wider.'}}</ref> This effect is not found in sixteenth-century typefaces (which, in any case, did not have bold versions); it is most associated with [[Didone (typography)|Didone]] type of the early nineteenth century (and with the more recent 'Ionic' styles of type influenced by it that were offered by Linotype, discussed below).<ref name=\"Anatomy of a Typeface\">{{cite book|last1=Lawson|first1=Alexander|title=Anatomy of a Typeface|date=1990|publisher=David R. Godine|location=New York|isbn=9780879233334|pages=270\u2013294|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FiJ87ixLs0sC&pg=PA270|accessdate=6 March 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Dutch type 94\">{{cite book|last1=Middendorp|first1=Jan|title=Dutch type|date=2004|publisher=010 Publishers|location=Rotterdam|isbn=9789064504600|page=94|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sR9g5xPPJVQC&pg=PA94|accessdate=26 January 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Three chapters in the development of Clarendon/Ionic typefaces\">{{cite journal|last1=Miklav\u010di\u010d |first1=Mitja |title=Three chapters in the development of Clarendon/Ionic typefaces |journal=MA Thesis (University of Reading) |date=2006 |url=http://www.typefacedesign.org/resources/essay/MitjaMiclavcic_essay_scr.pdf |accessdate=14 August 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111125001608/http://www.typefacedesign.org/resources/essay/MitjaMiclavcic_essay_scr.pdf |archivedate=25 November 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Coles|first1=Stephen|title=Times Bold Modified|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/stewf/8548006644|website=Flickr|accessdate=26 January 2016|}}</ref> Some commentators have found Times' bold unsatisfactory and too condensed, such as [[Walter Tracy]].{{sfn|Tracy|2003|p=204}}\n\n===Historical background===\nDuring the nineteenth century, the standard roman types for general-purpose printing were [[Didone (typography)|\"Modern\" or Didone]] designs,{{efn|Excluding some countries, such as Germany, where [[blackletter]] types were still very popular for extended text into the nineteenth century. For some higher-class literary printing eighteenth-century [[Caslon]] types, or more often [[Modernised Old Style (typeface)|Old Style]] faces in imitation of it, were common in Britain.<ref name=\"Ovink I\">{{cite journal|last1=Ovink|first1=G.W.|title=Nineteenth-century reactions against the didone type model - I|journal=Quaerendo|date=1971|volume=1|issue=2|pages=18\u201331|url=http://booksandjournals.brillonline.com/content/journals/10.1163/157006971x00301|accessdate=20 February 2016|doi=10.1163/157006971x00301}}</ref>}} and these were standard in all newspaper printing.{{sfn|Tracy|2003|p=181}}<ref name=\"Unger 1981\">{{cite journal|last1=Unger|first1=Gerard|authorlink1=Gerard Unger|title=Experimental No. 223, a newspaper typeface, designed by W.A. Dwiggins|journal=Quaerendo|date=1 January 1981|volume=11|issue=4|pages=302\u2013324|doi=10.1163/157006981X00274}}</ref> Designs in the nineteenth-century style remain a common part of the aesthetic of newspaper printing.{{efn|For example, in 2017 digital typeface designer [[Tobias Frere-Jones]] wrote that he kept his Exchange family, designed for the ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'', based on the nineteenth-century model as it \"had to feel like the news.\"<ref name=\"Frere-Jones Exchange\">{{cite web|last1=Frere-Jones|first1=Tobias|title=Decompiled & Remixed History: The Making of Exchange|url=https://frerejones.com/blog/decompiled-and-remixed-history-the-making-of-exchange|publisher=Frere-Jones Type|accessdate=1 August 2017}}</ref>}} According to Mosley and Williamson the modern-face used by ''The Times'' was Monotype's Series 7 or \"Modern Extended\", based on typefaces by [[Miller and Richard]].{{sfn|Williamson|1956|p=97}}<ref name=Mosley>{{cite web|last1=Mosley |first1=James|author-link=James Mosley |title=Comments on Typophile thread |url=http://typophile.com/node/49754 |website=Typophile |accessdate=27 July 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120612021330/http://typophile.com/node/49754 |archivedate=12 June 2012 }}</ref>{{efn|Because the cover of an issue of Monotype's trade magazine the ''Monotype Recorder'' compared the new \"Times New Roman\" with a sample of the previous type labelled as \"Times Old Roman\", some writers have assumed that the Times' previous typeface was actually called this, which it never was.<ref name=\"It was never called Times Old Roman\">{{cite web|last1=Rhatigan|first1=Dan|title=It was never called Times Old Roman|url=http://ultrasparky.org/archives/2011/08/it_was_never_ca.html|website=Ultrasparky|accessdate=27 July 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Mosley\" />}}\n\n[[File:Times prior newspaper faces.png|thumb|left|Times compared to a modern-face and the wide, monoline Excelsior, part of Linotype's [[Legibility Group]].]]\nBy the 1920s, some in the publishing industry felt that the modern-face model was too spindly and high-contrast for optimal legibility at the small sizes and punishing printing techniques of newspaper printing.{{sfn|Hutt|1960|p=54}}{{efn|Although it praised many-though not all-aspects of Times' design, so cannot be considered entirely unbiased, a 1937 article by the historian of printing [[Harry Carter (typographer)|Harry Carter]], who had been a draughtsman at the Monotype factory, commented in 1937 that modern faces at 9-point size made for \"a very fine engineer's job, but a poor design for reproduction on so small a scale.\"<ref name=\"Carter optical\">{{cite journal |last1=Carter |first1=Harry |authorlink1=Harry Carter (typographer) |title=Optical scale in type founding |journal=Typography |date=1937 |volume=4 |url=https://issuu.com/letterror/docs/harry_carter_optical_scale_in_typefounding |accessdate=15 September 2019}}</ref>}} In 1925, the Mergenthaler Linotype Company, Monotype's main competitor, launched a new newspaper typeface called Ionic, which became the first in a series known as the [[Legibility Group]].{{sfn|Hutt|1960|p=55}}<ref name=\"Three chapters in the development of Clarendon/Ionic typefaces\" /> These kept to the nineteenth-century model but greatly reduced the contrast of the letterform.<ref name=\"Gaultney Balancing\" /> The thinnest strokes of the letter were made thicker and strokes were kept as far apart as possible to maximise legibility. It proved extremely successful: Allen Hutt, Monotype's newspaper printing consultant in the late 1930s,<ref name=\"Allen Hutt Pimlott\">{{cite journal |last1=Pimlott |first1=Herbert |title=The Radical Type? G. Allen Hutt, the Communist Party and the politics of journalistic practice |journal=Journalism Practice |date=February 2013 |volume=7 |issue=1 |pages=81\u201395 |doi=10.1080/17512786.2012.685556}}</ref> later noted that it \"revolutionized newspaper text setting...within eighteen months it was adopted by 3,000 papers.\"{{sfn|Hutt|1960|p=55}} Although Times New Roman does not in any way resemble it, [[Walter Tracy]] commented that its arrival must at least have influenced the decision to consider a redesign.{{sfn|Tracy|2003|p=194}}\n\nThe development of Times New Roman was relatively involved due to the lack of a specific pre-existing model \u2013 or perhaps a surfeit of possible choices.<ref name=\"Lang 1946\">{{cite journal |last1=Lang |first1=Peggy |title=Times Roman: A Revaluation |journal=Alphabet & Image |date=1946 |pages=5\u201317}}</ref> Morison wrote in a memo that he hoped for a design that would have relatively sharp serifs, matching the general design of the Times' previous font, but on a darker and more traditional basic structure. Bulked-up versions of Monotype's pre-existing but rather dainty [[Baskerville]] and [[Perpetua (typeface)|Perpetua]] typefaces were considered for a basis, and the [[Legibility Group]] designs were also examined. (Perpetua, which Monotype had recently commissioned from sculptor [[Eric Gill]] at Morison's urging, is considered a 'transitional' design in aesthetic, although it does not revive any specific model.) Walter Tracy, who knew Lardent, suggested in the 1980s that \"Morison did not begin with a clear vision of the ultimate type, but felt his way along.\"{{sfn|Tracy|2003|p=202}}\n\n[[File:Ludlow Times New Roman Type Specimen (14204771208).jpg|thumb|left|A Ludlow Typograph specimen of Times New Roman Type Specimen from the metal type period. The design was altered in smaller sizes to increase readability, particularly obvious in the widened spacing of the six and eight point samples at centre right of the diagram.<ref name=\"Gaultney Balancing\">{{cite web|last1=Gaultney|first1=Victor|title=Balancing typeface legibility and economy Practical techniques for the type designer|url=http://scripts.sil.org/cms/scripts/page.php?site_id=nrsi&id=BalanLegEcon|publisher=University of Reading (MA thesis)|accessdate=13 October 2017}}</ref> The hollows at the top of upstrokes are also not seen in the standard digitisations.]]\nMorison's biographer [[Nicolas Barker]] has written that Morison's memos of the time wavered over a variety of options before it was ultimately concluded that Plantin formed the best basis for a condensed font that could nonetheless be made to fill out the full size of the letter space as far as possible. (Morison ultimately conceded that Perpetua, which had been his pet project, was 'too basically circular' to be practical to condense in an attractive way.{{efn|Dreyfus shows proofs of the experimental recut of Perpetua with shortened descenders to allow tighter linespacing.{{sfn|Dreyfus|1973|p=166}} Morison later commented that \"it stared at the reader\".}})\n\n[[Walter Tracy]] and James Moran, who discussed the design's creation with Lardent in the 1960s, found that Lardent himself had little memory of exactly what material Morison gave him as a specimen to use to design the typeface, but he told Moran that he remembered working on the design from archive photographs of vintage type; he thought this was a book printed by [[Christophe Plantin]].{{sfn|Tracy|2003|p=196}} Moran and Tracy suggested that this actually might have been the same specimen of type from the Plantin-Moretus Museum that Plantin had been based on.{{sfn|Tracy|2003|p=199}} (Although based on a type in the collection of the [[Plantin-Moretus Museum]], which preserves much of the collection of sixteenth-century printer [[Christophe Plantin]], Plantin is actually based specifically on a Granjon font for which matrices (moulds) only arrived in the collection after Plantin's death.<ref name=\"Vervliet2008\" />) The sharpened serifs somewhat recall Perpetua, although Morison's stated reason for them was to provide continuity with the previous Didone design and the crispness associated with the ''Times''' printing; he also cited as a reason that sharper serifs looked better after [[Stereotype (printing)|stereotyping]] or printed on a [[Rotary printing press|rotary press]].<ref name=\"From a Cambridge Diary\" /> Although Morison may not have literally drawn the design, his influence on its concept was sufficient that he felt in a letter to [[Daniel Berkeley Updike]] that he could call it \"my one effort at designing a font\".{{efn|Spelling modernised. Morison wrote \"fount\", the usual spelling in British English at the time.<ref name=\"Updike Morison Letters\" />}} Morison's several accounts of his reasoning in designing the concept of Times New Roman were somewhat contradictory and historians of printing have suggested that in practice they were mostly composed to rationalise his pre-existing aesthetic preferences. After Morison's death Allen Hutt went so far as to describe his unsigned 1936 article on the topic as \"rather odd\u2026it can only be regarded as a piece of Morisonian mystification\".{{sfn|Hutt|1970|p=264}}\n\nLardent's original drawings are according to Rhatigan lost, but photographs exist of his drawings. Rhatigan comments that Lardent's originals show \"the spirit of the final type, but not the details.\"<ref name=\"Time and Times again\">{{cite web|last1=Rhatigan|first1=Dan|title=Time and Times again|url=http://ultrasparky.org/archives/2011/09/time_and_times_.html|website=ultrasparky.org|accessdate=28 July 2015}}</ref> The design was adapted from Lardent's large drawings by the Monotype drawing office team in [[Salfords]], [[Surrey]], which worked out spacing and simplified some fine details.{{sfn|Tracy|2003|p=202}}  Further changes were made after manufacturing began (the latter a difficult practice, since new punches and matrices had to be machined after each design change).{{sfn|Tracy|2003|p=202}}\n\nMorison continued to develop a close connection with the ''Times'' that would last throughout his life. Morison edited the History of the Times from 1935 to 1952, and in the post-war period, at a time when Monotype effectively stopped developing new typefaces due to [[Social history of the United Kingdom (1945\u2013present)#Age of Austerity|pressures of austerity]], took a post as editor of the ''[[Times Literary Supplement]]'' which he held from 1945 to 1948.<ref name=\"oxdnb\">{{cite book|last=Carter|first=H. G.|others=rev. David McKitterick|title=Morison, Stanley Arthur (1889\u20131967)|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|year=2004|volume=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography}}</ref> Times New Roman remained Morison's only type design; he designed a type to be issued by the [[Bauer Type Foundry]] of Frankfurt but the project was abandoned due to the war. Morison's friend Brooke Crutchley recorded in his diary being told by Morison that the test type sent to him just before the war was sent to the government to be \"analysed in order that we should know whether the Hun is hard up for lead or antimony or tin.\"<ref name=\"From a Cambridge Diary\">{{cite journal |last1=Crutchley |first1=Brooke |title=From a Cambridge Diary |journal=Matrix |date=1990 |volume=10 |publisher=[[Whittington Press]]}}</ref>\n\n==Metal type versions==\nA large number of variants of Times were cut during the metal type period, in particular families of titling capitals for headlines.{{sfn|Williamson|1956|p=39}} Walter Tracy in ''Letters of Credit'', Allen Hutt and others have discussed these extensively in their works on the family.{{sfn|Hutt|1970|p=270}}{{sfn|Tracy|2003|p=207}}{{sfn|Hutt|1960|p=107}}\n\n===Titling===\nMonotype also created some caps-only 'titling' designs to match Times New Roman itself, which was intended for body text.<ref name=\"The Times: New roman and related founts.\" /> These are not sold by Monotype in digital format, although Linotype's Times Eighteen in the same style (see below) is.<ref name=\"Linotype Times Eighteen\" />\n\n===Times Hever Titling===\n[[File:Times Hever Titling.jpg|thumb|right|Times Hever Titling from a Monotype specimen.]]\nAn elegant titling caps design, quite different from Times New Roman with a [[Caslon|Caslon-style]] A (with a serif at top left of the letter, suggesting a stroke written with a quill) and old-style C and W; Tracy suggests Monotype's previous [[Bembo|Poliphilus]] design as an influence.{{sfn|Tracy|2003|p=208}} Named after [[Hever Castle]], the home of the ''Times''' owner [[John Jacob Astor|Lord Astor]] and designed early on, it was used by the ''Times'' for headings in the lighter sections such as [[Society reporting|society pages]], arts and fashion.{{sfn|Tracy|2003|p=207}}<ref name=\"Comments on Typophile thread Savoie Hudson\">{{cite web|last1=Savoie|first1=Alice|last2=Hudson|first2=John|title=Comments on Typophile thread |url=http://typophile.com/node/101099 |website=Typophile |accessdate=16 September 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140717150729/http://typophile.com/node/101099 |archivedate=17 July 2014 }}</ref> It has not been digitised.\n\n===Times Wide (1938, series 427)===\nA variant intended for book printing, avoiding the slight condensation of the original Times New Roman.<ref name=\"Monotype Recorder first showing\">{{cite journal|title=Typographic Problems of the Illustrated Book|journal=Monotype Recorder|date=1938|volume=37|issue=2|page=31|url=http://www.metaltype.co.uk/downloads/mr/mr_37_2.pdf|quote=Some types look larger, size for size, than others, because they have unusually short descenders and ascenders. This allows more room for the [[X-height|'x' or the middle part of the lower-case]] [but] a 'large x' is bound to waste space ''horizontally''...the imperceptible condensation of Monotype Times New Roman puts it in a class by itself as a news face. In the wider book measure, however, condensation is no asset.}}</ref> Although it was popular in the metal type period for book printing, it was apparently never digitised. Monotype also created a version, series 627, with long descenders more appropriate to classic book typography.{{sfn|Williamson|1956|p=102}} Optional [[text figures]] were also available.<ref name=\"Effra composition matrices\">{{cite web |title=Composition matrices |url=https://shop.effrapress.co.uk/composition-matrices/ |publisher=Effra Press |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Series 727 and 827===\nMonotype also produced Series 727, in which the heavier strokes of upper-case letters were made slightly thinner.<ref name=\"Monotype Recorder issue 3 1956\" /> This was done to produce a lighter effect in which capital letters do not stand out so much, and was particularly intended for [[German nouns|German use]], since in the German language capitals are far more common since they appear at the start of each noun.<ref name=\"Monotype Recorder issue 3 1956\" /> Series 827 modified some letters (notably the ''R'') to correspond to their appearance in other typefaces popular in French printing. This production of what are now called [[stylistic alternates]] to suit national tastes was common at the time, and many alternates were also offered for [[Gill Sans#History|Gill Sans]] for use in Europe.<ref name=\"Monotype Recorder issue 3 1956\">{{cite journal|title=Modifications and extensions of a single series|journal=Monotype Recorder|date=1956|volume=40|issue=3|page=14|url=http://www.metaltype.co.uk/downloads/mr/mr_40_3.pdf|accessdate=27 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Claritas===\nA modified 4\u00be point size of Times Roman was produced by Monotype for use in printing matter requiring a very small size of type. Listed as Times Newspaper Smalls, available as either Series 333 or 335, it was also referred to by the name Claritas.<ref name=\"Changing the Times\" />\n\n===Times 4-line Mathematics Series 569===\nThis is a variant designed for printing mathematical formulae, using the 4\u2011line system for mathematics developed by Monotype in 1957.<ref name=\"The Monotype 4-Line System for Setting Mathematics\">{{cite web |last1=Rhatigan |first1=Daniel |title=The Monotype 4-Line System for Setting Mathematics |url=http://typeculture.com/academic-resource/articles-essays/the-monotype-4-line-system-for-setting-mathematics/ |website=Type Culture |accessdate=17 August 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Three typefaces for mathematics\">{{cite web|last1=Rhatigan|first1=Daniel|title=Three typefaces for mathematics|url=http://ultrasparky.org/school/pdf/DanielRhatigan_Dissertation.pdf|publisher=[[University of Reading]] (MA thesis)|accessdate=2 February 2016}}</ref> This modified version of Times Roman was designed for use as part of Monotype's 4-line Mathematics system. The major changes to the Times Roman typeface itself were a reduction in the slope of italic characters to 12 degrees from 16 degrees, so as to reduce the need for kerning, and a change in the form of italic v and w so that italic v could be more easily distinguished from a Greek nu.<ref name=\"The Monotype 4-Line System for Setting Mathematics\" />\n\nThe 4-line system involved casting characters for 10-point Times Roman on 6-point [[Body (typography)|bodies]]. The top of the character would overhang the slug, forming a [[kern (typography)|kern]] which was less fragile than the normal kerns of foundry type, as it was on a slab of cast metal. This technique had been in previous use on Monotype machines, usually involving double-height matrices, to allow the automatic setting of \"advertising figures\" (numbers that occupy two or more lines, usually to clearly indicate a price in an advertisement set in small type). This meant that the same matrix could be used for both superscript and subscript numbers. More importantly, it allowed a variable or other item to have both a superscript and a subscript at the same time, one above the other, without inordinate difficulty.<ref name=\"The Monotype 4-Line System for Setting Mathematics\" />\n\nPreviously, while the Monotype system, due to its flexibility, was widely used for setting mathematical formulas, the typeface Modern Series 7 was usually used for this purpose.<ref>T. W. Chaundy, P. R. Barett, Charles Batey, ''The Printing of Mathematics'', Oxford University Press (1954, 1957)</ref> Because of the popularity of Times Roman at the time, Monotype chose to design a variant of Times Roman suited to mathematical composition, and recut many additional characters needed for mathematics, including special symbols as well as Greek and Fraktur alphabets, to accompany the system instead of designing it around the typeface that was being used, for which characters were already available. Matrices for some 700 characters were available as part of Times Roman Series 569 when it was released in 1958, with new characters constantly being added for over a decade afterwards (thus, in 1971, 8,000 characters were included, and new ones were being added at a rate of about 5 per week).<ref name=\"The Monotype 4-Line System for Setting Mathematics\" />\n{{clear}}\n\n==Usage==\n[[File:Colliers Times New Roman letter perfect.jpg|thumb|right|A 1943 brochure used by Crowell-Collier, one of the first major American users of Times New Roman, to promote the changeover.<ref name=\"Happiness is Times New Roman\" />]]\nTimes New Roman's popularity rapidly expanded beyond its original niche, becoming popular in book printing and general publishing. Monotype took advantage of this popularity by commissioning a widened version, Series 427, for book publishing, although many books ultimately used the original version.{{sfn|Williamson|1956|p=103}}\n\nAn early use of Times New Roman outside its origin was by [[Daniel Berkeley Updike]], an influential historian of printing with whom Morison carried an extensive correspondence. Impressed by the design, he used it to set his book ''Some Aspects of Printing, Old and New''.<ref name=\"Blackwell2004\">{{cite book|first=Lewis|last=Blackwell|title=20th-century Type|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WNUJ0dKGxmsC&pg=PA76|year=2004|publisher=Laurence King Publishing|isbn=978-1-85669-351-6|pages=76\u20139}}</ref><ref name=\"D.B. Updike Set Standard of Great Craftsmanship\">{{cite web|last1=Lawson|first1=Alexander S.|title=D.B. Updike Set Standard of Great Craftsmanship|url=http://www.alexanderslawson.com/d-b-updike-set-standard-of-great-craftsmanship/|website=The Alexander S. Lawson Archive|accessdate=15 December 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Lawson Morison Obituary\">{{cite web|last1=Lawson|first1=Alexander S.|title=Stanley Morison: Significant Historian (obituary)|url=http://www.alexanderslawson.com/stanley-morison-significant-historian/|website=The Alexander S. Lawson Archive|accessdate=14 May 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160527130023/http://www.alexanderslawson.com/stanley-morison-significant-historian/|archivedate=27 May 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It then was chosen by the Crowell-Collier magazines ''[[Woman's Home Companion]]'' and then its sister publications such as ''[[Collier's]]''.{{sfn|Dreyfus|1973|p=172}}<ref name=\"Lawson1990\">{{cite book|author=Alexander S. Lawson|title=Anatomy of a Typeface|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FiJ87ixLs0sC&pg=PA270|date=January 1990|publisher=David R. Godine Publisher|isbn=978-0-87923-333-4|pages=270\u2013294}}</ref><ref name=\"Crowell-Collier adopts a Type Developed by London Times\">{{cite journal|title=Crowell-Collier adopts a Type Developed by London Times|journal=Inland Printer and American Lithographer|volume=111}}</ref> A brochure was published to mark the change along with a letter from Morison hoping that the redesign would be a success.<ref name=\"Happiness is Times New Roman\">{{cite web|last1=Heller|first1=Steven|title=Happiness is Times New Roman|url=http://www.printmag.com/daily-heller/happiness-is-times-new-roman/|website=Print magazine|accessdate=15 December 2016}}</ref> Ultimately it became Monotype's best-selling metal type of all time.<ref name=Badaracco>{{cite journal|last1=Badaracco|first1=Claire|title=Innovative Industrial Design and Modern Public Culture: The Monotype Corporation, 1922\u20131932|journal=Business & Economic History|date=1991|volume=20 (second series)|pages=226\u2013233|url=http://www.thebhc.org/sites/default/files/beh/BEHprint/v020/p0226-p0233.pdf|accessdate=19 December 2015|publisher=Business History Conference}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet |author=Whittington Press |author-link= |user=whittingtonpres|number=720745586069213185|date=14 April 2016|title= Sales chart of Monotype die cases.}}</ref>\n\n[[Walter Tracy]], who worked on a redesign, however noted that the design's compression and fine detail extending to the edge of the [[Matrix (printing)|matrices]] was not ideal in the aggressive conditions of most newspaper printing, in which the ''Times'' was unusual for its particularly high standard of printing suiting its luxury market. Users found that in the hot metal period it was common for the molten metal to rapidly eat through the matrices as type was being cast, and so it did not become popular among other newspapers: \"Times Roman achieved its popularity chiefly in general printing, not in newspaper work.\"{{sfn|Tracy|2003|p=204}} He described it as particularly used in \"book work, especially non-fiction\" such as the ''[[Encyclopaedia Britannica]]''.{{sfn|Tracy|2003|p=204}} Hutt also commented that Times New Roman's relative condensation was less useful than might be expected for newspaper printing, since in a normal newspaper column frequent paragraph breaks tend to provide area that can absorb the space of wider letters without increasing the number of lines used\u2013but ''The Times'', whose [[Style guide|house style]] in the 1930s was to minimise the number of paragraph breaks, was an exception to this.{{sfn|Hutt|1970|p=264}}\n\nTimes New Roman remains popular in publishing, helped by the extremely large range of characters available for international and mathematics printing.{{sfn|Williamson|1956|p=102}}<ref name=\"Es gilt das gesprochene Wort\">{{cite web |last1=Bergmann |first1=Christopher |title=Es gilt das gesprochene Wort: Schriftarten f\u00fcr IPA-Transkriptionen |url=https://www.isoglosse.de/2014/03/schriftarten-ipa-transkriptionen/ |website=Isoglosse |accessdate=14 November 2018}}</ref> For example, the [[American Psychological Association]] suggests using Times New Roman in papers written in its [[APA style]].<ref name=\"APA Style Blog\">{{cite web |last1=Lee |first1=Chelsea |title=Fonts of Knowledge |url=https://blog.apastyle.org/apastyle/2013/03/fonts-of-knowledge.html |website=APA Style Blog |publisher=[[American Psychological Association]] |accessdate=14 November 2018}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n==Linotype releases==\n[[File:Many accented a (8277806822).jpg|thumb|Working drawings for a Linotype release of \"Times Roman\". Various accents are drawn together on the same sheet.<ref name=\"Charli Luc\">{{cite web |title=Pencil To Pixel \u2013 Monotype |url=https://luccharli.wordpress.com/2012/11/23/pencil-to-pixel-monotype-3/ |website=Charli Luc |accessdate=2 April 2019}}</ref>]]\n[[File:Times Roman vs Times New Roman.png|thumb|Some differences between Linotype's Times Roman and Monotype's Times New Roman typefaces.<ref name=\"Strizver TypeTalk\" /><ref name=\"Fonts in Use Low\u2190tech TNR vs. TR\">{{cite web |last1=Sluiter |first1=Matthijs |last2=Hardwig |first2=Florian |title=Low\u2190tech Magazine website |url=https://fontsinuse.com/uses/24504/low-tech-magazine-website#comment-630450 |website=Fonts in Use |accessdate=2 April 2019}}</ref>]]\nDespite Monotype's key role in creating Times New Roman, its rival  [[Mergenthaler Linotype Company|Linotype]] rapidly began to offer the design; ''The Times'' used Linotype equipment for much of its production. Linotype referred to the design as ''Times'' or ''Times Roman''. Monotype and Linotype have since merged, but slight differences have split the lineage of Times into two subtly different designs.\n\nAlthough Times New Roman and Times are very similar, various differences developed between the versions marketed by Linotype and Monotype when the master fonts were transferred from metal to [[cold type|photo]] and digital media. For example, Linotype has slanted [[serif]]s on the capital S, while Monotype's are vertical, and Linotype has an extra serif on the number 5.<ref name=\"Strizver TypeTalk\">{{cite web|first=Ilene|last=Strizver|url=http://www.creativepro.com/blog/typetalk-times-roman-vs-times-new-roman|title=TypeTalk: Times Roman vs Times New Roman|work=CreativePro.com}}</ref> Most of these differences are invisible in body text at normal reading distances, or 10pts at 300 dpi. Subtle competition grew between the two foundries, as the proportions and details as well as the width metrics for their version of Times grew apart.<ref name=\"times-development\" /> Differences between the two versions do occur in the lowercase z in the italic weight, (Times Linotype has a curl also followed in the STIX revival, Times New Roman is straight){{sfn|Tracy|2003|p=204}} and in the percent sign in all weights. (Linotype and STIX have a stroke connecting up the left-hand zero with a slash, Times New Roman does not.) Monotype's 'J' is non-descending, but Linotype's in the bold weight descends below the baseline.\n\nLinotype licensed its version to [[Xerox]] and then [[Adobe Systems|Adobe]] and [[Apple Inc.|Apple]], guaranteeing its importance in digital printing by making it one of the core fonts of the [[PostScript]] page description language.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Shaw|first1=Paul|title=Some history about Arial|url=http://www.paulshawletterdesign.com/2011/09/blue-pencil-no-18%E2%80%94some-history-about-arial/|website=Paul Shaw Letter Design|accessdate=22 May 2015}}</ref> Microsoft's version of Times New Roman is licensed from Monotype, hence the original name. For compatibility, Monotype had to subtly redraw their design to match the widths from the Adobe/Linotype version.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Simonson|first1=Mark|author-link=Mark Simonson|title=Monotype's Other Arials|url=http://www.marksimonson.com/notebook/view/monotypes-other-arials|publisher=Mark Simonson Studio|accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref> Versions of Times New Roman from Monotype (discussed below) exist which vary from the PostScript metrics.\n\nLinotype applied for registration of the trademark name ''Times Roman'' and received registration status in 1945. In the 1980s, there was an attempt by a group of entrepreneurs to seek from [[Rupert Murdoch]], who owned ''The Times'', the right to use the Times Roman name; separately, a legal action was also initiated to clarify the right of Monotype to use the name in the US despite Linotype's registration. As a result of legal action, Linotype and its licensees continued to use the name Times Roman, while Monotype and its licensees used the name Times New Roman.<ref name=\"times-development\">{{cite web |url= http://www.truetype-typography.com/articles/times.htm |title=Times (New) Roman and its part in the Development of Scalable Font Technology |author=Charles Bigelow |year=1994 |accessdate=4 July 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Modern releases==\n\n===As Times New Roman===\nMonotype sells a wider range of styles and [[Font#Optical size|optical sizes]] for Times New Roman than are offered with Windows, in order to meet the needs of newspapers and books which print at a range of text sizes.<ref name=\"Changing the Times\" /> Its current release includes Regular, Medium, Semi Bold and Bold weights with matching italics, Extra Bold, Condensed (in regular, italic and bold), Seven (for smaller text, in regular, italic, bold and bold italic) and Small Text (for very small text, in regular, italic and bold).<ref>{{cite web|title=Monotype Library: Times New Roman|url=http://www.linotype.com/1540/TimesNewRoman-family.html|publisher=Monotype|accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref> The four-weight version included with Windows was also distributed as part of Microsoft's [[Core Fonts for the Web]] package.<ref name=\"apple-techspot\">{{cite web | url=http://www.techspot.com/news/26438-microsoft-and-apple-extend-font-licensing-agreement.html |title=Microsoft and Apple extend font licensing agreement |author=Jose Vilches |date=2007-08-03 |accessdate=2011-06-25}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2017, the version of Times New Roman included with [[Windows 10]], version 6.96, includes [[small capitals]], [[text figures]], and italic [[swash capitals]].<ref name=\"TNR 6.96\">{{cite AV media | people = | date =\n | title = Times New Roman, v. 6.96 | medium = Font digitisation }}</ref><ref name=\"FIU New Roman Times Swash capital comment\">{{cite web |last1=Thiago |last2=Hardwig |first2=Florian |title=New Roman Times \u2013 Camper Van Beethoven |url=https://fontsinuse.com/uses/25135/new-roman-times-camper-van-beethoven#comment-631475 |website=Fonts in Use |accessdate=2 April 2019}}</ref> The Microsoft/Monotype digitisation of Times New Roman omits automatic [[typographic ligature|ligature]] insertion (although as of v. 6.96 it is selectable),<ref name=\"TNR 6.96\" /> which the version of Times installed with macOS has. (This can result in unsightly character collisions if the characters 'fi' are needed.)\n\n===Times New Roman World===\nThis is a version based on fonts released with [[Windows Vista]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Times New Roman OS|url=http://www.linotype.com/616201/TimesNewOSFamilyPack-valuepack.html?site=details&fetchPart=details|website=Linotype|publisher=Monotype|accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref> It includes fonts in [[Windows Glyph List|WGL]] character sets, Hebrew and Arabic characters. Similar to [[Helvetica#Helvetica World|Helvetica World]], Arabic in italic fonts are in roman positions.\n\n===Linotype variants===\nLike Monotype, Linotype released additional versions of Times for different text sizes. These include:\n*Times Ten is a version specially designed for smaller text (12 point and below). It features wider characters and stronger hairlines.<ref name=\"Linotype Times Ten\">{{cite web|title=Linotype Times Ten|url=http://www.myfonts.com/fonts/linotype/times-ten/|website=MyFonts|accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Adobe Times Ten|url=http://www.myfonts.com/fonts/adobe/times-ten/|website=MyFonts|accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref> In 2004 prominent typeface designer [[Erik Spiekermann]] said that he believed that it was the best Times New Roman digitisation then available.<ref name=\"State Department bans Courier New 12, except for treaties\">{{cite web |last1=Shaw |first1=Paul |authorlink1=Paul Shaw (design historian) |title=State Department bans Courier New 12, except for treaties |url=https://www.aiga.org/state-department-bans-courier-new-12-except-for-treaties |publisher=AIGA |accessdate=27 December 2018}}</ref>\n*Times Eighteen, a headline version for point sizes of 18 and larger. The characters are subtly condensed and the hairlines are finer. The current version has no italics, but does have a lower case (whereas some Times titling fonts were capitals only).<ref name=\"Linotype Times Eighteen\">{{cite web|title=Linotype Times Eighteen|url=http://www.myfonts.com/fonts/linotype/times-eighteen/|website=MyFonts|accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref>\n*Times Europa Office, a 2006 adaptation of ''The Times's'' 1972 design Times Europa (see below). This is a complete family of designs intended for use on poor-quality paper. The updating, created by Akira Kobayashi, contains [[Typeface#Typesetting numbers|tabular]] numbers, mathematical signs, and [[currency symbol]]s. Each character has the same advance width in all the fonts in the family so that changing from regular to bold or italic does not affect word wrap.<ref name=\"Europa Office\">{{cite web|url=http://www.linotype.com/en/137439/timeseuropaoffice-family.html |title=Times Europa Office Font Family |publisher=Linotype.com |accessdate=21 September 2013}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n==Later typefaces used by ''The Times''==\n[[File:Balfour Declaration in the Times 9 November 1917.jpg|thumb|''The Times''' previous typeface from an article describing the [[Balfour Declaration]] in 1917.]]\n''The Times'' newspaper has commissioned various successors to Times New Roman:\n*Times Europa was designed by [[Walter Tracy]] in 1972 for ''The Times'', as a sturdier alternative to the Times font family, designed for the demands of faster printing presses and cheaper paper.<ref name=\"Hutt Tracy 1973\">{{cite journal |last1=Hutt |first1=Allan |title=Walter Tracy, type designer |journal=[[The Penrose Annual]] |date=1973 |pages=101-115}}</ref> It has been released commercially by Adobe, among others, recently in an updating by Linotype as Times Europa Office (discussed above).<ref name=\"Adobe Times Europa\">{{cite web|title=Adobe Times Europa|url=http://www.myfonts.com/fonts/adobe/times-europa/|website=MyFonts|accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Europa Office\" />\n*Times Roman replaced Times Europa on 30 August 1982.<ref name=\"timesonline.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/news/uk/article1943001.ece |title=After 221 years, the world's leading newspaper shows off a fresh face |publisher=Thetimes.co.uk |date=20 November 2006 |accessdate=21 September 2013}}</ref>\n*Times Millennium was made in 1991, drawn by Gunnlaugur Briem on the instructions of Aurobind Patel, composing manager of News International.<ref name=\"timesonline.co.uk\"/><ref name=Briem>{{cite web|last1=Briem|first1=Gunnlaugur|title=BriemTimes|url=http://66.147.242.192/~operinan/2/2.2a/2.2.7.6.btim.letter.htm|publisher=Gunnlaugur SE Briem|accessdate=27 July 2015}}</ref>\n*Times Classic first appeared in 2001.<ref name=\"Hall Typography of News\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fontshop.com/blog/fontmag/002/02_news/|first=Peter|last=Hall|title=The Typography of News: Bigger, faster, better |publisher=Fontshop.com |accessdate=21 September 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120415015824/http://www.fontshop.com/blog/fontmag/002/02_news/|archive-date=15 April 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"New Cuts at The Times\">{{cite web |last1=Baines |first1=Phil |title=Face lift: new cuts at The Times |url=http://www.eyemagazine.com/feature/article/face-lift-new-cuts-at-the-times |website=Eye |accessdate=10 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Berry Typographic Texture of the News\">{{cite web |last1=Berry |first1=John |title=dot-font: The Typographic Texture of the News |url=https://creativepro.com/dot-font-the-typographic-texture-of-the-news/ |website=Creative Pro |accessdate=10 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Berry News on Paper\">{{cite web |last1=Berry |first1=John |title=dot-font: News on Paper in the Digital Age |url=https://creativepro.com/dot-font-news-on-paper-in-the-digital-age/ |website=Creative Pro |accessdate=10 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Design Week Housestyle\">{{cite web |title=Housestyle is just the type for redesign of The Times newspaper |url=https://www.designweek.co.uk/issues/14-february-2002/housestyle-is-just-the-type-for-redesign-of-the-times-newspaper/ |website=Design Week |accessdate=10 May 2019}}</ref> Designed as an economical face by Dave Farey and Richard Dawson, it took advantage of the new PC-based publishing system at the newspaper; the new typeface included 120 letters per font.<ref name=\"Driver 2006\">{{cite news |last1=Driver |first1=David |title=After 221 years, the world's leading newspaper shows off a fresh face |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/after-221-years-the-worlds-leading-newspaper-shows-off-a-fresh-face-vxs5wkc0ch6 |accessdate=9 April 2020 |work=The Times |date=2006}}</ref><ref name=\"Farey part 1\">{{cite journal|last1=Farey|first1=Dave|title=A Life and Times, Part 1|journal=Ultrabold|date=2014|issue=16|pages=16\u201325}}</ref><ref name=\"Farey part 2\">{{cite journal|last1=Farey|first1=Dave|title=A Life and Times, Part 2|journal=Ultrabold|date=2014|issue=15|pages=3\u201313}}</ref>\n*Times Modern was unveiled on 20 November 2006, as the successor of Times Classic.<ref name=\"timesonline.co.uk\"/> Designed for improving legibility in smaller font sizes, it uses 45-degree angled bracket serifs. It was designed by Research Studios, led by designer [[Neville Brody]] with input from [[Ben Preston]],  deputy editor of ''The Times''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prnewswire.co.uk/cgi/news/release?id=184449 |title=Neville Brody's Research Studios Creates New Font and Design Changes for The Times as Compact Format Continues to Attract Loyal Readership |location=LONDON |publisher=Prnewswire.co.uk |date=2006-11-15 |accessdate=21 September 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Luke Prowse interview\">{{cite web |first=Alan|last=Formby-Jackson|title=A conversation with Times Modern designer Luke Prowse |url=http://www.visualeditors.com/jackson/2006/11/a-conversation-with-time-modern-designer-luke-prowse/ |website=Visual Editors |accessdate=2 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070208180600/http://www.visualeditors.com/jackson/2006/11/a-conversation-with-time-modern-designer-luke-prowse/|archive-date=8 February 2007}}</ref> (Other designs have been released called Times Modern; see below.) During the Times New Roman period ''The Times'' also sometimes used [[Perpetua (typeface)|Perpetua Titling]].<ref name=\"Tally of Types\" /><ref name=\"The Times: New roman and related founts.\">{{cite web |title=The Times: New roman and related founts. |url=http://www.elbrecht.de/TNR&RF.jpg |publisher=Times/Monotype |accessdate=16 September 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150916043631/http://www.elbrecht.de/TNR%26RF.jpg |archivedate=16 September 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==William Starling Burgess==\nIn 1994 the printing historian [[Mike Parker (typographer)|Mike Parker]] published claims that the design of Times New Roman's roman or regular style was based on a 1904 design of [[William Starling Burgess]].<ref name=\"Burgess\">\n{{cite journal\n  | last = Parker\n  | first = Mike\n  | title = W. Starling Burgess, Type Designer?\n  | journal = Printing History\n  | volume = 31/32\n  | pages = 52\u2013108\n  | year = 1994}}\n</ref> This theory remains controversial.<ref name=\"Burgess2\">\n{{cite news\n | url = http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/a2fa033e-7ca1-11de-a7bf-00144feabdc0.html\n | last = Alas\n | first = Joel\n | accessdate = 26 August 2009\n | date = 1 August 2009\n | title = The history of the Times New Roman typeface\n | newspaper = Financial Times\n}}</ref><ref name=eastland>Katherine Eastland. [http://www.thedaily.com/page/2011/08/15/081511-opinions-history-times-new-roman-eastland-1-3/ The History Page: Exactly your type], TheDaily.com, 15 August 2011</ref> Parker and his friend [[Gerald Giampa]], a Canadian printer who had bought up the defunct American branch of Lanston Monotype, claimed that, in 1904, Burgess created a type design for company documents at his shipyard in Marblehead, Massachusetts, and hired Lanston Monotype to issue it.<ref name=eastland/> However, Burgess abandoned the idea and Monotype shelved the sketches, ultimately reusing them as a basis for Times New Roman. Giampa claimed that he stumbled upon original material in 1987, after he had purchased Lanston Monotype, and that some of the papers that had been his evidence had been lost in a flood at his house, while Parker claimed that an additional source was material in a section of the Smithsonian now closed due to [[asbestos]] contamination.<ref name=eastland/><ref name=\"Stanley Morison and Times New Roman\" /> Giampa asked Parker to complete the type from the limited number of surviving letters, which was issued in June 2009 by [[Font Bureau]] under the name of 'Starling'.<ref name=eastland/><ref name=\"Stanley Morison and Times New Roman\" />\n \nReception to the claims was sceptical, with dismissal from Morison's biographer [[Nicolas Barker]] and [[Luc Devroye]] among others; Barker suggested that the material had been fabricated in order to aid Giampa in embarrassing Monotype's British branch, while Devroye and Thomas Phinney of [[FontLab]] suggested that the claim had begun as a prank.<ref name=\"Stanley Morison and Times New Roman\">{{cite web|last1=Loxley|first1=Simon|title=Stanley Morison and Times New Roman|url=http://www.simonloxley.com/ar_02_stan.html|publisher=Ultrabold|accessdate=8 March 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Starling Burgess: No Type Designer\">{{cite book|last1=Barker|first1=Nicolas|title=Form and Meaning in the History of the Book : selected essays|date=2003|publisher=British Library|location=London|isbn=0-7123-4777-1|pages=[https://archive.org/details/formmeaninginhis0000bark/page/371 371\u2013390]|chapter=Starling Burgess: No Type Designer|chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/formmeaninginhis0000bark/page/371}}</ref><ref name=\"Devroye on Burgess\">{{cite web|last1=Devroye|first1=Luc|title=William Starling Burgess|url=http://luc.devroye.org/fonts-24415.html|website=Type Design Information|accessdate=8 March 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Hudson Phinney TypeDrawers\" /> In 2010, writer Mark Owens described Parker's article in retrospect as \"the scantest of evidence\" and a \"fog of irrelevant details\".<ref name=\"A Note on the Type\">{{cite book |last1=Owens |first1=Mark |title=A Note on the Type |date=2010 |publisher=Carnegie Museum of Art |pages=268\u2013270}}</ref>{{efn|Among the few prominent figures in typography to express even qualified support for the idea was Tiro Typeworks owner John Hudson, Giampa's neighbour. He wrote in 2008 that he had examined Giampa's claimed patterns and that they looked as if they were made using an early Monotype production process obsolete by 1931: \"the material evidence of the two-part patterns and their numbering -- if they are genuine --, suggests very strongly a design that significantly pre-dates 1931...The patterns are either deliberate hoax or they are historical artefacts\" and that he was \"unconvinced that this is a hoax\"; but in 2019, after Giampa and Parker's deaths, he said \"I do think it entirely possible that the whole thing was a hoax.\"<ref name=\"Hudson on Typophile\">{{cite web |last1=Hudson |first1=John |title=Comments on Typophile thread |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110908011822/http://typophile.com/node/50470 |website=Typophile (archived) |accessdate=30 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Hudson Phinney TypeDrawers\">{{cite web |last1=Hudson |first1=John |last2=Phinney |first2=Thomas |title=Comments on TypeDrawers thread |url=https://typedrawers.com/discussion/3073/never-mind-starling |website=TypeDrawers |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> The claims did convince prominent type designer [[Walter Tracy]], who had written a major analysis of Times New Roman's genesis in his book ''Letters of Credit''; however he died in April 1995, before Parker's finalised publication, and did not live to see the extensive rebuttals.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Tracy |first1=Walter |title=Letters of Credit: A Correction |journal=Journal of the Printing Historical Society |date=1995 |pages=2\u20133}}</ref>}} Monotype executive Dan Rhatigan described the theory as implausible in 2011: \"I'll admit that I tend to side with the more fully documented (both in general, and in agreement with what little I can find within Monotype to support it) notion that Times New Roman was based on Plantin...I won't rule out the possibility that Starling Burgess drew up the concept first, but [[Occam's razor]] makes me doubt it.\"<ref name=\"It was never called Times Old Roman\" />\n\nThe Times Online web site credits the design to \"Stanley Morrison, Victor Lardent and perhaps Starling Burgess\".<ref>\n{{cite news\n | url = http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/letters/feedback/article1185820.ece\n | accessdate = 26 August 2009\n | date = 25 January 2007\n | title = FAQ: infrequently asked questions\n | newspaper = Times Online\n}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n==Designs inspired by Times New Roman==\n[[File:Times Modern (7128712341).jpg|thumb|Times Modern [[Swash (typography)|Swash]], an exaggerated and unauthorised display adaptation of Times from the phototypesetting period.]]\n[[File:Pelham Infant.jpg|thumb|Pelham Infant]]\nIn the [[phototypesetting]] and digital typesetting periods many font designs have been published inspired by Times New Roman. Although the digital data of Monotype and Linotype releases of Times New Roman are copyrighted, and the name ''Times'' is trademarked,<ref name=\"Justus Estoesa\">{{cite web |last1=Justus |first1=Dana |last2=Estoesa |first2=Ivy Clarice |title=\"Types\" of Protection for Font and Typeface Designs |url=https://www.natlawreview.com/article/types-protection-font-and-typeface-designs |website=[[The National Law Review]] |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> the ''design'' is in many countries [[Intellectual property protection of typefaces|not copyrightable]], notably in the United States,<ref name=\"Compendium313.6C2\">{{cite web |url=http://copyright.gov/comp3/chap900/ch900-visual-art-122214.pdf |title=Compendium of U.S. Copyright Office Practices, \u00a7 906.4 (\"Typeface, Typefont, Lettering, Calligraphy, and Typographic Ornamentation\") |page=13 |publisher=[[United States Copyright Office]] |date=December 22, 2014 |accessdate=December 22, 2014 |quote=The copyright law does not protect typeface or mere variations of typographic ornamentation or lettering. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141223014120/http://copyright.gov/comp3/chap900/ch900-visual-art-122214.pdf |archive-date=23 December 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> allowing alternative interpretations if they do not reuse digital data.\n*Times Modern was a condensed and bold display variant published by, among others, [[Elsner+Flake]]. It was withdrawn from sale due to trademark disputes with the ''Times'' newspaper, which owns its own unrelated design named 'Times Modern' (see above).<ref>{{cite web|last1=Coles|first1=Stephen|title=Times Modern|url=http://fontsinuse.com/uses/3368/the-other-times-modern|website=Fonts in Use|accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref>\n*CG Times is a variant of Times family made by [[Compugraphic Corporation|Compugraphic]].\n*Pelham is a version of Times Roman by DTP Types of Britain, which also designed an [[Schoolbook characters|infant version]] with single-storey 'a' and 'g'.<ref name=\"Pelham Infant\">{{cite web |title=Pelham Infant |url=http://www.type.co.uk/categories/sp/Infant/id/42386 |website=Type.co.uk |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n[[File:Sample of IBM Magnetic Card Composer Output.png|thumb|Press Roman, a version of Times New Roman typed on a premium IBM typewriter.]]\n* In the mid-1960s, a derivative of Times New Roman known as 'Press Roman' was used as a font for the [[IBM Composer]]. This was an ultra-premium electric 'golfball' [[typewriter]] system, intended to be used for producing high-quality office documents or copy to be photographically enlarged for small-scale printing projects.<ref name=\"Typefaces - the complete works\">{{cite book|last1=Osterer|first1=Heidurn|last2=Stamm|first2=Philipp|last3=Frutiger|first3=Adrian|author-link3=Adrian Frutiger|title=Adrian Frutiger - Typefaces: The Complete Works|date=2009|publisher=Birkh\u00e4user|location=Basel|isbn=978-3764385811|page=192|edition=English}}</ref> Unlike most typewriters, the Composer produced proportional type, rather than monospaced letters. Ultimately the system proved a niche product, as it competed with increasingly cheap [[phototypesetting]], and then in the 1980s was largely displaced by word processors and general-purpose computers.<ref name=\"McEldowney2013\">{{cite book|first=Dennis|last=McEldowney|title=A Press Achieved: the Emergence of Auckland University Press, 1927-1972|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VT1eAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT102|date=1 October 2013|publisher=Auckland University Press|isbn=978-1-86940-671-4|pages=102\u20135}}</ref>{{efn|The system returned to public attention in 2004, during the [[Killian documents controversy]], when some documents apparently from the 1970s and presenting the future U.S. president [[George W. Bush]]'s [[George W. Bush military service controversy|military service]] in an unfavourable light were presented by the American news network CBS. The documents were typeset in a form of Times New Roman. As the documents [[Killian documents authenticity issues|looked unlike most typewritten documents]], having proportional spacing rather than the monospacing of almost all typewritten documents, some defenders of the documents suggested that they might have been typed using this method. It is now accepted that they were forged on a modern computer, according to digital font expert Thomas Phinney in the Linotype version of Times New Roman.<ref name=Typekit>{{cite web|last1=Phinney|first1=Thomas|title=Bush Guard memos used Times Roman, not Times New Roman|url=http://blog.typekit.com/2006/08/03/bush_guard_memo/|website=The Typekit Blog|accessdate=20 April 2015|date=3 August 2006}}</ref><ref name=WaPo0914>{{cite news | title=Expert Cited by CBS Says He Didn't Authenticate Papers  | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A18982-2004Sep13.html | accessdate=20 February 2007 | newspaper=The Washington Post | first1=Michael | last1=Dobbs | first2=Howard | last2=Kurtz | date=14 September 2004}}</ref>}}\n* Among many digital-period designs loosely inspired by Times, [[Kris Sowersby]]'s popular Tiempos family is a loose Times New Roman revival; it was created for a Spanish newspaper ('tiempo' is Spanish for 'time').<ref name=\"Tiempos Design Information\">{{cite web |last1=Sowersby |first1=Kris |title=Tiempos Design Information |url=https://klim.co.nz/blog/tiempos-design-information/ |publisher=Klim Type Foundry |accessdate=21 January 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Eye Reputations: Kris Sowersby\">{{cite web |last1=Thomson |first1=Mark |last2=Sowersby |first2=Kris |title=Reputations: Kris Sowersby |url=http://www.eyemagazine.com/feature/article/reputations-kris-sowersby |website=Eye |accessdate=12 September 2019}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n==Free alternatives==\n[[File:Times New Roman Liberation Serif comparison.png|thumb|Comparison between Times New Roman and Liberation Serif, showing its much squarer design]]\nThere are some [[free software]] fonts used as alternatives, including [[metric-compatible]] designs used for [[font substitution]].<ref name=\"gnufreefont-why\">{{cite web |url=https://www.gnu.org/software/freefont/articles/Why_Free_Fonts.html |title=GNU FreeFont - Why do we need free outline UCS fonts? |date=4 October 2009 |accessdate=2 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=A simple introduction to Font Licensing |url=https://www.keystonelaw.co.uk/keynotes/a-simple-introduction-to-font-licensing |website=Keystone |accessdate=7 June 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Times New Roman\u00ae Font Family License |url=https://www.fonts.com/font/monotype/times-new-roman/licenses |website=Fonts.com |accessdate=7 June 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=EULA - Monotype |url=https://www.monotype.com/legal/eula/ |website=monotype.com |accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref>\n*[[URW++]] produced a version of Times New Roman called [[Nimbus Roman]] in 1982. Nimbus Roman No9 L, URW's [[PostScript]] variant, was released under the [[GNU General Public License]] in 1996,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tug.org/fonts/deutsch-urw.txt |title=Finally! Good-quality free (GPL) basic-35 PostScript Type 1 fonts. |format=TXT |accessdate=6 May 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://mirror.cs.wisc.edu/pub/mirrors/ghost/aladdin/fonts/ghostscript-fonts-std-4.0.tar.gz |title=ghostscript-fonts-std-4.0.tar.gz - GhostScript 4.0 standard fonts - AFPL license |format=TAR.GZ |date=28 June 1996 |accessdate=6 May 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110424032316/http://mirror.cs.wisc.edu/pub/mirrors/ghost/aladdin/fonts/ghostscript-fonts-std-4.0.tar.gz |archivedate=24 April 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and available in major [[free software|free]] and [[open source software|open source]] operating systems.{{efn|This was later adapted in versions including [[FreeSerif]],<ref name=\"gnufreefont-why\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gnu.org/software/freefont/design-notes.html |title=GNU FreeFont - Design notes |date=4 October 2009 |accessdate=2 July 2010}}</ref> TeX Gyre Termes<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gust.org.pl/projects/e-foundry/tex-gyre/termes/index_html |title=TeX Gyre Termes \u2014 GUST Web Presence |accessdate=20 May 2018}}</ref> and TeX Gyre Termes Math.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gust.org.pl/projects/e-foundry/tg-math/download/readme-tex-gyre-termes-math.txt/view |title=README-TeX-Gyre-Termes-Math.txt \u2014 GUST Web Presence |accessdate=6 October 2018}}</ref>}} Like Times New Roman, many additional styles of Nimbus Roman exist that are only sold commercially, including condensed and extra-bold styles. URW also developed Nimbus Roman No. 4, which is metrically compatible with the slightly different CG Times.<ref name=\"Epson PCL Fonts\">{{cite web |title=PCL Fonts (WF-C5290) |url=https://files.support.epson.com/docid/cpd5/cpd55236/source/printers/source/specifications/reference/wfc5210_5290/pcl_font_table_wfc5290.html |publisher=Epson |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n[[File:Times and STIX.png|thumb|A standard Times New Roman digitisation compared to the STIX Two project, an open-source typeface for mathematics based on Times's smaller metal point sizes. STIX Two has a higher x-height and a reduction in fine detail.]]\n* The [[STIX Fonts project]] is a four-style set of open-source fonts. They were created for scientific publishing by the Scientific and Technical Information Exchange consortium of publishers, but are also very suitable for general use, including Greek and Cyrillic support.<ref name=STIX>{{cite web|title=STIX Project|url=http://www.stixfonts.org|publisher=Scientific and Technical Information Exchange|accessdate=16 September 2015}}</ref> The original version is installed by default on [[OS X|Mac OS X]], and adapted as [[XITS]]. In 2016, a completely redesigned version was released by Ross Mills and John Hudson of Tiro Typeworks. Unlike the previous version, it is an original design loosely inspired by a [[Optical size|smaller 10 point size]] of Times New Roman, with a higher [[x-height]] than Monotype's Times digitisation.<ref name=\"10pt metal Times\">{{cite web|title=Tweet|url=https://twitter.com/TiroTypeworks/status/804395547259867136|website=Twitter|publisher=Tiro Typeworks|accessdate=10 December 2016|quote=The original STIX fonts were based on a Times New Roman clone. The new #STIX2 faces are redesigned, inspired by 10pt metal Times fonts.}}</ref><ref name=\"stixfonts.org\">{{cite web|last1=Twardoch|first1=Adam|title=New \"STIX Two\" opensource fonts by Tiro: stixfonts.org|url=https://www.facebook.com/media/set/?set=a.10154700398143764.1073741830.561698763&type=1&l=16394cf489|website=Facebook|accessdate=10 December 2016|quote=The new design is fantastic \u2014 it can be described as \"the better Times New Roman\". It's somewhat similar to Times, but with a touch of [[Joan Micha\u00ebl Fleischman|Fleischmann]]. Its lower contrast, enlarged x-height and less inclined italic all contribute to superb(!) readability, in both web and print. STIX Text is a neutral, non-invasive text face for continuous reading.}}</ref> \n*[[Liberation Serif]] by [[Steve Matteson]] is metrically equivalent to Times New Roman.<ref name=\"CC Matteson\">{{cite web |last1=Middendorp |first1=Jan |title=Creative Characters: Steve Matteson |url=https://www.myfonts.com/newsletters/cc/201205.html |website=MyFonts |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> It was developed by [[Ascender Corporation|Ascender Corp.]] and published by [[Red Hat]] in 2007 under the GPL license with some exceptions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fedorahosted.org/liberation-fonts/browser/master/License.txt |title=Overview - liberation-fonts - Pagure |website=Red Hat pagure |accessdate=12 February 2018 }}</ref> It is used in some GNU/Linux distributions as a default font replacement for Times New Roman.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://archive.openmandriva.org/wiki/en/index.php?title=Mandriva_Linux_2008_Release_Tour#Liberation_font_set |title=Mandriva Linux 2008 Release Tour |quote=integrated into Mandriva Linux 2008 |accessdate=12 February 2018}}</ref> Widths aside, it does not particularly resemble Times New Roman, being much squarer in shape with less fine detail and blunt ends rather than ball terminals.<ref name=\"Bean Tinos\">{{cite journal |last1=Bean |first1=Jonathan |title=The Times New Roman lie |journal=interactions |date=27 April 2015 |volume=22 |issue=3 |pages=24\u201325 |doi=10.1145/2742938}}</ref> Google's Tinos in the [[Croscore fonts]] package is a derivative of Liberation Serif.\n* [[Bitstream Cyberbit]] is a roman-only font released by [[Bitstream Inc.|Bitstream]] for non-commercial use, with European alphabets based on Times New Roman.<ref name=\"Titus Unicode\">{{cite web|title=Titus Unicode|url=http://titus.fkidg1.uni-frankfurt.de/unicode/tituut.asp|website=Department of Empirical Linguistics|publisher=University of Frankfurt|accessdate=22 February 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Cyberbit Netscape\">{{cite web|title=pub/communicator/extras/fonts/windows|url=http://ftp.netscape.com/pub/communicator/extras/fonts/windows/|publisher=Netscape|accessdate=22 February 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080907182545/http://ftp.netscape.com/pub/communicator/extras/fonts/windows/|archivedate=7 September 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It has an expanded character range intended to cover a large proportion of [[Unicode]] for scholarly use. Bitstream no longer offers the font, but it remains downloadable from the [[Goethe University Frankfurt|University of Frankfurt]].<ref name=\"Titus Unicode 2\">{{cite web|title=Titus Unicode|url=http://titus.uni-frankfurt.de/indexe.htm?/unicode/unitest2.htm|publisher=University of Frankfurt|accessdate=22 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist|30em}}\n{{clear}}\n==References==\n===Cited literature===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Barker|first1=Nicolas|author-link=Nicolas Barker|title=Stanley Morison|date=1972}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Dreyfus|first=John|author-link=John Dreyfus|title=The Evolution of Times New Roman|journal=[[The Penrose Annual]]|date=1973|volume=66|}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Hutt |first1=Allen |title=Newspaper Design |date=1960 |publisher=Oxford University Press}}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Hutt|first1=Allen|title=Times Roman: a re-assessment|journal=Journal of Typographic Research|date=1970|volume=4|issue=3|url=http://visiblelanguagejournal.com/issue/15|accessdate=5 March 2017}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Moran |first1=James |title=Stanley Morison: His Typographic Achievement |date=1971 |publisher=Lund Humphries |location=London |isbn=0853313008}}\n* {{cite book|last=Tracy|first=Walter|author-link=Walter Tracy|title=Letters of Credit: A View of Type Design|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=y8NssjbqNcsC&pg=PA194|date=2003|publisher=D.R. Godine|isbn=978-1-56792-240-0}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Williamson|first1=Hugh|author-link=Hugh Williamson (book designer)|title=Methods of Book Design|date=1956|url=https://archive.org/details/MethodsOfBookDesign}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* Times Modern, by Dan Rhatigan: [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=n7hgQ_MXL8k&sns=tw  Part 1] and [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=szpBcBG9Vdw Part 2]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150916043631/http://www.elbrecht.de/TNR%26RF.jpg Times New Roman family] (different sizes, in hot metal type)\n* [https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/typography/font-list/times-new-roman Times New Roman font family - Typography | Microsoft Docs]\n* Fonts In Use: [https://fontsinuse.com/typefaces/5117/times-new-roman Times New Roman], [https://fontsinuse.com/typefaces/52/times Times]\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2011}}\n{{The Times}}\n{{Microsoft Windows Typefaces}}\n{{Monotype typefaces}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Articles with inconsistent citation formats]]\n[[Category:Monotype typefaces]]\n[[Category:Windows XP typefaces]]\n[[Category:Transitional serif typefaces]]\n[[Category:Corporate typefaces]]\n[[Category:Typefaces with optical sizes]]\n[[Category:Newspaper and magazine typefaces]]\n[[Category:Typefaces with infant variants]]\n[[Category:Typefaces and fonts introduced in 1932]]\n[[Category:The Times]]\n[[Category:Old style serif typefaces]]\n[[Category:Typefaces with text figures]]\n[[Category:Latin-script typefaces]]\n[[Category:IPA typefaces]]\n", "name_user": "Blythwood", "label": "safe", "comment": "Add template", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Times_New_Roman"}
{"title_page": "Angostura bitters", "text_new": "{{short description|Concentrated bitters made of water, alcohol, herbs and spices}}\n[[File:Angostura aromatic bitters dD.jpg|thumb|A bottle of Angostura aromatic bitters with its distinctive oversized label]]\n[[File:Angostura aromatic bitters dD2.jpg|thumb|Emperor Franz Joseph I of Austria is shown on the label, since Angostura won a medal at the 1873 World Fair in Vienna.]]\n'''Angostura bitters''' ({{IPAc-en|lang|pron|\u00e6|\u014b|\u0261|\u0259|\u02c8|s|tj|\u028a\u0259r|\u0259}}) is a concentrated [[bitters]] (herbal [[ethanol|alcoholic]] preparation) based on [[gentian]], herbs and spices,<ref name=\"Fallis\">{{cite book\n| author=Catherine Fallis\n| title=Wine\n| publisher=iUniverse\n| page=214\n| year=2004\n| url=https://books.google.com/?id=_VWKG1D55loC&pg=PA214&dq=angostura+gentian+water+alcohol\n| isbn=978-0-595-32699-0\n}}</ref> by [[House of Angostura]] in [[Trinidad and Tobago]]. It is typically used for flavouring beverages or, less often, food. The bitters were first produced in the town of Angostura (now [[Ciudad Bol\u00edvar]], [[Venezuela]]), hence the name, but do not contain [[angostura bark]]. The bottle is recognisable by its distinctive oversized label. 'Angostura' is Spanish for 'narrowing', the town of Angostura having been located at the first narrowing of the [[Orinoco River]].\n\n==History==\nThe recipe was developed as a tonic by [[:es:Johann Gottlieb Benjamin Siegert|Johann Gottlieb Benjamin Siegert]]<ref>Siegert v. Gandolfi et al., reported in ''The Federal Reporter'' '''149''' 1907:100ff.</ref>. A German surgeon general in [[Sim\u00f3n Bol\u00edvar]]'s army in Venezuela.  Siegert began to sell it in 1824 and established a distillery for the purpose in 1830.<ref>1830 date given as testimony in Siegert v. Findlater, 1876, reported  in N.C. Moak,''Reports of Cases Decided by the English Courts:'' \"8. Chancery Division\" (Albany, NY, 1880) pp21ff.</ref> Siegert was based in the town of Angostura and used locally available ingredients, perhaps aided by botanical knowledge of the local Amerindians.<ref name=\"Mysteries\">Raymond, J.[https://web.archive.org/web/20000925211208/http://www.nalis.gov.tt/Biography/bio_JGB_Siegert_bitters.htm \"Mysteries in Angostura Museum: Story of founder Dr. Siegert comes to life\", ''Trinidad Guardian''] January 10, 2000</ref> The product was sold abroad from 1853, and in 1875 the plant was moved from Ciudad Bolivar to Port of Spain, Trinidad, where it remains.<ref>Siegert v. Findlater; Siegert v. Gandolfi.</ref> Angostura won a medal at the [[Weltausstellung 1873 Wien]]. The medal is still depicted on the oversized label, along with reverse which shows Emperor [[Franz Joseph I of Austria]] in profile.\n\nThe exact formula is a [[Trade secret|closely guarded secret]], with only one person knowing the whole recipe, passed hereditarily.<ref>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.nbcnews.com/id/21134540\n| title = Sweet Bitters\n| first = Rachel\n| last = Maddow\n| authorlink = Rachel Maddow\n| publisher = NBC News\n| date = 2010-04-10\n}}</ref>\n\nSince 2007, Angostura has also produced Angostura Orange, an [[orange bitters]] with bright floral notes and fresh orange peel.<ref name=\"Parsons\">{{cite web |last1=Parsons |first1=Brad Thomas |title=Ten Essential Bitters and How to Use Them |url=https://punchdrink.com/articles/ten-essential-aromatic-cocktail-bitters-and-how-to-use-them/ |website=PUNCH |accessdate=18 July 2019 |date=24 July 2017}}</ref> Angostura orange bitters have not dominated the orange bitters market in the same way that its aromatic bitters have become a go-to product for bars and consumers.<ref name=\"Simonson\">{{cite web |last1=Simonson |first1=Robert |title=Will the Real Orange Bitters Please Stand Up? |url=https://punchdrink.com/articles/real-orange-bitters-angostura-regans-fee-brothers/ |website=PUNCH |accessdate=18 July 2019 |date=15 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009 there was a shortage of Angostura bitters;<ref name=shortage /> the company reported that this was caused primarily by a problem in their supply of bottles. There were incorrect rumours of a product recall, or that production of the bitters had stopped at the plant in Trinidad. The shortage was the subject of many news articles and blogs, particularly in the cocktail industry.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/01/19/AR2010011900877.html/|title=Spirits: The Angostura Bitters Shortage calls for creativity|author=|date=|website=washingtonpost.com|accessdate=20 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Uses==\nAngostura bitters are extremely concentrated and may be an [[acquired taste]]; though 44.7% alcohol by volume, bitters are not normally ingested undiluted, but instead are used in small amounts as flavouring.<ref name=shortage>{{cite web|url=http://www.herbcompanion.com/herbs-in-the-kitchen/in-the-news-angostura-bitters-shortage.aspx|title=In the News: Angostura Bitters Shortage|author=|date=|website=Mother Earth Living|accessdate=20 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Medicinal===\nAngostura bitters are alleged to have restorative properties.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Bhat |first1=Kartik |title=Beverages |date=2013 |publisher=Pearson |location=Delhi |isbn=9789332514072 |pages=307\u20138}}</ref>  Angostura bitters is often incorrectly believed to have poisonous qualities because it is associated with angostura bark (although it does not actually contain any), which, although not toxic, during its use as a medicine was often adulterated by unscrupulous sellers,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://earthnotes.tripod.com/angostura.htm|title=Angostura - Herb Database + Images|first=Ernestina Parziale|last=CH|date=|website=earthnotes.tripod.com|accessdate=20 April 2018}}</ref> who padded out the sacks of bark with cheaper, poisonous ''[[Strychnos nux-vomica]]'' or [[copalchi]] bark.<ref name=\"Fallis\" /><ref>{{cite book\n| author1 = Albert Y. Leung\n| author2 = Steven Foster\n| title = Encyclopedia of common natural ingredients used in food, drugs, and cosmetics\n| publisher = Wiley-Interscience\n| year = 2003\n| page = 35\n}}</ref>\nAngostura is still often used by Trinidadians to treat digestive problems. It contains gentian, which has been proven effective as treatment for indigestion.{{Citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n===Cocktails===\nAngostura bitters are a key ingredient in many [[cocktails]]. Originally used to help with upset stomachs of the soldiers in Sim\u00f3n Bol\u00edvar's army, it later became popular in soda water and was usually served with [[gin]]. The mix stuck in the form of a [[pink gin]], and is also used in many other alcoholic [[cocktails]] such as [[long vodka]], consisting of [[vodka]], bitters, and [[lemonade]]. In the United States, it is best known for its use in whiskey cocktails: [[Old fashioned (cocktail)|Old Fashioned]], made with [[whiskey]], bitters, sugar, and water,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.drinksmixer.com/drink407.html|title=Old Fashioned recipe|author=|date=|website=www.drinksmixer.com|accessdate=20 April 2018}}</ref> and [[Manhattan (cocktail)|Manhattan]], made usually with [[rye whiskey]] and red [[vermouth]]. In a [[Pisco Sour]] a few drops are sprinkled on top of the foam, both for aroma and decoration. In a [[Champagne Cocktail]] a few drops of bitters are added to a sugar cube.\n\nIn Hong Kong, Angostura bitters are included in the local [[Gunner (cocktail)|Gunner]] cocktail. Though not in the classic recipe, bartenders sometimes add more flavour to the [[Mojito]] cocktail by sprinkling a few drops of Angostura bitters on top. Bitters can also be used in \"soft\" drinks; a common drink served in Australian and New Zealand pubs is [[lemon, lime and bitters]]. In [[Malawi]], bitters are added to a mix of crushed ice, [[ginger ale]] and [[Sprite (drink)|Sprite]] to make a 'rock shandy'.\n\n''Angostura Bitters Drink Guide'', a promotional booklet of 1908, was reprinted in 2008 with a new introduction by Ross Bolton.\n\nAmong certain bartending communities (especially in Malaysia) shots of Angostura are taken as the 'bartender's handshake' either during or after the shift is done.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://talesofthecocktail.com/culture/praise-bartenders-handshake|title=In Praise of the Bartender's Handshake|date=2017-02-01|work=Tales of the Cocktail|access-date=2017-11-07|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe largest purveyor of Angostura bitters in the world is Nelsen's Hall Bitters Pub on [[Washington Island (Wisconsin)|Washington Island]] off the northeast tip of [[Door Peninsula]] in [[Door County, Wisconsin|Door County]], [[Wisconsin]].  The pub began selling shots of bitters as a ''stomach tonic for medicinal purposes'' under a pharmaceutical license during [[Prohibition in the United States]].  The practice, which helped the pub to become the oldest continuously-operating tavern in Wisconsin, remained a tradition after the repeal of Prohibition. As of 2018, the pub hosts a Bitters Club, incorporates bitters into food menu items, and sells upwards of 10,000 shots per year.<ref name=\"Kunkel\">{{cite web|last1=Kunkel|first1=Leigh|title=How a Tiny Wisconsin Island Became the World's Biggest Consumer of Bitters|url=https://www.atlasobscura.com/articles/washington-island-wisconsin-bitters-shots|website=[[Atlas Obscura]]|accessdate=6 March 2018|date=5 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Popular recipes===\n{{Div col}}\n* [[Bloody Mary (cocktail)|Bloody Mary]]\n* [[Bourbon Lancer]]\n* [[Brandy Sour (Cyprus)]]\n* [[Brut Cocktail]]\n* [[Champagne cocktail]]\n* [[Cuba Libre#Local variations|Cuba Libre Preparado]]\n* [[Fallen Angel (cocktail)|Fallen Angel]]\n* [[Gin pahit]]\n* [[Gunner (cocktail)|Gunner]]\n* [[Lemon, Lime and Bitters]]\n* [[Long vodka]]\n* [[Manhattan (cocktail)|Manhattan]]\n* [[Old fashioned (cocktail)|Old Fashioned]]\n* [[Peanut punch]]\n* [[Pink Gin]]\n* [[Pisco Sour]]\n* [[Planter's Punch]]\n* [[Prince of Wales (cocktail)|Prince of Wales]]\n* [[Rob Roy (cocktail)|Rob Roy]]\n* [[Shandy#Rock or non-alcoholic shandy|Rock Shandy]]\n* [[Punch (drink)#Rum punches|Rum punch]]\n* [[Rum Swizzle]]\n* [[Singapore Sling]]\n* [[Zombie (cocktail)|Zombie]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Gentian (spirit)]]\n* [[Meinhard's Bitters]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.angosturabitters.com/ Official  '''Angostura Bitters''' website]\n{{commonscat|Angostura bitters}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Angostura Bitters}}\n[[Category:Bitters]]\n[[Category:Drink companies of Trinidad and Tobago]]\n[[Category:Patent medicines]]\n[[Category:Spices]]\n[[Category:Trade secrets]]\n[[Category:Venezuelan cuisine]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Concentrated bitters made of water, alcohol, herbs and spices}}\n[[File:Angostura aromatic bitters dD.jpg|thumb|A bottle of Angostura aromatic bitters with its distinctive oversized label]]\n[[File:Angostura aromatic bitters dD2.jpg|thumb|Emperor Franz Joseph I of Austria is shown on the label, since Angostura won a medal at the 1873 World Fair in Vienna.]]\n'''Angostura bitters''' ({{IPAc-en|lang|pron|\u00e6|\u014b|\u0261|\u0259|\u02c8|s|tj|\u028a\u0259r|\u0259}}) is a concentrated [[bitters]] (herbal [[ethanol|alcoholic]] preparation) based on [[gentian]], herbs and spices,<ref name=\"Fallis\">{{cite book\n| author=Catherine Fallis\n| title=Wine\n| publisher=iUniverse\n| page=214\n| year=2004\n| url=https://books.google.com/?id=_VWKG1D55loC&pg=PA214&dq=angostura+gentian+water+alcohol\n| isbn=978-0-595-32699-0\n}}</ref> by [[House of Angostura]] in [[Trinidad and Tobago]]. It is typically used for flavouring beverages or, less often, food. The bitters were first produced in the town of Angostura (now [[Ciudad Bol\u00edvar]], [[Venezuela]]), hence the name, but do not contain [[angostura bark]]. The bottle is recognisable by its distinctive oversized label. 'Angostura' is Spanish for 'narrowing', the town of Angostura having been located at the first narrowing of the [[Orinoco River]].\n\n==History==\nThe recipe was developed as a tonic by a German, [[:es:Johann Gottlieb Benjamin Siegert|Johann Gottlieb Benjamin Siegert]] (1796\u20131870),<ref>Siegert v. Gandolfi et al., reported in ''The Federal Reporter'' '''149''' 1907:100ff.</ref> surgeon general in [[Sim\u00f3n Bol\u00edvar]]'s army in Venezuela.  Siegert began to sell it in 1824 and established a distillery for the purpose in 1830.<ref>1830 date given as testimony in Siegert v. Findlater, 1876, reported  in N.C. Moak,''Reports of Cases Decided by the English Courts:'' \"8. Chancery Division\" (Albany, NY, 1880) pp21ff.</ref> Siegert was based in the town of Angostura and used locally available ingredients, perhaps aided by botanical knowledge of the local Amerindians.<ref name=\"Mysteries\">Raymond, J.[https://web.archive.org/web/20000925211208/http://www.nalis.gov.tt/Biography/bio_JGB_Siegert_bitters.htm \"Mysteries in Angostura Museum: Story of founder Dr. Siegert comes to life\", ''Trinidad Guardian''] January 10, 2000</ref> The product was sold abroad from 1853, and in 1875 the plant was moved from Ciudad Bolivar to Port of Spain, Trinidad, where it remains.<ref>Siegert v. Findlater; Siegert v. Gandolfi.</ref> Angostura won a medal at the [[Weltausstellung 1873 Wien]]. The medal is still depicted on the oversized label, along with reverse which shows Emperor [[Franz Joseph I of Austria]] in profile.\n\nThe exact formula is a [[Trade secret|closely guarded secret]], with only one person knowing the whole recipe, passed hereditarily.<ref>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.nbcnews.com/id/21134540\n| title = Sweet Bitters\n| first = Rachel\n| last = Maddow\n| authorlink = Rachel Maddow\n| publisher = NBC News\n| date = 2010-04-10\n}}</ref>\n\nSince 2007, Angostura has also produced Angostura Orange, an [[orange bitters]] with bright floral notes and fresh orange peel.<ref name=\"Parsons\">{{cite web |last1=Parsons |first1=Brad Thomas |title=Ten Essential Bitters and How to Use Them |url=https://punchdrink.com/articles/ten-essential-aromatic-cocktail-bitters-and-how-to-use-them/ |website=PUNCH |accessdate=18 July 2019 |date=24 July 2017}}</ref> Angostura orange bitters have not dominated the orange bitters market in the same way that its aromatic bitters have become a go-to product for bars and consumers.<ref name=\"Simonson\">{{cite web |last1=Simonson |first1=Robert |title=Will the Real Orange Bitters Please Stand Up? |url=https://punchdrink.com/articles/real-orange-bitters-angostura-regans-fee-brothers/ |website=PUNCH |accessdate=18 July 2019 |date=15 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009 there was a shortage of Angostura bitters;<ref name=shortage /> the company reported that this was caused primarily by a problem in their supply of bottles. There were incorrect rumours of a product recall, or that production of the bitters had stopped at the plant in Trinidad. The shortage was the subject of many news articles and blogs, particularly in the cocktail industry.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/01/19/AR2010011900877.html/|title=Spirits: The Angostura Bitters Shortage calls for creativity|author=|date=|website=washingtonpost.com|accessdate=20 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Uses==\nAngostura bitters are extremely concentrated and may be an [[acquired taste]]; though 44.7% alcohol by volume, bitters are not normally ingested undiluted, but instead are used in small amounts as flavouring.<ref name=shortage>{{cite web|url=http://www.herbcompanion.com/herbs-in-the-kitchen/in-the-news-angostura-bitters-shortage.aspx|title=In the News: Angostura Bitters Shortage|author=|date=|website=Mother Earth Living|accessdate=20 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Medicinal===\nAngostura bitters are alleged to have restorative properties.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Bhat |first1=Kartik |title=Beverages |date=2013 |publisher=Pearson |location=Delhi |isbn=9789332514072 |pages=307\u20138}}</ref>  Angostura bitters is often incorrectly believed to have poisonous qualities because it is associated with angostura bark (although it does not actually contain any), which, although not toxic, during its use as a medicine was often adulterated by unscrupulous sellers,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://earthnotes.tripod.com/angostura.htm|title=Angostura - Herb Database + Images|first=Ernestina Parziale|last=CH|date=|website=earthnotes.tripod.com|accessdate=20 April 2018}}</ref> who padded out the sacks of bark with cheaper, poisonous ''[[Strychnos nux-vomica]]'' or [[copalchi]] bark.<ref name=\"Fallis\" /><ref>{{cite book\n| author1 = Albert Y. Leung\n| author2 = Steven Foster\n| title = Encyclopedia of common natural ingredients used in food, drugs, and cosmetics\n| publisher = Wiley-Interscience\n| year = 2003\n| page = 35\n}}</ref>\nAngostura is still often used by Trinidadians to treat digestive problems. It contains gentian, which has been proven effective as treatment for indigestion.{{Citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n===Cocktails===\nAngostura bitters are a key ingredient in many [[cocktails]]. Originally used to help with upset stomachs of the soldiers in Sim\u00f3n Bol\u00edvar's army, it later became popular in soda water and was usually served with [[gin]]. The mix stuck in the form of a [[pink gin]], and is also used in many other alcoholic [[cocktails]] such as [[long vodka]], consisting of [[vodka]], bitters, and [[lemonade]]. In the United States, it is best known for its use in whiskey cocktails: [[Old fashioned (cocktail)|Old Fashioned]], made with [[whiskey]], bitters, sugar, and water,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.drinksmixer.com/drink407.html|title=Old Fashioned recipe|author=|date=|website=www.drinksmixer.com|accessdate=20 April 2018}}</ref> and [[Manhattan (cocktail)|Manhattan]], made usually with [[rye whiskey]] and red [[vermouth]]. In a [[Pisco Sour]] a few drops are sprinkled on top of the foam, both for aroma and decoration. In a [[Champagne Cocktail]] a few drops of bitters are added to a sugar cube.\n\nIn Hong Kong, Angostura bitters are included in the local [[Gunner (cocktail)|Gunner]] cocktail. Though not in the classic recipe, bartenders sometimes add more flavour to the [[Mojito]] cocktail by sprinkling a few drops of Angostura bitters on top. Bitters can also be used in \"soft\" drinks; a common drink served in Australian and New Zealand pubs is [[lemon, lime and bitters]]. In [[Malawi]], bitters are added to a mix of crushed ice, [[ginger ale]] and [[Sprite (drink)|Sprite]] to make a 'rock shandy'.\n\n''Angostura Bitters Drink Guide'', a promotional booklet of 1908, was reprinted in 2008 with a new introduction by Ross Bolton.\n\nAmong certain bartending communities (especially in Malaysia) shots of Angostura are taken as the 'bartender's handshake' either during or after the shift is done.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://talesofthecocktail.com/culture/praise-bartenders-handshake|title=In Praise of the Bartender's Handshake|date=2017-02-01|work=Tales of the Cocktail|access-date=2017-11-07|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe largest purveyor of Angostura bitters in the world is Nelsen's Hall Bitters Pub on [[Washington Island (Wisconsin)|Washington Island]] off the northeast tip of [[Door Peninsula]] in [[Door County, Wisconsin|Door County]], [[Wisconsin]].  The pub began selling shots of bitters as a ''stomach tonic for medicinal purposes'' under a pharmaceutical license during [[Prohibition in the United States]].  The practice, which helped the pub to become the oldest continuously-operating tavern in Wisconsin, remained a tradition after the repeal of Prohibition. As of 2018, the pub hosts a Bitters Club, incorporates bitters into food menu items, and sells upwards of 10,000 shots per year.<ref name=\"Kunkel\">{{cite web|last1=Kunkel|first1=Leigh|title=How a Tiny Wisconsin Island Became the World's Biggest Consumer of Bitters|url=https://www.atlasobscura.com/articles/washington-island-wisconsin-bitters-shots|website=[[Atlas Obscura]]|accessdate=6 March 2018|date=5 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Popular recipes===\n{{Div col}}\n* [[Bloody Mary (cocktail)|Bloody Mary]]\n* [[Bourbon Lancer]]\n* [[Brandy Sour (Cyprus)]]\n* [[Brut Cocktail]]\n* [[Champagne cocktail]]\n* [[Cuba Libre#Local variations|Cuba Libre Preparado]]\n* [[Fallen Angel (cocktail)|Fallen Angel]]\n* [[Gin pahit]]\n* [[Gunner (cocktail)|Gunner]]\n* [[Lemon, Lime and Bitters]]\n* [[Long vodka]]\n* [[Manhattan (cocktail)|Manhattan]]\n* [[Old fashioned (cocktail)|Old Fashioned]]\n* [[Peanut punch]]\n* [[Pink Gin]]\n* [[Pisco Sour]]\n* [[Planter's Punch]]\n* [[Prince of Wales (cocktail)|Prince of Wales]]\n* [[Rob Roy (cocktail)|Rob Roy]]\n* [[Shandy#Rock or non-alcoholic shandy|Rock Shandy]]\n* [[Punch (drink)#Rum punches|Rum punch]]\n* [[Rum Swizzle]]\n* [[Singapore Sling]]\n* [[Zombie (cocktail)|Zombie]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Gentian (spirit)]]\n* [[Meinhard's Bitters]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.angosturabitters.com/ Official  '''Angostura Bitters''' website]\n{{commonscat|Angostura bitters}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Angostura Bitters}}\n[[Category:Bitters]]\n[[Category:Drink companies of Trinidad and Tobago]]\n[[Category:Patent medicines]]\n[[Category:Spices]]\n[[Category:Trade secrets]]\n[[Category:Venezuelan cuisine]]\n", "name_user": "MrGentleFish", "label": "safe", "comment": "reworded sentence and removed extraneous info", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angostura_bitters"}
{"title_page": "Tears in Heaven", "text_new": "{{for|the upcoming TV series|Tears in Heaven (TV series)}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Tears in Heaven\n| cover      = Tears in Heaven Vinyl Cover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Eric Clapton]]\n| album      = [[Rush (soundtrack)|Rush: Music from the Motion Picture Soundtrack]] And [[Unplugged (Eric Clapton album)|Unplugged]]\n| B-side     = Tracks and Lines\n| released   = 8 January 1992\n| format     =\n*[[Cassette single]]\n*[[CD single]]\n*[[7-inch single]]\n*[[12-inch single]]\n| recorded   = 1991\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Soft rock]]<ref>{{cite book|first= Chris |last= Smith |title= The Greenwood Encyclopedia of Rock History: From Arenas to the Underground, 1974\u20131980 |year= 2006 |publisher= Greenwood Press |isbn= 0-313-32937-0 |page= 102}}</ref>\n| length     = {{Duration|m=4|s=36}}\n| label      = [[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]]\n| writer     =\n*[[Eric Clapton]]\n*[[Will Jennings]]\n| producer   = [[Russ Titelman]]\n| prev_title = [[Wonderful Tonight]] (live)\n| prev_year  = 1991\n| next_title = [[Layla#Beyond the original album|Layla]] (acoustic version)\n| next_year  = 1992\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|JxPj3GAYYZ0|\"Tears in Heaven\"}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Tears in Heaven'''\" is a song by [[Eric Clapton]] and [[Will Jennings]], written about the death of Clapton's four-year-old son, Conor. It appeared  on the [[Rush (soundtrack)|1991 ''Rush'' film soundtrack]]. In January 1992, Clapton performed the song in front of an audience at [[Bray Studios (UK)|Bray Studios]], Berkshire, England for ''[[MTV Unplugged]]'', with the recording appearing on his ''[[Unplugged (Eric Clapton album)|Unplugged]]'' album.\n\nThe song was Clapton's best-selling single in the United States and reached number two on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. In his home country the United Kingdom it reached number five on the [[UK Singles Chart]], and also charted in the top 10 in more than twenty nations around the world. It won three [[Grammy Award]]s for [[Grammy Award for Best Male Pop Vocal Performance|Best Male Pop Vocal Performance]], [[Grammy Award for Song of the Year|Song of the Year]], and [[Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]]. In 2004, ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' ranked \"Tears in Heaven\" 362nd on its list of \"[[Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Songs of All Time|The 500 Greatest Songs of All Time]]\".\n\n==Writing and recording==\nIn August 1990, Clapton's manager, two of his [[Road crew|roadies]] and his friend and fellow musician [[Stevie Ray Vaughan]] were killed in a [[Death of Stevie Ray Vaughan|helicopter accident]]. On 20 March 1991, Clapton's 4-year-old son Conor died after falling from the 53rd-floor window of a New York City apartment belonging to Conor's mother's friend.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eric-clapton.co.uk/interviewsandarticles/loryinterview.htm|title=Interview with Lory del Santo|date=|publisher=Eric-clapton.co.uk|accessdate=2013-10-03}}</ref><ref>[http://ic.galegroup.com.mctproxy.mnpals.net/ic/suic/NewsDetailsPage/NewsDetailsWindow?displayGroupName=News&prodId=SUIC&action=2&catId=&documentId=GALE%7CA174530578&userGroupName=mnaminncom&jsid=affa8030d027d7b109681ef0a4755d83] {{dead link|date=February 2014}}</ref>\n\nAfter isolating himself for a period, Clapton began working again, writing music for the film ''[[Rush (1991 film)|Rush]]'' (1991). He dealt with the grief of his son's death by cowriting \"Tears in Heaven\" for the soundtrack with [[Will Jennings]]. In an interview in 1992, Clapton said of the song, \"It was in the back of my head but it didn\u2019t really have a reason for being until I was scoring this movie ... then it sort of had a reason to be. And it is a little ambiguous because it could be taken to be about Conor but it also is meant to be part of the film.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tmmBynDJzWw|title=Eric Clapton : Sue Lawley 1992|website=YouTube|accessdate=26 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview with Daphne Barak, Clapton said: \"I almost subconsciously used music for myself as a healing agent, and lo and behold, it worked... I have got a great deal of happiness and a great deal of healing from music.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/2020/Entertainment/story?id=2404474&page=1- |title=Exclusive: Mother of 'Tears in Heaven' Inspiration Shares Story|publisher=[[ABC News]] |date=2006-09-07 |accessdate=2014-02-16}}</ref> Jennings said:<blockquote>\n[Clapton] said to me, \"I want to write a song about my boy.\" Eric had the first verse of the song written, which, to me, is all the song, but he wanted me to write the rest of the verse lines and the release (\"Time can bring you down, time can bend your knees...\"), even though I told him that it was so personal he should write everything himself. He told me that he had admired the work I did with [[Steve Winwood]] and finally there was nothing else but to do as he requested, despite the sensitivity of the subject. This is a song so personal and so sad that it is unique in my experience of writing songs.{{ref|songfacts}}\n</blockquote>\n\n==Release==\nShortly after the single was released, Clapton recorded the song in front of an audience at [[Bray Studios]], Berkshire, England as part of a set for ''[[MTV Unplugged]],''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/unplugged-r4050|title=MTV Unplugged - Eric Clapton &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits, Awards|author=[[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]]|date=1992-08-18|website=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=2014-02-16}}</ref> released as ''[[Unplugged (Eric Clapton album)|Unplugged]].'' The album topped numerous charts, including the US, Japan and Australia, reached number two in the UK, and was nominated for nine [[Grammy Awards]] the year it was released.\n\n===United States and Canada===\n\"Tears in Heaven\" is Clapton's best-selling single in the United States. With more than 2,800,000 copies sold \u2013 both physical and digital \u2013 it remains one of the best-selling pop singles of the 1990s and one of the best-selling singles released by any non-American artist. The Reprise Records single reached number two on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] singles charts, where it charted for 26 weeks. It was kept from the number one spot by \"[[Save the Best for Last]]\" by [[Vanessa L. Williams|Vanessa Williams]]. It is also Clapton's highest charting single on the Hot 100 after \"[[I Shot the Sheriff]]\", which is Clapton's only Hot 100 number one single to date.<ref name=\"hot100\"/> While charting on Americas most important single chart, Clapton received several sales awards by the ''Billboard'' magazine, including a \"Hot Shot Debut\" and a \"Power Pick/Sales\" certificate.<ref name=\"bb1992\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/90s/1992/BB1992.pdf|title=Billboard Hot 100 Singles|magazine=Billboard Magazine|year=1992|volume=104|issn=0006-2510|accessdate=November 13, 2015}}</ref> After the physical single release was certified with a [[Gold disc]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA) on March 18, 1992,<ref name=\"riaa\">{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&ar=ERIC+CLAPTON&ti=TEARS+IN+HEAVEN|title=Eric Clapton - Tears in Heaven|work=RIAA|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref> the single was still selling about 150,000 copies every week.<ref name=\"bb1992\"/> On April 15, 1992, \"Tears in Heaven\" was certified with a [[Platinum certification]] award for sales of more than 1,000,000 copies in the United States.<ref name=\"riaa\"/> It topped the Top Single Sales chart, compiled by the ''Billboard'' magazine in 1992.<ref name=\"ustss\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/90s/1992/Billboard-1992-03-28.pdf|title=Top Singles Sales|magazine=Billboard Magazine|volume=104|number=13|date=March 28, 1992|page=69|issn=0006-2510|accessdate=November 12, 2015}}</ref> The release also topped ''Billboard'' magazines [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Adult Contemporary]] chart, on which \"Tears in Heaven\" charted for a total of 30 weeks,<ref name=\"usac\"/> and also became a number one single on the Top 100 [[Cashbox (magazine)|''Cashbox'']] charts.<ref name=\"cashbox\"/> By the end of 1992, \"Tears in Heaven\" sold more than 2,300,000 copies in the United States alone.<ref name=\"ussales\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/90s/1992/Billboard-1992-04-04.pdf|title=Warner Enjoys The Single Sales|magazine=Billboard Magazine|issn=0006-2510|volume=104|number=14|date=April 4, 1992|accessdate=November 12, 2015}}</ref> The pop single also received a lot of airplay, charting 20 weeks on the Top Radio Songs chart, peaking at number three, and reaching position nine on the [[Mainstream Rock (chart)|Mainstream Rock Songs]] chart, where \"Tears in Heaven\" stayed for a total of 18 weeks.<ref name=\"msrs\"/> Also, it was later the fourth-favourite recurrent airplay single, as the ''Billboard'' magazine reported in summer of 1992.<ref name=\"recurrent\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/90s/1992/Billboard-1992-07-11.pdf|title=Top 40 Recurrent Radio Songs|magazine=Billboard Magazine|volume=104|number=28|date=July 11, 1992|issn=0006-2510|accessdate=November 12, 2015}}</ref> The 1992 single release was the 6th-best-selling single recording in the United States that year, reaching number six on the ''Billboard'' year-end Hot 100 chart<ref name=\"hot100end\"/> as well as the 5th-most successful Adult Contemporary release. It also ranked at number five on the Top Single Sales chart, compiled by the ''Billboard'' magazine and reached position 25 on the Top Radio Songs year-end chart in 1992.<ref name=\"26-12-1992\"/>\n\nIn [[Canada]], the Reprise Records single release topped all of the three pop single sales chart in the country and is therefore Clapton's most successful single in Canada to date. The song reached the number one top position on both the Canadian Hot Adult Contemporary Tracks<ref name=\"rpmac\"/> and Top 100 Singles chart, compiled by the [[RPM (magazine)|''RPM'']] magazine.<ref name=\"rpm100\"/> In addition to the already rare success, reaching number one on both of the charts, \"Tears in Heaven\" was [[The Record (magazine)|''The Record'']] magazine's top retail selling single release.<ref name=\"therecord\"/> Shortly after the single was released in Canada and topped all of these three record charts, it was certified with a double Platinum sales certification for physical sales exceeding 200,000 copies.<ref name=\"can\">{{cite book|first=Alan|last=Schmidt|title=The sales boof of singles|location=[[Montreal]]|year=1993|pages=96\u201398}}</ref> In 1992, \"Tears in Heaven\" was the 17th-best-selling single on ''RPM'' magazine's Hot Adult Contemporary Tracks chart.<ref name=\"rpmacend\"/>\n\n===Europe and Oceania===\nThe pop single release was especially successful in [[Europe]], reaching the Top 10 in 12 countries and the Top 20 in 15 of them. The single charted at number three on the [[European Hot 100 Singles]] chart in 1992, and was Europes 21st best-selling single of 1992.<ref name=\"hawtin\"/> In [[Austria]], the physical single peaked at number 25 on the [[\u00d63 Austria Top 40]] singles chart, and eventually charted at number ten in week four, reaching its highest charting position in the country. In total, the single of \"Tears in Heaven\" spent 12 weeks on the nations single sales chart.<ref name=\"aut\"/> It was eventually certified with a Gold disc by the International Federation of the Phonographic Industry (IFPI) in Austria and reached number 61 on the country's year-end chart in 1992.<ref name=\"autend\"/> In [[Flanders]] ([[Belgium]]), the single reached three singles charts. In 1992, it peaked at position 44 on [[Ultratop]]s Top 50 single chart, and reached its peak position, 16, in week four and five, while on chart for a total of ten weeks.<ref name=\"flanders\"/> At that time, the single also peaked at number ten on the Belgian [[VRT Top 30]] singles chart, where \"Tears in Heaven\" spent eight weeks on chart.<ref name=\"vrt\"/>\n\nIn 2010, when a remastered physical edition of the single was released in Belgium, it reached number 16 on the Back Catalogue chart.<ref name=\"flanders\"/> The song was Belgiums 159th best-selling single in 1992,<ref name=\"hawtin\"/> and certified with a Platinum disc for sales over 50,000 copies by the [[Belgian Entertainment Association]].<ref name=\"bel\">{{cite web|url=http://www.directupload.net/file/d/4170/9ffwhpni_png.htm |title=Belgian single certifications \u2013 Eric Clapton \u2013 Tears in Heaven |publisher=[[Belgian Entertainment Association]] |language=nl |accessdate=November 12, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151112105115/http://www.directupload.net/file/d/4170/9ffwhpni_png.htm |archivedate=November 12, 2015 }}</ref> In [[Denmark]], \"Tears in Heaven\" topped the single sales chart and was certified Platinum for sales exceeding 10,000 copies by [[IFPI Denmark]], as it spent a total of 29 weeks on chart.<ref name=\"denmark\"/> In [[France]], the single peaked at number two on the French singles chart, where it charted for 34 weeks. On chart week 28, it was certified with a Platinum award by the [[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique]] (SNEP) for sales of more than 500,000 copies in the country.<ref name=\"heid\u00e9\"/> In [[Germany]], the single placed itself on its lowest charting position, number 42.<ref name=\"ger\"/> In total, the single charted for eleven weeks on the German singles chart,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.offiziellecharts.de/titel-details-2425|title=Eric Clapton \u2013 Tears in Heaven (Single)|publisher=Offizielle Deutsche Charts|work=GfK Entertainment|accessdate=November 12, 2015}}</ref> and sold more than 170,000 both digital and physical copies to date. \"Tears in Heaven\" topped<ref name=\"irl\"/> the single charts in [[Ireland]] and was certified with a Platinum disc by the [[Irish Recorded Music Association]] (IRMA), selling more than 50,000 copies in 1992, as it reached both of the year-end charts in 1992<ref name=\"martin\"/> and 1993 with positions five and 47.<ref name=\"martin2\"/> In [[Italy]], the single reached Top five positions as both a physical as well as a digital download single. In 1992, the single peaked at number four on the Italian single chart, compiled by [[Musica e dischi]].<ref name=\"md\"/> Later, the single re-entered the nations single chart as a digital download and streaming single, reaching number five on the charts, now compiled by the [[Federazione Industria Musicale Italiana]] (FIMI).\n\nIn addition, the digital single was certified with a Platinum disc, for sales and streams exceeding 30,000 units. The single was a medium successful hit in the [[Netherlands]]. It reached position 17 on the [[Dutch Top 40]] singles weekly chart, where it stayed for ten weeks,<ref name=\"dutch40\"/> and reached number 131 on the charts year-end compilation in 1992.<ref name=\"dutch40end\"/> It also reached the [[Single Top 100]] charts, peaking at number 13 and staying for 21 weeks on chart,<ref name=\"dutch100\"/> before placing itself on position 87 on the year-end Single 100 chart.<ref name=\"dutch100end\"/> In [[Norway]], the single topped the [[VG-lista]] singles chart in 1992, exactly like it did in [[Poland]], reaching the top spot on the [[Lista Przeboj\u00f3w Programu Trzeciego]] (LP3),<ref name=\"LP3\"/> where it stayed for 16 weeks.<ref name=\"hawtin\"/> In [[Spain]], the single charted at number seven on the nations single charts, and was eventually certified with a Gold disc, commemorating the sale of more than 25,000 copies in the country by the [[Productores de M\u00fasica de Espa\u00f1a]] (PROMUSICAE). In [[Sweden]], \"Tears in Heaven\" reached number four on the [[Sverigetopplistan]] singles chart, where it spent a total of 30 weeks on chart.\n\nIn October 1992, it was presented with a Platinum sales award by the [[Swedish Recording Industry Association]] (GLF), when it exceeded 50,000 sold units in the country.<ref name=\"GLF\"/> It reached number 86 on the 1992 Swedish year-end chart.<ref name=\"swe\"/> In [[Switzerland]], the single was also a Top ten hit, peaking at number seven on the [[Schweizer Hitparade]], where \"Tears in Heaven\" stayed for 15 weeks.<ref name=\"swi\"/> Here too, the single was presented with a Gold certification by the International Federation of the Phonographic Industry, for sales exceeding 25,000 copies in Switzerland. It was the 38th most-bought single in Switzerland in 1992.<ref name=\"swiend\"/> \"Tears in Heaven\" was also a major success for Clapton in his home country, the United Kingdom. The single reached number five on the charts, compiled by the [[Official Charts Company]] and spent a total of 14 weeks on the British charts,<ref name=\"uk\"/> selling 140,000 copies in the first five weeks.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/90s/1992/Billboard-1992-04-18.pdf|title=British Single Sales Shoot Up This Week|magazine=Billboard Magazine|date=April 18, 1992|volume=104|number=16|issn=0006-2510|accessdate=November 13, 2015}}</ref> Shortly after, the single was certified with a [[Silver disc]] by the [[British Phonographic Industry]] (BPI), for sales more than 200,000 copies in the country.<ref name=\"bpi\">{{cite book|first=Frank|last=Hoffmann|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-FOSAgAAQBAJ&hl=en|title=Encyclopedia of Recorded Sound|date=November 12, 2004|publisher=Taylor & Francis}}</ref> With total sales of more than 300,000 copies by the end of 1992,<ref name=\"uksales\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/90s/1992/Billboard-1992-06-27.pdf|title=Clapton, John And Bolan|magazine=Billboard Magazine|issn=0006-2510|volume=104|number=26|date=June 27, 1992|accessdate=November 12, 2015}}</ref> \"Tears in Heaven\" reached number 39 on Great Britain's 1992 year-end chart.<ref name=\"ukend\"/>\n\nIn [[Australia]], \"Tears in Heaven\" was a hit record despite charting in the lower positions of the [[ARIA Charts|ARIA Singles Chart]]. In 1992, the pop Reprise Records single placed itself at number 102 on Australias year-end chart.<ref name=\"aria\"/> However, in 1993, it would generate far more single sales, become Australia's 28th best-selling single alongside \"[[Layla#Unplugged version|Layla]]\".<ref name=\"aria93\"/> In 1993, the single release was also certified with a Platinum record sales certification by the [[Australian Recording Industry Association]] (ARIA) for sales figures exceeding 70,000 physical units.<ref name=\"aus\">{{cite web|url=http://australianfuncountdowns.blogspot.com/2010/01/accreditation-awards.html|title=Australian single certifications \u2013 Eric Clapton \u2013 Tears in Heaven|publisher=[[Australian Recording Industry Association]]|accessdate=November 12, 2015}}</ref> In [[New Zealand]], the single topped the country's single chart for the first five weeks on chart, and spent a total of 18 weeks on the country's single sales chart.<ref name=\"new\"/> On May 31, 1992 \u2013 just four weeks on chart in New Zealand \u2013 \"Tears in Heaven\" was certified with a Gold disc by the [[Recording Industry Association of New Zealand]] (RIANZ), commemorating the sale of more than 7,500 copies in the country.<ref name=\"nz\"/>\n\n===Asia and South America===\nIn Asia, \"Tears in Heaven\" was mostly successful in [[Japan]], [[Taiwan]] and [[Macao]]. In Japan, the single peaked at number two on the ''[[Oricon]]'' Japanese Hot 100 Singles sales chart in February 1992.<ref name=\"japan100\"/> In total, the Reprise Records single stayed thirty-seven weeks on the nation's Hot 100 single sales chart, compiled by ''Oricon''.<ref name=\"hawtin\"/> Because \"Tears in Heaven\" was not released as a maxi single or part of a [[Double A-sided|double A-side]] by Reprise or Warner Bros. Records in Japan, it was not eligible to chart on any other compilations. While charting in Japan in 1992, the pop single release was certified with a triple Platinum disc by the [[Recording Industry Association of Japan]] (RIAJ),<ref name=\"oricon\"/> for sales overstepping the 300,000 sales mark. By the end of 1992, \"Tears in Heaven\" sold more than 389,000 units in Japan,<ref name=\"jpnsales\">{{cite web|url=http://homepage1.nifty.com/tuty/ryokou_hakuba.htm|title=\u9ed2\u90e8\u30fb\u767d\u99ac|trans-title=Single Sales|publisher=JP&KIYO|work=Oricon Sales|accessdate=November 12, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304120036/http://homepage1.nifty.com/tuty/ryokou_hakuba.htm|archive-date=March 4, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> however, not more than 400,000 copies, quelling the quelling four a quadruple Platinum certification award.<ref name=\"oricon\"/> For the year-end closing of ''Oricon'', it was revealed, the 1992 single release was the fortieth best-selling release on the Hot 100 Singles chart.<ref name=\"hawtin\"/> On the summary of 1992's most-purchased international singles in Japan, \"Tears in Heaven\" reached number sixty-three.<ref name=\"oricon\"/> In Taiwan, the digital single of the song reached the [[G-Music]] charts in 2007, where the release stayed a total of seventeen weeks and topped the nation's singles chart three times.<ref name=\"gmusic\"/> During that year, the Recording Industry of Taiwan (RIT), awarded the single release with a Gold disc, for digital download sales exceeding more than 175,000 units in the country. On Taiwan's year-end chart of 2007, \"Tears in Heaven\" ranked at position seventy-seven.<ref name=\"twn\"/> In the special administrative region of Macao, the single was certified with a Gold disc by the International Federation of the Phonographic Industry of Macao for single sales of more than 15,000 physical copies.<ref name=\"MAC\">{{cite web|url=http://recordsales.2xik.com/The-first-blog-b1/Macao-Music-Sales-2001-2009-b1-p1.htm|title=Macao single certifications \u2013 Eric Clapton \u2013 Change the World|publisher=[[International Federation of the Phonographic Industry|International Federation of the Phonographic Industry of Macao]]|language=zh|accessdate=November 13, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150629231313/http://recordsales.2xik.com/The-first-blog-b1/Macao-Music-Sales-2001-2009-b1-p1.htm|archivedate=June 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\n\"Tears in Heaven\" is Clapton's commercially most successful single release in South America to date, as it reached the single sales charts of three countries. In [[Argentina]], the Reprise Records release topped the country's single charts, compiled by the [[C\u00e1mara Argentina de Productores de Fonogramas y Videogramas]] (CAPIF). Also, the pop tune topped the singles chart in [[Brazil]],<ref name=\"ABPD\"/> and reached the 1992 year-end charts, placing itself on number fourteen.<ref name=\"hawtin\"/> In Brazil, the single release was certified with a Platinum disc for physical sales of more than 250,000 copies.<ref name=\"ABPD\"/> It is Clapton's highest-selling single in Brazil, as \"Change the World\" was certified with a Gold disc,<ref>{{cite journal|first=Adelar|last=Gomes|title=Eric Clapton \u00e9 o primeiro colocado e ouro ainda com eles.|trans-title=Eric Claton takes the number one and a Gold record just as well|language=pt|publisher=[[Roberto Irineu Marinho]]|work=O Globo|date=October 21, 1997}}</ref> and a rare certification for any physical single, as the world's best-selling single \"[[Candle in the Wind 1997]]\" achieved similar sales figures.<ref name=\"ABPD\"/> At last, \"Tears in Heaven\" peaked at number eight on [[Asociaci\u00f3n Colombiana de Productores de Fonogramas]] (ASINCOL)'s physical format singles chart in [[Colombia]]. It also reached number thirty-eight on the country's year-end chart of 1992, compiled by ASINCOL, and is Clapton's only charting single in the country.<ref name=\"ASINCOL\"/>\n\n== Legacy ==\nClapton made numerous public service announcements to raise awareness for [[childproofing]] windows and staircases. Clapton stopped performing \"Tears in Heaven\" in 2004, as well as the song \"[[My Father's Eyes (song)|My Father's Eyes]]\", stating: \"I didn't feel the loss any more, which is so much a part of performing those songs. I really have to connect with the feelings that were there when I wrote them. They're kind of gone and I really don't want them to come back, particularly. My life is different now. They probably just need a rest and maybe I'll introduce them for a much more detached point of view.\"<!-- <ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://music.uk.msn.com/photos/photos.aspx?cp-documentid=154814955&page=2 |title=2. Tears In Heaven - Eric Clapton - Everybody hurts: songs that make men cry |publisher=Music.uk.msn.com |date= |accessdate=2014-02-16}}{{dl|date=September 2016}}</ref> --><ref name=\"TODAY\">{{cite news|url=http://www.today.com/id/4423742/ns/today-today_entertainment/t/no-more-tears-heaven-clapton/|title=No more 'Tears in Heaven' for Clapton|date=March 11, 2004|work=[[TODAY.com]]|accessdate=September 20, 2016|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref> Tears in Heaven was parodied on HBO's [[Mr. Show]].<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1NnDGd_luKE</ref>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Ceremony\n!Award\n!Result\n!{{Abbr|Ref.|References}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"6\"|1992\n!scope=\"row\"|''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''\n|Best-Selling Soundtrack Single\n|{{won}}\n|align=\"center\"|<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wBAEAAAAMBAJ&vq=Clapton&hl=en&source=gbs_navlinks_s|title=The International Newsweekly of Music, Video and Entertainment|magazine=Billboard Magazine|volume=104|number=26|issn=0006-2510|date=June 27, 1992|accessdate=November 6, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[Golden Globe Award]]s\n|[[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]]\n|{{nominated}}\n|align=\"center\"|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000292/1992|title=Golden Globes, USA (1992)|publisher=Amazon.com, Inc.|work=Internet Movie Database|accessdate=November 6, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[MTV Movie Awards]]\n|[[MTV Movie Award for Best Song from a Movie|Best Song from a Movie]]\n|{{nominated}}\n|align=\"center\"|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000453/1992|title=MTV Movie Awards (1992)|publisher=Amazon.com, Inc.|work=Internet Movie Database|accessdate=November 6, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"3\"|[[MTV Video Music Award]]s\n|[[MTV Video Music Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]]\n|{{nominated}}\n|align=\"center\"|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/ontv/vma/1992/|title=1992 MTV Video Music Awards &#124; Highlights, Winners, Performers and Photos from the 1992 MTV VMAs > Best Cinematography|publisher=Viacom International, Inc.|work=MTV Music|accessdate=November 6, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[MTV Video Music Award for Best Male Video|Best Male Video]]\n|{{won}}\n|align=\"center\"|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/ontv/vma/1992/|title=1992 MTV Video Music Awards &#124; Highlights, Winners, Performers and Photos from the 1992 MTV VMAs > Best Male Video|publisher=Viacom International, Inc.|work=MTV Music|accessdate=November 6, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[MTV Video Music Award for Best Video from a Film|Best Video from a Film]]\n|{{nominated}}\n|align=\"center\"|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/ontv/vma/1992/|title=1992 MTV Video Music Awards &#124; Highlights, Winners, Performers and Photos from the 1992 MTV VMAs > Best Video from a Film|publisher=Viacom International, Inc.|work=MTV Music|accessdate=November 6, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"|1993\n!scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"5\"|[[35th Annual Grammy Awards|Grammy Awards]]\